{"title_page": "2016 in aviation", "text_new": "{{short description|Aviation-related events during the year of 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{very long|date=July 2019}}\n{{yearbox\n|in?=in aviation\n|cp=20th century\n|c=21st century \n|cf=22nd century\n|yp1=2013\n|yp2=2014\n|yp3=2015\n|year=2016\n|ya1=2017\n|ya2=2018\n|ya3=2019\n|dp3=1980s\n|dp2=1990s\n|dp1=2000s (decade){{!}}2000s\n|d=2010\u20132019{{!}}2010s\n|dn1=2020s\n|dn2=2030s\n|dn3=2040s\n}}\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\nThis is a list of '''aviation-related events from 2016''':\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n\n*During the month, the [[Government of Italy]] gives permission for armed U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs) to fly strike missions from [[Naval Air Station Sigonella]] on [[Sicily]] \u2013 where the [[United States]] has based unarmed surveillance UAVs since [[2011 in aviation|2001]] \u2013 against Islamic State targets in [[Libya]], but only if they are \"defensive,\" meaning that they are flown to protect [[United States special operations forces|U.S. special operations forces]] operating in and near Libya or rescuers attempting to retrieve downed U.S. pilots. [[Italy]] continues to prohibit U.S. offensive strikes from Italian territory, and also reserves to itself the right to veto any U.S. mission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-quietly-agrees-to-armed-u-s-drone-missions-over-libya-1456163730|title=Italy Quietly Agrees to Armed U.S. Drone Missions Over Libya|first1=Gordon|last1=Lubold|first2=Julian E.|last2=Barnes|date=23 February 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n;2 January\n* Indian aerial surveillance platforms detect a group of gunmen entering an [[Indian Air Force]] base at [[Pathankot]], [[India]], and Indian Air Force security forces exchange fire with them in a housing area. Four of the gunmen and two Indian Air Force security personnel are killed. Gunfire erupts again two hours later, and Indian helicopters fire on gunmen in the base later in the day. Indian security forces finally declare the base secure in the late afternoon, 14 hours after the intrusion began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3f724972b8f142edb1c07486cde4c277/gunmen-attack-air-force-base-northern-india-1-killed|title=Anonymous, \"Gunmen attack Indian air base near Pakistan border; 2 killed,\" Associated Press, January 1, 2016, 9:47 PM EST.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/36cbdce4c8fe4aada082aed9bd64ce3d/4-gunmen-2-troops-dead-attack-indian-air-base|title=Anand, Channi, \"India air force base attack leaves 4 gunmen, 2 troops dead,\" Associated Press, January 2, 2016, 8:46 AM EST.}}</ref><ref name=\"lakshmi20160104\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indian-troops-battling-militants-at-key-air-force-base/2016/01/03/6b33d358-17b2-48fc-92c6-a8cf415fa791_story.html|title=Indian troops battle militants at key air force base}}</ref>\n\n;3 January\n* Combat again breaks out at India's air base at Pathankot after security forces discover two militants still hiding on the base. Security forces reportedly kill the militants.<ref name=\"lakshmi20160104\"/>\n* An official at the [[United States Embassy]] in [[Addis Ababa]] announces that by mutual agreement with the [[Government of Ethiopia]] the [[United States]] had shut down its military [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] base at [[Arba Minch Airport]] in [[Arba Minch]] in southern [[Ethiopia]] in [[2015 in aviation#September|September 2015]]. The two countries had agreed that the base, which had opened in 2011, was no longer necessary. It is the first public announcement that the base had been closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/embassy-official-us-shuts-drone-operation-ethiopia-36063848|title=International News: Latest Headlines, Video and Photographs from Around the World \u2013 People, Places, Crisis, Conflict, Culture, Change, Analysis and Trends|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/01/04/pentagon-shutters-african-drone-base-moves-aircraft-to-other-hotspots/|title=Pentagon shutters African drone base, moves aircraft to other hot spots}}</ref>\n\n;4 January\n* [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[civil aviation]] authority suspends all civilian flights between Saudi Arabia and [[Iran]]. The move, which comes a day after Saudi Arabia severed [[diplomatic relations]] with Iran, raises doubts about the future ability of [[Islam]]ic pilgrims from Iran to visit [[Mecca]] and of [[Shiite]] pilgrims from Saudi Arabia to visit religious sites in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bahrain-cuts-ties-with-tehran-as-crisis-widens-in-saudi-iran-split/2016/01/04/145c8824-b271-11e5-8abc-d09392edc612_story.html|title=Mideast tensions soar as Saudi Arabia rallies countries to cut ties with Iran}}</ref>\n* John Boggs files suit against William Merideth for shooting down his [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) in [[Bullitt County, Kentucky|Bullitt County]], [[Kentucky]], with a [[shotgun]] as the UAV hovered over Merideth's property, asserting that the drone was in public [[airspace]] when it was shot down and requesting [[USD|$1,800]] in damages and clarification as to how high above private property public airspace begins. Merideth had claimed the UAV was spying on his family and violating his privacy. The case promises to spur the U.S. judicial system to clarify where private property rights end and federal jurisdiction begins in U.S. [[airspace]], with a significant potential impact on future private and commercial UAV operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techworm.net/2016/01/drone-owner-sues-neighbour-for-shooting-down-his-drone.html|title=Drone owner sues neighbour for shooting down his aircraft with a shotgun|date=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/01/13/you-may-be-powerless-to-stop-a-drone-from-hovering-over-your-own-yard/|title=You may be powerless to stop a drone from hovering over your own yard}}</ref>\n\n;5 January\n* When two [[United States Air Force]] [[Sikorsky HH-60 Pave Hawk]] helicopters attempt to evacuate wounded Afghan military personnel near [[Marjah]], [[Afghanistan]], one strikes a wall and is disabled and the other is ordered to abort the mission under heavy ground fire. One American is killed and two wounded in the incident; they are the first U.S. casualties in Afghanistan in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/01/05/one-u-s-soldier-killed-two-wounded-in-helmand-province-afghanistan/|title=One U.S. soldier killed, two wounded in Helmand province, Afghanistan}}</ref>\n\n;7 January\n* [[Iran]] claims that an airstrike by the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] operating against rebel forces in [[Yemen]] struck its [[embassy]] in [[Sana'a]] overnight. Local residents and press observers report no signs of damage at the embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iran-claims-saudi-airstrike-on-yemen-embassy-amid-deepening-tensions/2016/01/07/fc6131ae-b52f-11e5-a76a-0b5145e8679a_story.html|title=Iran claims Saudi airstrike hit its embassy in Yemen}}</ref>\n* A report by the [[inspector general]] of the [[United States Department of Transportation]] to the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) expresses a concern that airline pilots have become so reliant on automation technology to fly their aircraft that they have lost the skills necessary to take manual control of an airliner in order to deal promptly and effectively with unforeseen events. The FAA responds that it will require enhancements in pilot training for the manual flight of aircraft, and the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] endorses the need for well-trained aircrew aboard airliners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/does-using-an-autopilot-dull-the-skills-of-us-commercial-pilots/2016/01/13/00e458fe-ba13-11e5-829c-26ffb874a18d_story.html|title=Does autopilot dull the skills of U.S. airline pilots?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oig.dot.gov/sites/default/files/FAA%20Flight%20Decek%20Automation_Final%20Report%5E1-7-16.pdf|title=\"Enhanced FAA Oversight Could Reduce Hazards Associated With Increased Use of Flight Deck Automation\" Federal Aviation Administration, Report Number: AV-2016-013, January 7, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n;8 January\n* [[West Air Sweden]] [[West Air Sweden Flight 294|Flight 294]], a [[Bombardier CRJ200|Canadair CL-600-2B19 Regional Jet CRJ-200PF]] (registration SE-DUX) on a domestic cargo flight in [[Norway]] carrying mail and packages from [[Oslo]] to [[Troms\u00f8]], suddenly goes into a steep descent after a brief [[Mayday]] call and crashes near [[Akkajaure]], [[Sweden]], killing its crew of two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160108-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Canadair CL-600-2B19 Regional Jet CRJ-200PF SE-DUX Oajev\u00e1gge|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;9 January\n\n* [[Tracey Curtis-Taylor]] completes a solo flight from [[Farnborough Airport]] in [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]], [[England]], to [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], in the [[Boeing-Stearman Model 75]] open-[[cockpit]] [[biplane]] ''Spirit of Artemis''. During the 100-day, {{convert|21000|km|mi|adj=on}} flight, begun on [[2015 in aviation#October|1 October 2015]], she has flown over 23 countries and made 50 refueling stops. The flight recreates the [[1930 in aviation|1930]] [[Croydon]]-to-[[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] flight of [[Amy Johnson]], the first solo flight between the [[United Kingdom]] and Australia by a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-34400824|title=Bi-plane pilot in Amy Johnson UK to Australia flight|date=1 October 2015|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35271182|title=Tracey Curtis-Taylor finishes UK to Australia biplane flight|date=9 January 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;10 January\n* As a show of force after a 6 January [[nuclear weapon]]s test by [[North Korea]], a [[Guam]]-based U.S. Air Force [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52H Stratofortress]] flies to [[South Korea]], where it circles over [[Osan Air Base]] flanked by a U.S. Air Force [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] and a [[Republic of Korea Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]] before returning to Guam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-nuclear-idUSKCN0UN0Y420160111|title=U.S. flies B-52 over South Korea after North's nuclear test|date=11 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;12 January\n* An unarmed Iranian unmanned aerial vehicle flies near the [[French Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle|Charles de Gaulle]]'' and directly over the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Harry S Truman|CVN-75}} as they operate in [[international waters]] in the [[Persian Gulf]]. Iran will announce the flight and release purported video from it on 29 January \u2013 implying that the video had been taken earlier that day rather than on 12 January \u2013 and a [[United States Fifth Fleet]] spokesman will respond by calling the flight \"abnormal and unprofessional.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/4fd95402fde146079290278bfae506b7/iran-says-it-flew-drone-over-us-aircraft-carrier|title=Karimi, Nasser, and John Gambrill, \"Iran flies unarmed military drone over US aircraft carrier,\" Associated Press, January 29, 2016, 2:29 PM EST.}}</ref>\n* An air-and-bus bridge begins operating as a pilot program to help 8,000 [[Cuba]]n immigrants stranded in [[Costa Rica]] since [[Nicaragua]] closed its border to them on 13 November 2015 by allowing them to fly out of Costa Rica and reach [[Mexico]], from which they can emigrate to the United States. The first flight of the air-and-bus bridge departs [[Liberia, Costa Rica|Liberia]], Costa Rica, during the evening as part of regional agreement to help the Cubans bypass Nicaragua.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6b77f374b14a461d9212c3ddeeaf4f2d/stranded-cuban-migrants-make-plans-cross-mexico|title=Sherman, Christopher, and Maria Verza, \"Stranded Cuban migrants make plans to cross Mexico,\" Associated Press, January 14, 2016, 12:36 PM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;13 January\n* An [[Israeli Air Force]] aircraft strikes a group of [[Palestinian people|Palestinians]] \u2013 members of the [[Al-Aqsa Martyrs Brigade]] \u2013 on a beach in the northern [[Gaza Strip]] near the Israeli border fence, killing one and injuring three others. The [[Israel Defense Force]] claims that they were planting explosives with which to target Israeli soldiers patrolling the border on the other side of the fence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6e0660ebc87449799d381baad5c69ef8/israeli-military-airstrike-targets-gaza-militants-1-killed|title=Anonymous, \"Israeli military: Airstrike targets Gaza militants, 1 killed,\" Associated Press, January 13, 2016, 5:49 AM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;14 January\n* [[Air France]] officially retires the [[Boeing 747]] from its fleet with Flight 744, a scenic flight by a [[Boeing 747-400]] with 432 people on board, including 380 paying passengers, in formation with 12 [[Dassault/Dornier Alpha Jet]]s of the [[French Air Force]]'s [[Patrouille de France]] aerobatic team. The airliner takes off from [[Charles de Gaulle Airport]] in [[Paris]] and makes a clockwise circuit that takes it over [[Lyon]], [[Geneva]], [[Marseille]], [[Montpellier]], [[Bordeaux]], and [[Deauville]] before returning to Charles de Gaulle Airport, offering passengers scenic views of [[Mont Blanc]], [[Normandy]], and [[Mont Saint-Michel]] along the way. The Boeing 747 had been part of the Air France fleet since 1974 and the 68 Boeing 747s the airline had operated had carried 250 million passengers. In the future plans to use its [[Airbus A380]]s and [[Boeing 777]]s for long-haul flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/15/aviation/air-france-boeing-747-retired-farewell/index.html|title=Air France retires Boeing 747s|first=Jim |last=Bittermann|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-14/air-france-grounds-747-after-40-years-as-icon-lives-on-at-klm|title=Air France Retires Its Last 747 After 40 Years|date=14 January 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avgeekery.com/air-france-says-au-revoir-747-stunning-flyby/|title=Air France Says Au Revoir to the 747 With This Stunning Flyby \u2013 Avgeekery.com \u2013 News and stories by Aviation Professionals}}</ref>\n* Two [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion]] helicopters of [[HMH-463|Marine Heavy Helicopter Squadron 463 (HMH-463)]], each carrying six Marines, [[2016 U.S. Marine helicopter collision|collide and crash]] in a fireball late in the evening over the [[Pacific Ocean]] north of [[Oahu]] just off [[Haleiwa, Hawaii|Haleiwa]], [[Hawaii]], and crash, leaving all 12 Marines missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/15/us/hawaii-military-aircraft-collision/index.html|title=Helicopter crash in Hawaii: Search for 12 missing Marines|author1=Michael Martinez |author2=Ben Brumfield |author3=Tina Burnside|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] will call off the search for the Marines on 19 January,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hawaii-marines-crash-idUSKCN0UY08H|title=Search called off for Marines missing since helicopter crash off Hawaii|date=20 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref> and the Marine Corps officially will declare them dead on 20 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hawaii-marines-crash-idUSKCN0V00A7|title=Twelve Marines declared dead after helicopter crash off Hawaii|date=22 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;15 January\n* A late-evening U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle-launched [[air-to-ground missile]] strike kills three suspected [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members as they drive in a car in Yemen's [[Shabwa Governorate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-drone-idUSKCN0UU0TI|title=Drone strike kills three suspected militants in Yemen|date=16 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully fires the engines of the first stage of [[Falcon 9]] rocket it had used to launch a satellite into orbit and then landed successfully on land in [[2015 in aviation#December|December 2015]], the first time in a history a rocket stage had made a soft, controlled landing. The firing of the engines demonstrates the feasibility of reusing the rocket stage, an important step in the development of reusable rockets that make space launches less expensive.<ref name=\"davenport20160117\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/01/17/elon-musks-spacex-to-attempt-another-rocket-landing-this-time-with-a-twist/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX successfully launches rocket but falls short on landing at sea}}</ref>\n\n;16 January\n* Speaking at the conclusion of a missile exercise at [[Skwierzyna]], [[Poland]], involving U.S. and Polish military forces, Polish [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Minister of National Defense]] [[Antoni Macierewicz]] says that the [[Government of Poland]] wants a permanent presence of [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) and U.S. military forces in Poland, including [[MIM-104 Patriot]] [[surface-to-air missile]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5339b118be984e89a6110505056996d3/polands-defense-chief-we-want-constant-nato-us-presence|title=Anonymous \"Poland's defense chief: We want constant NATO, US presence,\" Associated Press, January 16, 2016, 12:35 PM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;17 January\n* After successfully launching the [[Jason-3]] satellite into orbit from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] in [[California]], the first stage of a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket touches down on a landing platform in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|200|mi|km}} off California softly enough to land successfully, but topples over when of its landing legs fails to lock in place and collapses. It is SpaceX's third attempt to land a Falcon 9 first stage at sea; the two previous attempts, both in [[2015 in aviation|2015]], also had been unsuccessful, although SpaceX had made history's first successful landing of a reusable rocket stage \u2013 also of a Falcon 9 \u2013 on land in December 2015.<ref name=\"davenport20160117\" />\n* Just before midnight, aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike a police facility in Sana'a, Yemen, used by both security forces and the [[Houthi]] rebels as an assembly point, killing 26 people and injuring 15. The dead and wounded are all policemen and Houthi rebels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-01-18/airstrike-targets-police-facility-in-yemens-capital|title=al-Haj, Ahmed, \"Airstrike by Saudi-led coalition hits building used by police in Yemeni capital, killing at least 26,\" Associated Press, January 18, 2016, 2:49 p.m..}}</ref>\n\n;21 January\n* An air strike by the Saudi-led coalition against a rebel-held facility at [[Ras Isa]] on Yemen's [[Red Sea]] coast used to load [[tanker truck]]s with refined petroleum products for distribution in rebel-held areas of Yemen destroys trucks and starts a large fire, killing at least nine and perhaps as many as 16 people and injuring at least 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-oil-idUSKCN0UZ2NP|title=Yemen oil port fire from Saudi-led air strike kills at least nine|date=22 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;22 January\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike targets across Yemen, killing dozens of people. Houthi rebels in [[Saada Governorate]] report that the strikes kill 26 people in [[Dahyan]], including the driver of a [[Doctors Without Borders]] ambulance. Strikes against rebel weapon depots on the mountain of [[Nahdeen]] kill another 22 people, and strikes in [[Hodeida]] targeting trucks carrying smugged oil from the port there to rebel forces kill another 10 people. Strikes also target gatherings of Houthis and rebel [[Yemeni Army]] units allied with them in [[Al Jawf Governorate]], [[Dhamar, Yemen|Dhamar]], ad [[Taiz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/22/saudi-led-airstrikes-kill-dozens-in-yemen.html|title=Saudi-led airstrikes kill dozens in Yemen}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] announces that after the 2016 season it will end its support of the use of [[ultralight aircraft]] to lead [[whooping crane]]s on their migration from [[Wisconsin]] to the [[Florida Gulf Coast]] each autumn in [[Operation Migration]]. A conclusion by experts in whooping crane [[biology]] that human intervention such as ultralight flights impairs the ability of the cranes to learn the parenting skills necessary to raise chicks in the wild prompts the decision to end support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/24/feds-to-end-whooping-crane-wisconsin-florida-migration-support.html|title=Whooping crane migration program ending}}</ref>\n\n;26 January\n\n* The [[United States Department of the Treasury]] announces the lifting of major U.S. trade and travel restrictions on [[Cuba]]. The new regulations allow [[Codeshare agreement|code sharing]] between U.S. and Cuban airlines, airplane-leasing deals in the United States for Cuba, and permission for U.S. airline crews to travel to Cuba.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-opens-greater-channels-for-trade-air-links-with-cuba/2016/01/26/a36e13f2-c437-11e5-9693-933a4d31bcc8_story.html|title=U.S. opens greater channels for trade, air links with Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;28 January\n* [[Iran]] agrees to buy 118 airliners \u2013 73 [[Wide-body aircraft|wide-body]] and 45 [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrow-body]] \u2013 from [[Airbus]] in a deal worth [[USD|$]]27,000,000,000. The purchase consists of 12 [[Airbus A380|A380]], 16 [[Airbus A350-1000|A350-1000]], 45 [[Airbus A330|A330]], and 45 [[Airbus A320 family|A320-family]] aircraft. The deal is contingent on Airbus receiving export licenses from the [[United States]], where 10 percent of parts for Airbus aircraft are manufactured. Iran, which first plans to focus on expansion of its airports and more urgent [[civil aviation]] needs, does not plan to take delivery of the airliners until ca. 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-europe-airbus-idUSKCN0V62D6|title=Airbus signs Iran deal for 118 planes worth $27 billion|date=28 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n\n;1 February\n* Two evening airstrikes by U.S. aircraft operating as part of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) intervention in [[Afghanistan]] level the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] \"Voice of the Caliphate\" radio station, knocking it off the air during its nightly illegal propaganda broadcast from [[Nangarhar Province]]'s [[Achin District]]. The strikes combined with [[Afghan Army]] ground operations kill 29 Islamic State supporters, including eight who worked for the radio station and an associated [[Internet]] operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/02/us-airstrikes-destroy-isis-voice-caliphate-radio-station-in-afghanistan.html|title=US airstrikes destroy ISIS' 'Voice of the Caliphate' radio station in Afghanistan|date=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Nato-strikes-Islamic-State-radio-station-in-Afghanistan/articleshow/50824638.cms|title=Nato strikes Islamic State radio station in Afghanistan|work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n;2 February\n* [[Daallo Airlines Flight 159]], an [[Airbus A321-100]] (registration SX-BHS) with 81 people on board flying from [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]], to [[Djibouti City]], [[Djibouti]], experiences an explosion which sets one passenger on fire and blows a hole in the fuselage, through which the burning passenger is sucked from the plane at an altitude of {{convert|14000|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}. The airliner returns to Mogadishu and lands safely. The burned body of the man sucked from the plane is found near [[Balad, Somalia|Balad]], Somalia; two other people on board the plane suffer minor injuries.\n\n;7 February\n* A strike by unidentified aircraft hits a medical technology college in [[Derna, Libya|Derna]], [[Libya]], killing four people. The area is held by a coalition of [[Islamic militant]] groups who have been defending it from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/02/07/world/middleeast/ap-ml-libya.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrike Hits College in Eastern Libyan City, Killing 4,\" Associated Press, February 7, 2016, 10:39 a.m. EST.}}</ref>\n\n;8 February\n* [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Justin Trudeau]] announces that [[Canada]] will withdraw its six [[CF-18 Hornet]]s from bombing missions against the Islamic State within two weeks, but will extend its non-combat air support to the U.S.-led air campaign against the Islamic State until 31 March 2017, using one [[CC-150 Polaris]] [[aerial refueling]] aircraft and up to two [[CP-140 Aurora]] reconnaissance planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/canada-pull-jets-syria-iraq-weeks-160209042506120.html|title=Canada to end ISIL air strikes within weeks}}</ref>\n* A panel of the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] proposes history's first worldwide standards for [[carbon dioxide]] emissions for aircraft; the standards would apply to all new aircraft designs beginning in 2020 and to all newly delivered aircraft beginning in 2023. Environmental groups criticize the standard for not addressing emissions by existing aircraft or new aircraft designed before 2020 or delivered before 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/02/08/u-n-group-proposes-airline-emissions-cuts-but-environmentalists-say-its-not-enough/|title=U.N. panel proposes historic cuts to aircraft emissions \u2013 but environmentalists say it\u2019s not enough}}</ref>\n\n;10 February\n\n* During a flight from [[Punta Cana]] in the [[Dominican Republic]] to [[Moscow]] with 355 passengers on board, an [[Orenair]] [[Boeing 777-200]] (registration VP-BHB) experiences an engine failure and smoke in the cabin.<ref name=\"tah\">{{cite web | url =http://avherald.com/h?article=493c6485|title=Incident: Orenair B772 at Punta Cana on Feb 10th 2016, engine shut down in flight, burst tyre and smoke on landing|work=The Aviation Herald| date=11 February 2016| accessdate =12 February 2016}}</ref> The crew shuts down the malfunctioning engine, the smoke ceases, and the aircraft performs an [[emergency landing]] in Punta Cana during which a tire bursts and sparks appear.<ref name=\"tah\"/> The passengers and crew evacuate via [[evacuation slide]]s with no injuries.<ref name=\"tah\"/>\n* The president of the [[National Air Traffic Controllers Association]] (NATCA), Paul Rinaldi, tells the [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]] that NATCA supports a [[United States House]] bill that would create a federally chartered corporation to operate the [[air traffic control]] system in the [[United States]] and transfer 38,000 U.S. federal government workers, including 14,000 NATCA air traffic controllers who work for the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]], to the new corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/air-traffic-controllers-ready-to-break-away-from-faa/2016/02/10/12e6b14e-cf5a-11e5-b2bc-988409ee911b_story.html|title=Air traffic controllers ready to break away from FAA}}</ref>\n\n;15 February\n\n* Villagers and rebel forces in southwestern [[Somalia]] claim that a U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) has crashed in a village there. The United States responds that all of its UAVs have returned safely from their missions and are accounted for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/9f4e5402136c44c7a37e94d3ba73af8c/somalia-residents-say-us-drone-crashes-rebel-held-village|title=Guled, Abdi, \"US denies reports that 1 of its drones crashed in Somalia,\" Associated Press, February 15, 2016, 11:28 AM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;17\u201318 February\n* [[Turkish Air Force]] jets bomb Kurdish camps in northern [[Iraq]] hours after a suicide car bomb killed 28 people in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]], on 17 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/turkish-air-strikes-pkk_us_56c59113e4b0c3c55053d26f|title=Turkish Air Strikes Hit PKK Camps in Northern Iraq After Ankara Bombing|last=Reuters|date=18 February 2016|via=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\n;18 February\n* The [[United States Government]] grants [[Boeing]] a license allowing the company to enter into talks with airlines in [[Iran]] about sales of airliners. Iran's aging airliner fleet and lack of [[Boeing 777]]s raises the possibility of significant sales for Boeing, although the company will require additional approval from the [[United States Government]] ensuring the legitimacy of any transactions before actually selling Iran any aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/boeing-to-enter-talks-with-iranian-airlines/2016/02/19/59c65f00-d73f-11e5-9823-02b905009f99_story.html|title=Boeing to enter talks with Iranian airlines}}</ref>\n\n;19 February\n* Flying from bases in the [[United Kingdom]], [[United States Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]]s strike an Islamic State camp on the outskirts of [[Sabratha]], [[Libya]], killing Islamic State leader [[Noureddine Chouchane]] and 48 other Islamic State personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/reports-airstrikes-target-suspected-islamic-state-base-in-libya/2016/02/19/e622c12a-d6f7-11e5-be55-2cc3c1e4b76b_story.html|title=U.S. strike on Libya camp escalates campaign against Islamic State}}</ref><ref name=\"gibbonsneff201603037\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/07/u-s-drone-strike-kills-more-than-150-in-somalia/|title=U.S. airstrike kills more than 150 at Somalia terrorist camp, military says}}</ref>\n* In a ceremony in a [[hangar]] in [[Mojave, California|Mojave]], [[California]], Sir [[Richard Branson]] unveils [[Virgin Galactic]]'s new [[VSS Unity|VSS ''Unity'']], a [[SpaceShipTwo]]-class rocket-powered [[Sub-orbital spaceflight|suborbital]] [[spaceplane]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/02/19/richard-bransons-virgin-galactic-unveils-new-spacecraft/|title=Richard Branson\u2019s Virgin Galactic unveils new spacecraft 'Unity'}}</ref>\n\n;20 February\n* The [[Government of Serbia]] claims that the 19 February U.S. airstrike in Sabratha, Libya, killed two [[Serbia]]n diplomats. The [[United States Department of Defense]] responds that it does not believe the Serbians were at the targeted location during the airstrike and that the condition of their bodies is inconsistent with death in the airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/02/24/serbia-says-a-u-s-strike-in-libya-killed-two-of-its-diplomats-heres-why-the-pentagon-disagrees/|title=Serbia says a U.S. strike in Libya killed two of its diplomats; here\u2019s why the Pentagon thinks it didn\u2019t}}</ref>\n\n;21 February\n* British [[Royal Navy]] [[test pilot]] [[Eric Brown (pilot)|Eric \"Winkle\" Brown]] dies at the age of 97 at [[East Surrey Hospital]] in [[Redhill, Surrey|Redhill]], [[England]]. Surviving 11 plane crashes and the 1941 sinking of the [[escort aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Audacity|D10}}, he is credited with flying 487 different types of aircraft, more than anyone else in history, and with making 2,407 [[aircraft carrier]] landings, also a world record, as well as with making the first carrier landing in history, landing a [[de Havilland Sea Vampire]] aboard {{HMS|Ocean|R68}} in [[1945 in aviation|1945]]. Although he had retired in [[1970 in aviation|1970]], he had continued flying until [[1994 in aviation|1994]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-35626854|title=Eric 'Winkle' Brown: Celebrated British pilot dies, aged 97|date=21 February 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/eric-brown-unflappable-british-test-pilot-who-set-world-records-dies-at-97/2016/02/22/059d7a26-d974-11e5-925f-1d10062cc82d_story.html|title=Eric Brown, unflappable British test pilot who set world records, dies at 97}}</ref>\n\n;22 February\n\n* Russia requests permission to fly surveillance flights over the United States under the [[Treaty on Open Skies]] using [[Tupolev Tu-154]] (NATO reporting name \"Careless\") aircraft equipped with new, high-powered [[digital camera]]s. The request prompts a debate within the United States Government over whether it is a small concession worth making in order to keep the treaty viable or a violation of the spirit of the treaty that would allow surveillance unintended when the treaty was signed in 1992. The treaty, signed by 34 countries, has been in force since [[2002 in aviation|2002]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/23/world/europe/russia-wants-closer-look-from-above-the-us.html|title=Russia Wants Closer Look From Above the U.S.|first1=Eric|last1=Schmitt|first2=Michael R.|last2=Gordon|date=22 February 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 February\n* [[Tara Air Flight 193]], a [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter]] on a domestic flight in [[Nepal]] from [[Pokhara Airport]] in [[Pokhara]] to [[Jomsom Airport]] in [[Jomsom]], crashes and burns near [[Dana, Nepal|Dana]] in [[Myagdi District]] ten minutes after takeoff, killing all 23 people on board.\n\n;25 February\n* In the morning, [[Turkish Army]] [[Bell AH-1 Cobra]] attack helicopters attack a group of [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] personnel as they travel through a mountainous area near the [[\u0130dil]] district of Turkey's [[\u015e\u0131rnak Province]], killing nine of them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-military-helicopt/2544894.html|title=Tattersall, Nick, \"Turkish military helicopters kill nine in strikes on PKK targets,\" Reuters, 24 February 2016, 19:20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225103457/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-military-helicopt/2544894.html|archivedate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n* In the evening, Turkish Air Force jets based at [[Diyarbakir]], Turkey, strike Kurdistan Workers Party logistical centers, ammunition depots, and shelters in northern Iraq,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-warplanes-strike/2546502.html|title=Cakan, Seyhmus, \"Turkish warplanes strike PKK targets in northern Iraq \u2013 sources,\" Reuters, 25 February 2016, 03:35|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304141519/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-warplanes-strike/2546502.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;26 February\n* An [[Air Kasthamandap]] [[PAC 750XL]] (registration 9N-AJB) with 11 people on board [[2016 Air Kasthamandap crash|crash-lands]] at [[Chilkhaya]], [[Nepal]], killing both crew members and injuring all nine passengers.\n* An [[Azur Air]] [[Boeing 767-300]] makes a safe emergency landing in [[Tashkent]], [[Uzbekistan]], during a flight from [[Moscow]] to [[Phuket (city)|Phuket]], [[Thailand]], after an indicator shows low engine oil pressure.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://ria.ru/incidents/20160226/1380664212.html|title=\u0421\u041a \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0438 Boeing \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0448\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0435|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]| language=Russian|date=26 February 2016| accessdate =26 February 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'', grounded at [[Kalaeloa Airport]] in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalealoa]], [[Hawaii]], since [[2015 in aviation#July|3 July 2015]] due to battery damage caused by overheating during its attempt to become the first manned [[solar-powered aircraft]] to circumnavigate the Earth, makes it first test flight after repairs. Taking off from Kalealoa Airport, ''Solar Impulse 2'' flies over the [[Pacific Ocean]] for 90 minutes, reaching an altitude of {{convert|8000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} before returning. The [[Solar Impulse]] team plans to resume the [[circumnavigation]] in late [[2016 in aviation#April|April 2016]] with a flight from Hawaii to [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/solar-impulse-2-returns/42077/|title=Refurbished Solar Impulse 2 returns to the skies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manufacturing.net/news/2016/03/solar-impulse-2-undergoes-successful-test-flight|title=Solar Impulse 2 Undergoes Successful Test Flight|date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;27 February\n* Airstrikes attributed to the Saudi-led coalition targeting advancing rebel forces hit a market area in the [[Nehm]] region outside [[Sana'a]], [[Yemen]], killing at least 30 people and injuring at least 30 more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-35678326|title=Yemen conflict: air strike on market 'kills 30 people'|date=27 February 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;29 February\n* An American tourist turns over to authorities in [[Mozambique]] what appears to be part of the skin of a [[Boeing 777]] [[horizontal stabilizer]] found over the preceding weekend on a [[sandbar]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] just off the country's coast, raising expectations that it will turn out to be debris from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a Boeing 777 missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|8 March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/02/us/mh370-possible-debris-found/index.html|title=MH370: Likely piece of doomed plane found|author1=Rene Marsh |author2=Don Melvin|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* In the United States, the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA) announces that it has awarded a $20 million contract to [[Lockheed Martin]] to develop a quiet supersonic demonstration passenger aircraft using [[Quiet Supersonic Technology]] (QueSST). NASA hopes that the new technology, which allows aircraft flying at supersonic speeds to make only a soft thump instead of a loud and damaging [[sonic boom]], will prompt the development of a new generation of \"low-boom\" [[supersonic transport]]s that can fly over populated areas at supersonic speeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/29/us/nasa-quiet-supersonic-jet-contract-announced/index.html|title=NASA says it will build quiet supersonic passenger jet|first=Thom |last=Patterson|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* The United States has conducted 135 airstrikes in Yemen since its air campaign there began, five of them since 1 January. The strikes have killed more that 650 [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] personnel and 105 civilians.<ref name=\"gibbonsneff20160322\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/22/u-s-targets-al-qaeda-in-yemen-airstrike-that-kills-dozens-pentagon-says/|title=U.S. targets al-Qaeda in Yemen airstrike that kills dozens, Pentagon says}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n;3 March\n* A man finds a 40-by-40-centimeter (about 15.5-by-15.5-inch) square-shaped piece of debris with a blue border on a beach on [[R\u00e9union]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] in almost the same place he found a [[flaperon]] from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]] in [[2015 in aviation#July|July 2015]]. He turns it in to authorities the following day, raising hopes that it is also from Flight 370, missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|8 March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-malaysia-airlines-flight-370-part-20160306-story.html|title=Man who found MH370 flight part finds new item on La Reunion island|first=Tribune news|last=services}}</ref>\n\n;4 March\n\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully launches a [[satellite]] payload into space using an upgraded [[Falcon 9]] rocket, but its attempt to land the rocket's first stage on a floating platform \u2013 termed an \"autonomous space port droneship\" by SpaceX founder [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 is only partially successful: although the first stage lands on the platform, the landing is too hard for a successful recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/03/04/after-a-series-of-delays-spacex-launches-upgraded-falcon-9-rocket/|title=After a series of delays, SpaceX launches upgraded Falcon 9 rocket}}</ref>\n* The U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) responds to the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s (FAA) [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]] rejection of the NTSB's [[2014 in aviation#April|April 2014]] recommendation that the FAA establish licensing requirements and safety standards for commercial [[Balloon (aircraft)|balloon]] tour operators and make them subject to FAA safety inspections, regulating them in a manner similar to the way it regulates commercial airplane and helicopter tour operators. In its response, the NTSB informs the FAA that it finds the rejection unacceptable and that its recommendation remains open.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2016/07/30/least-16-people-died-hot-air-balloon-crash-texas-sheriff-says/87773736/|title=At least 16 dead in hot air balloon crash in Texas}}</ref><ref name=\"staging.hosted.ap.org\">{{cite web|url=http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_HOT_AIR_BALLOON_CRASH_TEXAS?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-07-30-22-15-19|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/safety/safety-recs/recletters/A-14-011-012.pdf|title=National Transportation Board Safety Recommendation April 7, 2014.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.recsearch/Recommendation.aspx?Rec=A-14-011|title=Safety Recommendation A-14-011}}</ref>\n\n;5 March\n* A series of U.S. airstrikes by manned aircraft and unmanned aerial vehicles against an [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] training camp in [[Raso, Somalia|Raso]], [[Somalia]], kills over 150 Al-Shabaab personnel.<ref name=\"gibbonsneff201603037\"/>\n\n;7 March\n\n* [[African Parks Network]] announces that the remains of its employee, American anti-[[poaching]] pilot Bill Fitzpatrick, have been recovered from a crash site in [[Cameroon]]. Fiztpatrick had disappeared on 22 June 2014 during a flight to a job in [[Odzala-Kokoua National Park]] in the [[Republic of the Congo]]. Local residents had discovered the wreckage of Fitzpatrick's plane in April 2015, but the remote site and dense vegetation in the area had made it difficult for helicopters to land there and bureaucratic procedures of the [[Government of Cameroon]] also had delayed the recovery of Fitzpatrick's remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/fea7c73dab954f5dba2b66c1bf3acd98/american-pilots-remains-recovered-cameroon-crash-site|title=Anonymous, \"American pilot's remains recovered from Cameroon crash site,\" Associated Press, March 7, 2016, 11:25 AM EST.|access-date=8 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308121549/http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/fea7c73dab954f5dba2b66c1bf3acd98/american-pilots-remains-recovered-cameroon-crash-site|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Boeing]] announces that it has filed a [[patent]] for a self-cleaning [[airplane lavatory]] which can sanitize itself in three seconds using [[far-ultraviolet]] light. The lavatory also features a hands-free faucet, soap dispenser, trash flap, toilet lid, [[toilet seat]], and hand dryer, and Boeing reports that it also is designing a hands-free door latch and is studying the design of a hands-free system to lift and close the toilet seat so that all surfaces are exposed to the far-ultraviolet light during the cleaning cycle. Once Boeing offers the new lavatories to customers, it is expected to take years for airlines to update their fleets with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2016/03/07/boeing-designs-self-cleaning-plane-bathrooms/|title=Boeing designs self-cleaning plane bathrooms|date=7 March 2016|access-date=8 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308085444/http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2016/03/07/boeing-designs-self-cleaning-plane-bathrooms/|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;8 March\n* U.S. [[Special Operations Forces]] conduct a joint U.S.-Somali helicopter raid against al-Shabaab in Somalia. The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that U.S. forces play only an advisory role and do not accompany the Somali forces on the raid, although the helicopters employed are U.S. military helicopters flown by U.S. crews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/09/u-s-special-operations-forces-conduct-helicopter-raid-in-somalia/|title=U.S. Special Operations forces conduct helicopter raid in Somalia}}</ref>\n\n;9 March\n* A [[True Aviation]] [[Antonov An-26]] cargo plane (registration S2-AGZ) carrying a cargo of [[shrimp]] suffers the failure of an engine shortly after takeoff from [[Cox's Bazar Airport]] in [[Cox's Bazar]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[2016 True Aviation An-26 crash|crashes]] into the [[Bay of Bengal]] five minutes after takeoff while attempting to return to the airport, killing three of the four people on board and critically injuring the only survivor.\n* [[Amazon.com]] announces that it has agreed to lease 20 [[Boeing 767-300]] cargo aircraft from [[Air Transport Services Group]] as a first step toward operating its own fleet of planes, part of a larger effort to reduce its shipping costs and its reliance on [[FedEx]] and the [[United Parcel Service]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-finds-air-freight-partner-1457538676 Bensinger, Greg, \"Amazon Finds Air Freight Partner,\" ''Wall Street journal'', 9 March 2016, 8:33 p.m. EST.]</ref>\n\n;12 March\n* A South African family announces that it contacted aviation authorities in [[South Africa]] during the previous week to report a piece of debris their teenaged son had found on a beach in [[Mozambique]] on [[2015 in aviation#December|30 December 2015]] which they had taken home to South Africa. Aviation officials plan to examine it to see if it is from Malaysian Airlines Flight 370.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/11/africa/mh370-mozambique-possible-debris/index.html|title=MH370: 2nd possible debris piece found in Mozambique|author1=Steve Almasy |author2=Faith Karimi |author3=Radina Gigova|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* In response to a rocket attack on [[Israel]] from the [[Gaza Strip]] the previous evening, the [[Israeli Air Force]] conducts airstrikes against four [[Hamas]] sites in the Gaza Strip. In one of the aistrikes, an [[air-to-ground missile]] strikes a family home on the perimeter of one of the sites, killing two [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israel-retaliates-for-gaza-rocket-fire-with-air-strikes-hamas-hacks-israel-tv/2016/03/13/0214541e-f9ee-48e0-8402-39fc4838b65c_story.html|title=Israel retaliates for Gaza rocket fire with airstrikes; Hamas hacks Israeli TV}}</ref>\n\n;13 March\n* As a result of the accident investigation into the [[2015 in aviation#March|25 March 2015]] crash of [[Germanwings Flight 9525]], French aviation authorities call for stricter international monitoring of the mental health of pilots as well as guidelines under which doctors would be required to report pilots whose psychological condition might put flight safety at risk. In their report, the French also urge German authorities to limit the legal penalties imposed on doctors who breach patient confidentiality in good faith in order to report psychological problems among pilots and to clearly define the types of health issues in airline pilots that can represent an \"imminent danger\" to flight safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/14/world/europe/germanwings-crash-inquiry-urges-stricter-oversight-of-pilots-mental-health.html|title=Germanwings Crash Inquiry Urges Stricter Oversight of Pilots' Mental Health|first=Nicola|last=Clark|date=13 March 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;14 March\n* In response to a suicide car bomb explosion in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]], that killed at least 37 people the previous day, [[Turkish Air Force]] jets strike at least 18 [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] positions in northern [[Iraq]], including ammunition depots, bunkers, and shelters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkish-warplanes-strike-kurdish-militant-bases-after-deadly-ankara-attack/2016/03/14/1272f05e-e9d3-11e5-a6f3-21ccdbc5f74e_story.html|title=Turkish warplanes strike Kurdish militant bases after deadly Ankara attack}}</ref>\n\n;15 March\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition conduct two airstrikes on a busy market in [[MAstaba, Yemen|Mastaba]] in [[Yemen]]'s [[Hajja Governorate]], killing at least 119 people and wounding 47.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/urn:publicid:ap.org:eb6ab6b0c6f2452b93910735c981d0fc|title= Al-Haj, Ahmed, \"Witnesses: Warplanes bomb Yemeni market, killing dozens\", Associated Press, March 15, 2016, 3:03 PM EDT.}}</ref><ref name=\"AP20160317\">{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/66550de27e1a44e0b6ba3a95cb2901e7/un-yemen-says-death-toll-tuesdays-strike-now-119|title=Al-Haj, Ahmed, and Maggie Michael, \"Saudi to scale down Yemen campaign; strike death toll rises,\" Associated Press, March 17, 2016, 12:03 p.m. EDT.}}</ref>\n* An [[Ecuadorian Air Force]] [[IAI Arava]] carrying 22 members of the [[Ecuadorian Army]] for [[parachute]] training and an air force crew of three [[2016 Ecuadorian Air Force Arava crash|crashes]] in Hacienda la Palmira near [[Shell Mera]], [[Ecuador]], killing all on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35818100|title=Ecuador army plane crashes in Amazon region killing 22 \u2013 BBC News|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/15/americas/ecuador-plane-crash/index.html|title=Ecuador plane crash kills 22|website=CNN|access-date=2016-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brecorder.com/world/south-america/285314-ecuador-army-plane-crash-kills-all-22-aboard-president.html|title=Ecuador army plane crash kills all 22 aboard: president|website=Business Recorder|access-date=2016-03-17}}</ref><ref name=Flight>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160315-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident IAI Arava 201 E-206 Hacienda la Palmira, Pastaza|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2016-03-16}}</ref>\n\n;16 March\n* New [[United States Department of the Treasury]] regulations go into effect that among other things allow increased travel to [[Cuba]] by American citizens and allow U.S. airlines to open offices in Cuba. The changes are expected to improve the market for commercial air travel between the [[United States]] and Cuba.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/treasury-eases-restrictions-on-travel-to-cuba/2016/03/15/10a225ec-eaaf-11e5-b0fd-073d5930a7b7_story.html|title=Treasury eases restrictions on travel, other dealings with Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;17 March\n* [[Saudi Arabia]] announces that its military coalition will scale back its operations against [[Houthi]] rebels in Yemen \u2013 maintaining only \"small\" teams of coalition forces on the ground to advise, train, and equip Yemeni forces \u2013 but will continue to provide air support to Yemeni forces battling the rebels.<ref name=\"AP20160317\"/>\n* Boasting that Russia's 167-day intervention in Syria saved the regime of Syrian [[President of Syria|President]] [[Basher al-Assad]] from defeat at a coast of only [[USD|$]]480 million, Russian President Vladimir Putin says that Russia could restore its military presence in Syria in a metter of hours if necessary and will maintain a powerful surface-to-air missile force there. He warns that Russia will respond with force if any rebel group breaks the Syrian ceasefire and or any attacks against Russian forces still in Syria occur, and suggests that Russia will intervene militarily in Syria again if it believes the Assad regime is in danger of losing power.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/russia-could-redeploy-to-syria-in-hours-putin-says/2016/03/17/845f8810-ec37-11e5-97c2-e9c9557fa1b0_story.html|title=Russia could redeploy to Syria in hours, Putin says}}</ref>\n\n;19 March\n* [[Flydubai Flight 981]], a [[Boeing 737-800|Boeing 737-8KN]] (registration A6-FDN), aborts two landing attempts in poor visibility at [[Rostov-on-Don Airport]] in [[Rostov-on-Don]] in southern Russia, making a [[go-around]] after each attempt. During its second go-around, it suddenly goes into a rapid descent from an altitude of {{convert|4050|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and crashes, killing all 62 people on board. It is the first fatal accident in [[Flydubai]]'s seven-year history.\n* Unidentified aircraft strike Islamic State-held [[Raqqa]], Syria, killing at least 39 \u2013 and perhaps as many as 43 \u2013 people and reportedly injuring at least 50 others. Different observers report the attacking aircraft as either [[Russian Federation Air Force]] or [[Syrian Air Force]] jets.<ref name=\"mroue20160319\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/airstrikes-on-is-held-syrian-city-kill-wound-dozens/2016/03/19/57776b40-edce-11e5-a9ce-681055c7a05f_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=19 March 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n* Unidentified aircraft strike Islamic State targets in Palmyra, Syria, killing seven Islamic State personnel during a Syrian Arab Army offensive to retake Palmyra.<ref name=\"mroue20160319\"/>\n\n;21 March\n\n* A South African [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] finds a piece of debris on a beach in southern South Africa. The following day, [[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Transport (Malaysia)|Minister of Transport]], [[Liow Tiong Lai]], will announce the discovery and that the debris bears an aircraft engine manufacturer's and logo and will be examined to determine whether it is from the missing Malaysian Airlines Flight 370.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-march-22-2016/2016/03/22/9c62f5dc-f038-11e5-85a6-2132cf446d0a_story.html|title=World Digest: March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 March\n* [[2016 Brussels bombings|Two terrorist bombs detonate]] at [[Brussels Airport]] in [[Zaventem]], [[Belgium]], killing at least 11 people and injuring around 100 others. The airport will remain closed until 3 April, with flights re-routed to nearby cities. A third bomb later explodes at [[Maelbeek/Maalbeek metro station|Maelbeek (or Maalbeek) metro station]] in the [[City of Brussels]], killing another 20 people and injuring another 130. The Islamic State claims responsibility for all three bomb blasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/03/22/471391497/what-we-know-terrorist-bombing-at-brussels-airport|title=Terrorist Bombings Strike Brussels: What We Know}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35876809|title=Brussels attacks: Police hunt Zaventem bombings suspect|date=23 March 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref name=\"touni20160403\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2016-04-03/a-very-small-start-3-flights-to-depart-from-brussels|title=El Touni, Bishr, and Elaine Ganley, \"A Brussels Airlines plane heading to the Portuguese city of Faro took off from Brussels Airport on Sunday, the first passenger flight to leave the airport since suicide bombings on March 22 ripped through its check-in counters,\" usnews.com, April 3, 2016, 11:38 a.m.}}</ref>\n* U.S. aircraft conduct a strike against an [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] training camp in the mountains of Yemen. The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that the attack killed \"dozens\" of the group's personnel.<ref name=gibbonsneff20160322/>\n\n;27 March\n* Suspected U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle strikes hit courtyards in two villages in Yemen with air-to-ground missiles, killing eight al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula members. Later in the day, a U.S. aircraft bombs a former Yemeni government intelligence building in Yemen's [[Abyan Governorate]] that al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula is using as a base, killing 14 members of the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-march-28-2016/2016/03/27/ee819296-f41c-11e5-9804-537defcc3cf6_story.html|title=World Digest: March 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Portuguese [[regional airline]] [[Portug\u00e1lia]] is rebranded as Tap Express.\n\n;27\u201328 March (overnight)\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike rebel targets in the suburbs of [[Aden]], Yemen.<ref name=\"mukhashaf20160328\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-swap-idUSKCN0WU0BX|title=Saudi-led alliance says completes Yemen prisoner swap|date=28 March 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;28 March\n* Unidentified aircraft thought to belong to the Saudi-led coalition strike rebel targets in Yemen's [[Hadhramaut]] region southeast of [[Mukalla]].<ref name=\"mukhashaf20160328\"/>\n\n;29 March\n* A man claiming to be wearing an explosive belt [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacks]] [[EgyptAir Flight 181]] \u2013 an [[Airbus A320-200]] (registration SU-GCB) with 61 other people on board on a domestic flight in [[Egypt]] from [[Alexandria, Egypt|Alexandria]] to [[Cairo]] \u2013 and forces it to fly to [[Larnaca International Airport]] in [[Larnaca]], [[Cyprus]], which is closed to all traffic after the hijacked airliner's arrival. The man is arrested and no one aboard the airliner is harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/egyptair-plane-hijacked/2016/03/29/09dd65ee-f579-11e5-9804-537defcc3cf6_story.html|title=Plane hijacking rekindles concerns about Egyptian airport security}}</ref>\n* A chartered [[Aero Teknic]] [[Mitsubishi MU-2]] flying in bad weather [[2016 Aero Teknic MU-2 crash|crashes]] into the [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]] on approach to [[\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine Airport]] in the [[Magdalen Islands]] in [[Quebec]], [[Canada]], killing all seven people on board. Canadian television commentator and former [[Minister of Transport (Canada)|Minister of Transport]] [[Jean Lapierre]], his wife, two of his brothers, and a sister are among the dead. They had been traveling to Lapierre's father's funeral in eastern Quebec.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/quebec-plane-crash-kills-7-ex-minister-reported-among-dead/ar-BBr5DJw?ocid=ansmsnnews11|title=Lampert, Allison, \"Former Canadian Cabinet minister killed in plane crash,\" Reuters, March 29, 2016.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403035122/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/quebec-plane-crash-kills-7-ex-minister-reported-among-dead/ar-BBr5DJw?ocid=ansmsnnews11|archivedate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;31 March\n* Heavy airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition support the beginning of an offensive by Iraqi military forces to take the city of [[H\u012bt]], [[Iraq]], from the Islamic State. Over the previous week, the coalition has conducted 17 airstrikes against Islamic State targets in the H\u012bt area in preparation for the offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-04-01/trapped-civilians-stall-iraqi-forces-battling-is-in-anbar|title=George, Susannah, \"Iraqi counterterrorism forces slow advance against IS as tens of thousands of civilians trapped in Anbar province,\" Associated Press, April 1, 2016.}}</ref>\n* An airstrike by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle {{convert|20|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Jilib]], [[Somalia]], hits a ground vehicle carrying senior [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] leader and [[al-Qaeda]] member [[Hassan Ali Dhoore]] and two other Al-Shabaab members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/04/01/pentagon-u-s-military-launches-drone-strike-on-al-shabab-leader-in-somalia/|title=Pentagon: U.S. military launches drone strike on al-Shabab leader in Somalia}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n;2 April\n* Since it began in [[2015 in aviation#October|October 2015]], the U.S.-led coalition in [[Operation Tidal Wave II]] has conducted over 200 airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] [[oil well]]s, [[Oil refinery|oil refineries]], [[oil pipeline]]s, and [[tanker truck]]s. Tidal Wave II is intended to degrade the Islamic State's finances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-led-strikes-putting-a-financial-squeeze-on-the-islamic-state/2016/04/02/e739a7be-f848-11e5-a3ce-f06b5ba21f33_story.html|title=U.S.-led strikes putting a financial squeeze on the Islamic State|work=The Washington Post|date=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;3 April\n* The [[Government of Australia]] announces that debris apparently from the interior of [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]] \u2013 a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]] \u2013 found by hotel guests on [[Mauritius]] during the previous week will be examined to ascertain whether or not it is from the missing airliner. It would be the first piece of the debris from the aircraft's interior to be recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/missing-jet/missing-mh370-suspected-debris-found-mauritian-island-be-examined-n549846|title=Missing MH370: Suspected Debris Looks Like 'Inside' of Plane|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n* Supported by [[Russian Federation Air Force]] airstrikes, [[Syrian Arab Army]] troops on the offensive against Islamic State forces retake [[Qaryatain]], [[Syria]].<ref name=\"aji20160404\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-04-04/air-strikes-kill-22-qaida-linked-militants-in-Syria|author=Aji, Albert |title=Syrian troops fire their guns in celebration amid smoldering buildings inside the town of Qaryatain, hours after recapturing it from Islamic State militants who had abducted and terrorized dozens of its Christian residents |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike against a senior [[al-Qaeda]] operational meeting in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] at the headquarters of [[Jund al-Aqsa]], which fights alongside the [[Nusra Front]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]], kills 21 [[Islamic militant]]s, including senior al-Qaeda member [[Abu Firas al-Souri]].<ref name=\"aji20160404\" />\n* On a limited basis, flight operations resume at [[Brussels Airport]] in [[Zaventem]], [[Belgium]], for the first time since the [[2016 Brussels bombings|terrorist bombings there]] on 22 March. Only three flights, all [[Brussels Airlines]] departures, operate from the airport during the day.<ref name=\"touni20160403\" />\n\n;4 April\n* During takeoff from [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport]] in [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]], [[Batik Air Flight 7703]], a [[Boeing 737-800|Boeing 737-8GP(WL)]] (registration PK-LBS) carrying 56 people, collides with a [[TransNusa Air Services]] [[ATR 42-600]] (registration PK-TNJ) being towed to a [[hangar]] with four people on board. The Boeing 737's left [[wing]] slices off the ATR 42's [[vertical stabilizer]] and outer left wing, and the Boeing 737's badly damaged left wing bursts into flames. All aboard both aircraft evacuate safely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Batik Air dan TransNusa Tabrakan di Runway Bandara Halim Perdanakusuma|url=http://news.detik.com/berita/3179649/batik-air-dan-transnusa-tabrakan-di-runway-bandara-halim-perdanakusuma}}</ref>\n* Supported by heavy airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition targeting Islamic State forces and position, [[Iraqi Armed Forces|Iraqi government forces]] enter the city of [[H\u012bt]], [[Iraq]], a week after operations to retake it from the Islamic State began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iraqi-forces-face-heavy-resistance-in-isis-held-town-of-hit/|title=Iraqi forces face heavy resistance in ISIS-held town of Hit|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n* The [[Syrian Arab Army]] releases video revealing that Russian [[Kamov Ka-52]] Alligator (NATO reporting name \"Hokum B\") [[attack helicopter]]s are operating in Syria. The video \u2013 purportedly the first video of the Ka-25 in combat ever made public \u2013 shows Ka-25s firing rockets at Islamic State forces in Syria near Qaryatain.<ref name=\"sputnik20160404\">{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20160404/1037447550/ka-52-syria-action.html|title=WATCH: First Ever Footage of Russia's Ka-52 Helicopters in Action in Syria|last=Sputnik}}</ref><ref name=\"birnbaum20160412\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/weeks-after-pullout-from-syria-russian-military-is-as-busy-as-ever/2016/04/11/d150a004-fd77-11e5-a569-2c9e819c14e4_story.html|title=Weeks after 'pullout' from Syria, Russian military is as busy as ever}}</ref>\n* A [[Bell 206]] sightseeing helicopter crashes in the [[Smoky Mountains]] near [[Sevierville, Tennessee|Sevierville]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]], killing all five people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b0b077feeb19447c880b951a180393f8/5-killed-tourist-helicopter-crash-smoky-mountains|title=5 killed in tourist helicopter crash in Smoky Mountains}}</ref>\n* [[Alaska Air]] agrees to buy [[Virgin America]] for [[USD|$]]2,600,000,000; including debt and aircraft leases, the deal is worth about $4,000,000,000. The combined airline will have 1,200 daily departures and [[Airline hub|hubs]] in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], [[Alaska]]; [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]; [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]. Virgin America had operated since [[2007 in aviation|2007]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/04/04/investing/virgin-america-alaska-air-deal/index.html|title=Alaska Air buys Virgin America for $2.6 billion|first=Ivana Kottasova and Jackie|last=Wattles|date=4 April 2016|publisher=CNN Money}}</ref>\n\n;5 April\n* Traveling from his sanctuary in [[Turkey]] to mediate a dispute between the [[Nusra Front]] and other [[Islamist]] groups in Syria, [[Al-Qaeda]] leader [[Ahmed Refai Taha]] is killed by an [[air-to-ground missile]] fired by a U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] when his car stops for fuel near [[Idlib]], Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/double-game-even-as-it-battles-isis-turkey-gives-other-extremists-shelter/2016/07/10/8d6ce040-4053-11e6-a66f-aa6c1883b6b1_story.html|title=Double game? Even as it battles ISIS, Turkey gives other extremists shelter|work=The Washington Post|date=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n* A [[surface-to-air-missile]] fired from rebel-held territory in Syria near [[Aleppo]] shoots down a [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] reconnaissance plane. Its pilot ejects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/rebel-fighters-down-aircraft-near-syrian-battle-front-activists-say/2016/04/05/921de55c-fa9a-11e5-813a-90ab563f0dde_story.html|title=Suspected Islamist militants down Syrian aircraft near Aleppo battle front|work=The Washington Post|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Morecambe Bay Community Primary School]] in [[Morecambe]], [[England]], launches a [[helium balloon]] carrying a toy stuffed dog named Sam, a [[GoPro]] camera, and a [[GPS navigation device]] from the grounds of a hotel in Morecambe as part of a school science project. Ascending at {{convert|6|m|ft|abbr=off}} per second, the balloon reaches an altitude of {{convert|15|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} without incident, but bursts during its descent and plummets to the ground, landing in a field in [[Burnley]], {{convert|30|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from its launch site, where the camera and GPS device are recovered. Sam is missing from the wreckage, prompting a search for the stuffed animal within a radius of {{convert|40|to|50|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} of the landing site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/find-sam-toy-dog-missing-space-morecambe-bay-burnley-a6973641.html|title=A group of schoolchildren have managed to launch a toy dog into space|date=7 April 2016|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n;6 April\n* A panel commissioned by the [[United States Government]] recommends that the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] lift its ban on [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs, or \"drones\") flying over people and issue new regulations that require only that UAVs fly no lower than {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} above people and come no closer to people than {{convert|10|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} while taking off or landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/ready-for-a-spy-in-the-sky-panel-says-faa-should-expand-commercial-drone-flights/2016/04/06/cd649ef0-fc0a-11e5-9140-e61d062438bb_story.html|title=Ready for a spy in the sky? Panel says FAA should expand commercial drone flights.|work=The Washington Post|date=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;7 April\n* Two hours into a flight to search for a [[skiff]] missing in the [[Pacific Ocean]] with three men aboard, the crew of a [[United States Navy]] [[P-8A Poseidon]] patrol plane spots the word \"HELP\" spelled out on a beach on uninhabited [[Fanadik Island]] in the [[Federated States of Micronesia]]. It was created by the three men, who soon are rescued by a small boat from the island of [[Pulap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/04/09/navy-rescues-3-castaways-who-wrote-help-with-palm-fronds-on-deserted-island.html|title=Navy rescues 3 castaways who wrote 'help' with palm fronds on deserted island|date=9 April 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n;8 April\n* After several unsuccessful attempts, [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform \u2013 which SpaceX refers to as an \"autonomous spaceport drone ship\" \u2013 floating in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] after a launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]]. The landing occurs nine minutes after liftoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/04/08/elon-musks-spacex-nails-landing-at-sea/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX nails landing at sea|work=The Washington Post |date=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Jetpack International vice president Nick Macomber crashes headfirst into the ground during a routine test flight of a [[jet pack]] he is flying in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], falling {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} to the ground after the jet pack malfunctions. He is injured, but is released from a hospital the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdvr.com/2016/04/08/jet-pack-crash-lands-pilot-in-burn-center/|title=Jet pack pilot released from hospital after crash|date=8 April 2016|publisher=KDVR}}</ref>\n\n;10 April\n* Unidentified aircraft conduct airstrikes around [[Raqqa]], Syria, killing dozens of Islamic State personnel and civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17b151c625b244c0b760bdb4ffc8f8c8/islamic-state-launches-syria-offensive-captures-2-villages|title=Syrian cease-fire strained by new clashes ahead of talks|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n\n;11 April\n* Two Russian [[Sukhoi Su-24]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Fencer\") jets make numerous low-level passes in close proximity to the [[United States Navy]] [[guided-missile destroyer]] {{USS|Donald Cook|DDG-75}} while the ship is conducting deck landing drills with an allied military helicopter in the [[Baltic Sea]], forcing ''Donald Cook'' to suspend flight operations until the Su-24s leave the area. The ship's [[commanding officer]] criticizes one of the passes, made while the helicopter is refueling on ''Donald Cook'''s [[flight deck]], as unsafe.<ref name=eucom20160413>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/News-Article-View/Article/720536/navy-ship-encounters-aggressive-russian-aircraft-in-baltic-sea|title=Navy Ship Encounters Aggressive Russian Aircraft in Baltic Sea|publisher=U.S. Department of Defense}}</ref>\n\n;12 April\n* A Russian [[Mil Mi-28]]N (NATO reporting name \"Havoc\") [[attack helicopter]] crashes in Syria, killing its two-man crew. The Russian [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Ministry of Defense]] announces that the helicopter was not shot down and blames the crash on bad weather. The increasing number of reports of Russian helicopter operations in Syria since late March have led [[Western world|Western]] military analysts to conclude that Russia's supposed withdrawal of its military aviation forces from Syria in [[2014 in aviation#March|mid-March]] was in reality merely the replacement of some Russian Federation Air Force jets there with attack helicopters more suitable to the support of [[Syrian Arab Army]] ground operations against rebel forces.<ref name=\"birnbaum20160412\" />\n* Russian aircraft fly in close proximity to the U.S. Navy guided-missile destroyer USS ''Donald Cook'' (DDG-75) in the Baltic Sea for a second straight day. First, a [[Kamov Ka-27]] (NATO reporting name \"Helix\") helicopter makes seven low circles around ''Donald Cook'' (DDG-75) in what the ship's commanding officer criticizes as an \"unprofessional\" manner. Forty minutes later, two Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") jets make 11 close-range, low-level passes which ''Donald Cook'''s crew assesses as fitting a simulated attack profile.<ref name=eucom20160413 />\n\n;13 April\n* A [[Sunbird Aviation]] [[Britten-Norman BN-2T Turbine Islander]] [[2016 Sunbird Aviation crash|crashes]] {{convert|1|km|mi|abbr=on}} short of the runway at [[Kiunga, Papua New Guinea|Kiunga]], [[Papua New Guinea]], killing all 12 people on board.\n\n;14 April\n* [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Ashton Carter]] announces that the United States will begin to send combat aircraft to the [[Philippines]] on regular and more frequent rotations and will conduct more air patrols jointly with Philippine forces in the [[South China Sea]] in order to help reduce growing tensions between the Philippines and the [[People's Republic of China]] over their competing claims in the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/bd92d542c71d409a82cac13981b2f461/us-keep-300-troops-philippines-through-end-month|title=US sending commandos, combat aircraft to Philippines|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n\n;17 April\n* [[Air France]] resumes flights to [[Iran]] after an eight-year hiatus with a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Imam Khomeini International Airport]] in [[Tehran]], beginning a three-times-per-week service. Air France joins [[Lufthansa]] and [[Austrian Airlines]] in providing commercial air passenger service between [[Europe]] and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/04/17/air-france-resumes-flights-to-iran-after-8-years0.html|title=Air France resumes flights to Iran after 8 years|date=17 April 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n* In the first incident of its kind in the [[United Kingdom]], the pilot of a [[British Airways]] [[Airbus A320]] with 127 people on board reports that an object that he believes to be an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] struck the front of his plane at an altitude of {{convert|1700|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over [[Richmond Park]], [[London]], while his airliner was on approach to land at [[Heathrow Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36067591|title='Drone' hits British Airways plane approaching Heathrow Airport|date=17 April 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"swinford20160421\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/21/drone-believed-to-have-hit-british-airways-flight-may-have-been/|title=Drone believed to have hit British Airways flight 'may have been a plastic bag'|work=Telegraph}}</ref> On 21 April, British [[Minister of State for Transport]] [[Robert Goodwill]] will announce that the object the airliner hit may have been a [[plastic bag]].<ref name=\"swinford20160421\" />\n\n;18 April\n* U.S. Secretary of Defense Ashton Carter announces that U.S. forces sent to assist the Iraqi armed forces in recapturing [[Mosul]] from the Islamic State will include [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3327956a32d7485a86725e141caa0b3b/carter-arrives-iraq-talks-how-beef-fightn|title=US to send 200 more troops, Apache helicopters to Iraq|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n* Making an implementation flight to test the route, ground operations, and handling, ahead of the beginning of scheduled airline services at [[Saint Helena Airport]], a [[Boeing 737-800]] operated by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]] for [[British Airways]] becomes the first passenger jet capable of seating 100 or more passengers to land on [[Saint Helena]]. High winds prevent the airliner from landing until its third attempt, indicating that [[wind shear]] conditions at the airport are dangerous for large commercial ircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |title=Pictures : Comair 737 arrives at new St Helena airport |publisher= [[FlightGlobal]] |date=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |title=British Airways flight struggles to land on St Helena runway |work=The Guardian |date=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;19 April\n* Four [[United States Air Force]] [[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 Thunderbolt II]] (nicknamed \"Warthog\") [[close air support]] aircraft of the [[51st Fighter Wing]] fly a patrol over the South China Sea west of [[Luzon]] from [[Clark Air Base]] in the Philippines. The [[maritime patrol]] mission is an unusual one for the A-10, but the U.S. Department of Defense announces that it is only the first of a planned series of joint South China Sea air patrols by U.S. and Philippine forces with goals of \"air- and maritime-domain awareness, personnel recovery, combating piracy, and [the] assurance [that] all nations have access to the regional air and maritime domains in accordance with [[international law]].\" The People's Republic of China, which claims the areas to be patrolled as its internal waters, condemns the planned patrols as reflecting a \"[[Cold War]] mentality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/get-ready-china-lethal-10-warthogs-are-patrolling-the-south-15886|title=Get Ready, China: Lethal A-10 Warthogs are Patrolling the South China Sea|first=David|last=Axe|work=The National Interest}}</ref>\n* A pro-Syrian-government aircraft strikes the main market in [[Maarat al-Nu'man]], [[Syria]], with two air-to-ground rockets while it is crowded with people shopping for fruits and vegetables, killing at least 37 people. It is unclear whether the attacking jet belonged to the Syrian Arab Air Force or the [[Russian Federation Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/pro-government-warplanes-bomb-a-rebel-town-that-hates-al-qaeda-killing-scores/2016/04/19/0a1d34ac-0641-11e6-bfed-ef65dff5970d_story.html|title=Pro-government warplanes bomb a rebel town that hates al-Qaeda, killing scores|work=The Washington Post|date=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 April\n* [[United States Central Command]] reveals that the authority to order airstrikes that might endanger civilians, originally given only to its top commander, has been delegated to its commander in [[Baghdad]] and his deputies.<ref name=\"lamothe20160422\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/04/22/u-s-military-doubles-the-number-of-civilians-it-admits-killing-in-anti-isis-fight/|title=U.S. military doubles the number of civilians it admits killing in anti-ISIS fight|work=The Washington Post|date=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;21 April\n* After a delay of almost 10 months, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) takes off from [[Kalaeloa Airport]] in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]], [[Hawaii]], bound for [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], on the ninth leg of its round-the-world flight to resume its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, with [[Bertrand Piccard]] at the controls, is expected to take about 62 hours. ''Solar Impulse 2'' had been at Kalaeloa since completing the eighth leg of its flight on [[2015 in aviation#July|3 July 2015]], delayed first by repairs necessitated by damage caused by an overheated battery and then by the need to wait for spring in the [[Northern Hemisphere]], when periods of daylight become long enough for the plane to charge its batteries in flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/04/21/travel/solar-impulse-2-plane/index.html|title=Solar Impulse 2 plane takes off from Hawaii to California \u2013 with no fuel|first=David |last=Molko|publisher=CNN|date=21 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/sciencefair/2016/04/20/solar-impulse-voyage-hawaii/83297824/|title=Sun-powered Solar Impulse resumes its round-the-world flight|work=USA Today|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] dismisses an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] [[lawsuit]] seeking access under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] to details of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s program of lethal airstrikes using unmanned aerial vehicles (or \"drones\") outside of the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and [[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]. The court finds that releasing such details to the public \"could reasonably be expected to damage [[national security]],\" and that \"[t]he agency's explanations as to why the records are classified are both 'logical' and 'plausible' and uncontroverted by evidence in the record.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/appeals-court-dismisses-lawsuit-seeking-access-to-records-on-lethal-drone-strikes/2016/04/21/8ae1321c-07d8-11e6-b283-e79d81c63c1b_story.html|title=Appeals court dismisses lawsuit seeking access to records on lethal drone strikes|work=The Washington Post|date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Doug Hughes is sentenced to four months in prison for an unauthorized [[gyrocopter]] flight from [[Pennsylvania]] he made on [[2015 in aviation#April|15 April 2015]] that ended with a landing on the [[United States Capitol Building]] grounds in [[Washington, D.C.]] He made the flight to protest the influence of money in American politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/gyrocopter-pilot-who-landed-at-us-capitol-to-be-sentenced/2016/04/20/3fe834ac-0703-11e6-bdcb-0133da18418d_story.html |title=Gyrocopter pilot who landed at U.S. Capitol sentenced to four months in prison|work=The Washington Post|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force raids on rebel-held parts of Aleppo kill at least 19 people. Additional government airstrikes in Idlib Governorate also kill people in areas under rebel control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/deadly-airstrikes-in-syria-further-strain-cease-fire-as-peace-talks-near-collapse/2016/04/22/2e56c96e-0899-11e6-b283-e79d81c63c1b_story.html|title=Deadly airstrikes in Syria further strain cease-fire as peace talks near collapse}}</ref>\n* U.S. Central Command announces that between [[2015 in aviation#September|10 September 2015]] and [[2016 in aviation#February|2 February 2016]] its airstrikes in Iraq and Syria killed 20 civilians and injured 11 more. The airstrikes killed two civilians in [[Kabisa]], Iraq, on 10 September 2015; eight in [[Atshanah]], Iraq, while hitting an Islamic State [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] position on [[2015 in aviation#October|5 October 2015]]; one in [[Ramadi]], Iraq, during a strike against Islamic State combat personnel on [[2015 in aviation#November|12 November 2015]]; one near Raqqa, Syria, on [[2015 in aviation#December|10 December 2015]]; five in Ramadi while hitting an Islamic State checkpoint on 12 December 2015; one in [[Tishreen (city)|Tishreen]], Syria, on 24 December 2015; one in [[Mosul]], Iraq, on [[2016 in aviation#January|11 January 2016]]; and one in [[Al Ghazli]], Syria, on 2 February 2016. In a previous announcement, the [[United States Department of Defense]] had acknowledged killing 15 civilians and wounding 15 more during earlier airstrikes in Iraq and Syria.<ref name=\"lamothe20160422\" />\n\n;23 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force planes strike rebel-held areas of Aleppo for a second straight day. They hit a residential area and a market in the city's Tareeq al-Bab district, killing at least 12 people.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Piloted by Bertrand Piccard, ''Solar Impulse 2'' completes the ninth leg of its around-the-world flight attempt, landing at Moffatt Field in Mountain View, California, after a nonstop flight from Kalaeloa, Hawaii, of 62 hours 29 minutes, covering {{convert|2206|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} at an average speed of {{convert|35.31|kn|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|28327|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/solar-powered-plane-successfully-crosses-pacific-ocean-lands/story?id=38622335|title=Solar-Powered Plane Finishes Pacific Ocean Crossing|publisher=ABC News|date=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-9-from-Hawaii-to-Mountain_View_CA|title=9th Leg from Hawaii to San Francisco|access-date=24 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424075146/http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-9-from-Hawaii-to-Mountain_View_CA|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;24 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force planes strike rebel-held areas in Aleppo for the third straight day, killing 16 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/least-14-killed-fighting-rages-syrias-aleppo-115338820.html|author1=Aji, Albert |author2=Philip Issa |title=At least 26 killed as fighting rages in Syria's Aleppo |agency=Associated Press |date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Ground forces of the Saudi-led coalition begin a ground offensive against [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] forces in southern [[Yemen]], advancing toward [[Mukalla]] and surrounding areas. Coalition aircraft supporting the offensive strike targets in Mukalla, hitting the city's cultural center and [[Riyan Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/war-in-yemen-takes-a-major-turn-with-offensive-against-al-qaeda/2016/04/24/b8e73a3e-0a2c-11e6-bc53-db634ca94a2a_story.html |title=War in Yemen takes a major turn with offensive against al-Qaeda|work=The Washington Post|date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;25\u201326 April (overnight)\n* An air-to-ground missile strike suspected to have been made by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle kills three prominent al-Qaeda leaders in [[Zinjibar]], Yemen.\n\n;26 April\n* The [[Government of Yemen|Yemeni government]] announces that Yemeni ground troops have retaken Mukalla from al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP) forces, adding that heavy airstrikes by the Saudi-led coalition combined with [[artillery]] fire had driven many AQAP members out of the city.\n*The Government of [[Saint Helena]] announces an indefinite delay to the opening of [[Saint Helena Airport]] to commercial traffic because of the problem the Comair Boeing 737-800 had encountered in landing on 18 April due to dangerous winds. The airport had been scheduled to open in May,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|title=MAINTAINING ACCESS TO ST HELENA & ASCENSION : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001524/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/#|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> but scheduled commercial air service will not begin until [[2017 in aviation#October|October 2017]].<ref name=bbc20171014>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003 Anonymous, \"First commercial flight lands on remote St Helena,\" bbc.com, 14 October 2017.]</ref>\n\n;27 April\n* Airstrikes by unidentified aircraft against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, collapse a hospital operated by [[Doctors Without Borders]] and the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]], killing at least 50 people, including patients and at least six hospital staff members. A [[Dentistry|dentist]] and two [[medical doctor]]s, one of them one of the area's last [[Pediatrics|pediatricians]], are among the dead.<ref name=\"cunningham20160428\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-destroys-doctors-without-borders-hospital-in-aleppo-killing-staff-and-patients/2016/04/28/e1377bf5-30dc-4474-842e-559b10e014d8_story.html|title=Airstrike destroys Syrian hospital amid fears of 'catastrophic' turn in fighting|work=The Washington Post|date=28 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cunningham20160429\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-syrias-battered-aleppo-ongoing-airstrikes-defy-international-outrage/2016/04/29/8e26c7c6-0d7c-11e6-bc53-db634ca94a2a_story.html|title=In Syria\u2019s battered Aleppo, death toll rises as international outrage mounts|work=The Washington Post|date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;28 April\n* The Russian Ministry of Defense denies Russian involvement in the 27 April airstrike against a hospital in Aleppo, Syria.<ref name=\"cunningham20160428\" />\n\n;29 April\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas in Aleppo, Syria, by unidentified aircraft destroy a medical clinic and hit other targets. Airstrikes against rebel-held areas and rebel [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] barrages have combined to kill more than 200 people in Aleppo during the preceding week.<ref name=\"cunningham20160429\" />\n* Russia and the United States announce a renewed ceasefire in two parts of Syria where fighting in violation of the [[2015 in aviation#February|27 February]] ceasefire has escalated during April and that it is scheduled to begin at midnight on 29\u201330 April. The Russian Ministry of Defense announces that the ceasefire applies to [[Latakia Governorate]] and will last 72 hours, while the [[United States Department of State]] later announces that it also includes East Ghouta outside Damascus and has no expiration date. The agreement excludes Aleppo, where the heaviest fighting since the 27 February ceasefire has broken out.<ref>Bergen Airport, Flesland DeYoung, Karen, \"U.S., Russia push for new Syria cease-fire deal,\" ''The Washington Post'', 29 April 2016.</ref>\n* A [[Eurocopter EC225 Super Puma]] helicopter (registration LN-OJF) operated by [[CHC Helikopter Service]] loses its main [[Helicopter rotor|rotor]] in flight while carrying oil workers from the [[Gullfaks B]] oil field in the [[North Sea]] to [[Bergen Airport, Flesland|Bergen Airport]], [[Flesland]], in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], and [[CHC Helikopter Service Flight 241|crashes]] on Norway's Skitholmen islet between the islands of [[Tur\u00f8y]] and [[Toft\u00f8y]], killing all 13 people on board.\n* The commander of [[United States Central Command]], [[United States Army]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Joseph Votel]], announces that a U.S. Department of Defense investigation into a [[United States Air Force]] airstrike against a Doctors Without Borders hospital in [[Kunduz]], [[Afghanistan]], on [[2015 in aviation#October|3 October 2015]] did not amount to a [[war crime]] because American military personnel responsible for the strike attacked the hospital by mistake while attempting to support [[Afghan Armed Forces|Afghan troops]] and U.S. Army [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces]] in combat against [[Taliban]] forces. The incident resulted in 16 American military personnel facing disciplinary action for their role in it, but the investigation found that their misjudgments did not involve any criminal intent.<ref name=\"cunningham20160429\" />\n\n;30 April\n* Nearly 30 airstrikes hit rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria. It is the ninth day of lethal bombardments in the city, and they have killed nearly 250 people since beginning on 22 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-idUSKCN0XR0CT|title=Aleppo bombed as Syrian army begins 'calm' plan elsewhere|date=1 May 2017|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n;3 May\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Phoenix Goodyear Airport]] outside [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]], [[Arizona]], completing the tenth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun on 2 May at [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], covers {{convert|691|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} in 15 hours 52 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|43.56|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|22001|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-10-from-San_Francisco-to-Phoenix|title=10th Leg from San Francisco to Phoenix}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/southwest-valley/2016/05/02/solar-impulse-aircraft-california-phoenix/83822062/|title=Solar plane lands in Phoenix area as global trek continues}}</ref>\n\n;5 May\n* [[Amazon.com]] and [[Atlas Air Worldwide Holdings]] announce a deal in which Amazon.com will acquire up to 30 percent of Atlas's stock and Atlas will acquire 20 [[Boeing 767-300]] cargo aircraft, lease them to Amazon.com for ten years, and operate them for Amazon.com for seven years via its [[Atlas Air]] subsidiary. Operations are expected to begin during the latter half of 2016 and grow to their maximum planned size by 2018. It is Amazon.com's second investment in an air cargo carrier \u2013 its first was announced on [[2016 in aviation#March|5 March]] \u2013 and it doubles the size of Amazon.com's air cargo fleet from 20 to 40 aircraft, all Boeing 767-300s.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-partners-with-atlas-air-worldwide-for-cargo-services-1462455676 Jamerson, Joshua, \"Amazon Partners with Atlas Air Worldwide for Cargo Services,\" ''Wall Street Journal'', 5 May 2016, 7:40 p.m. EDT.]</ref>\n\n;6 May\n* A U.S. airstrike against a ground vehicle driving near [[Ar-Rutbah]], [[Iraq]], kills four Islamic State members, including the \"military [[emir]]\" of [[Anbar Governorate]], [[Abu Wahib]], notorious for his appearances in Islamic State videos. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce his death on 9 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/09/notorious-islamic-state-leader-killed-in-airstrike-pentagon-says/|title=Notorious Islamic State leader killed in airstrike, Pentagon says}}</ref>\n* For the second time, [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform floating in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] after a launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]] which placed a Japanese satellite in orbit. The first successful landing had occurred four weeks earlier, on [[2016 in aviation#April|8 April 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4320750/spacex-falcon-9-rocket-lands-second/|title=SpaceX Successfully Lands a Rocket on a Drone Ship, Again}}</ref>\n\n;7 May\n* [[Turkish Air Force]] [[F-4 Phantom II]] and [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] aircraft strike [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] shelters, ammunition depots, and weapon positions in northern Iraq, including in the [[Qandil Mountains]], where the group's headquarters is located.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/d2fa95b2da424cfd83d196b04e179c0b/report-turkey-attacks-syria-55-militants-killed|title=Report: Turkey attacks IS in Syria; 55 militants killed}}</ref>\n\n;9 May\n* Airstrikes by the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]]-led coalition against a rebel military camp in [[Yemen]]'s [[Amran Governorate]] kill at least 10 Yemeni rebels and wound more than 15 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/airstrikes-saudi-led-coalition-yemen-kill-10-rebels-38980567|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;11 May\n* In a [[Freedom of navigation|freedom-of-navigation]] operation in the [[South China Sea]], the [[United States Navy]] [[guided missile destroyer]] {{USS|William P. Lawrence|DDG-110}} steams within {{convert|12|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} of [[Fiery Cross Reef]], which the [[People's Republic of China]] claims as its territory along with adjacent waters which the United States views as [[international waters]]. In response, China scrambles three jet fighters, which join three Chinese ships in monitoring the destroyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/10/china-scrambles-fighters-jets-as-u-s-destroyer-steams-past-disputed-island/|title=China scrambles fighter jets as U.S. destroyer steams past disputed island}}</ref>\n* [[Iran]]'s [[Ministry of Defense (Iran)|Minister of Defense]], [[Brigadier General]] [[Hossein Dehghan]], announces that Iran has taken delivery of at least one [[S-300 (missile)|S-300]] [[surface-to-air-missile]] system from [[Russia]], the first of five to be delivered under a 2007 contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iran-announces-delivery-of-russian-s-300-missile-defense-system/2016/05/10/944afa2e-16ae-11e6-971a-dadf9ab18869_story.html|title=Iran announces delivery of Russian S-300 missile defense system}}</ref>\n\n;12 May\n* [[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Transport (Malaysia)|Minister of Transport]], [[Liow Tiong Lai]], announces that two pieces of debris found in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]] \u2013 an engine cowling piece with a partial [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] logo discovered on the southern coast of [[South Africa]] and an interior panel piece from an aircraft cabin found on [[Rodrigues]] \u2013 \"almost certainly\" are from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b2d55dc21f4e4c4eb3b3dc472b1ff9aa/malaysia-2-more-pieces-almost-certainly-flight-370|title=Malaysia: 2 more pieces 'almost certainly' from Flight 370}}</ref>\n* After a [[Uganda]]n assault team comes under fire while attempting to secure an [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] checkpoint west of [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]], suspected of being used by the group to extort money from travelers, a U.S. special operations team assisting the Ugandans calls in a U.S. airstrike against the checkpoint. The strike kills five Al-Shabaab personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/may/12/us-airstrike-kills-5-al-shabaab-militants-somalia/|title=U.S. airstrike kills 5 al-Shabaab militants in Somalia|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n* Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Tulsa International Airport]] outside [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]], completing the eleventh leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun on 11 May at Phoenix Goodyear Airport in Phoenix, Arizona, covers {{convert|975|mi|km}} in 18 hours 10 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|53.67|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}r), reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|22001|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 11: Phoenix to Tulsa|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-11-from-Phoenix-to-Tulsa|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;13 May\n* Airstrikes suspected of having been conducted by [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] aircraft reportedly kill at least 12 people in [[Idlib]], [[Syria]], and injure at least 38 others. One report places the death toll at 15. Additional strikes reportedly occur around [[Zaara, Syria|Zaara]], Syria. The [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]]'s official [[Syrian Arab News Agency]] claims that the strikes targeted [[Nusra Front]] strongholds in [[Idlib Governorate]] and [[Hama]], and that they killed 30 members of the militant group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5b74c9a7c7f04cfbba896bac3b3992d6/airstrikes-kill-least-5-syria|title=Airstrikes kill at least 12 in northern Syria}}</ref>\n* [[United States Air Force]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Lori Robinson]], previously the commander of the U.S. Air Force's [[Pacific Air Forces]], takes command of [[United States Northern Command]], becoming the first woman to command a U.S. [[Unified Combatant Command|unified combatant command]]. She simultaneously becomes the [[commanding officer]] of the [[North American Aerospace Defense Command]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/13/air-force-gen-lori-robinson-becomes-first-woman-ever-to-lead-u-s-combatant-command/|title=Air Force Gen. Lori Robinson becomes first woman ever to lead U.S. combatant command}}</ref>\n\n;15 May\n* According to Turkish military sources, airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition and a [[Turkish Army]] [[artillery]] bombardment combine to kill 27 Islamic State personnel in northern Syria about {{convert|10|km|mi|abbr=off|sp=us}} from the Turkish border as they prepare to fire rockets into [[Turkey]]. The strikes and bombardment destroy five \"fortified defence posts\" and two \"gun posts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36302995|title=Islamic State: Turkish strikes in Syria 'kill 27 militants'|date=16 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;17 May\n* At least two Chinese [[Shenyang J-11]] fighters intercept a [[United States Navy]] [[Lockheed EP-3]] signals reconnaissance aircraft over the [[South China Sea]] in [[international airspace]] east of [[Hainan Island]]. The following day, a U.S. Department of Defense official says that the Chinese aircraft came within {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of the EP-3 and that the interception was unsafe. China responds that its fighters maintained a safe distance.<ref name=\"idrees20160519\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southchinasea-china-usa-idUSKCN0YA0QX|title=China demands end to U.S. surveillance after aircraft intercept|date=20 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] announces that there were 764 reports of [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs, or \"drones\") sighted near airplanes in the [[United States]] in [[2015 in aviation|2015]], and that it has begun a research program to explore ways of detecting (UAVs) that are operating near airports. It also announces that the initial investigation of drone detection technology had taken place earlier in May 2016 at [[New York City]]\u2032s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[Queens, New York|Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], employing a technology used by the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]. The experiment tested the technology's capability to detect five kinds of UAVs, including common [[rotorcraft]] and more advanced [[Fixed-wing aircraft|fixed-wing]] UAVs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/worried-that-drones-might-strike-airplanes-faa-seeks-airport-detection-system/2016/05/17/92fb76d8-1c3c-11e6-9c81-4be1c14fb8c8_story.html|title=Worried that drones might strike airplanes, FAA seeks airport detection system}}</ref>\n\n;18 May\n* A [[Silk Way Airlines]] [[Antonov An-12]] cargo plane suffers an engine failure shortly after taking off from [[Dwyer Airport]] in southern [[Afghanistan]] and [[2016 Silk Way Airlines Antonov An-12 crash|crashes]], killing seven of its nine-member crew.\n* [[Saab Group|Saab]] debuts its new [[Saab JAS 39 Gripen|JAS 39 Gripen E]] fighter in a rollout at [[Link\u00f6ping]], [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/air-space/2016/05/18/gripen-e-debuts-saab-reports-continued-interest-c-variants/84537568/|title=gripen-e-debuts-saab-reports-continued-interest-c-variants|first=Defense|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;19 May\n* [[EgyptAir Flight 804]], an [[Airbus A320|Airbus A320-232]] (registration SU-GCC) on a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Cairo]], crashes into the [[Mediterranean Sea]] south of [[Karpathos]], killing all 66 people on board.\n* In response to a U.S. Defense Department accusation on 18 May that Chinese fighter aircraft made an unsafe interception of a U.S. Navy reconnaissance aircraft over the South China Sea on 17 May, the [[People's Republic of China]] demands that the United States cease reconnaissance flights in the vicinity of China.<ref name=\"idrees20160519\"/>\n\n;20 May \n* Russian [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Minister of Defense]] [[Sergei Shoigu]] proposes that Russia and the U.S.-led coalition conduct joint airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] and against ground convoys carrying weapons and reinforcements into Syria from Turkey. The U.S. Department of State responds that no agreement to conduct joint airstrikes exists, and the U.S. Department of Defense informs the press that it has no plans to expand cooperation with Russia in Syria beyond existing flight-safety communications intended only to deconflict coalition and Russian air operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-proposes-joint-airstrikes-with-us-led-coalition-in-syria/2016/05/20/3f679bfc-1e92-11e6-9c81-4be1c14fb8c8_story.html|title=Russia proposes joint airstrikes with U.S.-led coalition in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;21 May\n* A U.S. airstrike involving several unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) hits a ground vehicle driving on a road near [[Ahmad Wal]] in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Balochistan]] province, reportedly killing [[Taliban]] leader [[Akhtar Mansour]] and the driver of the vehicle. It is the first U.S. UAV strike in that part of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-on-taliban-leader-escalates-us-involvement-in-afghan-war/2016/05/22/f26ced5a-2014-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html |last1=Craig|first1=Tim|first2=Antonio|last2=Olivo|first3=Missy|last3=Ryan|title=U.S. takes war back to Pakistan with drone strike aimed at Taliban leader|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date= 22 May 2016|time= 8:39 a.m. EDT}}</ref>\n* An airstrike allegedly conducted by aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition flying into Syria from Turkey hits the Islamic State-held town of [[Arshaf]], Syria, near [[Mare']], killing seven members of one family and perhaps as many as 10 people in total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dccd1bb3528d476d8f4f6e30001e35f4/activists-suspected-coalition-airstrike-kills-syrian-family|title=Activists: Suspected coalition airstrike kills Syrian family}}</ref>\n* Flown by Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Dayton International Airport]] in [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]], [[Ohio]],<ref name=nbc20160522>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/innovation/solar-impulse-2-lands-ohio-complete-latest-leg-global-trip-n578171|title=Solar Impulse 2 Lands in Ohio to Complete Latest Leg of Global Trip}}</ref> completing the twelfth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun early in the day at Tulsa International Airport in Tulsa, Oklahoma,<ref name=nbc20160522/> covers {{convert|691|mi|km}} in 16 hours 34 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|41.72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|21000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=nbc20160522/><ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 12: Tulsa to Dayton|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-12-from-Tulsa-to-Dayton|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;22 May\n* [[Prime Minister of Iraq]] [[Haider al-Abadi]] announces that [[Iraqi Air Force]] [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]]s are bombing Islamic State targets in [[Fallujah]], Iraq, at the beginning of a drive by Iraqi military and security forces and militias allied with them to retake the city from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iraqi-military-preparing-to-retake-fallujah-from-islamic-state/2016/05/22/15c832cc-200c-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=Operation to retake Fallujah has begun, Iraqi prime minister says}}</ref>\n\n;23 May\n* U.S. airstrikes support Iraqi military and security forces and militias allied with them moving into Fallujah, Iraq. A U.S. spokesman for the U.S.-led coalition announces that coalition aircraft have struck 21 Islamic State targets in and around Fallujah since 17 May.<ref name=salim20160523>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi-military-claims-advances-in-jihadist-held-fallujah/2016/05/23/45b266c6-20e6-11e6-b944-52f7b1793dae_story.html|title=Iraqi military claims advances in Islamic State-held Fallujah}}</ref>\n* An Iraqi Air Force F-16 Fighting Falcon destroys an Islamic State bomb-making factory in Fallujah, Iraq, and hits Islamic State rocket launchers in the city.<ref name=salim20160523/>\n* The first two Dutch [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 both [[Royal Netherlands Air Force]] F-35A models \u2013 arrive in the [[Netherlands]], landing at [[Leeuwarden Air Base]]. They are the first examples of the F-35 to arrive in [[Europe]].<ref name=aviationistf35>{{cite web|url=https://theaviationist.com/category/f-35/page/2/|title=The Aviationist \u00bb F-35}}</ref>\n\n;24 May\n* Iraqi Air Force and U.S. aircraft strike Islamic State targets in and around Fallujah, Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/mixed-iraqi-force-prepares-for-push-into-militant-stronghold-of-fallujah/2016/05/24/475f6b98-21b0-11e6-b944-52f7b1793dae_story.html|title=Mixed Iraqi force prepares for push into militant stronghold of Fallujah}}</ref>\n\n;25 May\n* The brother of a taxi driver killed in the 21 May U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle strike that also killed Taliban leader Akhtar Mansour files a police report in Balochistan, Pakistan, requesting that his brother's death be investigated and noting that the United States claimed responsibility for the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-afghanistan-taliban-idUSKCN0YK0Q2|title=Brother of man killed in U.S. strike on Taliban chief files police report|date=30 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* Russia announces that is suspending airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] to allow rebels not affiliated with the group to distance themselves from it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-says-it-is-suspending-attacks-against-syrias-al-qaeda-franchise/2016/05/25/afd236b0-a40a-475e-af5c-030ee541a77f_story.html|title=Russia calls off attacks against Syria\u2019s al-Qaeda franchise}}</ref>\n* With Bertrand Piccard at the controls, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) flies from Dayton International Airport in Dayton, Ohio, to [[Lehigh Valley International Airport]] in [[Hanover Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Hanover Township]], [[Pennsylvania]], completing the thirteenth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight covers {{convert|649|mi|km}} in 16 hours 49 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|38.63|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|15000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 13: Dayton to Lehigh Valley|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-13-from-Dayton-to-Lehigh_Valley|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n* U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) Administrator [[Peter V. Neffenger]] says in testimony before the [[United States Congress]] that a projected 740 million people will pass through TSA security checkpoints at U.S. airports during the 2016 summer travel season, 97 million more than the 643 million who did in 2013, that the 45,000-strong TSA workforce is not large enough to prevent excessively long lines at the checkpoints, and that the recent cancellation of plans to lay off 1,600 TSA employees and hire 768 more will be insufficient to reduce lines. He reports that he plans to convert part-time TSA employees into full-time ones and to increase the number of enrollees in trusted traveler programs from 9.5 million to 25 million as ways of reducing airport security waits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/tsa-chief-takes-another-crack-at-explaining-long-airport-security-lines/2016/05/25/b9c95534-2270-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=TSA chief Neffenger takes another crack at explaining long airport security lines}}</ref>\n\n;26 May\n* An airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition in Fallujah, Iraq, kills Maher al-Bilawi, the commander of Islamic State forces in the city.<ref name=reuters20160528>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-iraq-falluja-idUSKCN0YI1AD|title=Islamic State commander in Falluja killed, U.S. military says|date=28 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* An [[American Airlines]] vice president, Kerry Philipovitch, and executives from the airport authorities of [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]], testify before the U.S. Congress asking it to take action to reduce security lines at Transportation Security Administration (TSA) checkpoints at U.S. airports. Philipovitch says, \"We have never seen TSA wait times that affect airlines and passengers throughout the United States like we\u2019ve seen in recent months...More needs to be done, and fast. Programs that had been in place to drive efficiency and increase security throughout were eliminated without adding commensurate resources required to support longer passenger processing times.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/american-airlines-something-needs-to-be-done-and-fast-about-tsa-lines/2016/05/26/5811e50e-2338-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=American Airlines: Something 'needs to be done, and fast' about TSA lines}}</ref>\n\n;27 May\n* [[Korean Air Flight 2708]], a [[Boeing 777-300]] (registration HL7534), suffers an engine failure during its takeoff roll at [[Haneda Airport]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], that results in a fire. The flight crew aborts the takeoff, and the 319 people aboard evacuate the aircraft. Twelve of them are injured in the incident.\n* The U.S.-led coalition has conducted 20 airstrikes against Islamic State targets in Fallujah, Iraq, since 24 May, killing 70 Islamic State personnel.<ref name=reuters20160528/>\n* Russia warns that it will escalate its air campaign in Syria if the United States does not respond positively to its long-standing proposal to conduct joint airstrikes in Syria with the [[Russian Federation Air Force]].<ref name=sly20160531>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/airstrikes-kill-dozens-near-a-hospital-in-syria-as-violence-escalates/2016/05/31/edc5bd03-0b09-4bf6-a182-69cda8b75a3e_story.html|title=Airstrikes kill dozens near a hospital in Syria as violence escalates}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike kills [[Abdullahi Haji Da\u2019ud]], Al-Shabaab's top commander, as he travels in southern Somalia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/1/abdullahi-daud-key-al-shabaab-leader-killed-us-air/|title=Abdullahi Da\u2019ud, key al-Shabaab leader, killed by U.S. airstrike in Somalia|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n* A Vietnamese man, Minh Quang Pham, is sentenced in [[New York City]] to 40 years in prison for providing material support to [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] in a 2011 plot to bomb [[Heathrow Airport]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scnow.com/news/national/wire/article_8cf9d08e-5b29-5d4e-8634-4925712117b5.html|title=Anonymous, \"40 years for Vietnamese man accused in plot to bomb Heathrow\", Associated Press, May 27, 2016.}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* A [[World War II]]-era [[P-47 Thunderbolt]] crashes into the [[Hudson River]] off [[Edgewater, New Jersey|Edgewater]], [[New Jersey]], killing its pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/small-plane-carrying-people-lands-hudson-river-article-1.2652690|title=Vintage World War II plane crashes in Hudson River; pilot killed}}</ref>\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform at sea, the fourth time it has made such a landing. The landing, made aboard a platform in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|422|mi|km}} off the coast of [[Florida]] after launching a communications satellite into orbit, is particularly challenging because of the distance the rocket travels to deliver its payload and the large amount of energy required, subjecting the first stage to extreme speeds and re-entry heating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/05/27/elon-musks-spacex-does-it-again-nails-fourth-landing-in-a-row/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX does it again. Nails fourth landing.}}</ref>\n\n;29 May\n* [[Lufthansa]] announces that it will suspend service to [[Venezuela]] beginning on 18 June, saying that Venezuela owes it millions of [[United States dollar]]s in ticket revenues and that Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult to convert ticket sales revenue to dollars that can be sent abroad. Lufthansa adds that it hopes to restore service to Venezuela in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36407570|title=Lufthansa to suspend flights to Venezuela|date=29 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;30 May\n* Intense late-evening strikes by three unidentified aircraft \u2013 reported by some observers to be Russian \u2013 against buildings around the National Hospital in [[Idlib]], Syria, kill at least 23 and perhaps as many as 50 people and injure about 250 others. Over the preceding weekend, Russian Federation Air Force and [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] aircraft had conducted hundreds of strikes against rebel-held areas in [[Aleppo]], Syria.<ref name=sly20160531/>\n* [[LATAM Airlines Group]] announces that its subsidiary airlines will suspend service to Venezuela, making it the second airline company to do so. Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult for airlines to convert ticket sales revenue to [[United States dollar]]s to cover their costs of operating in Venezuela. LATAM plans for its subsidiary airlines to cease service between [[Caracas]], Venezuela, and [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]], first, with suspension of service between Caracas and [[Lima]], [[Peru]], and between Caracas and [[Santiago]], [[Chile]], to halt by 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36414733|title=Second airline suspends flights to Venezuela|date=30 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;31 May\n* The U.S. Transportation Security Administration reports that the major delays expected at its security checkpoints at U.S. airports over the 2016 [[Memorial Day]] weekend did not materialize. From 26 May through 30 May, wait times in security lines averaged less than 10 minutes in regular security lines nationwide, with the majority of the 10.3 million passengers having a wait time of less than 30 minutes. The longest wait was at [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]], where passengers waited 75 minutes on 26 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/tsa-says-most-airport-security-lines-werent-so-bad-over-memorial-day-weekend/2016/05/31/a537e9f8-2731-11e6-b989-4e5479715b54_story.html|title=TSA says most airport security lines weren\u2019t so bad over Memorial Day weekend}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n* With international sanctions having largely prevented [[Iran]] from purchasing new airliners or spare parts for its commercial aircraft since the [[Iranian Revolution]] of 1979, 88 of Iran's 250 commercial aircraft are grounded due to a lack of spare parts.<ref name=gambrell20160922>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_IRAN_AIRBUS_BOEING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME|title=Gambrell, John, \"US grants Airbus, Boeing permission to sell aircraft to Iran,\" Associated Press, September 22, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n;1 June\n* The [[French Navy]] [[survey ship]] ''[[French ship Laplace (A 793)|Laplace]]'' detects signals in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] believed to be from the [[flight recorder]] of [[EgyptAir Flight 804]], an [[Airbus A320|Airbus A320-232]] which crashed on [[2016 in aviation#May|19 May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/02/world/middleeast/egyptair-black-box.html|title=Black Box From Missing EgyptAir Flight 804 Is Said to Be Detected|first1=Nicola|last1=Clark|first2=Nour|last2=Youssef|date=1 June 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;2 June\n* In an extremely unusual coincidence, two U.S. military flight demonstration [[Aviation squadron|squadrons]] suffer crashes on the same day. A [[United States Air Force]] [[United States Air Force Thunderbirds|Thunderbirds]] [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] crashes in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], [[Colorado]], just after the Thunderbirds perform a [[Flypast|flyover]] for the 2016 [[graduation]] ceremony at the [[United States Air Force Academy]]; its pilot ejects safely. Hours later, a [[United States Navy]] [[Blue Angels]] [[F/A-18 Hornet]] crashes in [[Smyrna, Tennessee|Smyrna]], [[Tennessee]], while practicing for an [[air show]], killing its pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/02/air-force-f-16-crashes-just-minutes-after-flying-over-air-force-academy-graduation/|title=In bizarre coincidence, a Blue Angels F-18 and a Thunderbirds F-16 crash on same day}}</ref>\n\n;3 June\n* The [[United Nations Security Council]] agrees to request formally that the [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] allow airlifts of food and medical supplies to civilians in besieged, rebel-held areas of [[Syria]]. Plans call for [[United Nations]] representatives to make the request in [[Damascus]], Syria, on 5 June. The Syrian government has not permitted deliveries of humanitarian aid to besieged areas despite a 1 June deadline set by an international task force for it to permit full ground access to the areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/un-security-council-will-formally-request-syrian-approval-of-humanitarian-air-drops/2016/06/03/a733e73a-29ce-11e6-ae4a-3cdd5fe74204_story.html|title=U.N. Security Council to formally request Syrian approval of humanitarian airdrops}}</ref>\n* The U.S. Navy announces that [[Carrier Air Wing Seven]] aboard the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Harry S. Truman|CVN-75}} has begun launching airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] targets from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] during the day. It is the first time that aircraft from a U.S. aircraft carrier have struck targets in the [[Middle East]] from the Mediterranean since the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|beginning of the Iraq War]] in [[2003 in aviation|2003]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/03/as-pressure-mounts-on-the-islamic-states-capital-u-s-aircraft-carrier-starts-striking-from-the-mediterranean/|title=As pressure increases on Islamic State\u2019s capital, U.S. aircraft carrier starts striking from the Mediterranean|publisher=}}</ref>\n* A [[Guardian Air]] [[Dassault Falcon 20]] air ambulance arrives at [[Saint Helena Airport]] to make the first [[medical evacuation]] flight in the history of [[Saint Helena]]. It departs the following morning, taking a critically ill baby and its mother to [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|title=FIRST EVER MEDEVAC FLIGHT \u2013 CRITICALLY ILL SAINT TRANSFERRED TO CAPE TOWN : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917192453/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;4 June\n* Turkish officials sink a 36-year-old [[Airbus A300]] in the [[Aegean Sea]] off [[Ku\u015fadas\u0131]], [[Turkey]], to serve as an [[artificial reef]] and recreational [[Underwater diving|dive]] site. The fourth aircraft sunk off the Turkish coast recently, it reportedly is the largest aircraft ever sunk for use as a reef or dive site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/06/06/turkey-sinks-an-airbus-jumbo-jet-in-aegean-sea-to-attract-fish-and-tourists/|title=Turkey sinks an Airbus jumbo jet in Aegean Sea to attract fish \u2013 and tourists}}</ref>\n\n;5 June\n* During a flight from [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]], to [[London]], [[England]], Malaysian Airlines Flight 1, an [[Airbus A380]] with 378 people on board, encounters severe turbulence over the [[Bay of Bengal]]. Some passengers and crew suffer minor injuries. The airliner returns safely to Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/06/05/world/asia/ap-as-malaysia-airline-turbulence.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Malaysia Airlines Passengers Injured Due to Turbulence,\" Associated Press, June 5, 2016, 12:12 P.M. EDT.}}</ref>\n* [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] warns the [[People's Republic of China]] not to declare to an [[air defense identification zone]] over the [[South China Sea]], saying that to do so would be a \"provocative and destabilizing act.\"<ref name=denyer20160608>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-spy-plane-buzzed-by-chinese-jets-in-unsafe-intercept/2016/06/08/160d607f-770a-484c-8339-62c0816487fe_story.html|title=U.S. spy plane buzzed by Chinese jets in 'unsafe' intercept}}</ref>\n\n;6 June\n* [[Foreign Minister of Russia]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announces that [[Russia]] will intensify its airstrikes in the area around [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]], in support of [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] forces defending against a [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] offensive there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/assad-pledges-more-bloodshed-in-syria-says-the-peace-process-has-failed/2016/06/07/efcd0e96-2cb6-11e6-b9d5-3c3063f8332c_story.html|title=Assad pledges more bloodshed in Syria, says the peace process has failed}}</ref>\n\n;7 June\n* Two Chinese [[Chengdu J-10]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Firebird\") fighters intercept a U.S. Air Force [[Boeing RC-135]] reconnaissance plane in [[international airspace]] over the [[East China Sea]] in what the [[United States Pacific Command]] describes the next day as an \"unsafe\" manner. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] responds that the Chinese pilots did nothing unsafe and protests what it calls \"frequent close reconnaissance on China's coast by U.S. military aircraft.\"\n* In testimony before the [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]], U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) Administrator [[Peter V. Neffenger]] says that it is reducing passenger delays at TSA security checkpoints at airports in the [[United States]] by focusing on speeding the processing of passengers at seven major airports ([[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]] in the [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]-[[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] area of [[Texas]]; [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]; [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]]; [[Los Angeles International Airport]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[Miami International Airport]] in [[Miami-Dade County, Florida]], [[California]]; [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]]; and [[O'Hare International Airport]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]). He adds that the success of the program over the 2016 [[Memorial Day]] weekend has spurred TSA to expand it to airports at [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]; [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]]; [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]], [[Michigan]]; [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], Florida; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], Texas; [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]; [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]; [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], Florida; [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]; [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]]; [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], California; and [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]; and at New YorkCity's [[LaGuardia Airport]]. He informs the committee that he expects 768 newly trained TSA agents to join the lines during June, and, if the [[United States Congress]] approves it, will shift 2,784 part-time TSA workers to full-time work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/focusing-on-keeping-lines-moving-at-mega-airports-tsa-says-its-doing-better/2016/06/07/a45bbc98-2ca5-11e6-9de3-6e6e7a14000c_story.html|title=TSA says it\u2019s improving at keeping lines moving at mega-airports}}</ref>\n\n;8 June\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, kill 15 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/06/08/syrian-activists-airstrikes-aleppo/85589260/|title=Syrian activists say airstrikes in Aleppo kill at least 15}}</ref>\n\n;9 June\n* According to the [[Al Sumaria]] television network, an airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition on this date against an Islamic State headquarters in [[Nineveh Governorate]] in northern [[Iraq]] near the border with Syria wounds the Islamic State leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]] and several other Islamic State personnel. The following day, a spokesman for the coalition announces that the coalition cannot confirm the strike or any injury to al-Baghdadi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-baghdadi-idUSKCN0YW0QT|title=U.S, Iraqi officials can't confirm report Islamic State leader wounded|date=10 June 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;10 June\n* Over eastern [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Luminati Aerospace]]'s solar-powered [[VO-Substrata]] aircraft makes its first test flight open to the public, flying from an airfield at [[Calverton, New York|Calverton]], New York, for about 20 minutes with a pilot at the controls, although it is also configured for unmanned flight. It is the prototype for a fleet of solar-powered [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s Luminati Aerospace hopes to build starting in late 2016 that will fly at altitudes of more than {{convert|60000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and provide [[Internet]] service to over 4,000,000,000 people worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2daadfec9c824c9c8bb682b56ea0c216/aerospace-firm-unveils-solar-powered-aircraft|title=Aerospace firm successfully tests solar-powered aircraft}}</ref>\n* [[United States Department of Defense]] officials announce that in late May 2016 [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] granted U.S. military commanders in [[Afghanistan]] expanded powers to assist Afghan military and security forces in combat against the [[Taliban]]. Among them is the authority to order U.S. airstrikes in support of Afghan offensive operations against the Taliban in limited circumstances in which the strikes are expected to have \"strategic effect.\" Previously, U.S. airstrikes in Afghanistan had been authorized only to defend U.S. personnel, protect Afghan forces facing serious danger, or conduct counterterrorism operations against [[al-Qaeda]] or the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/09/defense-official-u-s-to-begin-striking-taliban-advise-regular-afghan-soldiers-again/|title=U.S. widens war in Afghanistan, authorizes new action against Taliban}}</ref>\n* The [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] makes its international airshow debut when two [[Royal Netherlands Air Force]] F-35A aircraft perform during the ''Luchtmachtdagen 2016'' airshow at [[Leeuwarden Air Base]] in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=aviationistf35/>\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] grants permission to six U.S. airlines \u2013 [[American Airlines]], [[Frontier Airlines]], [[JetBlue]], [[Silver Airways]], [[Southwest Airlines]], and [[Sun Country Airlines]] \u2013 to provide the first scheduled airline service between the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]] in over 50 years, joining 46 non-U.S. airlines that already serve Cuba. The airlines are to provide 155 round-trip flights per week between five U.S. cities (Chicago, Illinois; Fort Lauderdale, Florida; Miami, Florida; Minneapolis, Minnesota; and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania) and nine Cuban destinations ([[Camag\u00fcey]], [[Cayo Coco]], [[Cayo Largo del Sur]], [[Cienfuegos]], [[Holgu\u00edn]], [[Manzanillo, Cuba|Manzanillo]], [[Matanzas]], [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]], and [[Santiago de Cuba]]). Flights are expected to begin in the autumn of 2016 and early in the winter of 2016\u20132017. A decision on flights by U.S. airlines to [[Havana]] is expected later in the summer of 2016. Although U.S. law still prohibits tourist travel to Cuba, it permits a dozen other categories of travel, including family visits, official business, journalist visits, professional meetings and educational and religious activities, and the [[United States Government]] has relaxed oversight of travel to the point that U.S. travelers are allowed to design their own \"people-to-people\" cultural exchanges in Cuba that in essence permit leisure travel under the guise of a cultural exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/389c209f926940ee97c44128c13a832f/us-airlines-start-scheduled-flights-cuba|title=US airlines to start scheduled flights to Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;11 June\n* An estimated 2,000 people gather outside [[Ramstein Air Base]] in [[Germany]] to protest the base's alleged role in supporting the U.S. \"drone war,\" the U.S. practice of using unmanned aerial vehicles to strike terrorist targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/europe/no-drone-war-thousands-converge-in-protest-outside-ramstein-1.414238|title='No Drone War.' Thousands converge in protest outside Ramstein}}</ref>\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) flies from [[Lehigh Valley International Airport]] in [[Hanover Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Hanover Township]], [[Pennsylvania]], to [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]], completing the 14th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any [[fossil fuel]]. The flight covers {{convert|164.5|mi|km}} in 4&nbsp;hours 41&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|35.14|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|3002|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 14: Lehigh Valley to New York|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-14-from-Lehigh_Valley-to-New_York|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;12 June\n* A man throws a homemade explosive device made out of a beer bottle at the ticketing counter in the check-in area of Terminal 2 at [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport]] at [[Shanghai]], [[China]]; it explodes, injuring four people with flying glass. He then slashes his own throat with a knife, injuring himself seriously.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/three-injured-as-home-made-explosives-detonated-at-shanghai-airport/2016/06/12/be34b036-2e11-47fd-9fb0-e0acaa84ddc3_story.html|title=Explosive device at Shanghai airport leaves 5 injured}}</ref>\n* An unmanned aerial vehicle operating without permission near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]], forces the airport to close for 69 minutes.<ref name=bbc20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37493404|title=Dubai airport grounds flights due to 'drone activity'|date=28 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes ascribed to Russian aircraft hit Syria's rebel-held [[Idlib Governorate]]. A series of them against targets in [[Idlib]], including one that hits a popular market, kills at least 21 people, while a strike in [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]] that collapses an apartment building kills six others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-june-12-2016/2016/06/12/fe7acb86-309e-11e6-8ff7-7b6c1998b7a0_story.html|title=World digest: June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;12\u201313 June (overnight)\n* An airstrike on a ground vehicle in [[Yemen]]'s [[Shabwa Governorate]] kills three [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members in the vehicle. The strike is suspected of having been conducted by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b139df4d42904c2db908c404a57b5f82/suspected-us-drone-kills-3-al-qaida-suspects-yemen|title=Suspected US drone kills 3 al-Qaida suspects in Yemen}}</ref>\n\n;13 June\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) charges [[Amazon.com]] with shipping a [[hazardous material]] as air cargo, alleging that the company shipped a caustic [[drain cleaner]] without properly declaring, packaging, or labeling it, including emergency response information with it, or training employees in how to handle it, and that a package of the drain cleaner leaked at a [[United Parcel Service]] facility and came in contact with nine workers. The FAA asks that Amazon.com be fined $350,000 for the incident. The FAA alleges that Amazon.com violated hazardous materials regulations on 24 other occasions between February 2013 and September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-06-13/amazon-fined-by-u-s-faa-for-shipping-dangerous-cargo-on-planes|title=Amazon Fined by U.S. FAA for Air Shipment of Dangerous Cargo|date=13 June 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;14 June\n* The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) asks pilots in to avoid flying too low over [[walrus]] haul-out sites along the [[Chukchi Sea]] coast of northern [[Alaska]] because of the danger of frightening the walruses into stampeding and injuring and killing one another and nearby humans. Although the FAA says it does not plan to establish formal flight path and altitude restrictions on flights near walrus haul-out sites, it reminds pilots that harassing walruses is illegal under the U.S. [[Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972]]. Earlier in 2016, the FAA had instructed airplane pilots to fly no closer than {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} to walrus haul-outs and no lower than an altitude over {{convert|2000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and helicopter pilots to fly no closer than {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} and no lower than {{convert|3000|ft|km}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2016/06/23/the-grim-reason-pilots-need-to-worry-about-walruses/|title=The grim reason pilots need to worry about walruses}}</ref>\n\n;15 June\n* The [[Government of Egypt]] announces that it has found and made images of the wreckage of Egyptair Flight 804 on the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea. The Airbus A320-232 had crashed on 19 May 2016, killing all 66 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/dde4f3596024470486050521ae995328/egypt-says-it-has-found-plane-wreckage|title=Egypt says it has found plane wreckage|access-date=16 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616221758/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dde4f3596024470486050521ae995328/egypt-says-it-has-found-plane-wreckage|archive-date=16 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* After it successfully launches a [[satellite]] into Earth orbit, the first stage of [[SpaceX]]'s [[Falcon 9]] rocket fails to make what would have been the fifth successful landing of a reusable booster rocket when one of its booster engines fails, causing it to descend far too quickly toward the floating platform in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] on which SpaceX intended it to land. The rapid descent causes it to make what SpaceX founder [[Elon Musk]] deems the \"hardest impact\" ever by a Falcon 9 first stage and results in its destruction \u2013 what Musk terms its \"rapid unscheduled disassembly.\" Musk adds that upgrades to correct the problem could be in service by the end of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/06/15/spacexs-latest-rocket-landing-ended-in-a-rapid-unscheduled-disassembly/|title=SpaceX\u2019s latest rocket landing ended in a 'rapid unscheduled disassembly'}}</ref>\n\n;16 June\n* The [[cockpit voice recorder]] from Egyptair Flight 804 is recovered from a depth of about {{convert|9800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} in the Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36551464|title=EgyptAir MS804 crash: Voice recorder recovered from sea|date=16 June 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;17 June\n* Two [[Japan Air Self-Defense Force]] fighter aircraft scramble to intercept two Chinese fighters over the [[East China Sea]] near the Japanese-controlled [[Senkaku Islands]] (called the Diaoyu Islands in China). In [[2016 in aviation#July|July]], the [[People's Republic of China]] will criticize the Japanese pilots' actions during the encounter.<ref name=\"ap20160705\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/china-confirms-close-encounter-japan-fighter-jets-over-east-china-sea/|title=China confirms fighter jet encounter with Japan}}</ref>\n* [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] strikes on rebel targets in Aleppo, Syria, during the evening kill at least seven people, with one report placing the death toll at nine. According to [[Doctors Without Borders]], one of the strikes puts Aleppo's biggest hospital out of service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/848713a21a0141f496c0c97bbeb0e99f/2-syrian-media-activists-seriously-wounded-explosion|title=Strikes on Syria's divided Aleppo kill 7; activists wounded}}</ref>\n* The [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] releases images which suggest that the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] used [[cluster bomb]]s in a raid against U.S.-backed Syrian rebels near [[Al-Tanf]], Syria, earlier in the week that killed two people and wounded four. The images show what appears to be the tail section of a Russian RBK-500 cluster bomb.<ref name=gibbonsneff201606818>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/18/images-suggest-that-russia-cluster-bombed-u-s-backed-syrian-fighters/|title=Images suggest that Russia cluster-bombed U.S.-backed Syrian fighters}}</ref>\n* The [[flight data recorder]] from Egyptair Flight 804 is recovered from a depth of about {{convert|9800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} in the Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/17/middleeast/egyptair-wreckage-found/index.html|title=EgyptAir Flight 804: Second black box found|author1=Michael Pearson |author2=Lorenza Brascia|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Later in the day, the [[Government of Egypt]] announces that the aircraft's cockpit voice recorder and flight data recorder had suffered extensive damage prior to their recovery, necessitating repairs that will delay processing of the information they recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jun/17/egyptair-flight-ms804-extensively-damaged-black-boxes-will-need-repairs-before-analysis|title=EgyptAir flight MS804: repairs needed to 'extensively damaged' black boxes|first=Associated|last=Press|date=17 June 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n* At a conference of [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] Administrator [[Charles Bolden]] announces plans for the [[NASA X-57 Maxwell|X-57 Maxwell]], a 14-motor, all-electric airplane. The program is intended spur the development of more energy-efficient and cleaner [[general aviation]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/18/science/nasa-electric-plane-x57.html|title=NASA Unveils Plans for Electric-Powered Plane|first=Kenneth|last=Chang|date=17 June 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;18 June\n* Touring [[Fallujah]], Iraq, the day after the [[Government of Iraq]] declared victory in its operation to retake Fallujah from the Islamic State, [[Lieutenant General]] Abdelwahab al-Saedi, the [[Iraqi Army]] commander of the operation, tells the press that an estimated 300 to 700 Islamic State personnel had been in the city when the operation began and that most had been killed by airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-gains-on-the-islamic-state-in-fallujah-iraqi-forces-strike-south-of-mosul/2016/06/18/0414a862-34bb-11e6-ab9d-1da2b0f24f93_story.html|title=Inside Fallujah, Iraqi forces dodge snipers and car bombs in final fight for the city}}</ref>\n* A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman announces that during a [[video teleconference]] the Department of Defense had \"expressed strong concerns\" to the [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Russian Miniistry of Defense]] about the Russian Federation Air Force's use of cluster bombs in a raid in Syria earlier in the week.<ref name=gibbonsneff201606818/>\n\n;19 June\n* Aircraft supporting a Syrian government ground offensive against Islamic State forces holding Tabqa air base strike the nearby city of [[Al-Thawrah]], Syria, with [[cluster munition]]s, reportedly killed 10 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2f834ca0edea4fd284cd8cff8c9e5063/activists-say-8-syrians-killed-trying-cross-turkey|title=Syrian forces advance on IS-held air base}}</ref>\n* During a [[parachute]] failure test, [[Blue Origin]] lands its [[New Shepard]] [[Reusable launch system|reusable space launch system]] in [[West Texas]], the fourth time the same Blue Origin rocket has made a [[Sub-orbital spaceflight|suborbital flight]] into space and landed intact. During the unmanned flight, New Shepard's capsule and rocket separate and controllers deliberately induce a parachute failure to test the capsule's ability to land safely after the failure of one of its three parachutes. The rocket, using [[wing]]s and firing of its engine to make its descent, lands about seven minutes before the capsule, and both landings are successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/reusable-rocket-clears-fourth-trial-run-at-bezos-space-exploration-firm/2016/06/19/90a89978-366e-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Reusable rocket clears fourth trial run at Bezos space-exploration firm}}</ref>\n* The [[Terrafugia Transition]] [[Roadable aircraft|roadable airplane]] receives exemptions from the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration as a \"light sport aircraft.\" The administrative action puts the United States on track to legalize a flying car for consumer use for the first time. Provided that their roadable aircraft overcome various regulatory barriers, manufacturers of such aircraft expect them to enter the consumer market over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/06/20/flying-cars-just-took-a-big-step-closer-to-being-legal/|title=Flying cars just took a big step closer to being legal}}</ref>\n\n;20 June\n* With [[Bertrand Piccard]] at the controls, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) departs John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City to begin the 15th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for the nonstop [[transatlantic flight]] to [[Seville Airport]] in [[Seville]], [[Spain]], to cover {{convert|3564|mi|km}} and take at least 90 hours.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 15: New York to Sevillerk|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-15-from-New_York-to-Seville |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;21 June\n* After a 10-hour flight from [[Rothera Research Station]] on the [[Antarctic Peninsula]], a Canadian [[Kenn Borek Air]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter]] lands at [[Amundsen\u2013Scott South Pole Station]] at the [[Geographic South Pole]] in [[Antarctica]] to evacuate two workers there who have fallen ill. It is only the third flight to the station to take place during the Antarctic winter during the 60 years since the station opened in 1956; generally, no flights to the station occur from February to October each year. After a layover at the Amundsen-Scott station, the plane makes a 10-hour return flight to the Rothera station the following day with the patients on board. It is only the third time that anyone has been evacuated from the South Pole during the Antarctic winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/06/16/a-rare-risky-mission-is-underway-to-rescue-sick-scientists-from-the-south-pole/|title=Plane takes off from the South Pole in rare, risky effort to rescue sick workers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/06/22/rescuers-succeed-in-evacuating-sick-workers-at-the-south-pole/|title=Rescuers succeed in evacuating sick workers at the South Pole}}</ref>\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] releases U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) regulations for the use of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs, or \"drones\") by hobbyists in the [[United States]]. They require drone pilots to keep their UAVs in sight, to operate them only in daylight, and to fly them no higher than an altitude of {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and prohibit their operation over strangers. The regulations also require that hobbyists' UAVs weigh no more than {{convert|55|lb|kg}} and prohibit them from flying over the [[District of Columbia]]. The FAA reports that 2.5 million UAVs will be sold to hobbyists in the United States during 2016 and that 7 million will be sold in 2020. The new regulations require U.S. commercial UAV operators to be vetted by the U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] and to pass an aeronautical knowledge examination administered at an FAA-approved test center, but do not address over-the-horizon operations by commercial UAVs; the FAA reports that there are 10,602 registered commercial UAVs in the United States and projects that 600,000 UAVs intended for commercial use will be sold in the United States during 2016 and that 2.7 million will be sold for commercial use in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/white-house-rolls-out-rules-for-drone-operations/2016/06/21/0508557a-3763-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Before feared spike in drone crashes, White House sets new rules}}</ref>\n* The [[Boeing|Boeing Company]] announces a tentative deal in which [[Iran Air]], which is seeking to upgrade its aging fleet of pre-1979 Boeing aircraft with new [[Boeing 737]]s and [[Boeing 777]]s, has signed an agreement expressing its \"intent\" to buy airliners from Boeing in the first major U.S. trade deal with [[Iran]] following a 2015 nuclear accord between Iran and the United States. The deal is expected to face political and regulatory hurdles, but if it proceeds on schedule the first new Boeing airliners are expected to arrive in Iran in October 2016. Depending on the number of new aircraft purchased and the number of leased and older aircraft ultimately included in the transaction, the deal could be worth up to $25,000,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/boeing-reaches-tentative-plane-sale-pact-with-iran-in-first-major-post-sanction-outreach/2016/06/21/2f38e7c6-379d-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Boeing reaches tentative plane-sale deal with Iran in first major post-sanctions outreach}}</ref>\n\n;22 June\n* The [[Australian Transport Safety Bureau]] announces that a piece of aircraft debris found in a pile of seaweed and wood in the [[Indian Ocean]] off [[Kangaroo Island]] off the coast of [[South Australia]] on 9 June is not from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]] with 239 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/22/asia/mh370-debris-kangaroo-island-atsb/index.html|title=Officials: Australian plane debris not from MH370|first=Ben |last=Westcott|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n;23 June\n* Airstrikes combine with [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] attacks to kill eight people in Aleppo, Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/939c655a16c9442b8229e7602426923b/shelling-and-airstrikes-kill-8-syrian-city-aleppo|title=US-backed forces enter IS bastion in Syria amid clashes}}</ref>\n* Flown by Bertrand Piccard, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) lands at Seville Airport in Seville, Spain, completing the 15th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. The nonstop transatlantic flight from John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City, begun on 20 June, covers {{convert|3890.5|mi|km}} in 71&nbsp;hours 8&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|54.7|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 15: New York to Seville|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-15-from-New_York-to-Seville |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n* An [[Air Serbia]] [[Airbus A330]] lands at John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City after a nonstop flight from [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], inaugurating the airline's first transatlantic route and Serbia's first nonstop airline service to the United States by a local airline since [[Jat Airways]], the national airline of the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]], discontinued the route in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/06/23/new-airline-us-first-nonstop-serbia-flight-24-years/86281150/|title=USA-Serbia nonstops now flying for first time in 24 years}}</ref>\n* [[Aerom\u00e9xico]] announces that it is suspending service to [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]], due to the complicated economic situation in Venezuela. It is the third airline to halt service to Venezuela. Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult for airlines to convert ticket sales revenue to [[United States dollar]]s to cover their costs of operating in Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/aeromexico-latest-airline-suspend-flights-venezuela-40085608|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;24 June\n* A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman announces that U.S. forces have conducted airstrikes against the Taliban in southern Afghanistan during the previous week. The strikes follow a decision by President Barack Obama earlier in June to expand U.S. airstrikes in Afghanistan to assist Afghan forces in offensive operations against the Taliban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/us-launches-first-airstrikes-against-afghan-taliban/2016/06/24/e96e8c3e-3a29-11e6-af02-1df55f0c77ff_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=24 June 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-june-24-2016/2016/06/24/1533bf98-3a15-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=World Digest: June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;25 June\n* Airstrikes reportedly made by Russian planes kill at least 30 people in the Islamic State-held town of [[Qourieh]] in Syria's [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]]. One report puts the death toll a 46.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6b87ecb1cf54418594d5cd231edd088d/hundreds-syrian-kurds-flee-held-areas-amid-abductions|title=Hundreds of Syrian Kurds flee IS-held areas amid abductions}}</ref>\n\n;26 June\n* A [[National Army of Colombia]] [[Mil Mi-17]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter crashes in mountainous terrain in [[Caldas Department]] in central [[Colombia]], killing all 17 people on board. Its wreckage is not found until the following day.\n\n;27 June\n* After the crew of [[Singapore Airlines Flight 368]], a [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777-312ER]] (registration 9V-SWB), sees an oil leak warning for its right engine two hours into a flight from [[Singapore Changi Airport]], [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], to [[Milan\u2013Malpensa Airport]], [[Ferno]], [[Italy]], the crew opts to return to Singapore Changi. Upon landing there, the right engine catches fire, and the fire quickly engulfs the entire right wing. It is extinguished in five minutes, and none of the 241 people on board are injured. \n* [[President of Turkey|Turkish president]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] sends an apology in writing to [[President of Russia|Russian president]] [[Vladimir Putin]] for the [[Turkish Air Force]]'s downing of a Russian Federation Air Force aircraft over Syria in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-apologizes-for-shooting-down-russian-warplane-last-year/2016/06/27/d969e0ea-3c6d-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Turkish president apologizes for downing of Russian warplane last year}}</ref>\n\n;28 June\n* A three-person suicide team armed with [[Kalashnikov rifle]]s and [[suicide bomb]]s attacks the international terminal at [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]] in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], blowing themselves up in the terminal's arrival and departure areas and in a nearby parking lot. The attack kills at least 44 people and injures more than 230 others. All flights into and out of the airport are temporarily suspended after the attack, and the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration temporarily grounds all flights to and from Istanbul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36658187|title=Istanbul Ataturk airport attack: 41 dead and more than 230 hurt|date=29 June 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/turkey-ataturk-airport-attack-explosions-gunfire-latest-a7108241.html|title=Dozens killed after suicide bombers attack airport in Istanbul|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=cunningham20160629>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-urges-world-to-stand-firm-against-terrorism-after-airport-carnage/2016/06/29/6457228c-3d70-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Turkey and the Islamic State appear to be headed toward outright war}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkish-police-conduct-raids-on-suspected-islamic-state-hideouts-after-deadly-airport-attack/2016/06/30/2b91d61a-3e5e-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Istanbul airport attackers identified as Russian, Uzbek and Kyrgyz nationals}}</ref>\n\n;29 June\n* Iran announces that it has suspended all commercial flights to Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport.<ref name=cunningham20160629/>\n* After a nonstop transatlantic flight from [[Marine Corps Air Station Beaufort]], [[South Carolina]], three Lockheed Martin F-35B Lightning II aircraft arrive at [[RAF Fairford]] in the [[United Kingdom]], making the first landing in the United Kingdom by any variant of the F-35. A [[Royal Air Force]] F-35B lands first, followed by two [[United States Marine Corps]] F-35Bs that accompanied it on the flight. Supporting the flight are two [[United States Air Force]] [[McDonnell Douglas KC-10 Extender|KC-10A Extender]] tankers, a U.S. Marine Corps [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|KC-130J Super Hercules]] tanker, and a Royal Air Force C-130J Super Hercules [[search-and-rescue]] plane.<ref name=aeroresource20160629>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeroresource.co.uk/news/f-35-arrives-uk/|title=First F-35 Lightning IIs arrive in United Kingdom \u2013 AeroResource}}</ref>\n\n;29\u201330 June (overnight)\n* U.S. and British planes and Iraqi planes and [[attack helicopters]] attack two large [[convoy]]s of ground vehicles carrying Islamic State combatant personnel and their families attempting to flee Fallujah, Iraq. The strikes destroy at least 150 vehicles and kill about 250 people; the Iraqi armed forces claim that the strikes destroy 798 vehicles including eight [[car bomb]]s and kill hundreds of Islamic State combat personnel, with the U.S.-led coalition responsible for 117 of the vehicles and three of the car bombs and Iraqi aircraft destroying the rest. A spokesman for the U.S.-led coalition says that coalition aircraft attempted to avoid striking portions of the convoys it thought included civilians. The U.S. aircraft participating in the attack had been called away from supporting Syrian rebel forces attempting to capture [[Bukamal]], Syria, from the Islamic State and, lacking air support, the Syrian rebels are defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/30/iraqi-gunships-u-s-jets-target-islamic-state-convoys-outside-fallujah-and-ramadi/|title=Iraqi, U.S. aircraft bomb convoy of Islamic State fighters fleeing Fallujah with their families}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/07/06/u-s-jets-abandoned-syrian-rebels-in-the-desert-then-they-lost-a-battle-to-isis/|title=U.S. jets abandoned Syrian rebels in the desert. Then they lost a battle to ISIS.}}</ref>\n\n;30 June\n* [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Ashton Carter]] announces that earlier in the week the United States offered to share intelligence with Russia to improve Russian targeting of terrorist groups in Syria if Russia agrees to cease airstrikes against civilians and against rebel groups that have agreed to a ceasefire and to use its influence with the [[Government of Syria]] to force the regime of [[Bashar al-Assad]] to sign on to the ceasefire. The United States offer does not include joint military planning, joint targeting, or coordination of Russian airstrikes with U.S. airstrikes or other U.S. operations in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-offers-to-share-syria-intelligence-on-terrorists-with-russia/2016/06/30/483a2afe-3eec-11e6-84e8-1580c7db5275_story.html|title=U.S. offers to share Syria intelligence on terrorists with Russia}}</ref>\n* U.S. Air Force F-35 Lightning II aircraft deploy outside the United States for the first time when three F-35A aircraft of the [[56th Fighter Wing]] land at RAF Fairford in the United Kingdom after a nonstop transatlantic flight supported by a U.S. Air Force KC-10A Extender tanker.<ref name=aeroresource20160629/>\n\n===July===\n*[[Tunisair]] inaugurates its first [[Transatlantic flight|transatlantic]] service, operating between [[Tunis]] and [[Montreal]].\n\n;1 July\n* A U.S. airstrike in southern [[Yemen]] kills two members of [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=ap20160708>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5f02012d830d4c68aeeb14898b6b5fd9/us-says-2-drone-strikes-yemen-killed-4-al-qaida-members|title=US Central Command: 2 Yemen strikes kill 4 al-Qaida members}}</ref>\n* A [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] fighter aircraft crashes near [[Jeiroud]] in a rebel-held part of [[Syria]] during what the [[Government of Syria]] claims was a training flight. Rebels capture and interrogate its pilot, then shoot him to death.<ref name=Issa20160702>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ae6ef8f5175547e6909af374791bc168/airstrikes-kill-25-opposition-area-near-syrian-capital|title=Syrian activists say airstrikes on rebel-held area kill 25}}</ref>\n* A Russian [[Ministry of Emergency Situations (Russia)|Ministry of Emergency Situations]] [[Ilyushin Il-76]] [[aerial firefighting]] plane (registration RA-76840) [[2016 Ministry of Emergency Situations fire fighting Il-76 crash|crashes]] in the [[Kachugskiy District]] near [[Lake Baikal]] in [[Russia]] while fighting a [[forest fire]], killing all 10 people on board. Its wreckage will be found on 3 July.\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] releases a report claiming that between 2009 and the end of 2015 the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] and the [[United States armed forces]] have carried out a combined 473 airstrikes using [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (or \"drones\") against terrorist targets in countries where it defines the [[United States]] as not being at war \u2013 not named in the report, but including [[Libya]], [[Pakistan]], [[Somalia]], and [[Yemen]] \u2013 killing between 2,372 and 2,581 \"combatants\" and inadvertently killing between 64 and 116 civilians. The report excludes deaths in [[Afghanistan]], [[Iraq]], and [[Syria]], which are countries in which the administration deems the [[United States]] to be at war. Critics of the report claim that it underestimates civilian casualties; the [[Long War Journal]] puts the civilian death toll at 212, the [[New America Foundation]] estimates it at 219, and the [[Bureau of Investigative Journalism]] claims it is at least 325.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/white-house-releases-its-count-of-civilian-deaths-in-counterterrorism-operations-under-obama/2016/07/01/3196aa1e-3fa2-11e6-80bc-d06711fd2125_story.html|title=White House releases its count of civilian deaths in counterterrorism operations under Obama}}</ref>\n\n;2 July\n* [[State of Israel|Israeli]] aircraft strike four [[Hamas]] training sites in the [[Gaza Strip]], damaging buildings but harming no one. The strike is in response to a rocket attack against Israel from the Gaza Strip the previous day that damaged an empty [[kindergarten]] building without killing or injuring anyone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_ISRAEL_PALESTINIANS?SITE=AP|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held Jeiroud, Syria \u2013 suspected of being Syrian government strikes conducted in retaliation for the kiliing of a captured Syrian Arab Air Force pilot by rebels in the area the previous day \u2013 kill at least 25 people. One report puts the overall death toll at 31, and another report claims that seven medical personnel are among those killed in at least 40 air attacks against the town during the day.<ref name=Issa20160702/>\n\n;3 July\n* Airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition support an offensive by U.S.-backed Syrian rebel forces against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] positions near [[Manbij]], Syria, but the Islamic State succeeds in repelling the rebel attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-july-3-2016/2016/07/03/a670d282-411f-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|title=World Digest: July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;4 July\n* China protests the \"provocative actions\" of two [[Japan Air Self-Defense Force]] fighter aircraft on [[2016 in aviation#June|17 June]] when they intercepted two Chinese fighters over the [[East China Sea]] near the Japanese-controlled [[Senkaku Islands]] (called the Diaoyu Islands in China), claiming that the Chinese fighters were on a routine patrol when the Japanese aircraft locked onto them with [[fire control radar]] and adding that the Chinese planes took \"tactical measures\" before the Japanese aircraft left the area.<ref name=\"ap20160705\"/><ref name=rajagopalan20160704>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-japan-idUSKCN0ZL28B|title=China criticizes Japan over 'dangerous' jet scramble|date=5 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike in Yemen's [[Shabwa Governorate]] kills two members of Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula.<ref name=ap20160708/>\n\n;5 July\n* [[Japan]] denies that its aircraft engaged in any provocative or dangerous activities while intercepting two Chinese fighters over the East China Sea on 17 June, adding that its aircraft scrambled to intercept Chinese military aircraft about 200 times between 1 April and 30 June 2016, up from about 80 times during the same period in [[2015 in aviation|2015]].<ref name=\"ap20160705\"/><ref name=rajagopalan20160704/>\n\n;7 July\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] announces that it has tentatively awarded eight U.S. airlines \u2013 out of 12 that applied for them \u2013 nonstop flights between the [[United States]] and [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], with the awards to be finalized at the end of July and service to begin during the autumn of 2016. The flights are: [[Alaska Airlines]] from [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[American Airlines]] from [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]], and [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]; [[Delta Airlines]] from [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], Miami, and [[New York City]]'s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]; [[Frontier Airlines]] from Miami; [[JetBlue]] from [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]] and [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], Florida, and John F. Kennedy International; [[Southwest Airlines]] from Fort Lauderdale and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida; [[Spirit Airlines]] from Fort Lauderdale; and [[United Airlines]] from [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]], and [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]]. The flights will provide the first scheduled commercial air service between the United States and Havana since the early 1960s. Among rejected routes is a proposed United Airlines service from [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/eight-us-airlines-will-fly-between-american-cities-and-havana/2016/07/07/8184c5a8-4464-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|title=Eight U.S. airlines will fly between American cities and Havana}}</ref>\n\n;8 July\n* On the last day of a three-day ceasefire declared by the [[Syrian Arab Army]] but widely violated, unidentified jets belonging to either the Syrian Arab Air Force or the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] strike rebel-held [[Darkush]], Syria \u2013 a vacation spot for Syrians \u2013 during the [[Eid al-Fitr]] holiday weekend, killing at least 23 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-idlib-idUKKCN0ZO1BZ|title=Almost 50 killed in Syria on ceasefire's last day: monitor|first=Reuters|last=Editorial}}</ref>\n* Islamic State forces shoot down a helicopter near [[Palmyra]], Syria, killing two Russian pilots on board. Russia claims the helicopter was a Syrian [[Mil Mi-25]] helicopter the Russians were flying on a training mission when they were diverted to take action against an Islamic State ground attack, which they thwarted before they were shot down by a U.S.-made [[BGM-71 TOW]] missile. News reports and independent experts, however, claim that the downed helicopter actually was a [[Mil Mi-35|Mil Mi-35M]] [[attack helicopter]] belonging to the Russian armed forces and operating on a combat mission, and that whatever shot it down was very unlikely to have been a BGM-71 TOW.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/12/russia-just-lied-about-losing-a-gunship-to-isis-heres-why-thats-not-surprising/|title=Russia may have lied about losing a gunship to ISIS}}</ref>\n\n;9 July\n* A U.S. air-to-ground missile strike by an unmanned aerial vehicle in [[Afghanistan]] targeting members of the [[Islamic State-Khorasan Province]] group kills five [[Islamist]] militants including Umar Narai, also known as Khalifa Umar Mansoor, a leader of the [[Tariq Gidar Group]] who masterminded a [[2014 Peshawar school massacre|2014 attack]] by the [[Pakistani Taliban]] on a school in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]], that killed 148 people and injured 114.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-taliban-idUSKCN0ZT21O|title=Pakistan says leader of school attack killed in U.S. drone strike|date=14 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* Supported by airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition, Iraqi ground forces recapture [[Qayyarah Airfield West|Qayyarah Air Base]] in the [[Qayyarah subdistrict]] of [[Mosul District]] in [[Nineveh Governorate]], Iraq, from the Islamic State. The commander of Iraqi counterterrorism forces credits the coalition airstrikes with destroying 60 Islamic State car bombs. With a runway capable of handling heavy cargo planes and room for many helicopters, the newly captyured air base promises to allow the support of further Iraqi advances into Islamic State-held territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/07/11/seizure-of-key-air-base-near-mosul-raises-prospect-of-u-s-escalation-against-isis/|title=Pentagon will send hundreds more troops to Iraq following seizure of key airfield}}</ref>\n* Using a plane chartered by the [[World Food Programme]], the [[United Nations]] begins an airlift of humanitarian aid to an estimated 275,000 people in Syria's [[Al-Hasakah Governorate]] who have been cut off from food and other supplies for six months. The first flight delivers 40 [[metric ton]]s of food, arriving during the evening at [[Kamishly Airport]] in [[Qamishli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/airlifts-food-cut-off-families-northeast-syria-40470850|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref> Plans call for the plane to make at least 25 flights between [[Damascus]], Syria, and Qamishli over the course of a month, delivering over 1,000 metric tons of food, medicine, and other relief supplies to Kamishly Airport.<ref>[http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/wfp-flight-delivers-40-tonnes-food-in-syria-2016-07-11-1.635371 Wam, \"WFP flight delivers 40 tonnes food in Syria,\" emirates247.com, 11 July 2016.]</ref>\n\n;10 July\n* Syrian government air raids strike a rebel-held neighborhood in [[Aleppo]] and a [[diesel fuel]] market in [[Turmanin]]. The Aleppo strike reportedly kills 10 people, while the air raids on Turmanin set several [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] on fire and kill at least eight and perhaps as many as 14 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/7292729de44a4616af8bf27f1b41b616/air-raids-hit-diesel-market-syria-killing-8|title=More fighting in Syria's Aleppo, Idlib kills at least 26}}</ref>\n* In a briefing ahead of the opening of the [[Farnborough International Airshow]], the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Boeing]]'s commercial aircraft unit, Ray Conner, says that his company is seeing strong interest among airlines in a new mid-range airliner that could seat between 200 and 270 passengers and have a range of between {{convert|4500|and|5100|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}}, creating a new, larger market beyond that of the [[Boeing 757]] and [[Airbus A321neo]]. The first all-new Boeing aircraft since the [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]], the new airliner would cost $10,000,000,000 to $15,000,000,000 to develop and be the company's biggest potential product development over the next 10 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-10/boeing-sees-airline-thirst-for-new-mid-range-jetliner-family|title=Boeing Sees Airline Thirst for New Mid-Range Jetliner Family|date=10 July 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;11 July\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) departs [[Seville Airport]] in [[Seville]], [[Spain]], to begin the 16th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for the two-day nonstop solo flight to [[Cairo International Airport]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to pass over the [[Mediterranean Sea]], [[Tunisia]], [[Algeria]], [[Malta]], [[Italy]], and [[Greece]].<ref name=solar16>{{cite web|title=Leg 16: Seville to Cairo |url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-16-from-Seville-to-Cairo |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n*A [[Portuguese Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] transport aircraft crashes just after takeoff from [[Montijo Air Base]], [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], killing its entire three-man crew.<ref name=airlive20160711>{{cite web|url=http://www.airlive.net/breaking-a-lockheed-c-130-hercules-just-crashed-in-portugal/|title=BREAKING A Lockheed C-130 Hercules started to burn on take off from Portugal - AIRLIVE.net|first=Melanie|last=Kraft}}</ref>\n\n;12 July\n* [[Fedor Konyukhov]] departs [[Northam, Western Australia|Northam]], [[Western Australia]], to begin an attempt to circumnavigate the world solo in a [[hot-air balloon]]. He will complete the journey on 23 July.<ref name=Aljazeera20160724>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/07/fedor-konyukhov-breaks-world-hot-air-balloon-record-160723101753237.html|title=Fedor Konyukhov breaks world hot air balloon record}}</ref>\n* After nearly 45 years, the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] announces it has closed its investigation of the [[1971 in aviation#November|24 November 1971]] hijacking of Northwest Airlines Flight 305 by a man identifying himself as \"Dan Cooper\" \u2013 and misidentified by the press as \"[[D. B. Cooper]],\" the name by which he goes down in history \u2013 who parachuted from the airliner with $200,000 he had demanded and was never seen or heard from again. The \"D. B. Cooper\" skyjacking is the only unsolved American [[aircraft hijacking]] case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/07/12/the-d-b-cooper-case-has-baffled-the-fbi-for-45-years-now-it-may-never-be-solved/|title=The D.B. Cooper case has baffled the FBI for 45 years. Now it may never be solved.}}</ref>\n\n;13 July\n* The day after the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]] ruled against the [[People's Republic of China]] in ''[[Philippines vs. China]]'' regarding a [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|territorial dispute]] with the [[Philippines]] in the [[South China Sea]], two Chinese civilian aircraft fly to Chinese-claimed islands in the South China Sea, one each landing at [[Mischief Reef]] and [[Subi Reef]]. Both return to China later in the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/china-faces-dilemma-after-ruling-double-down-or-cool-down/2016/07/13/7ae5edfc-486b-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Beijing\u2019s dilemma after South China Sea ruling: Double down or cool down?}}</ref>\n* An airstrike hits a market in rebel-held [[Ariha, Syria|Ariha]], Syria, killing at least nine and perhaps as many as 12 people. Another airstrike targeting a market in rebel-held [[Al-Rastan]], Syria, kills reportedly kills 16 people and wounds dozens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b1d44e6217aa4c98bda824a5d3155b8b/air-raids-northern-and-central-syria-kill-and-wound-many|title=Air raids in northern and central Syria kill and wound many}}</ref>\n* Flown by Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) lands at Cairo International Airport in Cairo, Egypt, completing the 16th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. The nonstop flight from Seville Airport in Seville, Spain, began on 11 July and passes over the Mediterranean Sea and portions of southern [[Europe]] and [[North Africa]], covering {{convert|2326|mi|km}} in 48&nbsp;hours 50&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|45.8|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}. ''Solar Impulse 2'' passes over the [[Giza pyramid complex]] before landing at Cairo International.<ref name=solar16/>\n* At a meeting of the [[NATO-Russia Council]], Russian diplomats propose to the representatives of [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) member countries that all aircraft flying over the [[Baltic Sea]] do so with their [[Transponder (aeronautics)|transponders]] on as a way of improving air safety. Although NATO requires all aircraft flown under its command to fly with their transponders on, the aircraft of NATO member countries do not always turn them on when flying separately from NATO control, and Russian aircraft also have flown with them off. The NATO representatives welcome the proposal and promise to study it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-vents-anger-over-natos-latest-moves/2016/07/13/37404e7c-48fb-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Russia offers plan to improve air safety over Baltics}}</ref>\n* Citing a need to strike back against those responsible for terrorist attacks in [[France]] in [[January 2015 \u00cele-de-France attacks|January 2015]] and [[November 2015 Paris attacks|November 2015]], [[President of France]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] announces that the [[French Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91)|Charles de Gaulle]]'' will deploy to the [[Middle East]] to participate in operations against the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0ZT276|title=France to deploy aircraft carrier against Islamic State: Hollande |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n;14 July\n* A series of airstrikes on rebel-held districts of Aleppo, Syria, reportedly kill 12 people.<ref name=eldeeb20160714>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-07-13-13-30-30|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* The Islamic State reportedly shoots down a Syrian Arab Air Force jet near the military airport at [[Deir ez-Zor]], Syria, killing its pilot. The Islamic State releases a video purportedly showing the pilot's body strung up on a pole, and the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] reports that his body had been [[Crucifixion|crucifed]].<ref name=eldeeb20160714/>\n* [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] meets in [[Moscow]] with [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] to discuss a U.S. proposal supported by senior [[United Nations]] officials to \"integrate\" U.S. and Russian air operations against Islamic State and [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] targets in Syria and halt Syrian government and Russian air attacks against civilians and moderate Syrian rebel forces that are parties to a widely violated February 2016 ceasefire agreement. The proposal calls for Russia to pressure the Syrian government to ground all Syrian military aircraft and restrict Russian airstrikes to Islamic State and Jabhat al-Nusra targets, and for U.S. airstrikes against Jabhat al-Nusra \u2013 previously conducted only rarely to avoid direct U.S. involvement in the [[Syrian Civil War]] \u2013 to expand alongside strikes against Islamic State targets in Syria. Under the proposal, Russia and the United States \u2013 via a Joint Implementation Group headquartered in [[Amman]], [[Jordan]] \u2013 would share intelligence and strike planning for Jabhat al-Nusra leadership targets, headquarters, training camps, logistical depots, and supply lines, with other areas off-limits to airstrikes by either country, and a \"liaison body\" would ensure that Russia and the United States inform one another at least a day in advance of planned strikes against agreed-upon targets. The proposal calls for implementation of an agreement by 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/kerry-says-iran-deal-has-made-world-a-safer-place-one-year-later/2016/07/14/a954071c-484f-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Kerry arrives in Moscow with a proposal for Syria in hand}}</ref> The following day, Kerry and [[Foreign Minister of Russia]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announce after day-long talks that the two countries have reached an agreement that could reduce civilian casualties and improve targeting of terrorist groups, but they reveal no details to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-and-russia-have-plan-to-quell-conflict-in-syria-but-wont-say-what-it-is/2016/07/15/4cfb6a72-4850-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=U.S. and Russia have plan to quell conflict in Syria but won\u2019t say what it is}}</ref>\n* [[Airbus]] and [[Boeing]] experience their lowest airliner sales totals at the [[Farnborough Air Show]] in six years, securing deals for about 400 aircraft worth about $50,000,000,000, only half their sales at the previous year's show. American, European, and [[Persian Gulf]] carriers make almost no deals, and only carriers in [[Asia]] make large orders. No orders materialize for the [[Boeing 777]], [[Airbus A330neo]], or [[Bombardier C-Series]], and [[Airbus A380]] production rates are greatly reduced. Industry analysts blame the reduced sales on uncertainty over the future of the global economy and on the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|23 June 2016 vote]] to leave the [[European Union]], popularly known as the \"Brexit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-14/air-show-pop-fizzles-as-airbus-boeing-orders-at-six-year-low|title=Air-Show Pop Fizzles as Airbus, Boeing Orders at Six-Year Low|date=14 July 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;15\u201316 July (overnight)\n* A group of military officers in [[Turkey]] \u2013 mostly from the [[Turkish Air Force]], [[Turkish Army]] armored forces, and police and security organizations \u2013 [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|attempts a ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']] against the government of [[President of Turkey|President]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]. In [[Ankara]], [[Esenbo\u011fa International Airport]] closes. In [[G\u00f6lba\u015f\u0131, Ankara|G\u00f6lba\u015f\u0131]], just outside Ankara, pro-''coup'' military helicopters attack the police special forces headquarters, the police air force headquarters, and the headquarters of [[T\u00fcrksat (company)|T\u00fcrksat]], leaving 42 dead and 43 injured. Pro-''coup'' helicopters also attack the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|parliament]] building in Ankara; the [[Government of Turkey|Turkish government]] declares a [[no-fly zone]] over the city and a pro-government Turkish Air Force [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] shoots down a pro-''coup'' helicopter in the area. In [[Istanbul]], pro-''coup'' military forces move into [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]], forcing it to close and all flights there to be cancelled, and [[Turkish Air Force]] jets fly low over the city, generating [[sonic boom]]s. In [[Marmaris]], two or three helicopters attack a hotel where Erdo\u011fan had been vacationing and discharge troops who exchange gunfire with police officers, killing two and injuring eight of the police. At [[Incirlik Air Base]], from which [[United States Air Force]] aircraft are operating as part of the [[American-led intervention in Syria]], authorities close all access and cut power to the base, but normal operations there are restored within 24 hours. The ''coup'' attempt soon is defeated, and one Turkish military [[Black Hawk helicopter]], escorted by [[Hellenic Air Force]] F-16s, makes an emergency landing at [[Alexandroupoli Airport]] in [[Alexandroupoli]], [[Greece]], where Greek authorities arrests its eight occupants \u2013 who request [[political asylum]] \u2013 for making an illegal landing; their helicopter is returned to Turkey on 17 July.\n\n;17 July\n* [[Israel]] fires two [[MIM-104 Patriot]] [[surface-to-air missile]]s at an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) that flies from Syria into airspace over the Israeli-controlled [[Golan Heights]]. The UAV turns away and flies back into Syria.<ref name=reuters20160717>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-syria-interception-idUSKCN0ZX0OR|title=Israel launches anti-aircraft missiles at Syrian drone: army|date=17 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* According to Syrian rebels, the Syrian military conducts a rare air raid along the border with [[Jordan]], striking the village of al-Shajara, Syria, held by [[Shuhada al-Yarmouk]], group thought to be aligned with [[al-Qaeda]].<ref name=reuters20160717/>\n* Libyan militia forces fighting against the [[United Nations]]-backed [[Government of Libya]] shoot down a French helicopter in [[Libya]], killing three French soldiers on board. On 19 July, the Libyan government will announce that the helicopter had been shot down by an [[Islamist]] militia; on 20 July the [[Government of France]] will make its first public admission that French [[special forces]] are operating in Libya, and President of France Fran\u00e7ois Hollande will announce that the three dead soldiers were carrying out \"dangerous intelligence operations\" when their helicopter was shot down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36843186|title=Libya attack: French soldiers die in helicopter crash|date=20 July 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*An experienced pilot is killed after crashing while performing at an airshow in [[Cold Lake, Alberta]], [[Canada]]. He was flying a [[North American T-28 Trojan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/experienced-pilot-dies-after-plane-crashes-at-cold-lake-air-show-1.3683081|title=Pilot Bruce Evans dead after plane crash at Cold Lake Air Show}}</ref>\n\n;18 July\n* Airstrikes against Islamic State-held areas in Syria by the U.S.-led coalition kill 15 people in [[Manbij]] and six people in nearby [[Tokhar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/article/6783267/2016/07/18/coalition-raids-kill-21-civilians-syria|title=Anonymous, \"Coalition raids kill 21 civilians in Syria,\" Agence France-Presse, July 18, 2016, 11:05 a.m.}}</ref> [[United States Central Command]] announces that during the day the coalition conducted 18 airstrikes, destroying 13 Islamic State fighting positions, two car bombs, and seven other Islamic State ground vehicles.<ref name=mroue20160719>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-activists-airstrikes-on-is-held-villages-in-syria-kill-56-2016-7|title=Activists: Airstrikes on IS-held villages in Syria kill 56}}</ref>\n* The pilot and copilot of [[Air Transat]] Flight 725, an [[Airbus A310]] with about 250 passengers on board, are arrested at [[Glasgow Airport]] for being drunk as they prepare to fly the aircraft from [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], to [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. The airline suspends them the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/19/pilots-arrested-glasgow-toronto-flight-suspicion-too-drunk-to-fly|title=Pilots arrested on suspicion of being too drunk to take Glasgow-Toronto flight|first=Press|last=Association|date=19 July 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/air-transat-pilots-arrest-1.3684955 Lupton, Andrew, and Errol Nazareth, \"2 Air Transat pilots charged with being impaired before Glasgow to Toronto flight\", ''CBC News'', 19 July 2016, 6:41 AM EDT.]</ref>\n* After launching a [[Dragon spacecraft]], the first stage of a [[SpaceX]] [[Falcon 9]] rocket returns to make a soft landing at the [[Kennedy Space Center]] in [[Cape Canaveral, Florida|Cape Canaveral]], [[Florida]], landing about eight minutes after liftoff. It is only the second time a Falcon 9 first stage has made a successful landing on land, and it is the first such landing since [[2015 in aviation#December|21 December 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2016/07/18/spacex-sends-supplies-to-space-station-lands-another-falcon-rocket/|title=SpaceX sends supplies to space station, lands another Falcon rocket \u2013 Spaceflight Now|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref>\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] agrees to pay 2.6 million [[euro]]s to the relatives of Italian aid worker Giovanni Lo Porto, who was mistakenly killed in a [[Central Intelligence Agency]] unmanned aerial vehicle strike in Pakistan in [[2015 in aviation#January|January 2015]]. On 16 September 2016, [[United States Government]] officials will confirm the settlement publicly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-agrees-to-pay-nearly-3-million-to-family-of-italian-killed-in-cia-strike/2016/09/16/5c213af6-7c1a-11e6-bd86-b7bbd53d2b5d_story.html|title=U.S. agrees to pay nearly $3 million to family of Italian killed in CIA strike}}</ref>\n\n;19 July\n* The U.S.-led coalition strikes Islamic State-held territory in northern Syria to help counter an Islamic State ground offensive against the U.S.-backed [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF). According to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights, 56 civilians die in the strikes, while other reports put the death toll as high as 212; for example, the Islamic State claims that U.S. strikes kill 160 civilians in Tokhar, and the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates (Syria)|Syrian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates]] claims a strike by French aircraft against Tokhar kills 120 civilians. An SDF spokesman disputes the claims of civilian deaths, saying that the strikes have killed large numbers of Islamic State personnel, and that the Islamic State has simply buried them quickly and falsely claimed that civilian deaths have occurred.<ref name=mroue20160719/> The U.S. military announces that U.S. aircraft have conducted 18 strikes in the Manbij area over the previous 24 hours \u2013 out of 450 in the area since [[2016 in aviation#May|May]] \u2013 and that it is launching an investigation to determine whether the allegations of civilian casualties are true.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/scores-of-civilians-killed-in-suspected-us-strikes-in-syria/2016/07/19/0246d5e0-89a4-458a-9c50-50095c9a12d9_story.html|title=Suspected U.S. airstrikes in Syria kill scores of civilians, activists say}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/21/an-airstrike-in-syria-killed-entire-families-instead-of-isis-fighters/|title=An airstrike in Syria killed entire families instead of ISIS fighters}}</ref> By late August, [[United States Central Command]] will report that it has concluded that the Tokhar strike \u2013 conducted by U.S. Air Force [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]] and [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52H Stratofortress]] aircraft using 500-pound (227-kg) [[GBU-31]] and [[GBU-54]] [[laser-guided bomb]]s to knock out a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] position \u2013 killed 85 Islamic militants and 10 civilians, while Syrian activists claim that all or most of the 95 dead were civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-500-pound-bombs-struck-their-targets-in-a-syrian-village-but-whom-did-they-kill/2016/08/26/30324884-649d-11e6-be4e-23fc4d4d12b4_story.html|title=500-pound bombs struck their targets in a Syrian village. But who was killed?}}</ref> \n* Since the U.S.-led coalition's air campaign in Iraq and Syria against the Islamic State began in [[2014 in aviation#August|August 2014]], U.S. aircraft have carried out over 10,500 strikes and the rest of the coalition combined has conducted 3,200.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-assembles-allied-nations-to-plot-out-next-stage-of-islamic-state-fight/2016/07/19/5adf337c-4da9-11e6-aa14-e0c1087f7583_story.html|title=Pentagon assembles allied nations to plot out next stage of Islamic State fight}}</ref>\n;20 July\n* A [[network router]] fails in [[Southwest Airlines]]\u2032 computer system and back-up systems fail to activate, causing a 12-hour outage that cripples the airline's flight operations throughout the [[United States]]. Normal operations will not resume fully until 24 July, by which time Southwest will have cancelled about 2,300 of the approximately 19,500 flights scheduled during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20160725-2300-canceled-flights-later-southwest-airlines-recovers-from-technical-outage.ece|title=2,300 canceled flights later, Southwest Airlines recovers from technical outage  \u2013 Southwest Airlines \u2013 Dallas News|date=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 July\n* An [[Indian Air Force]] [[Antonov An-32]] with 29 people on board [[2016 Indian Air Force An-32 disappearance|disappears]] over the [[Bay of Bengal]] during a flight from [[Tambaram]], [[India]], to [[Port Blair]] in the [[Andaman Islands]].\n\n;23 July\n* [[Fedor Konyukhov]] lands near [[Bonnie Rock, Western Australia|Bonnie Rock]], [[Western Australia]], setting a new world record for the fastest around-the-world flight in a [[hot-air balloon]] and becoming the second person in history \u2013 after [[Steve Fossett]] in [[2002 in aviation|2002]] \u2013 to pilot a [[Balloon (aircraft)|balloon]] around the world solo. He also sets a new speed record for an around-the-world balloon flight, completing it in 11 days, breaking the record Fossett set during his 2002 flight by two days. Departing Northam, Western Australia, on 12 July, he has flown over [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], the [[Pacific Ocean]], [[South America]], the [[Cape of Good Hope]] and the [[Southern Ocean]] before landing at Bonnie Rock, covering a distance of {{convert|34820|km|mi|abbr=on}} and reaching altitudes of {{convert|10000|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=Aljazeera20160724/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/jul/24/russian-adventurer-fedor-konyukhov-breaks-record-for-flying-solo-around-the-world|title=Russian adventurer Fedor Konyukhov breaks record for flying solo around the world|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=23 July 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n;23\u201324 July (overnight)\n* Syrian government airstrikes hit five medical clinics in Syria's [[Aleppo Governorate]] \u2013 four in Aleppo and one in [[Atarib]] \u2013 and a [[blood bank]] in Aleppo. The strikes kill at least five people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/07/24/world/middleeast/ap-ml-syria.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Intense Airstrikes in Syria's Aleppo Province Hit 5 Clinics,\" Associated Press, July 24, 2016, 12:51 P.M. EDT.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/07/syria-civil-war-airstrikes-hit-aleppo-hospitals-160724090834185.html|title=Syria civil war: Air strikes hit Aleppo hospitals}}</ref>\n\n;24 July\n* Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) departs [[Cairo International Airport]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to begin the 17th and final leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for a two-day nonstop solo flight to [[Al Bateen Executive Airport]] in [[Abu Dhabi]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]], where the journey had begun on [[2015 in aviation#March|9 March 2015]].<ref name=solar17>{{cite web|title=Leg 17: Cairo to Abu Dhabi |url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-17-from-Cairo-to-Abu_Dhabi|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;25 July\n* The U.S. [[Environmental Protection Agency]] issues an \"endangerment finding\" \u2013  a scientific assessment describing a danger to the environment \u2013 that determines that emissions from commercial airplane engines including [[carbon dioxide]], [[methane]], and [[nitrous oxide]] pose health risks to Americans and contribute to [[climate change]]. It is a first step in what could be a years-long process leading to the regulation of commercial aircraft engine emissions by the [[United States Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/07/25/white-house-takes-aim-at-a-fast-growing-source-of-emissions-airplanes/|title=White House takes aim at a fast-growing source of emissions: airplanes}}</ref>\n\n;26 July\n* A U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle-launched [[air-to-ground missile]] strike in Afghanistan's [[Nangarhar Province]] kills the Islamic State leader [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]]. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce his death on 12 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/us-drone-strike-killed-islamic-state-leader-afghanistan-41340026|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n* ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) becomes the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], it completes the final leg of its journey, flying nonstop from Cairo International Airport in Cairo, Egypt, to Al Bateen Executive Airport in Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates \u2013 where its round-the-world flight had begun on [[2015 in aviation#March|9 March 2015]] \u2013 covering {{convert|1673|mi|km}} in 48&nbsp;hours 37&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|34.4|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>[http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-17-from-Cairo-to-Abu_Dhabi \"We Are in Abu Dhabi\"], Solar Impulse, 26 July 2016</ref> Flown alternately by Piccard and Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' has made the {{convert|42428|km|abbr=on}} trip in 17 legs over 505&nbsp;days, spending 558&nbsp;hours 7&nbsp;minutes in the air at an average speed of {{convert|47.2|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|29114|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.\n\n;28 July\n* Syrian Arab Air Force aircraft drop leaflets over Aleppo, Syria, informing residents that the Government of Syria will allow them to escape the surrounded city via three safe corridors and that rebel soldiers wishing to lay down their arms would be granted safe passage through a fourth corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrias-jabhat-al-nusra-splits-from-al-qaeda-and-changes-its-name/2016/07/28/5b89ad22-54e6-11e6-b652-315ae5d4d4dd_story.html|title=Syria's Jabhat al-Nusra splits from al-Qaeda and changes its name}}</ref>\n\n;29 July \n* According to the [[International Air Transport Association]], commercial air traffic to and from [[Venezuela]] has dropped 30 by percent since the [[Venezuelan bol\u00edvar]] began a steep decline in value in 2013 despite a rapid increase in air travel almost everywhere else in the world. International air carriers have accumulated about $4,000,000,000 in almost worthless bol\u00edvars which the [[Government of Venezuela]] prohibits them from converting into [[hard currency]], prompting various airlines since 2014 \u2013 including [[Aerom\u00e9xico]], [[Air Canada]], [[Alitalia]], [[LATAM]], and [[Lufthansa]] \u2013 to cease service to Venezuela and others to reduce flights or provide service with smaller planes; only Venezuelan airlines are permitted to pay for fuel with bol\u00edvars, all other carriers being required to pay in [[United States dollar]]s. [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport (Venezuela)|Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport]] in [[Caracas]], long a major [[Airline hub|hub]] for airlines serving [[South America]], has been replaced in that role by airports such as [[El Dorado International Airport]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], which now handles three times as many passengers as Caracas, and [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]] in [[Callao]], [[Peru]], which has enjoyed a 35 percent increase in passengers over the previous two years. Caracas has become so dangerous that [[Copa Airlines]] crews are prohibited from leaving their hotel rooms when staying there, massive shipments of [[cocaine]] originating in Caracas have been interdicted in the airport's terminal, and gunfights between police and criminals occur every few months in the airport's parking lots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/29/venezuela-was-once-an-aviation-gateway-to-south-america-now-its-an-outcast/|title=Venezuela was once an aviation gateway to South America. Now it\u2019s an outcast.}}</ref> \n* A medical transport plane crashes in northern California in the [[United States]]. All four people on board the [[Piper PA-31 Navajo]] die.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2857019/small-medical-plane-crashes-in-california-4-killed/|title=Small medical plane crashes in California, 4 killed}}</ref>\n\n;30 July\n* A [[hot-air balloon]] operated by the company Heart of Texas Hot Air Balloon Rides [[2016 Lockhart hot air balloon crash|catches fire and crashes]] in a field in [[Maxwell, Texas|Maxwell]], [[Texas]], killing all 16 people on board. It is the deadliest ballooning accident in U.S. history and the second-deadliest in world history, exceeded only by [[2013 Luxor hot air balloon crash|a hot-air balloon crash]] in [[Egypt]] in [[2013 in aviation#February|February 2013]] that killed 19 people.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\"/><ref name=\"staging.hosted.ap.org\"/>\n* [[Skydiving|Skydiver]] Luke Aikins becomes the first person in history to jump from an airplane into a net on the ground without wearing a [[parachute]]. Jumping from an altitude of {{convert|25000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, he lands safely after a two-minute freefall in a 100-by-100-foot (30.5-meter-by-30.5-meter) net at the [[Big Sky Ranch]] in [[Simi Valley]], California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SKYDIVING_WITHOUT_PARACHUTE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|title=Rodgers, John, \"Skydiver becomes first person to jump and land without chute,\" Associated Press, July 31, 2016, 9:52 AM EDT.}}</ref>\n\n;31 July\n* In response to a rebel offensive attempting to break the Syrian government's [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|siege of Aleppo]], Syria, that begins during the day, helicopters drop barrel bombs on the city's rebel-held neighborhood of Bustan al-Basha. Later in the day, jets \u2013 presumably of the Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force \u2013 bomb rebel-held areas in the eastern part of the city. During the day, people in rebel-held areas of the city burn [[tire]]s to create plumes of black smoke in an attempt to interfere with visibility for attacking aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/syrian-activists-hospital-bombed-daraa-province-132127626.html|title=Anonymous, \"Syrian rebels launch push aimed at breaking Aleppo siege,\" Associated Press, July 31, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n=== August ===\n* During the month, [[Delta Air Lines]] sends a letter of protest to the U.S. [[General Services Administration]], complaining that GSA's award to [[JetBlue Airways]] of the U.S. government contract routes from [[New York City]] to [[Dubai]] and from New York City to [[Milan]], Italy, in 2015 violates the 1981 [[Fly America Act]] \u2013 which requires U.S. federal government employees, their families, and federal consultants and contractors to travel aboard U.S. carriers when on official business paid for by the U.S. government \u2013 because JetBlue has no aircraft that can fly that far and will book its passengers to those destination on its codeshare partner [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], a [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE) airline based in Dubai. Delta joins [[American Airlines]] and [[United Airlines]] in arguing that they should be selected for such routes to reduce the disadvantage they face when competing with Emirates, the UAE's [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[Etihad Airways]], and [[Qatar]]'s [[Qatar Airways]], all of which receive substantial subsidies from their governments. The GSA responds that JetBlue offers cheaper prices that Delta, American, and United and that its selection does not violate the Fly America Act, regardless of its use of foreign codeshare partners for the routes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/latest-skirmish-in-war-to-control-international-travel-has-the-fly-america-act-been-violated/2016/08/30/4c23a380-6e1b-11e6-9705-23e51a2f424d_story.html|title=Latest skirmish in war to control international travel: Has the Fly America Act been violated?}}</ref>\n\n;1 August\n* The [[Government of Singapore]] restructures its Air Accident Investigation Bureau to establish the [[Transport Safety Investigation Bureau]] as an independent government agency responsible for investigating aviation and marine accidents and incidents in [[Singapore]].\n* Syrian rebels shoot down a Russian [[Mil Mi-8]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter in [[Syria]]'s [[Idlib Governorate]] during fighting around [[Aleppo]], Syria, killing all five people on board. [[Russia]] claims the helicopter was returning to its base after delivering a cargo of humanitarian goods to Aleppo. It is the deadliest single incident for the Russian military since it began its intervention in Syria in [[2015 in aviation#September|September 2015]]. Videos show rebels abusing the bodies of the dead Russian crew and passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/S/SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-08-01-16-04-02|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* At the request of [[Libya]]'s [[Government of National Accord]] (GNA), U.S. manned and unmanned military aircraft conduct two strikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces in [[Sirte]], Libya, destroying a [[T-72]] [[tank]] and two other ground vehicles. They are the first strikes requested by the GNA and the first direct U.S. military intervention in the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan Civil War]]. [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] approves the strikes, but [[United States Africa Command]] commander [[General (United States)|General]] [[Thomas D. Waldhausen]] receives the authority to approve future strikes. The [[United States Navy]] [[amphibious assault ship]] {{USS|Wasp|LHD-1}} is operating off Libya, carrying [[United States Marine Corps]] [[AV-8B Harrier]] aircraft and helicopters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/01/united-states-strikes-islamic-state-stronghold-in-libya-expands-campaign-against-militant-group/|title=U.S. strikes Islamic State stronghold in Libya, expanding campaign against militant group}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/story/military/war-on-is/2016/08/01/us-air-strikes-sirte-libya-islamic-state/87909908/|title=404|first=Military|last=Times}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n;2 August\n* [[IndiGo]] Flights 6E-813 and 6E-136 \u2013 each with at least 100 people on board \u2013 narrowly avoid a mid-air collision over [[Guwahati]], [[India]], when Flight 6E-813 goes into a steep dive to avoid Flight 6E-136, approaching from the opposite direction, 25 seconds before a likely collision. The emergency maneuver leaves six people on board Flight 6E-813 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mid-air-scare-over-guwahati-as-two-indigo-flights-cross-path/story-Z6Zac1UjMNTohhUiJj6wIL.html|title=Guwahati: Mid-air scare for passengers as two Indigo flights cross path|date=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes attributed to the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] or [[Russian Federation Air Force]] kill 11 people in [[Atarib]], Syria. People in rebel-held portions of Aleppo, Syria, burn [[tire]]s to create plumes of dark black smoke in an attempt to interfere with airstrikes.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* The [[United States Air Force]] announces that its first [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]] of [[F-35A Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 the [[34th Fighter Squadron]] at [[Hill Air Force Base]], [[Utah]] \u2013 is combat-ready. The F-35A is the second variant of the F-35 to be declared ready for combat, following the [[United States Marine Corps]]'s F-35B variant. The U.S. Air Force is the largest customer for the F-35, planning to buy 1,763 F-35A aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/breaking-news/2016/08/02/f35-ioc-air-force-operational-acc-combat/87948142/|title=f35-IOC-air-force-operational-ACC-combat|first=Defense|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;3 August\n* After [[air traffic control]] at [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), instructs [[Emirates Flight 521]] \u2013 a [[Boeing 777-300|Boeing 777-31H]] (registration A6-EMW) arriving from [[Thiruvananthapuram]], India \u2013 to abort its landing and conduct a [[go-around]], the airliner instead crashes on the runway and catches fire. All 300 people on board evacuate the airliner with 14 suffering non-life-threating injuries. A firefighter dies during the rescue operation after the crash, and the plane is destroyed by the fire and a series of explosions that follow the evacuation of the passengers and crew; it is the first [[hull loss]] and most serious accident in the airline's history. The airport closes for 5\u00bd hours after the crash, and several incoming flights divert to [[Sharjah International Airport]] outside [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]], UAE, and [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] in [[Jebel Ali]], UAE. Emirates flights experience widespread disruption throughout the airline's system.\n\n;4 August\n* A Pakistani helicopter manned by seven Pakistani [[civil engineer]]s flying from [[Pakistan]] to Russia for routine maintenance crash-lands in [[Afghanistan]]'s [[Logar Province]]. The [[Taliban]] takes either six of its occupants or all seven of them hostage, according to various reports. The [[Pakistan Army]] requests U.S. military assistance in recovering the captured Pakistanis,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-ambush-convoy-with-us-european-tourists-in-afghanistan-injuring-6/2016/08/04/863e68a4-5a37-11e6-9aee-8075993d73a2_story.html|title=Taliban ambushes tourist convoy in west, takes helicopter crew hostage in east}}</ref>\n* [[Amazon.com]] unveils ''Prime One'', a [[Boeing 767]] which is the first of the company's 40 leased cargo planes \u2013 all Boeing 767s \u2013 branded as \"Prime Air,\" a new air cargo service tasked with delivering goods to [[Amazon Prime]] customers. Although Prime Air already is operating 11 of the Prime Air aircraft, ''Prime One'' is the first to operate in Prime Air livery. Its [[Aircraft registration|tail number]], N1997A, is selected as an Amazon prime marketing gimmck because 1997 is a [[prime number]]. ''Prime One'' makes its first flight in the new livery the following day at the [[Seafair]] festival in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. Amazon plan to phase the remaining aircraft into service over the next several years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/2016/0805/Amazon-unveils-Prime-Air-its-new-cargo-plane|title=Amazon unveils Prime Air, its new cargo plane|first=Christina|last=Beck|date=5 August 2016|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/08/05/amazons-latest-weapon-in-the-e-commerce-wars-its-own-air-force/|title=Amazon\u2019s latest weapon in the e-commerce wars: Its own air force}}</ref>\n\n;5 August\n* [[ASL Airlines Hungary Flight 7332]], a [[Boeing 737-400|Boeing 737-476SF]] cargo aircraft, slides off a runway at [[Il Caravaggio International Airport]] in [[Bergamo]], [[Italy]], while landing in bad weather conditions. It crashes through a perimeter fence and rolls onto a four-lane highway, narrowly avoiding collisions with cars on the highway and destroying several cars in an adjacent parking lot. Both people aboard the aircraft are uninjured. The airport is closed for three hours after the crash, with incoming flights diverted to [[Milan\u2013Malpensa Airport]] in [[Milan]], Italy.\n* [[Black Lives Matter]] protesters block a roadway into [[Heathrow Airport]] outside [[London]], temporarily bringing ground traffic into the airport to a halt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/08/05/black-lives-matter-protest-blocks-access-to-londons-heathrow-airport/|title=Black Lives Matter branches out to U.K., launches protests}}</ref>\n* In response to a July 2016 court order to release to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] a May 2013 Presidential Policy Guidance (PPG) document laying out the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]'s guidelines for airstrikes by [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (popularly called \"drones\"), the [[United States Government]] releases a declassified, redacted version of the PPG. It requires \"near certainty\" that the terrorist target is at the targeted location, that no civilians be injured or killed in the strike, that the target poses a \"continuing and imminent\" threat to Americans, that capture of the target is not feasible, and that all relevant domestic and international laws are obeyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/newly-declassified-document-sheds-light-on-how-president-approves-drone-strikes/2016/08/06/f424fe50-5be0-11e6-831d-0324760ca856_story.html|title=Newly declassified document sheds light on how president approves drone strikes}}</ref>\n\n;6 August\n* The [[People's Republic of China]]'s [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] announces that it has conducted [[combat air patrol]]s over disputed areas in the [[South China Sea]] \u2013 the [[Spratly Islands]], [[Scarborough Shoal]], and nearby areas \u2013 \"to enhance combat capabilities to deal with various security threats\" as well as to protect China's sovereignty and maritime interests. It says the flights include bombers, fighters, early warning aircraft, and reconnaissance planes, and that at least some of the aircraft are capable of [[Aerial refueling|refueling in mid-air]], but it does not say when the flights occurred. In July 2016, after a 12 July 2016 ruling against its South China Sea territorial claims by the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]], it also announced that it had made such flights and that doing so would become \"regular practice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/4761dde1297741b2bc803e0a0f9f55e6/chinas-air-force-flies-combat-patrol-over-disputed-islands|title=China's air force flies combat patrol over disputed islands}}</ref>\n* A series of airstrikes by unidentified aircraft destroy a hospital operated by [[Doctors Without Borders]] in [[Millis, Syria|Millis]] in Syria's Idlib Governorate, killing 13 people and injuring at least six. A [[United States Department of Defense]] spokesman announces that U.S. aircraft have not conducted any airstrikes near Idlib Governorate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/547a7c3ae69d4d358d25ad9a755a3e74/msf-says-hospital-it-supports-syria-bombed-13-killed|title=MSF says a hospital it supports in Syria bombed, 13 killed}}</ref>\n\n;8 August\n* [[Delta Air Lines]] experiences computer problems that force it to cancel 451 of its nearly 6,000 daily flights, delaying tens of thousands of passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/delta-airlines-computer-systems-crash-causing-flight-delays-and-cancellations/2016/08/08/7d5e8fa0-5d72-11e6-af8e-54aa2e849447_story.html|title=Delta computers crash, causing delays and cancellations. Experts say it shouldn\u2019t have happened.}}</ref> Before the airline recovers, it cancels 2,300 flights over three days.<ref name=investors20160902>[http://www.investors.com/news/flight-cancellations-hurt-deltas-august-figures-threatens-q3/ Peters, Bill, \"Delta Says Flight Cancellations Cost $100 Million, Cites Other Industry Woes,\" ''Investor\u2032s Business Daily'', 2 September 2016.]</ref> On 2 September, Delta will announce that the cancellations cost it $100 million in revenue, or two percent of passenger unit revenue, a metric for unit revenue as it relates to a carrier's flight capacity and distance flown which dropped 9.5% in August.<ref name=investors20160902/>\n\n;9 August\n* The [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] conducts its first airstrikes in [[Yemen]] since a much-violated ceasefire in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] began on 11 April 2016. The coalition's aircraft strike a [[potato]] processing factory inside a [[Yemeni Army]] maintenance camp in [[Sana'a]], killing at least 14 people working there. One estimate puts the death toll at 16. At least 10 other people are injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/09/saudi-led-airstrikes-yemen-food-factory-kill-people|title=Saudi-led airstrikes on Yemen food factory kill at least 14 people|first=Saeed Kamali|last=Dehghan|date=9 August 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref> The strikes begin a stepped-up effort by the coalition after five months of relative calm in the air campaign in Yemen.<ref name=almujahed20160813>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-airstrike-hits-a-school-in-northern-yemen-killing-10-children/2016/08/13/07039cf2-617c-11e6-84c1-6d27287896b5_story.html|title=Saudi airstrike hits a school in northern Yemen, killing 10 children}}</ref>\n\n;10 August\n* According to Syrian activists, [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] helicopters drop barrel bombs on rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, killing at least two people.<ref name=ap201608110951>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/08/11/strikes-islamic-state-syria/88558178/|title=Airstrikes on Islamic State-held city in Syria kill at least 20 civilians}}</ref> Khaled Harah, one of the best-known members of [[Syrian Civil Defense]] for his rescue of a baby from a collapsed building in 2014 and his testimony before the [[United Nations Security Council]] about violence in Aleppo, is buried in the rubble of a building and killed. The following day, activists will claim that some people on the ground suffered breathing problems after the attack and allege that at least one of the barrel bombs contained [[chlorine gas]]; the Syrian government will deny that it used any [[chemical weapon]]s.<ref name=ap201608110951/> On 13 August, the [[Syrian American Medical Society]] will claim that a bomb dropped by a jet during the day contained chlorine gas and killed three people.<ref name=loveluck20160813>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/aleppos-humanitarian-crisis-worsens-as-islamic-state-loses-key-syrian-city/2016/08/13/04a1c01e-60a6-11e6-84c1-6d27287896b5_story.html|title=Aleppo\u2019s humanitarian crisis worsens while Islamic State loses key Syrian city}}</ref>\n* An [[Iraqi Air Force]] helicopter crashes in [[Iraq]]'s [[Maysan Governorate]] southwest of [[Amarah]] while attempting an [[emergency landing]] after a technical malfunction, injuring all nine people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqinews.com/iraq-war/iraqi-military-helicopter-falls-south-iraq/|title=Anonymous, \"Iraqi military helicopter falls south of Iraq,\" iraqinews.com, August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;11 August\n* Airstrikes on Islamic State-held [[Raqqa]], Syria, kill at least 20 civilians and perhaps as many as 24 civilians and six other people whose military or civilian status could not immediately be determined. According to Syrian activists, Russian Federation Air Force jets are responsible for the strikes.<ref name=ap201608110951/>\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] announces that the [[Turkish Air Force]] will resume airstrikes against Islamic State targets in Syria as part of the U.S.-led coalition and offers to carry out joint operations against the Islamic State with [[Russia]]. [[Turkey]] had discontinued airstrikes against the Islamic State in Syria after shooting down a Russian Federation Air Force aircraft in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]] and subsequently experiencing tension in its relationship with Russia.\n* [[JetBlue]] Flight 429, an [[Airbus A320]] bound from [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], to [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], encounters severe turbulence over [[South Dakota]]. It diverts to [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]], South Dakota, where 20 passengers and two crew members are hospitalized with injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/da6b6bc5447541db99e10d047d4cc6fe/turbulence-leaves-more-20-injured-jetblue-flight|title=People thrown 'like little rag dolls' in JetBlue turbulence|access-date=12 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812125602/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/da6b6bc5447541db99e10d047d4cc6fe/turbulence-leaves-more-20-injured-jetblue-flight|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;12 August\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 18 people. The strikes \u2013 suspected of having been conducted by the Syrian Arab Air Force or Russian Federation Air Force.<ref name=loveluck20160813/> \u2013 hit the only hospital for women and children in [[Kafr Hamrah]], killing at least four people and burying at least 10 others who are pulled alive from the rubble; a market in [[Urum al-Kubra]], killing at least six people; and the village of [[Hayan]], killing at least 10 people. Prayers are cancelled for the day in [[Idlib]] because of the intensity of the airstrikes.\n* Mohammad Hassan Chaudhary, a 20- or 21-year-old (sources differ) [[schizophrenic]] man who allegedly has no flight training, steals a privately owned [[Piper PA-38 Tomahawk]] at [[Markham Airport]] in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], and crashes it near Landsdowne Place mall in [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], Ontario. The incident sparks concerns about security at private airports in Canada, as Chaudhary, wbo dies in the crash, stole the aircraft with relative ease, and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] investigate the matter as a \"national security issue.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2879025/man-dead-after-small-plane-crashes-on-street-in-peterborough/|title=Markham man killed after stolen small plane crashes in Peterborough}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2890098/rcmp-investigating-peterborough-plane-crash-as-national-security-issue/|title=RCMP investigated Peterborough plane crash as 'national security issue'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2892781/peterborough-plane-crash-should-there-be-more-security-at-private-airports/|title=Peterborough plane crash: Should there be more security at private airports?}}</ref>\n\n;13 August\n* A member of the provincial council of Afghanistan's [[Helmand Province]] claims that an ongoing [[Taliban]] offensive to capture [[Lashkar Gah]] would have surrounded the city if not for the recent addition of U.S. airstrikes in support of Afghan forces defending the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-push-toward-strategic-provincial-afghan-capital/2016/08/13/53c04fe4-615f-11e6-9fd0-0b47b4fac0a4_story.html|title=Taliban pushes toward strategic provincial capital in Afghanistan}}</ref>\n* A [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] airstrike in northern [[Yemen]] hits a school in [[Sa'dah]], killing 10 children and injuring 28 others. Local reports state that the children were students taking exams at the time of the strike, while a spokesman for the Saudi-led coalition claims that the strike hit a rebel training camp and the children were rebel recruits.<ref name=almujahed20160813/>\n\n;14 August\n* Aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition conduct airstrikes in support of an offensive by [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] ''[[peshmerga]]'' troops against Islamic State forces in [[Iraq]] east of [[Mosul]] that captures five villages. One of the strikes destroys a [[car bomb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/ap/top-news/peshmerga-launch-operation-to-clear-villages-east-/nsFqc/|title=Szlanko, Balint, and Qassim Abdul-Zahra, \"Iraqi Kurds advance near Islamic State-held city,\" Associated Press, Sunday, Aug. 14, 2016, 5:30 p.m.}}</ref>\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition conduct airstrikes in support an offensive by pro-government troops in Yemen against [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] forces that captures [[Zinjibar]] and [[Ja\u02bf\u0101r]]. The strikes kill more than 40 Islamic militants and destroy several of their ground vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_YEMEN?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* [[Boko Haram]] releases a video in which one of the [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|girls the group kidnapped in 2014]] from a school in [[Chibok]], [[Nigeria]], claims that [[Nigerian Air Force]] strikes against Boko Haram have killed some of the girls. The video also shows what purportedly are the bodies of kidnapped schoolgirls allegedly killed in an air raid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2151cbf4262e4ed3a93cfe5b865e931f/boko-haram-some-abducted-chibok-girls-killed-air-strikes|title=Boko Haram: Some abducted Chibok girls killed in air strikes}}</ref>\n* Reports 45 minutes apart of shots fired in two different terminals at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[Queens, New York|Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], lead to a panic in which thousands of people are evacuated from the terminals and all air traffic at the airport is grounded. After police find no signs of any shots having been fired, a senior law enforcement official announces that it appears that loud cheering, clapping, and banging by people watching television coverage of [[Jamaica]]n [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] [[Usain Bolt]] competing in the [[100 metres|100-meter dash]] during the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] had been misinterpreted as the sounds of a fight and gunfire.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/jfk-airport-terror-alert-may-have-been-sparked-by-people-cheering-for-usain-bolt-at-the-olympics-2016-8 Bates Daniel, \"Shooting alert at JFK Airport may have been sparked by people cheering for Usain Bolt in the Olympics,\" ''Evening Standard'' via businessinsider.com, 15 August 2016, 8:01 a.m. EDT.]</ref>\n\n;15 August\n* An airstrike by the Saudi-led coalition hits a Doctors Without Borders hospital in Yemen's [[Hajjah Governorate]], killing 19 people injuring 24. It is at least the fourth airstrike by the coalition against a Doctors Without Borders hospital in Yemen since the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] began in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-hits-doctors-without-borders-hospital-in-northwestern-yemen/2016/08/15/f1f44aa2-62ff-11e6-b4d8-33e931b5a26d_story.html|title=Airstrike hits Doctors Without Borders hospital in northwestern Yemen}}</ref><ref name=almosawa20160816>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/19/world/middleeast/yemen-doctors-without-borders-hospitals.html|title=Doctors Without Borders Is Pulling Staff After Hospital Bombings in Yemen|first1=Shuaib|last1=Almosawa|first2=Rod|last2=Nordland|date=18 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* Six people were killed in a small plane crash in [[Alabama]], United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/alabama-plane-crash-kills-married-couples-mississippi-41393981|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;16 August\n* Russian Federation Air Force [[Tupolev Tu-22M]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Backfire\") bombers fly from a base near [[Hamadan]], [[Iran]], to hit Islamic State and [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] targets in northern and eastern Syria. It is the first time that Russian aircraft conduct strikes against targets in Syria from bases in Iran. Russian fighters based in Syria join the bombers over Syria. The Russians inform U.S. military forces of the bombers' flight over Iraqi and Syrian territory in advance in accordance with an agreement to deconflict air operations over Syria with the United States. The bombers previously had made {{convert|2000|km|abbr=on}} flights from bases in Russia to strike Syrian targets, but the use of Iranian bases reduces the distance to {{convert|400|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}}, allowing them to carry larger payloads and use less fuel and allowing Russia to intensify its air campaign against rebel forces in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-uses-iranian-air-base-to-bomb-syria/2016/08/16/6b2a30e2-6393-11e6-96c0-37533479f3f5_story.html|title=Strikes from Iranian air base show Russia\u2019s expanding footprint in the Middle East}}</ref> The following day, an Iranian lawmaker will confirm that Russian aircraft are using Iran's Shahed Nojah Air Basem adding that Russian fighter aircraft are using the base only to refuel.<ref name=ap20160817>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/the-latest-syrian-media-say-7-killed-in-aleppo-shelling/15936497/|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrikes on Rebel-Held Syrian City Kill 17,\" Associated Press, August 17, 2016.|access-date=18 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820161613/http://www.wral.com/the-latest-syrian-media-say-7-killed-in-aleppo-shelling/15936497/|archive-date=20 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Syrian activists report an airstrike against a [[field hospital]] in rebel-held [[Daret Azzeh]] in Syria's [[Aleppo Governorate]] just after the hospital's staff and patients had evacuated it. Reportedly scoring a direct hit on the hospital, the strike injures one person.<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* [[Air Djibouti]] relaunches flight operations, using a [[Boeing 737-400]]. It is the first time the airline has flown since [[2002 in aviation|2002]].\n\n;17 August\n* Unidentified aircraft conduct airstrikes against rebel-held Idlib, Syria, killing 17 people and injuring at least 30 others.<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force [[Sukhoi Su-24]] (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") aircraft conduct the Syrian government's first airstrikes against forces of the Kurdish [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) in Syria's [[Hasakah Governorate]] near [[Hasakah]], killing several Kurds. The bombs fall near U.S. and coalition [[special operations forces]] working on the ground with the YPG but inflict no casualties on them. As the strike begins, the U.S. military contacts Russian forces in Syria to inform them that U.S. aircraft would respond if forces of the U.S.-led coalition were under attack; the Russians reply that the Syrians are conducting the strike. Coalition forces on the ground are unable to contact the Syrian jets, and U.S. fighter aircraft scrambled to intercept the Syrians arrive as the Syrian jets leave the area. The incident prompts the U.S.-led coalition to maintain increased [[combat air patrol]]s over the area and to warn the Syrian government not to interfere with coalition ground forces in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/18/politics/us-ypg-syria-bombed/index.html|title=Key ally in Syria bombed while US troops 'nearby'|first=Ryan|last=Browne}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-military-comes-under-attack-syrian-regime-airstrikes-n634521|title=The U.S. military came under attack from Syrian Regime airstrikes}}</ref><ref name=gibbonsneff20160819>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-jets-scramble-as-syrians-bomb-near-american-forces/2016/08/19/bef78558-6636-11e6-be4e-23fc4d4d12b4_story.html|title=U.S. jets scramble as Syrians bomb near American forces}}</ref>\n* The [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defense]] announces that Russian aircraft have conducted airstrikes against rebel targets in eastern Syria from bases in Iran for the second straight day, flying from a base southwest of [[Tehran]].<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* The [[Hybrid Air Vehicles]] [[Hybrid Air Vehicles HAV 304 Airlander 10|Airlander 10]] [[hybrid airship]] makes its first flight, a 30-minute flight at [[RAF Cardington|Cardington Airfield]] in [[Bedfordshire]], [[England]]. Although larger [[airship]]s existed in the early 20th century, the 302-foot-long (92-meter-long) Airlander 10 is the world's largest existing operational aircraft at the time of the flight.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com 2016-08-18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/08/18/historys-largest-aircraft-just-took-flight-but-observers-are-stuck-on-what-it-looks-like/|title=World\u2019s largest aircraft just took flight. But, observers are stuck on what it looks like.}}</ref>\n\n;18 August\n* Doctors Without Borders announces that it is evacuating its staff from six hospitals in northern Yemen, saying that the Saudi-led coalition's bombing of the area is \"indiscriminate\" and the coalition's assurances of protection for health workers are \"unreliable.\" The group explains that airstrikes have continue to target its hospitals despite its provision of the [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] coordinates of its hospitals to the coalition and two meetings with high-ranking military officials of the coalition over the last previous eight months in which the officials promised that aerial bombing of hospitals would end.<ref name=almosawa20160816/>\n\n;19 August\n* Two Syrian Arab Air Force Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") aircraft attempt to transit the area near Hasakah, Syria, where Syrian aircraft had come close to bombing U.S. and coalition special operations forces on the ground while attacking Kurdiish forces the previous day. Fighter aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition intercept them and, according to a U.S. Department of Defense spokesman, \"encouraged\" the Syrian aircraft to leave the area \"without further incident.\"<ref name=gibbonsneff20160819/>\n\n;21 August\n* After a rocket fired from the [[Gaza Strip]] lands in [[Sderot]], [[Israel]], [[Israeli Air Force]] aircraft join [[Israel Defense Forces]] [[tank]]s in bombarding the Gaza Strip town of [[Beit Hanoun]]. As the evening progresses, Israeli aircraft strike at least 30 targets belonging to [[Hamas]], the [[Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine]], and other militant groups in the Gaza Strip. The strikes slightly injure two people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israeli-palestinians-rocket-idUSKCN10W0HZ|title=Gaza militant rocket hits Israel, Israel responds with air strikes, shells|date=22 August 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[United States Army]] [[Lieutenant General (United States)|Lieutenant General]] [[Stephen J. Townsend]], the new commander of [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve]] \u2013 the military command responsible for the U.S.-led coalition's operations against the Islamic State \u2013 announces that U.S. and allied forces will intensify airstrikes against Islamic State targets in support of planned offensives by Syrian rebel ground forces against Raqqa, Syria, and by Iraqi government ground forces against Mosul, Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/21/new-commander-will-increase-tempo-of-u-s-operations-in-conclusive-stage-of-isis-fight/|title=New commander will increase tempo of U.S. operations in conclusive stage of ISIS fight}}</ref>\n\n;22 August\n* A U.S. military spokesman in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, announces that [[Embraer EMB 314 Super Tucano|Embraer A-29 Super Tucano]] light attack aircraft flown by U.S.-trained Afghan pilots have deployed to [[Kunduz]], Afghanistan, to operate against Taliban forces conducting an offensive to capture the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-forces-consolidate-gains-around-kunduz/2016/08/22/aab91c04-686c-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=Taliban forces consolidate gains around Kunduz}}</ref>\n* A spokesman for the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)|Iranian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] announces that Iran no longer will permit Russian aircraft to use bases in Iran, apparently because of Iran's displeasure with the publicity given the Russian deployment of aircraft to Iran by Russia's public announcement of it. The spokesman says that the Russian use of [[Hamadan Airbase]] outside [[Hamadan]], Iran, was \"temporary, based on a Russian request\" and was \"finished for now,\" adding that \"Russia has no base in Iran.\" Since beginning strikes against rebel targets in Syria on 16 August, Russia had operated Tupolev Tu-22M (NATO reporting name \"Backfire\") bombers, [[Sukhoi Su-34]] (NATO reporting name \"Fullback\") strike aircraft, [[Sukhoi Su-30]]SM (NATO reporting name \"Flanker C\") fighters, and [[Sukhoi Su-35]]S (NATO reporting name \"Flanker E\") fighters from Hamadan, launching at least three strikes into Syrian territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iran-ends-russian-use-of-air-base-because-of-unwanted-publicity/2016/08/22/87364e5e-2dbe-4544-889b-2cb7f233fc62_story.html|title=Iran ends Russian use of air base because of unwanted publicity}}</ref>\n\n;23 August\n* The [[Nigerian Army]] claims that \"the most unprecedented and spectacular air raid\" by the Nigerian Air Force against a village in the [[Sambisa Forest]] in northeastern Nigeria's [[Borno State]] on 19 August as members of Boko Haram met for morning prayers mortally wounded the group's leader, [[Abubakar Shekau]] \u2013 the fourth time Nigerian forces have claimed to have killed him \u2013 and killed three other top Boko Haram commanders. A separate Nigerian Air Force announcement claims that the strike killed 300 Boko Haram personnel. Neither of the reports can be verified, and later in the day Nigerian forces claim merely to have seriously wounded Shekau in the strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted2.ap.org/APDEFAULT/cae69a7523db45408eeb2b3a98c0c9c5/Article_2016-08-23-AF--Nigeria-Boko%20Haram/id-18047b5206214dd393c9bedc9bc53a63|title=Associated Press|first=AP|last=Story}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/23/nigeria-says-boko-haram-commanders-killed-airstrike-wounded-abubakar-shekau|title=Nigeria says Boko Haram commanders killed in airstrike|first=Ruth|last=Maclean|date=23 August 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/24/world/africa/boko-haram-abubakar-shekau-airstrike.html|title=Boko Haram Leader Is Wounded in Airstrike, Nigeria\u2019s Military Says|first=Dionne|last=Searcey|date=23 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37163949|title=Boko Haram crisis: Nigeria air strike 'kills commanders'|date=23 August 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 August\n* [[Turkish Army]] forces enter Syria to assist [[Free Syrian Army]] troops in capturing [[Jarabulus]] from the Islamic State. Turkish Air Force and U.S. aircraft conduct airstrikes in support of the offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-launches-operation-against-islamic-state-held-town-on-border/2016/08/24/4983b9d2-b71a-446e-967e-894bf4b9a845_story.html|title=Turkish troops enter Syria to take on ISIS, backed by U.S. warplanes}}</ref>\n* The [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) announce that they have cleared their forces of wrongdoing in two airstrikes against targets in the [[Gaza Strip]] that killed civilians during the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict]]. They find that a [[2014 in aviation#July|20 July 2014]] airstrike that killed seven members of one family at the refugee camp in [[Bureij]] was justified because the house was in use as a Hamas military [[Command and control|command-and-control]] center and because the strike killed a senior Hamas commander and three members of the family who were Hamas members; that a [[2014 in aviation#August|1 August 2014]] airstrike against a house in [[Rafah]] that killed 15 members of one family also was justified because the house was in use by Hamas as a military command-and-control center; that [[international law]] permits attacks on houses used for military purposes; and that one of the dead family members in the 1 August strike was a senior Hamas commander. The IDF also finds that the deaths of 12 members of a family in Rafah on 21 July 2014 were due to [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] fire rather than an Israeli airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3caf434feda5453dbd9df7477363489a/israel-clears-forces-several-deadly-2014-gaza-war-cases|title=Israel clears forces in several deadly 2014 Gaza war cases}}</ref>\n\n;25 August\n* A weeklong search in the [[Federated States of Mirconesia]] for a couple aboard a missing sailboat ends when a [[United States Navy]] helicopter investigating a report from the previous evening of a light seen on uninhabited [[Fayu Atoll]] discovers a large \"[[SOS]]\" drawn in the sand and spots the couple waving. The couple is rescued by boat on 26 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/couple-stranded-fayu-micronesia-desert-island-rescued-after-writing-sos-message-on-beach-a7212776.html|title=Couple stranded on desert island rescued after writing SOS message on beach|date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n;26 August\n* Russian news media report that the [[Government of Russia|Russian government]] has asked the [[Government of Turkey|Turkish government]] for information on Turkish air operations over Syria. A spokesman for the Russian Ministry of Defense explains that Russia wishes to use the information \"to prevent air incidents because it will be the first time when Turkish warplanes will intensively bomb targets in Syria and [they] may meet Russian warplanes in midair.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/kerry-meets-lavrov-in-geneva-in-bid-to-forge-truce-deal-in-syrian-war/2016/08/26/95aaf690-6af9-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=U.S., Russia say they are close to cooperation deal in Syrian war}}</ref>\n\n;27 August\n* Syrian warplanes attack a funeral in [[Al-Nayrab]], Syria, with a barrel bomb, then return to strike with another barrel bomb after rescue workers arrive. The attacks reportedly kill more than two dozen people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-in-east-aleppo-hits-childrens-funeral/2016/08/27/2917db58-6c69-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=Airstrike in east Aleppo hits funeral}}</ref>\n* The Turkish Air Force conducts airstrikes against Kurdish targets in [[Al-Amarna]], Syria, south of Jarabulus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/how-turkeys-offensive-into-syria-is-opening-up-a-hornets-nest/2016/08/27/c1edd776-6bb8-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=How Turkey\u2019s offensive into Syria is opening up a hornet\u2019s nest}}</ref>\n* The left engine of Southwest Airlines Flight 3472 (registration N766SW) \u2013 a [[Boeing 737-700]] flying from [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], to [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Florida]], with 104 people on board \u2013 explodes at an altitude of {{convert|30700|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, damaging the engine [[nacelle]] and tearing a gash in the airliner's [[fuselage]]. The aircraft makes an [[emergency landing]] at [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]], Florida, without injury to anyone on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airlive.net/breaking-southwest-boeing-737-sw3472-looses-part-of-left-engine-after-explosion/|title=BREAKING Southwest Boeing 737 #WN3472 loses part of left engine after inflight explosion - AIRLIVE.net|first=Melanie|last=Kraft}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/scare-sky-after-passenger-jet-engine-suffers-major-malfunction-n638811|title=Passenger jet suffers major engine malfunction in mid-air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url = http://avherald.com/h?article=49d2d7e3\n  |title = Accident: Southwest B737 near Pensacola on Aug 27th 2016, uncontained engine failure\n  |author = Simon Hradecky\n  |date = 27 August 2016\n  |work = [[The Aviation Herald]]\n}}</ref>\n\n;28 August\n* Russia lifts its ban on charter flights to Turkey. The ban had been in place since Turkey shot down a Russian Federation Air Force Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") near the Turkish border with Syria in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/business/357469-turkey-charter-ban-lifted/|title=Russia lifts ban on charter flights to Turkey, airlines start submitting requests}}</ref> On 29 August, the executive director of the [[Association of Tour Operators of Russia]] will announce that the first charter flights will take place on 4\u20135 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rbth.com/news/2016/08/29/first-charter-flights-from-russia-to-turkey-will-fly-on-sept-4-5_625109|title=First charter flights from Russia to Turkey will fly on Sept. 4\u20135|last=TASS|date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Iranian state television airs video of a Russian-supplied mobile [[S-300 (missile)|S-300]] (NATO reporting name \"SA-10 Grumble\") [[surface-to-air missile]] system deployed around the nuclear site at [[Fordo]], Iran. It is not clear whether the system is fully operational or that it will remain at the site.<ref name=karimi20160829>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/31bb5fa1ccdd4ac38269a045d1608b04/iran-deploys-s-300-air-defense-around-nuclear-site|title=Iran deploys S-300 air defense around nuclear site}}</ref>\n* Just after police at [[Los Angeles International Airport]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], California, detain a man in the terminal carrying a plastic sword and dressed as [[Zorro]], a report of shots fired leads to a panic in which police evacuate terminals, people run onto the airfield, and flights to and from the airport are halted. The loud noises mistaken for shots turn out to be harmless, and the man dressed as Zorro, who tells police he had come to meet an arriving passenger, is released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2016/08/29/man-dressed-as-zorro-detained-at-lax-moments-before-false-active-shooter-reports-surfaced/|title=Man Dressed as Zorro Detained at LAX Moments Before False Active Shooter Reports Surfaced|date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n* American [[reality television]] personality [[Darrell Ward]], a star of the television series ''[[Ice Road Truckers]]'', and his pilot are killed when their [[Cessna 182 Skylane Skylane]] (registration N9936T) crashes on a highway and catches fire while trying to land at an airstrip at [[Rock Creek, Montana|Rock Creek]], [[Montana]], at the end of a flight from [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]], Montana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planecrashinfo.com/famous2010s.htm|title=Famous people who died in aviation accidents}}</ref>\n\n;29 August\n* Iranian state television reports that Iran has put into operation the [[Nazir (radar)|Nazir]] [[radar]] system, which it claims can detect radar-evading aircraft, [[ballistic missile]]s, [[cruise missile]]s, and unmanned aerial vehicles flying at altitudes of over {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=karimi20160829/>\n* The first nationwide regulations governing the use of unmanned aerial vehicles (popularly known as \"drones\") go into effect in the United States. They apply only to commercial-purpose UAVs weighing {{convert|55|lb|kg|abbr=off}} or less including payload, and require that the UAVs fly only during daylight, remain within sight of their operators, not fly directly over people not involved in their operation, fly no higher than an altitude of {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and fly no faster than {{convert|100|mph|km/h|order=flip|abbr=on}}; operations outside these parameters require a waiver from the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA). They also require that UAV pilots pass a written test of aeronautical knowledge administered by the FAA to receive an FAA certification to operate UAVs \u2013 the FAA has received about 3,000 requests for such certifications \u2013 although UAV pilots are not required to possess a formal license. The regulations do not apply to privately owned UAVs operated by hobbyists. They also do not address the operation of UAVs over private property, although the FAA recommends that UAV operators receive the permission of property owners before operating UAVs over their property and specific permission to take photographs and videos over their property if the UAVs are to be used for those purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/29/as-of-today-its-finally-legal-to-fly-drones-commercially/|title=As of today, it\u2019s finally legal to fly drones commercially}}</ref>\n\n;30 August\n* The Islamic State announces that its chief spokesman, [[Abu Mohammad al-Adnani]], has been killed in an airstrike. The U.S. Department of Defense reports that it targeted Adnani in a \"precision strike\" in [[Al-Bab]], Syria, with an [[AGM-114 Hellfire]] [[air-to-ground missile]] fired by an unmanned aerial vehicle but says it cannot confirm his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/30/islamic-state-reports-death-of-spokesman-and-senior-leader-in-aleppo/|title=In potential blow to propaganda power, Islamic State reports death of senior leader in Syria}}</ref> On 31 August, Russia will claim that a strike by a Russian Federation Air Force Sukhoi Su-34 (NATO reporting name \"Fullback\") killed as many as 40 Islamic State personnel on 30 August, one of whom was Adnani, but offers no evidence for its claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russian-claims-airstrike-that-killed-senior-islamic-state-leader/2016/08/31/4b551701-c880-4c0c-ac92-24df06c1195c_story.html|title=Russian military claims it killed senior ISIS strategist}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Sutter]], the American engineer known as the \"father of the 747\" who served as chief engineer for the design and development of the [[Boeing 747]] in the 1960s, leading a team of 4,500 people including 2,700 engineers, dies at the age of 95.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/joe-sutter-boeing-engineer-who-led-project-to-build-the-first-jumbo-jet-dies-at-95/2016/08/31/9564bc62-6f8f-11e6-9705-23e51a2f424d_story.html|title=Joe Sutter, Boeing engineer who led project to build the first jumbo jet, dies at 95}}</ref>\n\n;31 August\n* An airstrike in [[Saada]], Yemen, by the Saudi-led coalition kills at least 16 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/08/31/world/middleeast/ap-ml-yemen.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Yemeni Rebels: Saudi-Led Airstrikes Kill 16 Civilians,\" Associated Press, August 31, 2016, 11:04 a.m. EDT.}}</ref> According to one report, the dead are an [[imam]] and 15 members of his extended family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-idUSKCN1161MA|title=Air strike kills 16 members of Yemeni imam's family|date=31 August 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The first scheduled commercial air service between the United States and [[Cuba]] in over 50 years begins with [[JetBlue Airways]] Flight 387 \u2013 an [[Airbus A320]] \u2013 making a flight from [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], to [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]], Cuba. It is also the first scheduled commercial passenger jet flight between the two countries in history, propeller-driven airliners having been in use when flights ceased in the early 1960s. Among passengers on the first flight are [[United States Secretary of Transportation]] [[Anthony Foxx]] and JetBlue [[Chief Executive Officer]] Robin Hayes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/01/world/americas/cuba-us-first-flight-jetblue.html|title=Scheduled Flights to Cuba From U.S. Begin Again, Now With Jet Engines|first=Frances|last=Robles|date=31 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=ap20160831>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/27c0276eeb4d4294aef559960f653132/historic-commercial-flight-us-cuba-set-take|title=Historic commercial flight from US lands in Cuba}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] announces that it has selected [[Alaska Airlines]], American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, JetBlue Airways, [[Southwest Airlines]], [[Spirit Airlines]], and United Airlines to provide scheduled airline service to [[Havana]], Cuba, requiring them to begin service within 90 days. The airlines are to provide the service from [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]; [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]; Fort Lauderdale, [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]]; Los Angeles, California; [[New York City]]; and [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]].<ref name=ap20160831/>\n* A private [[Cessna]] aircraft hired by a woman so that her boyfriend could celebrate his birthday by seeing New Orleans, Louisiana, from the air and carrying the woman, her boyfriend, and a pilot, crashes into [[Lake Pontchartrain]] after flying into a rainstorm. The crash kills the woman's boyfriend and the plane's pilot, but her boyfriend pushes her from the plane moments before the crash, saving her life. A private boat rescues her from the lake and she is taken to a hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fox43.com/2016/08/31/man-pushes-girlfriend-from-plane-saves-her-life-before-dying-in-crash/|title=Man pushes girlfriend from plane, saves her life before dying in crash|date=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n* A mid-air collision over a remote area near [[Russian Mission, Alaska|Russian Mission]], [[Alaska]], between a [[Hageland Aviation]] [[Cessna 208B Grand Caravan]] carrying three people and a [[Renfro's Alaskan Adventures]] [[Piper PA-18 Super Cub]] carrying two people kills everyone aboard both planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160831-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Cessna 208B Grand Caravan EX N752RV Russian Mission Airport, AK (RSH)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref> Mid-air collisions are rare in the [[United States]] and usually happen near airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-37239683|title=Five killed in Alaska mid-air collision|date=1 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n\n;1 September\n* Suspected [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] airstrikes kill at least 25 civilians in [[Syria]]'s [[Hama Governorate]].<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ab4d169b4fed4c818a0d238b7c6bb494/syrian-activists-airstrikes-hama-province-kill-25-people Issa, Philip, \"Syrian Activists Airstrikes Hama Province Kill 25 People\" ''Associated Press'', 1 September 2016, 10:35 PM EDT.]</ref>\n\n;2 September\n* The Syrian rebel group [[Jaish al-Izzah]] claims to have shot down a \"Russian helicopter\" with a [[BGM-71 TOW]] [[anti-tank missile]] during the day as the helicopter was landing outside [[Rahbat al-Khattab]] northwest of [[Hama]], Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/1.739981|title=Syrian Rebels Shoot Down Helicopter Amid Hama Offensive|date=2 September 2016|via=Haaretz}}</ref> According to one report, the helicopter was Russian- or French-made and operated by the Syrian government, and two people aboard it were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/middleeast/20160903/1044914418/hama-helicopter-downing.html|title=Syrian Source Confirms Government Helicopter Downing by Terrorists in Hama|last=Sputnik}}</ref>\n\n;3 September\n* [[Iraqi Air Force]] fighter aircraft drop leaflets to residents of [[Shirqat]] and [[Zuwiyah]], Iraq. The leaflets ask them to support and assist Iraqi forces and their allies advancing into the area during an offensive against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].<ref name=dolomari20160915>[http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/e60bef37-6271-43ef-9315-e79aa4890d1d/PHOTOS--Iraqi-planes-drop-seven-million-leaflets-on-Mosul Dolomari, Mewan, \"Iraqi planes drop seven million leaflets on Mosul,\" kurdistan24.net, 15 September 2016.]</ref>\n\n;4 September\n* A U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] fires an [[air-to-ground missile]] at a gathering of [[al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members in [[Yemen]]'s [[Shabwah Governorate]], killing six of them.<ref name=ryan20160908>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-reminder-of-the-permanent-wars-dozens-of-us-airstrikes-in-six-countries/2016/09/08/77cde914-7514-11e6-be4f-3f42f2e5a49e_story.html|title=A reminder of the permanent wars: Dozens of U.S. airstrikes in six countries}}</ref>\n* Supported by [[Russian Federation Air Force]] strikes, [[Syrian Arab Army]] forces close off the \"[[Ramouseh]] corridor,\" completing an encirclement of rebel-held portions of [[Aleppo, Syria|Aleppo]], Syria, and cutting them off from reinforcement and supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-still-trying-for-a-syria-ceasefire-deal-with-russia/2016/09/05/c56d710a-72ec-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Obama and Putin unable to reach cease-fire agreement for Syria}}</ref>\n\n;5 September\n* Since 3 September, U.S. aircraft have conducted about 20 strikes against Islamic State targets in [[Iraq]], centering on [[Nineveh Province]] and [[Mosul]] but also in [[Anbar Province]]; at least 25 strikes against Islamic State targets in northern and eastern [[Syria]], at least 20 strikes against Islamic State targets in [[Sirte]], [[Libya]]; and several counterterrorism strikes in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=ryan20160908/>\n* U.S. forces conduct two airstrikes in [[Tortoroow]], [[Somalia]], in defense of [[Africa]]n peacekeeping forces that had come under attack by [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]].<ref name=ryan20160908/>\n\n;6 September\n* Visiting [[Laos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] pledges that the [[United States]] will provide $90 million in additional aid to Laos to help in cleaning up an estimated 80 million unexploded bombs remaining in that country after the U.S. air campaign there during the [[Vietnam War]]. Between 1964 and 1973, the United States conducted 580,000 bombing raids over Laos, dropping an estimated 270 million [[cluster bomb]]s, in an effort to cut off supplies passing through Laos to [[Viet Cong]] and [[North Vietnamese Army]] forces operating in [[South Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/obama-pledges-90-million-to-help-clear-remnants-of-us-bombing-in-laos/2016/09/06/f7d9db6a-6ee1-11e6-993f-73c693a89820_story.html|title=Obama pledges $90 million to help clear remnants of U.S. bombing in Laos}}</ref>\n* A Syrian government aircraft drops a barrel bomb containing [[chlorine gas]] on the rebel-held [[Sukkari]] neighborhood of Aleppo. According to [[Syrian Civil Defense]], 120 people are hospitalized with breathing problems after the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/chlorine-attack-deepens-fears-among-besieged-aleppo-residents/2016/09/06/96c86796-7441-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Chlorine attack deepens fears among besieged Aleppo residents}}</ref> The following day, medical workers claim that they treated 70 people for breathing problems and that two of them had died on 7 September.<ref name=issa20160907>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3cd742c399bd41709ca38534aaed69ff/un-fighting-displaces-100000-central-syria-8-days|title=Aleppo bombed as US and Russia plan Syria talks}}</ref>\n* A Mexican police helicopter crashes in [[Mexico]]'s [[Michoac\u00e1n]] state, killing three police officers and the pilot, during a police operation to capture leaders of criminal groups and drug cartels in [[Apatzing\u00e1n]], including the [[Knights Templar Cartel]]. An initial report that the helicopter was shot down by a criminal group later comes into question, prompting an investigation into the cause of the crash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salazar|first1=Juan Ignacio|title=Mexico probes if gang downed police helicopter|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/criminals-down-police-helicopter-mexico-four-dead-011310542.html|website=yahoo.com|publisher=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;7 September\n* A U.S. airstrike near [[Raqqa]], Syria, kills Islamic State minister of information [[Wael Adel Salman al-Fayad]], also known as Abu Mohamed Furqan. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce the successful strike on 16 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/16/u-s-strike-kills-another-senior-islamic-state-militant-official-says/|title=Pentagon says Raqqa strike kills Islamic State information minister}}</ref>\n* A Syrian government airstrike in the rebel-held al-Sukkari neighborhood of Aleppo, Syria, kills at least 10 civilians.<ref name=issa20160907/>\n\n;8 September\n* Afghan [[attack helicopter]]s support Afghan ground troops opposing a [[Taliban]] ground offensive in street-to-street fighting in [[Tarinkot]], Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-launch-surprise-surge-into-former-southern-afghan-stronghold/2016/09/08/c63eb570-75d1-11e6-b786-19d0cb1ed06c_story.html|title=Taliban launches surprise surge into former southern Afghan stronghold}}</ref>\n* An evening airstrike by unidentified aircraft against a meeting of [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] commanders in the village of [[Kafr Naha]] on the western outskirts of Aleppo, Syria, kills commander [[Abu Omar Saraqib]]. The strike also reportedly kills or injures other senior members of the group, including the commander [[Abu Muslem al-Shami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37314280|title=Syria conflict: Senior militant leader 'killed' near Aleppo|date=9 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-syrian-rebel-commander-killed-in-airstrike-1473428873|title=Top Syrian Rebel Commander Killed in Airstrike|first=Maria|last=Abi-Habib|date=9 September 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n* A [[Diamond DA20|Diamond DA20C]] with two people on board collides with a [[Beech F-33|Beech F-33A]] carrying only a pilot near [[West Georgia Regional Airport]] in [[Carroll County, Georgia|Carroll County]], [[Georgia, United States|Georgia]], in mid-air killing all three people on board the planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myfox8.com/2016/09/08/3-killed-in-mid-air-collision-near-west-georgia-airport/|title=3 killed in mid-air collision near west Georgia airport|date=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;10 September\n* A series of airstrikes by aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition on a water well in [[Beit Sadaan]], Yemen, kill at least 30 people and wound at least 17, according to the [[United Nations]], although [[Houthi]] rebels claim that the strikes kill or wound 100 people. Later strikes in the sequence of air raids on the well reportedly kill first responders attempting to help the wounded from earlier strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-air-defense-shoots-down-missile-fired-from-yemen/2016/09/12/153486fc-78b9-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=- The Washington Post}}</ref>\n* In [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John F. Kerry]] and [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Russia)|Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announce a ceasefire agreement between the [[United States]] and [[Russia]] intended to lead to a negotiated settlement that will end the [[Syrian Civil War]]. The ceasefire between the Syrian government and opposition groups is to begin at sundown on 12 September. If the ceasefire holds for seven days, the agreement as outlined by Kerry calls among other things for the protection of civilians in Syria from airstrikes, for the United States and Russia to make arrangements to conduct coordinated airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] and the Islamic State, and for the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] to resume combat missions only over yet-to-be-selected areas that contain no rebel forces.<ref name=sly20160910>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/doubts-concerns-greet-syria-cease-fire-deal/2016/09/10/0f9f13f4-76e0-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Doubts, concerns greet Syria cease-fire deal as violence surges}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/09/09/politics/syria-ceasefire-kerry-lavrov/index.html|title=Kerry announces US-Russia deal on Syrian ceasefire|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Elise Labott|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force jets strike a busy market in [[Idlib]], Syria, killing at least 36 people, and various neighborhoods in Aleppo, Syria, killing at least another 45 people.<ref name=sly20160910/> Airstrikes from the day resulted in the deaths of over 100 people, all civilians, and the injuring of also more than 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/us-and-russia-announce-syria-peace-plan-10571819|title=More Than 100 Dead in Attacks Before Syria Truce}}</ref>\n\n;11 September\n* As part of an effort to improve [[crowd control]] at the annual [[Hajj]] pilgrimage and avoid a repeat of a [[2015 Mina stampede|disastrous stampede]] that killed hundred of people in September 2015, authorities in [[Saudi Arabia]] deploy unmanned aerial vehicles to monitor pilgrims ascending [[Mount Arafat]], east of [[Mecca]], at the climax of the 2016 Hajj.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N1BN05K?sp=true|title=Drones keep watch as pilgrims ascend Mount Arafat for haj climax|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n;12 September\n* A ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War under an agreement between Russia and the United States goes into effect at sundown, but is almost immediately violated during the evening. Among the violations is a barrel-bomb attack against a neighborhood of Aleppo by Syrian government helicopters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ceasefire-in-syria-set-to-take-hold-as-scores-die-in-air-strikes/2016/09/12/c93bbf4e-7850-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=Syrian cease-fire backed by U.S. and Russia gets off to rocky start}}</ref>\n\n;14 September\n* Iraqi Air Force aircraft drop 7 million leaflets over Iraq's [[Nineveh Governorate]] \u2013 2 million over the center of [[Mosul]], 500,000 each over [[Hamdaniya]], [[al-Ba\u2019aaj]], [[al-Hazar]], and [[Talafar]], and 250,000 each over [[Bashiqa]], [[Hamam Alil]], [[al-Shura]], [[al-Mahaliya]], [[al-Hmidat]], [[Bartila]], [[al-Namroud]], [[Qahtaniyah, Iraq|Qahtaniyah]], [[Til Abta]], [[al-Ayaziya]], and [[al-Qirwan]]. The leaflets inform civilians of a planned offensive to retake Mosul from the Islamic State and asks civilians in the governorate to stop fighting for the Islamic State, avoid Islamic State bases and help the anti-Islamic State coalition target the bases, and support advancing Iraqi troops and their allies.<ref name=dolomari20160915/>\n* Based on the results of a [[United States Navy]] investigation into a fatal crash while the [[Blue Angels]] flight demonstration [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]] was practicing for an [[air show]] on [[2016 in aviation#June|2 June]], the Blue Angels receive orders to eliminate the [[split S]] maneuver from their shows until further notice, put dive recovery rules with specific airspeed limitations in place, use a greater safety buffer between aircraft and the ground for the remainder of the air show season, and make positive radio confirmation with instruments that measure altitude prior to takeoff. The Navy also directs that after the conclusion of the current air show season a safety team review the Blue Angels' training, maintenance and culture; review their aerial maneuvers in order to increase safety; and determine adjustments to future air show schedules to allow more rest for pilots and support staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/15/navy-will-alter-how-the-blue-angels-stunt-team-flies-after-investigation-of-fatal-crash/|title=After investigation, Navy\u2019s Blue Angels will stop using maneuver that killed a pilot}}</ref>\n\n;16 September\n* The [[United States Air Force]] announces the grounding of 15 [[F-35A Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 13 belonging to the U.S. Air Force and two to the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] \u2013 due to \"peeling and crumbling\" insulation inside their fuel tanks. The insulation problem also affects another 42 F-35A aircraft still in production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/16/air-force-grounds-15-f-35-joint-strike-fighters-because-of-peeling-and-crumbling-insulation/|title=Air Force grounds 15 F-35 Joint Strike Fighters because of 'peeling and crumbling' insulation}}</ref>\n* [[Bulgaria]]'s national airline [[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will make commercial flights to the [[United States]] for the first time since the 1990s. It plans to begin its new transatlantic service in March 2017.\n\n;17 September\n* Believing that they are attacking Islamic State forces, aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition \u2013 which the Syrian government claims are two [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]]s and two [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]]s flying into Syria from Iraq \u2013 mistakenly strike Syrian Arab Army forces in Syria's [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]]. The strike destroys approximately six ground vehicles according to a [[United States Central Command]] estimate before Russia alerts Central Command that the strike is targeting Syrian Arab Army forces; the aircraft then cease fire and the United States express regret over the strike. Russia and Syria claim that the targeted forces were fighting against the Islamic State and that the strike killed 62 Syrian soldiers and wounded 100. It is the first combat engagement between the U.S.-led coalition and Syrian forces since the coalition began air raids in Syria in [[2014 in aviation|2014]]. Arguing that the strike is a ceasefire violation that may be evidence of U.S. military support for the Islamic State in the Syrian Civil War, Russia calls an emergency Saturday-evening meeting of the [[United Nations Security Council]] to discuss the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/russia-and-syria-blame-us-led-coalition-for-deadly-strike-on-syrian-troops/2016/09/17/8dabf5d6-7d03-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=U.S. admits carrying out airstrike that Russia says killed 62 Syrian soldiers}}</ref>\n\n;18 September\n* The U.S.-led coalition in Afghanistan comnducts two airstrikes against a highway in Afghanistan's [[Urozgan Province]] on the outskirts of [[Tarinkot]] in support of Afghan forces in combat against the [[Taliban]]. Local officials claim that the strikes mistakenly kill eight Afghan police officers, with the second strike killing people who were attempting to help those injured in the first strike; the coalition does not comment on the allegation. The strikes are among several the coalition carries out during the day, including in [[Kabul Province]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-airstrikes-in-afghanistan-killed-eight-policemen-say-local-officials-1474300170 Amiri, Ehsanullah, and Jessica Dona, \"U.S. Airstrikes in Afghanistan Killed Eight Policemen, Local Officials Say\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 19 September 2016, 11:49 a.m. EDT.]</ref>\n* Warplanes \u2013 suspected of being Syrian Arab Air Force or Russian Federation Air Force aircraft \u2013 strike rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo, Syria, killing at least one person and injuring several others. Another suspected Syrian or Russian airstrike in Syria's [[Daraa Governorate]] kills eight people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/barrel-bombs-fall-on-aleppo-with-ceasefire-deal-close-to-unraveling/2016/09/18/64d2589c-7d1e-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=New violence in Syria threatens cease-fire, as U.S. and Russia blame each other}}</ref>\n* Iranian state television announces that [[Iran]] is reducing the number of airliners it agreed to purchase from [[Airbus]] in [[2016 in aviation#January|January]] from 118 to 112.<ref name=gambrell20160922/>\n\n;19 September\n* The Syrian government declares an end to a week-long nationwide ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War and the Syrian Arab Air Force conducts at least 35 airstrikes and barrel-bomb attacks against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria. One air raid strikes a ground convoy as it unloads aid packages at a warehouse operated by the [[Syrian Arab Red Crescent]] west of Aleppo, Syria, hitting the warehouse, destroying at least 18 of the convoy's 31 trucks, and killing about 20 civilians, including at least 12 humanitarian aid workers, most of them truck drivers. The United States claims that only Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force aircraft could have conducted the strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrias-7-day-grace-period-ends-with-no-aid-and-cease-fire-in-tatters/2016/09/19/633ecd72-7dea-11e6-ad0e-ab0d12c779b1_story.html|title=At least 12 aid workers killed in Syria airstrike}}</ref>\n* [[United States Secretary of the Air Force]] [[Deborah Lee James]] announces that the new bomber under development by [[Northrop Grumman]] for the U.S. Air Force's [[Long-Range Strike Bomber]] program will be named the [[Northrop Grumman B-21 Raider|B-21 Raider]]. The B-21 is expected to reach [[initial operational capability]] in the mid-2020s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.af.mil/News/ArticleDisplay/tabid/223/Article/948366/the-b-21-has-a-name-raider.aspx|title=The B-21 has a name: Raider}}</ref>\n\n;20 September\n* Bulgaria Air confirms the lease of 14 new [[Boeing 737]] aircraft, which will replace the [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320s]] currently operated by the airline. The deal is valued at more than $8,000,000,000.\n* A military helicopter belonging to the [[Libyan National Army]] crashes near [[Tobruk]], killing all eight people on board, including the [[Libyan National Army|Libyan armed forces']] commander-in-chief, [[Idris Younis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/09/20/485524/Libya-Helicopter-Crash-Tobruk|title=PressTV-'Military helicopter crash kills 8 in Libya'}}</ref>\n\n;21 September\n* After the Russian Ministry of Defense claims that a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle was in the vicinity of the 19 September airstrike on a humanitarian aid convoy and warehouse outside Aleppo, Syria, and implies that it could have conducted the attack, the U.S. Department of Defense responds that no manned or unmanned aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition were in the area at the time.<ref name=deyoung20160921>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-calls-on-russia-and-syria-to-ground-all-aircraft-in-northwest-syria/2016/09/21/ea602cbc-8013-11e6-8d0c-fb6c00c90481_story.html|title=U.S. calls on Russia and Syria to ground all aircraft in northwest Syria}}</ref> At the U.N. Security Council, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry accuses Moscow of inventing its \"own facts\"<ref name=deyoung20160921/> to explain the air attack, which the United States had blamed on the Russian Federation Air Force, adding that \"We don\u2019t get anywhere by ignoring facts and denying common sense;\"<ref name=deyoung20160921/> he calls for Russia and Syria to \"immediately ground all aircraft\" flying in areas of northwest Syria where the convoy was hit.<ref name=deyoung20160921/>\n* The [[United States Department of the Treasury]]'s [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] grants [[Airbus]] and [[Boeing]] licenses to sell airliners to [[Iran]]. Airbus's license covers the first 17 [[Airbus A320|A320s]] and [[Airbus A330|A330s]] that Iran agreed to purchase in a [[2016 in aviation#January|January]]; although based aboard, the company required U.S. Government permission because at least 10 percent of the airliners' components are manufactured in the United States. Boeing's license allows it to sell 80 airliners and lease another 29 new [[Boeing 737]]s to Iran.<ref name=gambrell20160922/>\n\n;22 September\n* Throughout the day, suspected Syrian Arab Air Force and Russian Federation Air Force aircraft strike targets in rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria; twenty-one people die in evening air raids on two Aleppo neighborhoods, and scores have died in airstrikes in the city since 19 September.<ref name=deyoung20160922>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-russia-continue-to-exchange-charges-amid-effort-to-salvage-cease-fire/2016/09/22/303bd2bc-80f1-11e6-8327-f141a7beb626_story.html|title=U.S., Russia continue to exchange charges amid effort to salvage cease-fire}}</ref> At the U.N. Security Council, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry repeats his 21 September call for Syria and Russia to ground their aircraft in northeastern Syria, saying that \"the only way\" for the Syrian ceasefire to succeed is \"if the ones who have the air power in this part of the conflict simply stop using it...\u2009. Absent a major gesture like this, we don\u2019t believe there is a point in making more promises, issuing more plans.\"<ref name=deyoung20160922/> The U.S. [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Joseph Dunford]], tells the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]] that \"I would not agree that coalition aircraft ought to be grounded...I do agree that Syrian regime aircraft and Russian aircraft should be grounded...There's no reason to ground our aircraft...We\u2019re not barrel-bombing civilians; we\u2019re not causing collateral damage.\"<ref name=deyoung20160922/>\n* The [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO) rules that the [[European Union]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]] have failed to halt illegal subsidies to Airbus that the WTO had ordered them to stop in [[2011 in aviation|2011]] despite reporting in late 2011 that they had done so. The WTO adds that the subsidies \u2013 which total $22,000,000,000 over ten years \u2013 have cost the economy of the United States tens of billions of dollars and cost Boeing nearly 400 potential airliner sales in 2012 and 2013 alone. The ruling is a sweeping victory for the United States and its [[aerospace industry]], which has disputed European aircraft subsidies for 40 years and first filed a complaint with the WTO about Airbus subsidies in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/09/22/wto-rules-europe-illegally-subsidized-airlines-handing-victory-to-obama-administration-ahead-of-trade-fight/|title=WTO rules Europe illegally subsidized airlines, handing victory to Obama administration ahead of trade fight}}</ref>\n\n;23 September\n* After the Syrian government announces an offensive against rebel forces in and around Aleppo, Syria, the previous evening, Syrian government aircraft pound rebel-held areas of Aleppo during the day, conducting more than 70 strikes and dropping at least 100 bombs. Observers describe the strikes during the day as the most intense of the Syrian Civil War. Targets include at least three of the four [[Syrian Civil Defense]] in the eastern part of the city; damaging [[fire truck]]s and [[ambulance]]s; two of the centers are knocked out. More than 70 strikes have hit the Aleppo area since 21 September; since the collapse of the ceasefire in Syria on 19 September, airstrikes have killed scores of people, including at least 30 in Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/un-hopes-to-soon-resume-aid-convoys-inside-syria/2016/09/22/b0fcb2c0-80ad-11e6-b002-307601806392_story.html|title=Syria ignores Kerry and launches an offensive to recapture Aleppo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-airstrikes-hammer-aleppo-amid-expanding-offensive-against-rebels/2016/09/23/4d247c50-818a-11e6-b002-307601806392_story.html|title=Syrian airstrikes hammer Aleppo amid expanding offensive against rebels}}</ref>\n\n;24 September\n* Syrian and Russian airstrikes against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria, continue to escalate, reaching levels unseen previously in the five-year Syrian Civil War, with reports indicating at least 92 people killed since dawn.<ref name=loveluck20160924>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-and-russian-airstrikes-continue-major-offensive-to-take-back-aleppo/2016/09/24/cebf5bb4-81cf-11e6-8327-f141a7beb626_story.html|title=Syrian and Russian airstrikes continue major offensive to take back Aleppo}}</ref> [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] suggests that the reported systematic use of [[Incendiary device|incendiary weapons]] and \"[[bunker buster]]\" bombs may be a [[war crime]].<ref name=loveluck20160924/>\n\n;25 September\n* Intense Russian and Syrian airstrikes in and around rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 85 people, with observers claiming that attacking aircraft are employing [[white phosphorus munitions]], [[cluster munitions]], and incendiary and \"bunker buster\" bombs. Since 19 September, the strikes have destroyed so many ambulances that humanintarian aid workers and first responders have great difficulty responding to reports of casualties. At the U.N. Security Council, [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Samantha Power]] accuses Russia of \"barbarism\" and claims the strikes are a war crime, while the [[Permanent Representative of Russia to the United Nations]], [[Vitaly Churkin]], responds that the collapse of the ceasefire is due to transgressions by U.S.-backed rebel forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/us-accuses-russia-of-barbarism-and-war-crimes-in-syria/2016/09/25/c3a00750-833d-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=U.S. accuses Russia of 'barbarism' and war crimes in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;26 September\n* In the first week since the collapse of the ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War, Syrian and Russian aircraft have dropped at least 1,700 bombs on the rebel-held eastern portion of Aleppo, Syria.<ref name=sly20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/darkness-and-fear-in-aleppo-as-the-bombs-rain-down/2016/09/28/07b65246-842e-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Darkness and fear in Aleppo as the bombs rain down}}</ref>\n* The Russian government announces that it has radio location data implicating the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukrainian armed forces]] in the destruction of [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 17]] over eastern [[Ukraine]] in [[2014 in aviation#July|July 2014]] and has ruled out the possibility that a [[surface-to-air missile]] fired from territory held by pro-Russian separatists in [[Ukraine]] shot the airliner down.<ref name=roth20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/dutch-probe-missile-brought-from-russia-downed-malaysia-airline-plane-over-ukraine/2016/09/28/05a9770c-84c5-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Dutch probe: Missile brought from Russia downed Malaysia Airlines plane over Ukraine}}</ref>\n\n;27 September\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] demonstrates its [[Next Generation Data Communications]] (also called \"Nexcom\" or \"Data Comm\") system \u2013 a component of its [[Next Generation Air Transportation System]] \u2013 to the media at [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] in [[Virginia]]. The system, already installed at [[air traffic control]] towers at 45 airports in the United States, is intended to replace the existing archaic U.S. system of communications between airline pilots and control towers \u2013 which requires printing out [[flight plan]]s in towers, discussion by radio between towers and pilots, and pilots writing down flight plans by hand in the [[cockpit]] \u2013 with all-digital communications, allowing improved speed and efficiency. The FAA plans to install the system at 50 more U.S. airports before the end of 2016, and then to install it at en route air traffic control centers across the United States, with a goal of achieving voiceless, in-flight communications between air traffic controllers and airliner pilots throughout the country by mid-2019. The FAA estimates that the new system will save air carriers $10,000,000,000 over the next 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atwonline.com/connected-aerospace/faa-touts-data-comm-installations-45-us-airport-atc-towers|title=FAA touts Data Comm installations at 45 US airport ATC towers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/new-direct-digital-link-between-tower-and-cockpit-will-speed-planes-on-their-way/2016/09/27/50eb9ec8-843b-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=New direct digital link between tower and cockpit will speed planes on their way}}</ref>\n\n;28 September\n* An Afghan official announces that an early-morning airstrike against a residential building in the [[Achin District]] in eastern Afghanistan's [[Nangarhar Province]] has killed 13 civilians. U.S. military forces in Afghanistan acknowledge that they carried out a \"counterterrorism airstrike\" in Achin and aare investigating whether any civilian casualties resulted from it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/eb969180d190470e9761c395e0a699fb/afghan-official-13-civilians-killed-airstrike-house|title=Afghan official: Airstrike hits house, killing 13 civilians}}</ref>\n* The United States conducts a predawn airstrike in northern [[Somalia]] in defense of troops from Somalia's [[Puntland]] region who report that they have come under fire from [[al-Shabaab (militant group)|al-Shabaab]] forces. Post-strike photographs show two burned-out [[armored vehicle]]s and a number of badly burned bodies at the scene of the strike. A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman claims that the strike killed nine al-Shabaab members and a Puntland police officer says it killed more than a dozen al-Shabaab personnel, while officials of Somalia's [[Galmudug]] [[Administrative divisions of Somalia|autonomous region]] claim that Puntland had tricked the United States into attacking Galmudug soldiers and that the strike had killed 22 of them. The U.S. Department of Defense announces that it will investigate whether the strike killed anyone other than al-Shabaab personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-somalia-security-idUSKCN11Y0UC|title=U.S. accused of killing 22 in misdirected Somalia air strike|date=28 September 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=guled20160930>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b5354cd3f76843e188ea8f801d536c7f/somalia-accuses-us-over-airstrike|title=Somalia accuses US over airstrike}}</ref>\n* During the predawn hours, airstrikes hit two hospitals and a bakery in eastern Aleppo, Syria. Both hospitals are put out of action, and two patients are killed.<ref name=sly20160928/>\n* The [[United States Department of State]] announces that the United States is making preparations to suspend all bilateral cooperation with Russia over Syria \u2013 including the sharing of information between the United States and Russia to support airstrikes against terrorist targets in Syria via a \"Joint Implementation Center\" \u2013 unless Russia takes steps to end the ongoing Syrian and Russian ground and air assault against rebel-held eastern Aleppo and moves to restore the ceasefire agreed to on 12 September. The announcement states that in a telephone conversation earlier in the day with Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergey Lavrov, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry \"made clear that the United States and its partners hold Russia responsible for the situation, including the use of incendiary and 'bunker buster' bombs in an urban environment, a drastic escalation that puts civilians at great risk\" and \"informed [Lavrov] that the United States is making preparations to suspend U.S.-Russia bilateral engagement on Syria \u2013 including on the establishment of a Joint Implementation Center to coordinate [air]strikes on terrorist targets \u2013 unless Russia takes immediate steps to end the assault on Aleppo and restore the cessation of hostilities.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-threatens-to-suspend-all-bilateral-cooperation-with-russia-over-syria/2016/09/28/1ed4a554-8591-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=U.S. threatens to suspend bilateral engagement with Russia over Syria}}</ref>\n* A [[Netherlands|Dutch]] team investigating the crash of Malaysian Airlines Flight 17 in Ukraine in July 2014 announces that it has concluded that the airliner was shot down by a surface-to-air missile fired by a Russian-made [[Buk missile system]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Gadfly,\" U.S. Department of Defense designation SA-11) smuggled from Russia into an area of eastern [[Ukraine]] held by pro-Russian separatists a few hours before it fired at the airliner and returned to Russian territory the following day. The Dutch team says that it has identified over 100 people linked to the firing of the missile and that it will continue its investigation \u2013 extended into at least 2018 \u2013 \u2013in order to determine who ordered it fired. The U.S. Department of State notes that the Dutch team's findings match those of American investigators, while the Russian ministries of defense and foreign affairs dismiss some of the Dutch team's evidence and declare its investigation biased and Russian separatists in Ukraine claim they have no access to sophisticated surface-to-air missiles and blame the airliner's destruction on the Ukrainian armed forces.<ref name=roth20160928/>\n* \"Unauthorized...activity\" by an unmanned aerial vehicle near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), forces the airport to halt all arrivals and departures. Arrivals resume after about 35 minutes and full operations after about 67 minutes. The incident prompts UAE officials to announce plans to tighten the country's regulations regarding drone operations. A similar incident had caused the airport to close on [[2016 in aviation#June|12 June]].<ref name=bbc20160928/>\n\n;29 September\n* United Nations officials condemn the 28 September U.S. counterterrorism airstrike in Afghanistan's Achin District, saying it killed 15 civilians and wounded 12 others; they demand a complete investigation of the incident. Although the United States and the Afghan government claim that the strike targeted a residential compound used by Islamic State personnel, local Afghan officials claim that it killed and injured only civilians. U.S. military officials respond that they take \"all allegations of civilian casualties very seriously\" but add that the Islamic State continues \"to put innocent lives at risk by deliberately surrounding themselves with civilians and dressing in female attire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/un-officials-criticize-fatal-us-airstrike-in-afghanistan/2016/09/29/9d06d122-8672-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=U.N. officials criticize fatal U.S. airstrike in Afghanistan}}</ref>\n* The [[Government of Somalia]] accuses the United States Government of killing 13 Somali soldiers in its 28 September airstrike against al-Shabaab forces and demands an explanation from the United States.<ref name=guled20160930/>\n* Russia responds to U.S. criticism of its air campaign in eastern Aleppo, Syria, by saying that the airstrikes are justified because the United States violated the ceasefire agreement of 12 September by failing to fulfill its promise to separate [[al-Qaeda]]- and Islamic State-linked forces from other rebel forces and because the ceasefire agreement had become unacceptable because it a;;owed \"terrorist groups to take necessary measures to replenish supplies [and] regroup forces.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/russia-says-us-criticism-of-its-actions-in-aleppo-disagrees-with-reality/2016/09/29/9da7cc48-8673-11e6-92c2-14b64f3d453f_story.html|title=Russia says U.S. criticism of its actions in Aleppo 'disagrees with reality'}}</ref>\n\n;30 September\n* Russian and Syrian aircraft conduct heavy airstrikes against rebel-held residential areas in eastern Aleppo, Syria, including the use of white phosphorus and cluster munitions; two more hospitals are among the targets hit during the day. The [[World Health Organization]] estimates that Russian and Syrian airstrikes have killed 338 people in Aleppo since 19 September. The [[Syrian Network for Human Rights]] estimates that Russian airstrikes have killed 3,624 civilians since they began on [[2015 in aviation#September|30 September 2015]], while the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] estimates that they have killed 3,804 civilians. A Russian government spokesman says that Russia has no intention of reducing its involvement in the Syrian Civil War and has no projected end date for its intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/no-sign-of-obamas-predicted-quagmire-as-russias-engagement-in-syria-escalates/2016/09/30/5b3e4d18-8723-11e6-ac72-a29979381495_story.html|title=No sign of Obama\u2019s predicted 'quagmire' as Russia\u2019s engagement in Syria escalates}}</ref>\n* Dutch Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Bert Koenders]] summons the Russian ambassador to the [[Netherlands]] to a meeting in [[The Hague]] to complain about Russian Government statements criticizing the Dutch team investigating the July 2014 crash of Malaysian Airlines Flight 17 in Ukraine. Koenders describes the Russian criticism as \"unsubstantiated\" and \"unacceptable,\" adding, \"Given the convincing nature of the evidence, Russia should respect the results that have been presented, rather than impugning the investigation and sowing doubt.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dutch-call-russian-ambassador-to-hague-meeting-over-flight-mh17-1475241060|title=Dutch Call Russian Ambassador to Hague Meeting Over Flight MH17|first=Maarten van|last=Tartwijk|date=30 September 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n\n;1 October\n* [[Iran]]'s [[Tasnim News Agency]] and [[Press TV]] report that the [[Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps]] has built a new [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) with lethal attack capabilities. Named \"Saegheh\" (\"Thunderbolt\"), the new UAV reportedly is similar to a U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[RQ-170 Sentinel]] UAV that crashed in Iran in [[2011 in aviation#December|December 2011]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2a09bacb3a064aa6aef6049ed4145c20/iran-says-new-attack-drone-modeled-captured-us-aircraft|title=Iran says new attack drone modeled on captured US aircraft}}</ref>\n* Iraqi troops shoot down an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) measuring about {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us|spell=in}} long and {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us|spell=in}} wide in [[Iraq]] and discover that it has an explosive attached to its top.<ref name=schmidt20161011>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/12/world/middleeast/iraq-drones-isis.html|title=Pentagon Confronts a New Threat From ISIS: Exploding Drones|first1=Michael S.|last1=Schmidt|first2=Eric|last2=Schmitt|date=11 October 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] or [[Russian Federation Air Force]] aircraft bomb a major hospital known as \"M10\" in rebel-held eastern [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]], for the second time in a week, killing or wounding more than a dozen patients. Doctors at M10 report that the attack includes [[barrel bomb]]s, [[incendiary bomb]]s, and [[cluster munition]]s. Syrian government and Russian aircraft have dropped nearly 2,000 bombs on eastern Aleppo in less than two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/bombing-in-aleppo-puts-another-major-hospital-out-of-service/2016/10/01/1d6dacd8-8802-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Bombing in Aleppo puts another major hospital out of service}}</ref>\n* [[Belavia]] retires its last two [[Tupolev Tu-154]]s from scheduled service, one of the last airlines to retire the Tu-154.\n\n;2 October\n* After [[Kurds in Iraq|Kurdish]] forces shoot down an Islamic State unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) in northern Iraq, take it back to their outpost to examine it, and begin to take it apart, a bomb in the UAV disguised as a battery explodes, killing two Kurdish soldiers and injuring two French paratroopers. It is the first time the Islamic State succeeds in using a UAV to kill people.<ref name=schmidt20161011/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/10/isis-uses-exploding-drones-to-kill-kurdish-troops.html|title=ISIS Uses Exploding Drones to Kill Kurdish Troops|first=Charley|last=Lanyon}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] says that it is interested in beginning passenger service at the airports in [[Stara Zagora]], [[Gorna Oryahovitsa]], and [[Ruse, Bulgaria|Ruse]], Bulgaria, in 2017, with a final decision on the service to be made in the coming months.\n* [[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will add 10 [[ATR 72-500]] airliners to its fleet to provide service on domestic routes, replacing the airline's [[ATR 42]]s. The airline is to take delivery of its first ATR 72-500 in early 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/166648687096617/photos/a.180194489075370.1073741828.166648687096617/190892348005584/?type=3|title=Log in or Sign Up to View}}</ref>\n*[[Argentina]]'s national airline [[Aerolineas Argentinas]] announces that it has converted its existing order for [[Boeing 737-800]] airliners to an order for the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] variant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49738-aerolineas-argentinas-converts-b737-800-order-to-max|title=Aerolineas Argentinas converts B737-800 order to MAX}}</ref>\n* In six flights flown by four [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17 Globemaster III]] and two [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]] aircraft provided by [[United States Transportation Command]], the [[United States Navy]] evacuates about 700 spouses and children and a number of family pets from [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] in [[Cuba]] to [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]], [[Florida]], as [[Hurricane Matthew]] approaches [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay]]. It is the first major airlift of non-essential residents from the Guantanamo Bay base since September 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=96983|title=Families Evacuating Naval Station Guantanamo Bay, Cuba|first=This story was written by Navy Region Southeast Public|last=Affairs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article105393586.html|title=Guant\u00e1namo Navy base begins evacuating 700 parents and kids, plus pets, ahead of Hurricane Matthew \u2013 Miami Herald}}</ref>\n\n;3 October\n* In support of [[Afghan Army]] and security forces fighting against [[Taliban]] ground offensives in [[Afghanistan]], [[Afghan Air Force]] aircraft conduct airstrikes around [[Kunduz]], while in [[Lashkargah]], U.S. aircraft strike Taliban forces and [[United States Army]] [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s operate in support of Afghan ground forces fighting to retake the city from Taliban insurgents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-opens-offensives-in-afghanistan-before-government-appeal-to-aid-donors/2016/10/03/d42e05d0-8938-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Taliban opens offensives in Afghanistan ahead of government appeal to donors}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of State]] announces that it is withdrawing U.S. personnel from [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], who had spent several weeks there planning the coordination of U.S. and Russian airstrikes against terrorist forces in Syria. The withdrawal comes as the [[United States]] abandons its efforts to work with [[Russia]] in Syria because of heavy civilian casualties resulting from intense Russian Federation Air Force and Syrian Arab Air Force airstrikes against rebel-held eastern Aleppo, Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-suspends-efforts-to-work-with-russia-on-syria-cease-fire/2016/10/03/b907dbe2-8991-11e6-bff0-d53f592f176e_story.html|title=U.S. abandons efforts to work with Russia on Syria}}</ref>\n* Since the spring of 2015, U.S. aircraft have flown more than 1,000 [[aerial refueling]] sorties in support of [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] aircraft engaged in combat in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]], providing them with tens of millions of pounds of fuel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-casualties-in-yemen-bring-charges-of-us-responsibility-for-saudi-actions/2016/10/03/29a9b606-864d-11e6-ac72-a29979381495_story.html|title=Civilian casualties in Yemen bring charges of U.S. responsibility for Saudi actions}}</ref>\n\n;4 October\n* U.S. military officials in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, announce that one U.S. Army helicopter has fired at [[Taliban]] insurgent forces in Kunduz, Afghanistan, in defense of Afghan ground forces opposing a Taliban offensive there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-forces-battle-in-key-northern-city-amid-taliban-offensives-around-country/2016/10/04/7dd88736-8a1f-11e6-bff0-d53f592f176e_story.html|title=Afghan forces battle in key northern city amid Taliban offensives across country}}</ref>\n* Russia announces that it has added operational [[S-300 (missile system)|S-300]] (U.S. DoD designation \"SA-10,\" NATO reporting name \"Grumble\") [[surface-to-air missile]] systems to its air defense forces in Syria, where they join Russian [[S-200 (missile)|S-200]] (U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] designation \"SA-5,\" [[NATO reporting name]] \"Gammon\"), and [[Buk missile system|Buk]] (U.S. DoD designation \"SA-17,\" NATO reporting name \"Grizzly\") already there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/776de7fbc4bc4d14a8ef950e94bac593/russia-sends-more-air-defense-missiles-Syria|title=Russia sends more air defense missiles to Syria}}</ref><ref name=oliphant20161006>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/06/russian-air-defence-missiles-would-respond-if-us-launches-air-st/|title=Russia warns it will shoot down alliance jets over Syria if US launches air strikes against Assad}}</ref> The S-300 and S-400 missiles give Russian forces the capability to shoot down aircraft at a range of up to {{convert|250|mi|km}}, covering almost all of Syria, all of [[Cyprus]], and significant portions of [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Turkey]], and the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/russian-air-defense-raises-stakes-of-us-confrontation-in-syria/2016/10/17/85c89220-948c-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Russian air defense raises stakes of U.S. confrontation in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;6 October\n* Russia warns that it will view any airstrikes in Syria by the U.S.-led coalition against pro-Syrian-government forces as a threat to Russian military personnel and that its surface-to-air missile systems deployed in Syria would fire immediately at any aircraft appearing to pose a threat to them.<ref name=oliphant20161006/>\n* [[Finland]] notes what it suspects are two separate violations of its [[airspace]] by Russian [[Sukhoi Su-27]] (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighters over the [[Gulf of Finland]].<ref name=\"ap20161007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/finland-us-to-deepen-military-ties-through-pact/2016/10/07/fc8eaf7a-8cb7-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Finland, U.S. to deepen military ties through pact}}</ref>\n* At a meeting in [[Montreal]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO) overwhelmingly ratifies a 15-year agreement to curb [[Global warming|global-warming]]-related emissions from civil airliners on international flights (domestic flights already are covered separately by the [[Paris Agreement]] of December 2015, set to take effect in November 2016) by an estimated 2,500,000,000 tons between 2021 and 2035; it is the first international [[Climate change|climate-change]]-related pact to govern a single industry. Under the agreement, the maximum permissible emissions level permitted for commercial airlines beginning in 2021 will be set at the level of emissions in 2020; after that, and through 2035, airlines that exceed the 2020 limit will have to buy [[carbon credit]]s from other industries to compensate for exceeding the emissions limit. Participation is voluntary from 2021 through 2027, then mandatory from 2028 through 2035. The agreement is expected to cost airlines $5,300,000,000 annually and as much as $23,900,000,000 in 2035. Each of the ICAO's 191 member countries still must act on their own to put the agreement's limits into effect; 65 countries \u2013 including [[China]], the United States, and all 44 member countries of the [[European Union]]'s aviation conference \u2013 have agreed to participate, while Russia plans not to participate in the voluntary phase and [[India]] has expressed reservations about the agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_AIRCRAFT_EMISSIONS_AGREEMENT?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-10-06-13-25-15|title=Lowy, Joan, \"UN agreement reached on aircraft climate-change emissions,\" Associated Press, October 6, 2016, 1:54 p.m. EDT.}}</ref>\n\n;7 October\n* The [[Government of Finland]] announces its suspicions that Russian Sukhoi Su-27 (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighters violated Finnish airspace over the Gulf of Finland the previous day. Russia responds by denouncing the Finnish claim, asserting that its aircraft remained over [[international waters]].<ref name=\"ap20161007\"/>\n*[[Estonia]] announces that a Russian Sukhoi Su-27 (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighter violated its airspace for less than a minute earlier in the day.<ref name=\"ap20161007\"/>\n*Russia ratifies a treaty with Syria which among other things grants it a permanent airbase in Syria at [[Khmeimim (air base)|Khmeimim]], effective retroactively to [[2015 in aviation#August|26 August 2015]], the date it was signed.<ref name=filipov20161007>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/10/07/russia-has-its-permanent-airbase-in-syria-now-its-looking-at-cuba-and-vietnam/|title=Russia has its permanent air base in Syria. Now it\u2019s looking at Cuba and Vietnam.}}</ref>\n*The Russian newspaper ''[[Kommersant]]'' reports that a Russian military official said that Russian forces in Syria are under orders to \"shoot to kill\" if they come under attack, presumably by aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition.<ref name=filipov20161007/> It also reports that Russia is considering deploying [[Sukhoi Su-25]] (NATO reporting name \"Frogfoot\") aircraft to Syria. Russia had withdrawn all Su-25s from Syria in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]].<ref name=filipov20161007/>\n*[[United States Secretary of State]] [[John F. Kerry]] calls for Russia and Syria to face [[war crime]]s charges for bombing civilian targets in Aleppo, Syria. Russian officials condemn the idea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/john-kerry-urges-war-crimes-probe-into-syrian-and-russian-bombing-of-civilians/2016/10/07/8056426c-8c9c-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Kerry urges war crimes probe into Syrian and Russian bombing of civilians}}</ref>\n*[[Qatar Airways]] announces that it has made a deal with [[Boeing]] worth up to $18,600,000,000 to buy up to 100 airliners. The deal includes purchasing 10 [[Boeing 777]]s and 30 [[Boeing 787]]s for a combined $11,700,000,000 and up to 60 [[Boeing 737]]s for as much as $6,900,000,000. The purchase of Boeing 737s marks the first Qatar Airways purchase of single-aisle airliners from Boeing since 2001. Qatar Airways had expressed frustration with [[Airbus]] over delays in the delivery of [[Airbus A320neo|A320neo]] airliners it had ordered, but says it will continue to work with Airbus for delivery of the A320neos despite its Boeing 737 order.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n*[[Belarus]]\u2032 national airline [[Belavia]] officially retires its last [[Tupolev Tu-154|Tupolev Tu-154M]] (NATO reporting name \"Careless\") airliner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49901-belaruss-belavia-ends-scheduled-tu-154m-operations|title=Belarus's Belavia ends scheduled Tu-154M operations}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] outlines [[Sofia Airport]] as its first international long-haul base, with flights to begin in March 2017 using a pair of [[Airbus A330-200]]s offering service to [[Beijing]], China; [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]; and [[New York City]] in the [[United States]]. Bulgaria Air also is contemplating service from Sofia to [[Mumbai]], India, and [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]].\n*[[Airbus]] officials indicate that three unwanted [[SriLankan Airlines]] [[Airbus A350 XWB|Airbus A350-900]]s may be delivered instead to Bulgaria Air.\n*Turkey's regional carrier [[Borajet]] signs a long-term lease agreement with [[AerCap]] involving five [[Embraer E-Jet E2 family|Embraer E-Jet E2]]s, consisting of three E190 E2s and two E195-E2s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49920-turkeys-borajet-confirms-emb-190-e2-lease-plans|title=Turkey's Borajet confirms EMB-190-E2 lease plans}}</ref>\n\n;8 October\n* The [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] conducts [[October 2016 Sana'a air raid|at least three airstrikes]] against the Grand Hall in [[Sana'a]], [[Yemen]], as mourners gather for the funeral of the father of a senior [[Houthi]] official, killing 140 people and injuring 534 others. It is one of deadliest single attacks since the Saudi coalition began its intervention in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] in [[2015 in aviation#March|March 2015]]. The [[Al-Arabiya]] satellite news network airs a report saying that various Saudi military officials deny that the coalition conducted the strike; [[Saudi Arabia]] often has denied involvement in airstrikes against civilian targets during its intervention in Yemen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/airstrike-killed-more-than-80-injured-hundreds-at-yemen-funeral/2016/10/08/64a31eae-8d74-11e6-8cdc-4fbb1973b506_story.html|title=Airstrike kills more than 100, injures hundreds at Yemen funeral}}</ref><ref name=oliphant20161009>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/09/saudi-arabia-promises-investigation-following-outrage-at-funeral/|title=Saudi Arabia promises investigation following outrage at Yemen funeral airstrike that killed 140}}</ref>\n* Russia vetoes a [[United Nations Security Council resolution]] intended to bring the Russian and Syran bombing of the rebel-held eastern portion of Aleppo, Syria, to an immediate end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-vetoes-unsecurity-council-resolution-to-end-aleppo-bombing/2016/10/08/bfc67d32-8d72-11e6-8cdc-4fbb1973b506_story.html|title=Russia vetoes U.N. Security Council resolution to end Aleppo bombing}}</ref>\n\n;9 October\n*An [[Afghan Army]] [[Mil Mi-17]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter crashes in [[Baghlan Province]] in northern Afghanistan, killing all eight Afghan Army soldiers on board. The [[Taliban]] claims to have shot it down, but the [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Defense]] says the crash resulted from a technical failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/world/1106281/seven-dead-as-afghan-army-helicopter-crashes-officials|title=Bangkok Post|first=Post Publishing|last=PCL.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/10/09/eight-killed-in-afghanistan-army-helicopter-crash.html|title=Eight killed in Afghanistan army helicopter crash|date=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Saudi Arabia]] promises an investigation into the Saudi-led coalition's deadly 8 October airstrike against a funeral in Yemen, adding that it will invite U.S. experts to take part.<ref name=oliphant20161009/>\n*The [[United Nations]] estimates that airstrikes by the Saudi-led coalition are responsible for 60 percent of the estimated 3,800 civilian deaths in Yemen since the airstrikes began in March 2015.<ref name=oliphant20161009/>\n\n;10 October\n*Airbus announces that its Chief Operating Officer for Customers [[John Leahy (executive)|John Leahy]] will visit Bulgaria in November, the first visit to southeastern Europe by an Airbus executive.\n*[[Air Madagascar]] announces the resumption services to [[China]] in 2017 with flights between [[Antananarivo]], [[Madagascar]], and [[Guangzhou]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49926-air-madagascar-to-resume-china-flights-in-mid-1q17|title=Air Madagascar to resume China flights in mid-1Q17}}</ref>\n\n;11 October\n* Airstrikes targeting the rebel-held Bustan al-Qasr neighborhood of Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 14 people, with one report placing the number of dead at 16. Activists report the use of \"[[bunker buster]]\" bombs during the strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-10-11/syrian-opposition-activists-airstrikes-kill-8-in-aleppo|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrikes in Syria's Aleppo and shelling in south kill 20,\" Associated Press, 11 October 2016, 8:18 p.m.}}</ref>\n* A [[Piper PA-34 Seneca]] carrying a student pilot and his flight instructor crashes into a utility pole in [[East Hartford, Connecticut|East Hartford]], [[Connecticut]], and bursts into flames, killing the student and injuring the instructor, who tells investigators that the crash occurred after a physical altercation in the [[cockpit]] between the two men. The following day, the U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] announces that it believes that the crash was intentional and that it is transferring the crash investigation to the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/12/us/connecticut-plane-crash-possibly-intentional/index.html|title=Fatal plane crash in Connecticut was intentional, authorities suspect|author1=Rene Marsh |author2=Chris Boyette |author3=Shachar Peled|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/fbi-joins-connecticut-plane-crash-probe-tight-lipped/story?id=42746661|title=NTSB Cites 'Intentional Act' in Connecticut Plane Crash|work=ABC News|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;12 October\n*[[China Southern Airlines]] finalizes an order with [[Boeing]] for twelve [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787-9]] airliners, becoming China's first Boeing 787 customer. The deal is worth up to $3,200,000,000, and China Southern is to take delivery of the airliners between 2018 and 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-boeing-china-southern-20161012-story.html|title=Boeing wins $3.2 billion order from China Southern as 787 soars|first=Anand Krishnamoorthy and Julie|last=Johnsson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20161012/161019838/china-southern-airlines-to-buy-a-dozen-dreamliners-from-boeing-co|title=China Southern to buy 12 787 jets|first=David|last=Wren}}</ref>\n* The U.S. startup company Zipline uses an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) to deliver blood to a remote hospital in western [[Rwanda]]. Plans call for Rwanda to officially launch the world's first nationwide UAV delivery service on 14 October, with Zipline's UAVs operating 24 hours a day to make up to 150 deliveries a day. The 31-pound (14-kg) fixed-wing UAVs, which have an operational range of {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}}, fly below {{convert|500|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} to avoid commercial aircraft and drop packages to customers using disposable [[parachute]]s. Zipline plans to expand its operations into eastern Rwanda in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewashingtonpost.pressreader.com/the-washington-post|title=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2016/10/13/in-rwanda-life-saving-blood-now-drops-from-the-sky/|title=In Rwanda, lifesaving blood now drops from drones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37646474|title=Rwanda begins Zipline commercial drone deliveries|first=Dan|last=Simmons|date=14 October 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/13/13267868/zipline-drone-delivery-rwanda-blood-launch|title=Drones begin delivering blood in Rwanda|date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/10/13/technology/rwanda-drone-hospital/index.html|title=Rwanda's hospitals will use drones to deliver medical supplies|first=Matt|last=McFarland|date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trucks.com/2016/10/13/ups-zipline-drone-deliveries/|title=Zipline, UPS Begin Using Drones for Rwanda Blood Deliveries|first=Jerry|last=Hirsch|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;13 October\n*Airbus president [[Fabrice Br\u00e9gier]] holds talks with [[Ministry of Finance (Bulgaria)|Bulgarian Finance Minister]] [[Vladislav Goranov]] wants that the national airline [[Bulgaria Air]] agrees to possibility order for two next generation wide body airliners believed to be [[Airbus A350 XWB|A350-900]] worth up to $3,000,000,000. It is the first time that Br\u00e9gier and Goranov should visit in Sofia, to begin in November. A cooperation deal is signed between Airbus and Bulgaria whereas the company's subsidiary head office is located in [[Sofia, Bulgaria|Sofia]], with its renewal program of this new models.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* Former [[Premier of Alberta]] [[Jim Prentice]] is killed in the crash of a [[Cessna Citation family]] shortly after take-off from [[Kelowna, British Columbia|Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. The other three people on the plane also die.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jim-prentice-plane-crash-killed-1.3804941|title=Ex-Alberta premier Jim Prentice killed in B.C. plane crash with 3 others}}</ref>\n\n;14 October\n*[[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Defence (Malaysia)|Minister of Defense]], [[Hishammuddin Hussein]], announces that Malaysia will send fixed-wing combat aircraft and helicopters to the [[Philippines]] for the first time since [[2013 in aviation#March|March 2013]]. The aircraft will support nearly 100 Malaysian troops in operations on [[Mindanao]] against the Islamic State-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]], [[Khalifa Islamiyah Mindanao]], and [[Maute group|Maute]] factions. The deployment awaits the completion of final negotiations.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n* During the preceding two weeks, aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition have conducted 66 strikes against Islamic State targets around [[Mosul]], Iraq, in preparation for a ground offensive by [[Iraqi Army]] and allied forces intended to recapture the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/mosul-offensive-poses-key-test-for-us-strategy-against-islamic-state/2016/10/14/d6c883a6-920c-11e6-9c85-ac42097b8cc0_story.html|title=Mosul offensive poses key test for U.S. strategy against Islamic State}}</ref>\n\n;15 October\n* The [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]-based [[Joint Incidents Assessment Team]] (JIAT), an investigative body created by the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen, issues a statement that the coalition wrongly [[October 2016 Sana'a air raid|bombed]] a funeral on 8 October in Sana'a, Yemen, killing more than 100 people. The JIAT finds that the strike occurred because someone affiliated with the chief of staff of [[President of Yemen]] [[Abdrabbuh Mansour Hadi]] had incorrectly assured the coalition that the funeral was a gathering of armed [[Houthi]] rebel leaders and that the coalition's air operations center ordered the attack without the approval of the coalition command and without following precautionary procedures designed to avoid strikes against civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-backed-saudi-led-coalition-claims-responsibility-for-yemen-funeral-attack-that-killed-more-than-150/2016/10/15/43a3adea-92bf-11e6-a6a3-d50061aa9fae_story.html|title=U.S.-backed, Saudi-led coalition found responsible for Yemen funeral attack that killed more than 100}}</ref>\n* The [[Turkish Air Force]] conducts strikes against Islamic State targets in support of a ground offensive by Syrian opposition groups intended take [[Dabiq, Syria]], from the Islamic State.<ref name=mroue20161015>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/25934af492684715b92c94485b23fdfa/turkey-backed-rebels-attack-stronghold-syria|title=Turkey-backed forces attack IS stronghold in Syria}}</ref>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force and Russian Federation Air Force raids hit rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo, Syria, and an air attack probably by either Russian or Syrian aircraft in [[Termanin]], Syria, kills at least eight people and injures dozens of others.<ref name=mroue20161015/> \n* A [[United States Department of Transportation]] ban announced the previous day on [[Galaxy Note 7]] [[smartphone]]s aboard any airliner flying within, to, or from the United States goes into effect throughout the country at 12:00 noon [[Eastern Daylight Time]]. [[Samsung Electronics]] already had recalled the Galaxy Note 7 because of reports of it catching fire or exploding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/10/14/wp/2016/10/14/samsung-galaxy-note-7-banned-from-airplanes/|title=The Samsung Galaxy Note 7 is officially banned from airplanes}}</ref>\n\n;16 October\n* Airstrikes by the Turkish Air Force and international coalition strike Islamic State targets in Dabiq and [[Arshak, Syria|Arshak]], Syria, as Turkish-backed Syrian opposition ground forces capture Dabiq from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/a5b5d097a193499f900fb70a83cbdb3d/turkish-backed-syrian-opposition-captures-dabiq|title=Turkish-backed Syrian opposition captures Dabiq from IS}}</ref>\n\n;17 October\n* Aircraft and [[artillery]] of the U.S.-led coalition strike Islamic State targets around Mosul as a ground offensive to take Mosul, Iraq, from the Islamic State by [[Iraqi Army]] and police forces and Kurdish ''[[pesh merga]]'' forces begins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi-forces-ready-for-zero-hour-in-assault-on-mosul/2016/10/16/e899f83c-9246-11e6-bc00-1a9756d4111b_story.html|title=Iraqi forces begin assault to retake Mosul from Islamic State}}</ref>\n* Syrian government and Russian airstrikes in eastern Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 36 people.<ref name=mroue20161017>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/037dc6e614a14b0680a7ffb29e5de0c3/syrias-assad-seeks-egypts-help-fighting-terrorism|title=Russia sets brief cease-fire for Aleppo as strikes kill 36}}</ref>\n* The Russian government announces that Russia and the Syrian government will observe a unilateral cease fire from 8:00&nbsp;a.m. to 4:00&nbsp;p.m. on 20 October for a \"humanitarian pause\" to allow people to evacuate to [[Idlib Governorate]] from rebel-held areas in Aleppo.<ref name=mroue20161017/>\n\n;19 October\n* [[United States Secretary of Transportation]] [[Anthony Foxx]] announces new rules to protect airline passengers in the United States. They include an eventual requirement for airlines to refund baggage fees when baggage is \"substantially\" delayed, rather than only when it is lost; a requirement likely to go into effect in January 2018 for airlines to report the number of mishandled bags as a proportion of checked bags rather than in relation to the number of passengers carried; a requirement likely to go into effect by the end of 2016 for online airline booking services to disclose any bias they have toward booking on particular airlines; an eventual requirement for airlines to include regional airlines that operate as part of their networks when reporting their on-time performance; and, for the first time, a requirement likely to go into effect in 2018 for airlines to report the number of [[wheelchair]]s they mishandle. Foxx notes that the U.S. Department of Transportation expects 700 million passengers to travel on 9 million airline flights in the United States during 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/obama-administration-unveils-new-rules-to-protect-air-travelers/2016/10/19/1dc7cd3e-960e-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Obama administration unveils new rules to protect air travelers}}</ref>\n\n;19\u201320 October (overnight)\n* Turkish Air Force jets carry out 26 strikes against positions of the [[Kurds in Syria|Kurdish]] [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) in three villages \u2013 [[al-Hasiya]], [[Um al-Qura, Syria|Um al-Qura]], and [[Maarat Umm Hawsh]] \u2013 northeast of Aleppo, Syria, that the Kurdish-led [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] had recently captured from the Islamic State. Turkey claims that the strikes destroy nine buildings, an [[armored vehicle]], and four other ground vehicles belonging to the YPG. Reports of the number of casualties vary from 14 plus dozens wounded, according to the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]], to 160 to 200 killed, according to the [[Turkish Armed Forces|Turkish armed forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUSKCN12K0ER|title=Turkey bombs Syrian Kurdish militia allied to U.S.-backed force|date=20 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;20 October\n* Iraqi Army [[attack helicopter]]s support ground forces attacking Islamic State positions in [[Bartella]], Iraq, during the offensive to retake Mosul. Islamic State gunfire damages one helicopter, but it lands safely and its crew is evacuated.<ref name=morris20161020>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/new-kurdish-offensive-opens-on-mosuls-north-as-iraqi-forces-push-from-the-east/2016/10/20/19092040-9645-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=Iraq\u2019s U.S.-trained counterterrorism troops join attack on Mosul}}</ref>\n* Kurdish ''peshmerga'' forces suffer increased casualties during the day in combat against the Islamic State during the Mosul offensive. A statement by the Kurdish general command ascribes the increase to a lack of air support, saying that support and air cover by the U.S.-led coalition \"were not as decisive as in the past.\"<ref name=morris20161020/>\n* Russia and the Syrian government begin a three-day pause in their bombardment of rebel-held eastern Aleppo, Syria, to allow the delivery of humanitarian supplies and the evacuation of around 200 critically injured people. The ceasefire is longer than the eight-hour pause Syria and Russia had announced on 17 October, but less than the five days requested by international aid officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/aleppo-residents-in-rebel-held-areas-wary-of-russian-syrian-humanitarian-pause/2016/10/20/26d17fa2-96a8-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Aleppo residents in rebel-held areas wary of Russian-Syrian humanitarian pause}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]] warns Russia that it could face sanctions if its bombardment of civilians in Aleppo, Syria, continues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/european-leaders-threaten-new-sanctions-against-russia/2016/10/20/ce5f8240-960e-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=European leaders threaten new sanctions against Russia}}</ref>\n* [[American Airlines]] reports a drop of 56 percent in net income during the third quarter of 2016, with net income between 1 July and 30 September of $737.000,000 representing a decline from $1,700,000,000 from the same period in 2015. Planes flying less full and increased labor costs are factors in the decline, as is a large tax bill. Overall revenue for the quarter was $10,600,000,000, a decline of 1.1 percent from the same period in 2015. American is the world's largest airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2016/10/20/american-airlines-earnings/92451704/|title=American Airlines earnings drop 56% in 3Q, but meet expectations}}</ref>\n* The French start-up company Skylights releases the second iteration of its Bravo wearable headset device that allows airline passengers to view two-dimensional and three-dimensional movies and [[virtual reality]] entertainment content in their seats. The company has conducted trial runs of the technology over the previous year on European airlines, including [[Air France]], [[KLM]], and [[XL Airways France|XL Airways]], and hopes that rentable Bravo devices will become a mainstream form of in-flight entertainment aboard airliners around the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2016/10/20/the-airplane-is-preparing-to-land-please-remove-your-virtual-reality-headset/ |last=Overly|first= Steven|title=The airplane is preparing to land. Please remove your virtual reality headset|work=[[The Washington Post]] |date= 20 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;21 October\n*A [[Skol Airlines]] [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopter with at least 22 people on board [[2016 Skol Airlines Mil Mi-8 Siberia crash|crashes]] in Russia's [[Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug]], killing at least 19 people.\n*Amid growing complaints by the Iraqi Army and Kurdish ''peshmerga'' forces of inadequate air support by the U.S.-led coalition for their ground offensive to retake Mosul, Iraq, from the Islamic State, the [[United States Department of State]] envoy to the coalition, Special Presidential Envoy for the Global Coalition to Counter the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant [[Brett H. McGurk]], reports massive coalition airstrikes during the day in support of both forces. The airstrikes have involved aircraft ranging from attack helicopters to [[United States Air Force]] [[B-52H Stratofortress]] bombers. Iraqi ground forces also complain of insufficient aerial reconnaissance support by coalition unmanned aerial vehicles. The coalition's air power reportedly has been spread thin by the size and scope of the ground offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi--kurdish-forces-say-they-feel-let-down-by-level-of-us-led-air-support/2016/10/21/f37b0b02-97c2-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=Iraqi, Kurdish forces say they feel let down by level of U.S.-led air support}}</ref>\n*Bulgaria Air announces that it will begin round-trip service to [[Turkey]], with flights between [[Sofia Airport]] in Sofia, Bulgaria, and [[Istanbul]]'s [[Atat\u00fcrk International Airport]] in Turkey commencing in January 2017. [[Turkish Airlines]] also will provide service between the two airports, with a codeshare partnership between the two airlines expected to come in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n*[[Turkish Airlines]] announces that it has suspended services to [[Najaf]], [[Sulaymaniyah]], and [[Basrah]], Iraq, because of the Iraqi and Kurdish offensive to retake Mosul from the Islamic State.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n* The [[Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden]] rules that unmanned aerial vehicles equipped with cameras are a form of surveillance device requiring a special surveillance permit to operate. The application process in [[Sweden]] for such permits is expensive, with no guarantee that a license will be granted, and the ruling causes consternation among UAV owners and the UAV industry in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/sweden-just-made-whole-lot-073337188.html|title=Sweden has just made it a whole lot harder to fly camera drones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37761872|title=Sweden bans cameras on drones|date=25 October 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n* Amid border tensions between [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]], at least one and possibly two [[Venezuelan Air Force]] fighter aircraft approach [[Avianca]] Flight 011, a [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]] flying at an attitude of over {{convert|36000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over western Venezuela en route from [[Madrid]], [[Spain]], to [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], with 250 passengers aboard. The airliner makes a sharp turn off course to the north in order to reach Colombian [[airspace]] quickly. In the wake of the incident, Colombia suspends all flights by Colombian aircraft to and from Venezuela and orders its aircraft to avoid flying over Venezuelan airspace, and [[President of Venezuela]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] orders an investigation of the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/22/colombia-venezuela-airline-warplane-diplomatic-incident|title=Colombia airline avoids Venezuela after warplane approaches flight|last=Reuters|date=22 October 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=forero20161022>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/airline-suspends-venezuela-flights-after-plane-is-tracked-1477165809|title=Colombian Airline Avianca to Resume Flights to Venezuela|first=Juan|last=Forero|date=23 October 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n;22 October\n* The humanitarian pause in the bombardment of Aleppo, Syria, that Russia and the Syrian government had declared on 20 October comes to an end during the evening as aircraft \u2013 presumably belonging to the Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force \u2013 bomb rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/cease-fire-crumbles-in-aleppo-as-fighting-resumes/2016/10/23/a30d7c16-9918-11e6-b3c9-f662adaa0048_story.html|title=Cease-fire crumbles in Aleppo as fighting resumes}}</ref> A planned evacuation of injured people and of civilians from eastern Aleppo \u2013 the main purpose of the pause \u2013 did not take place during the pause.<ref name=mroue20161024>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-10-24-10-55-48|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n;23 October\n* Following diplomatic talks between the [[Government of Colombia]] and the [[Government of Venezuela]], Colombia lifts its suspension of flights by Colombian aircraft to, from, and over Venezuela. It had instituted the flight ban after at least one Venezelan Air Force fighter aircraft approached an Avianca Boeing 787 Dreamliner over western Venezuela on the evening of 21 October, forcing the airliner to veer off course and into Colombian airspace.<ref name=forero20161022/>\n* A [[Morton County, North Dakota]], Sheriff's Department helicopter monitoring a protest at a [[Dakota Access Pipeline]] construction site in [[North Dakota]] reports that an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) operated by the protestors has approached it in a threatening manner. Law enforcement officers in [[North Dakota]] open fire on the UAV with \"less than lethal\" ammunition, damaging it, after which its operator lands it. Protestors claim that police shot at the UAV because they do not want their activities filmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/oct/23/north-dakota-pipeline-protesters-drone-shot-after-/|title=North Dakota pipeline protesters' drone shot after buzzing police helicopter|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/10/24/authorities-open-fire-at-unmanned-drone-during-north-dakota-pipeline-protests.html|title=Authorities open fire at unmanned drone during North Dakota pipeline protests|date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;24 October\n*The [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] announces that [[Singapore]]'s low-cost carrier [[Jetstar Asia Airways]] would consider developing [[Manila]]'s [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] into an operational base in 2017. It will be the first foreign airline to set up a base in the [[Philippines]]. Ninoy Aquino International is also the base of [[Philippine Airlines]], [[Cebu Pacific]], [[AirAsia Philippines]], and [[Cebgo]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n*Airstrikes kill at least 13 people in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]].<ref name=mroue20161024/> In [[Moscow]], Russian Deputy Foreign Minister [[Sergei Ryabkov]] says that Russia is not planning another \"humanitarian pause\" in Syria anytime soon because rebel forces did not \"behave properly\" during the 20\u201322 October pause.<ref name=mroue20161024/> \n*A [[Luxembourg]]-registered [[CAE Aviation]] [[Fairchild Swearingen Metroliner|Fairchild SA227-AT Merlin IVC]] (registration N577MX) on a surveillance mission for the French [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes]] [[2016 Malta Fairchild Merlin crash|crashes]] just after takeoff from [[Malta International Airport]] in [[Malta]], killing its entire crew of five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20161024-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Swearingen SA227-AT Expediter N577MX Malta-Luqa Airport (MLA)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;25 October\n* British [[Secretary of State for Transport]] [[Chris Grayling]] announces that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] had decided to endorse the addition of a third runway at [[London]]'s [[Heathrow Airport]] after decades of delay. The construction project, under consideration since the 1970s and not expected to begin for years, will require the demolition of 738 homes in [[Harmondsworth]], [[Longford, London|Longford]], and [[Sipson]] and cost an estimated \u00a317,600,000,000. [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] postpones a vote in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on the matter until 2017, and the vote may not take place for as long as a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/26/world/europe/heathrow-airport-expansion.html|title=Third Heathrow Airport Runway Backed by British Government|first=Stephen|last=Castle|date=25 October 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bt.com/news/news-extra/how-the-cost-of-a-third-heathrow-runway-would-stack-up-11363990002861|title=How the cost of a third Heathrow runway would stack up}}</ref>\n* Disabled [[United States Army]] veteran Lisa McCombs, a sufferer of [[post-traumatic stress disorder]], files a lawsuit against [[American Airlines]] for a series of incidents between 25 and 27 October 2015 at [[Manhattan, Kansas|Manhattan]], [[Kansas]], and [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]], [[Texas]], while she was on her way to [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], [[Mississippi]], in which airline personnel refused to allow her to board aircraft operated by the [[American Airlines Group]] subsidiary [[Envoy Air]] with her [[service dog]] and publicly humiliated and intimidated her when she protested that her dog was pre-approved to travel with her aboard the planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/articles/combat-vet-sues-american-airlines-for-rejecting-her-service-dog|title=Combat vet sues American Airlines for rejecting her service dog|first=Army|last=Times}}</ref>\n* Legendary American [[World War II]], [[air show]], and [[test pilot]] [[Bob Hoover]] dies at the age of 94.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/top-pilot-who-stole-plane-to-escape-wwii-prison-camp-dies/2016/10/25/3edcb86a-9b25-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=- The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n;26 October\n*Russian or Syrian airstrikes against a residential area, an [[elementary school]], and a [[middle school]] in the village of [[Haas, Syria|Haas]] in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] kill at least 26 civilians, 15 to 20 of them children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-attack-idUSKCN12Q19D|title=Air strikes in Syria's Idlib kill 26, mostly children: rescuers, monitor|date=26 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n*Two [[Eritrean Air Force]] pilots defect to [[Ethiopia]], flying their jet fighters from [[Eritrea]] to [[Mek'ele]]. [[Ethiopian Air Force]] fighters escort them to Mek'ele after they enter Ethiopian [[airspace]]. It is the first time that Eritrean pilots have defected to Ethiopia with their jets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/eritrean-pilots-defect-ethiopia-jets-opposition-43096487|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;27 October\n* The [[Government of Turkey]] issues warrants for the detention of 73 Turkish military pilots \u2013 two [[colonel]]s and 71 [[lieutenant]]s \u2013 suspected of involvement in the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|19 July 2016 attempted ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']] in [[Turkey]], bringing 45 of them in for detention, and arrests another 29 military pilots that already had been detained for their alleged participation in the ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]''. Eighteen other military pilots previously detained are released, although nine of them are placed on [[probation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-issues-warrants-for-73-pilots-linked-to-gulen/2016/10/27/92cdde68-9c1f-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=27 October 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n* [[Eastern Air Lines Flight 3452]], a [[Boeing 737-700]] (registration N278EA) serving as the [[2016 United States presidential election|campaign]] plane for the 2016 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] nominee for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president of the United States]], [[Governor of Indiana]] [[Mike Pence]], skids off the runway while landing at [[La Guardia Airport]] in [[New York City]]. The airport's [[engineered materials arrestor system]] bed stops the plane before it reaches [[Grand Central Parkway]]. Neither Pence nor the other 47 people on board are injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/10/27/mike-pence-plane-laguardia/|title=Mike Pence's Plane Skids Off Runway While Landing at LaGuardia}}</ref>\n\n;28 October\n* The right engine of [[American Airlines Flight 383 (2016)|American Airlines Flight 383]], a [[Boeing 767-300ER]] (registration N345AN), suffers an [[Turbine engine failure|uncontained failure]] during the airliner's takeoff roll at [[O'Hare International Airport]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], with pieces of the engine flying from the aircraft; one of them strikes a [[United Parcel Service]] building {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} away, but no one on the ground is injured. The engine \u2013 a [[General Electric CF6]] \u2013 then catches fire. The crew aborts the takeoff and brings the plane to a stop {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} before the end of the runway and all 170 people and a dog aboard the airliner exit via [[evacuation slide]]s. Twenty people suffer minor injuries during the evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/us/ohare-aircraft-incident/index.html|title=At Chicago O'Hare, American 767 catches fire on runway|author1=Steve Almasy |author2=Jon Ostrower |author3=Rene Marsh|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-chicago-airplane-engine-idUSKCN12T0Q7|title=American Airlines plane engine flung debris in rare failure|date=30 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[Fedex Express Flight 910]], a [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10|McDonnell Douglas MD-10-10F]] [[cargo aircraft]] (registration N370FE), suffers a [[landing gear]] collapse as it lands at [[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport]] in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]], [[Florida]]. The plane skids to a halt and a fire breaks out that destroys the left engine and [[wing]]. The aircraft's crew of three escapes.\n* The Government of Turkey announces that it expects the Turkish Air Force to take delivery of its first six [[Lockheed Martin F-35A Lightning II]] fighters in 2018 and has decided to order more for delivery in 2021 and 2022; U.S. officials familiar with the deal say the second order will be for 24 aircraft. Turkey plans eventually to purchase a total of 100 F-35A fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lockheed-fighter-turkey-idUSKCN12S2G1|title=Turkey expects first F-35 delivery in 2018, plans more orders|date=28 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;29 October\n* An unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) operating without permission near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), forces the airport to close for 84 minutes and prompts UAE authorities to close nearby [[Sharjah International Airport]] for a similar amount of time. It is the third time that an unauthorized drone flight has caused Dubai International Airport to close in 2016, previous incidents having occurred on [[2016 in aviation#June|12 June]] and [[2016 in aviation#September|28 September]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2016/10/30/Thousands-impacted-as-drone-halts-traffic-at-Dubai-airport.html|title=Anonymous, \"Thousands impacted as drone halts traffic at Dubai airport,\" Reuters, 30 October 2016.}}</ref>\n* Strikes by aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition targeting a security complex in [[Houthi]]-rebel-held [[Hodeidah]], Yemen, kill at least 43 people and injure scores more; one report puts the death total at 60. Most of the dead are inmates held in prisons in the complex. The coalition says that the complex was a legitimate target because the Houthis were using it as a [[Command and control|command-and-control]] center for their military operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrikes-kill-more-than-40-and-wound-scores-in-yemeni-port-city/2016/10/30/4666dbfd-afa3-4f8f-9542-7ad77664d4ee_story.html|title=Airstrikes kill more than 40 and wound scores in Yemeni port city}}</ref>\n\n;30 October\n* [[Airbus]] announces that the [[Airbus A320neo|A320neo]] prototype could make to land in [[Bulgaria]] in November 2016, claims to be directly first to visit in [[southeastern Europe]]. The A320neo becomes the second leg of the European destination, after [[Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JajaDeleraINTL/status/792522697066418176|title=JDGlobal on Twitter}}</ref>{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;31 October\n* An [[Alfa Indonesia]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou|PEN Turbo DHC-4T Turbo Caribou]] (registration PK-SWW) on a domestic flight from [[Timika]] to [[Ilaga, Indonesia|Ilaga]], [[Indonesia]], [[2016 Alfa Indonesia DHC-4 crash|crashes]] into the side of Ilaga Pass near [[Jita, Indonesia|Jita]] in Indonesia's [[Papua (province)|Papua]] province on [[New Guinea]] at an altitude of {{convert|12800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, killing all four people on board. Its wreckage is found the next day.\n\n===November===\n\n;1 November\n*China-based [[Donghai Airlines]] finalizes its order with [[Boeing]] for five [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787-9 Dreamliner]] airliners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/50599-chinas-donghai-airlines-commits-to-five-b787s|title=China's Donghai Airlines commits to five B787s}}</ref>\n\n;2 November\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] announces that [[Plovdiv Airport]] will close to all commercial traffic temporarily for runway work beginning in February 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n*The [[Lebanese Civil Aviation Authority]] announces a ban on [[Samsung Galaxy Note 7]] smartphones on its flights due to safety concerns based on the [[2016 in aviation#October|15 October]] ban the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] placed on them because of their tendency to catch fire or explode.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2016/Nov-02/379255-aviation-authority-bans-samsung-galaxy-note-7.ashx dailystar.com.lb Aviation authority bans Samsung Galaxy Note 7 \u2013 ''The Daily Star'' (Lebanon), 2 November 2016.]</ref>\n\n;3 November\n* Airstrikes supporting [[Government of Afghanistan|Afghan government]] troops fighting to push [[Taliban]] forces out [[Kunduz]], [[Afghanistan]], reportedly kill 30 civilians and injure 25 others in and around the city. One report puts the death toll at up to 100 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-civilians-killed-in-errant-airstrikes-in-kunduz-2-us-soldiers-killed-in-clashes/2016/11/03/4c9a76a6-a1ae-11e6-a44d-cc2898cfab06_story.html|title=2 U.S. troops killed fighting Taliban in Afghanistan; civilians hit by airstrike}}</ref><ref name=constable20161105>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/us-military-acknowledges-anti-taliban-airstrikes-killed-afghan-civilians/2016/11/05/ed303aee-a364-11e6-8864-6f892cad0865_story.html|title=U.S. military acknowledges anti-Taliban airstrikes killed Afghan civilians}}</ref> U.S. military officials will acknowledge on 5 November that the airstrikes inflicted casualties on civilians, but do not estimate the number of casualties.<ref name=constable20161105/>\n\n;5 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that the [[Airbus A320neo]] as its next generation candidate of narrow body airliners, [[Airbus]] said in a directly press statement. [[France|French]] foreign trade minister Matthias Fekl says renegotiations with the Balkan carrier as its order for up to six aircraft, any not it finalizes agreement.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Philippine Airlines]] announces that it will withdraw the [[Airbus A320]] from its fleet beginning in 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n;6 November\n*[[Slovakia]]-based [[Go2Sky]] announces it will add an [[Airbus A320]] to its fleet in late December 2016, becoming the first Slovak operator of [[Airbus]] aircraft. The A320 will become the fifth aircraft in the Go2Sky fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/photos/a.355324357939379.1073741827.159511714187312/782209621917515/?type=3|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n* [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] jets have scrambled over 600 times since 1 January to monitor Russian military air traffic around [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russian-warplanes-keep-buzzing-the-baltics-heres-how-nato-scrambles/2016/11/06/15c1ea6e-9df4-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=Russian warplanes keep buzzing the Baltics. Here\u2019s how NATO scrambles.}}</ref>\n\n;7 November\n* Airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces near [[Ayn Issa]], [[Syria]], destroy six fighting position and seven ground vehicles, including two vehicles filled with explosives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/islamic-state-car-bombs-in-syria-hit-us-backed-forces-aiming-for-stronghold-raqqa/2016/11/07/901acbd2-a4d9-11e6-ba59-a7d93165c6d4_story.html|title=Islamic State sends car bombs against U.S.-backed forces advancing on Raqqa}}</ref> \n* A [[United States Department of Defense]] spokesman says that the [[United States]] is ready to conduct more airstrikes against Islamic State forces in [[Libya]] if the Libyan [[Government of National Accord]] requests them. The United States has conducted over 350 airstrikes against the Islamic State in Libya since [[2016 in aviation#August|August]], but none since 31 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-libya-airstrikes-idUSKBN1322M1|title=U.S. ready to resume air strikes in Libya if needed: Pentagon|date=7 November 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;8 November\n* Seven airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition targeting six Islamic State tactical units near Ayn Issa, Syria, destroy three fighting positions, a ground vehicle, and a [[car bomb]] facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37922167|title=Syria conflict: Coalition strike 'kills 20 civilians near Raqqa'|date=9 November 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;9 November\n* The [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] claims that a strike by the U.S.-led coalition in [[Heisha]], Syria, kill at least 20 civilians and injure 30 others. The coalition says it will investigate the claim of civilian casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-syria-airstrike-20161109-story.html|title=Activists blame U.S.-led coalition for airstrike in Syria that kills at least 20 people|first=Molly|last=Hennessy-Fiske|date=9 November 2016|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n* [[United States Central Command]] announces that it has reexamined its estimate of the number of civilians its airstrikes have killed in [[Iraq]] and Syria since its air campaign against the Islamic State began in 2014 based on allegations by activist groups and that has added 64 deaths to is estimate, bringing its estimate to a total of 119 civilians killed. It continues to investigate allegations of additional civilian deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/11/09/u-s-military-announces-that-civilian-casualties-in-iraq-and-syria-are-more-than-double-previous-estimate/|title=U.S. military announces that civilian casualties in Iraq and Syria are more than double previous estimate}}</ref>\n\n;11 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] Chief Executive Officer Hristo Todorov requests that the wide body airliners candidate  \u2013 [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-200]] and [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]] will yet to be selected before the launch of transatlantic service in 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Taiwan]]-based [[TransAsia Airways]] officially retires the [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-300]] from its fleet.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n*Computer problems at [[Sabre Corporation]] cause check-in and flight delays on [[Alaska Airlines]], [[American Airlines]], [[JetBlue Airways]], [[Southwest Airlines]], and [[Virgin America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/business/computer-outage-briefly-grounds-flights-on-several-airlines/|title=Computer outage briefly grounds flights on several airlines|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n;13 November\n*Airstrikes targeting rebel-held areas in western [[Aleppo Governorate]] in Syria knock out a [[Syrian Civil Defense]] center in [[Atareb]] and kill three people. In northern [[Idlib Governorate]], an airstrike kills a woman and her four children. In the western [[Ghouta]] region outside [[Damascus]], an airstrike on a [[mosque]] in [[Khan al-Shih]] kills two people. And an explosion attributed to an airstrike at a crossing point between Syria's [[Syrian Kurds|Kurdish]]-held [[Afrin District]] and rebel-held parts of Aleppo Governorate kills at least eight\u2014as perhaps as many as 12\u2014people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/fab6efc20da84824b542166ccab34f3d/violence-northern-syria-kills-12|title=Violence in northern Syria kills 23}}</ref>\n\n;15 November\n*Syrian government and Russian forces renew their offensive against rebels in Syria. Heavy Syrian government airstrikes hit rebel-held eastern [[Aleppo]], Syria. Russia denies that it has struck Aleppo during the day, but announces that Russian aircraft and land-based and ship-launched [[cruise missile]]s have struck Islamic State targets and positions of an [[al-Qaeda]]-linked rebel group in Syria's [[Homs Governorate]] and [[Idlib Governorate]], claiming that the targets were industrial sites the groups were using to manufacture toxic substances used in [[weapons of mass destruction]]. A Russian [[aircraft carrier]] sees combat for the first time in history during the day, when the [[Russian Federation Navy]] carrier ''[[Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov|Admiral Kuznetsov]]'', operating in the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]], launches [[Sukhoi Su-33]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Flanker D\") aircraft which strike targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russian-warplanes-from-mediterranean-carrier-join-syria-attacks/2016/11/15/fe0056d2-ab26-11e6-977a-1030f822fc35_story.html|title=Russian warplanes from Mediterranean carrier join Syria attacks}}</ref>\n*[[Will Rogers World Airport]] in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]], closes to commercial traffic for several hours \u2013 although a [[United States Government]] aircraft carrying prison inmates to a federal inmate transfer center is allowed to land \u2013 after a former Southwest Airlines employee who had been fired in 2015 uses a rifle to kill another Southwest Airlines employee just outside the airport, then shoots himself to death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/15/us/oklahoma-city-airport-shooting/index.html|title=Airline employee killed at Oklahoma City airport; suspect dead|author1=Keith Allen |author2=Steve Almasy|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/11/16/oklahoma-airport-shoot-airlines-employee/93958962/|title=Former Southwest Airlines employee named as shooter in Okla. airport murder}}</ref>\n*At [[Centennial Airport]] in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Boom Technology]] unveils the engineering design for its XB-1 Baby Boom supersonic technology demonstrator aircraft, a scaled-down version of a 45-passenger [[Supersonic transport|supersonic airliner]] it hopes to produce and place in service by 2023. The Baby Boom is expected to make its first flight in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/baby-boom-supersonic-demonstrator-unveiled |title= 'Baby Boom' Supersonic Demonstrator Unveiled |date= 15 November 2016 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/awincommercial/baby-boom-demonstrator-passes-design-review |title= 'Baby Boom' Demonstrator Passes Design Review |date= 15 June 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Daily |publisher= Aviation Week Network |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n\n;16 November\n*Syrian government airstrikes pound eastern Aleppo, Syria, badly damaging the city's last remaining children's hospital; Russia denies any involvement in strikes against eastern Aleppo, claiming to have conducted none there since 18 October. At least 87 people are killed in Aleppo Governorate during the day. Russian air and cruise missile strikes continue in Idlib Governorate, where 34 sites have been hit and six people killed and dozens wounded since 15 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/warplanes-bomb-childrens-hospital-as-assad-renews-aleppo-offensive/2016/11/16/a9784fa8-abd9-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=Warplanes bomb children\u2019s hospital as Assad renews Aleppo offensive}}</ref>\n\n;19 November\n*According to officials in Afghanistan, an airstrike by an unmanned aerial vehicle in [[Nangahar Province]] in eastern Afghanistan kills eight Islamic State personnel including [[Mullah Bozorg]], a top Islamic State commander.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-nov-19-2016/2016/11/19/cf995b7e-ae8f-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=World Digest: Nov. 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 November\n*After a U.S. military unmanned aerial vehicle spots Islamic State personnel [[Decapitation|beheading]] and shooting civilians in the [[Mosul]], Iraq, area, a U.S. [[laser-guided bomb]] is used to scatter the executioners.<ref name=ryan20161220>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/20/when-air-power-works-and-when-it-doesnt/|title=When air power works, and when it doesn\u2019t: A snapshot of U.S. operations against the Islamic State}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] confirms to acquire at least four [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]] aircraft in giving instead of [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-200]] already to enter service in 2017. In addition, the airline agrees to ten [[Airbus A320 family]] in anticipation to join the fleet with bringing the operator of A320 family to fifteen.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;21 November\n*The [[United States]] grants a license to [[Airbus]] to sell 106 airliners to [[Iran]]; it will announce that it has granted the license the following day. Airbus required the license because at least 10 percent of the airliners' parts are manufactured in the United States. Previously, Airbus had had a U.S. license to sell only 17 airliners to Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-aviation-usa-idUSKBN13H1W0|title=Exclusive: U.S. grants second Airbus license to sell planes to Iran|date=22 November 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;22 November\n* Approximately 250 pilots who fly cargo aircraft for [[ABX Air]] go on strike, claiming the airline is violating their contract by giving them too many flight assignments. ABX Air says it views the strike as illegal. The strike affects package deliveries by ABX Air's two biggest customers, [[Amazon.com]] and [[DHL Express]], as the 2016 [[Christmas and holiday season|Christmas shopping season]] begins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/11/22/amazon-holiday-shipments/|title=Pilot Strike Could Delay Amazon's Holiday Shipments}}</ref>\n* The [[Government of Canada]] announces that it will buy 18 [[F-18 Super Hornet]]s from [[Boeing]] as a stopgap measure and begin a process of as long as five years to determine how to replace its aging fighter fleet, which consists of 77 [[McDonnell Douglas CF-18 Hornet]]s, a decline from what once had been a force of 138 CF-18s. The announcement is a blow to [[Lockheed Martin]], which had hoped to sell [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] fighters to [[Canada]]. Although Canada plans to remain one of the countries contributing to the development of the F-35, it has backed off its earlier plans to purchase F-35s.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/23/business/international/canada-to-buy-f-18s-from-boeing-to-shore-up-its-fighter-fleet.html ]</ref>\n\n;23 November\n*An airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition \"disables\" the fourth of five bridges across the [[Tigris]] in Mosul, Iraq, leaving only one bridge intact. Airstrikes had destroyed another bridge earlier in the week and two in October. The destruction of the bridges has disrupted Islamic State supply lines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/nov/23/is-claims-coalition-airstrike-disables-fourth-mosu/|title=Airstrike hits Mosul bridge, disrupting ISIS supply lines|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n*[[Spain]]'s national airline [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] formally its last flight for the [[Airbus A340|Airbus A340-300]] from service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/50594-iberia-ends-a340-300-operations|title=Iberia ends A340-300 operations}}</ref>\n*A [[United States federal judge|U.S. federal judge]] in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], orders ABX Air pilots who had gone on strike the previous day to return to work. Their union says that it will obey the judge's order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/23/technology/airline-used-by-amazon-goes-to-court-as-pilot-strike-enters-day-2.html|title=Airline Used by Amazon Wins Order to End Cargo Pilots' Strike|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|date=23 November 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 November\n* [[Turkey]] agrees to send a large firefighting aircraft to [[Israel]] to assist in [[aerial firefighting]] efforts against major wildfires burning there. [[Russia]], meanwhile, agrees to send two large firefighting aircraft to Israel. [[Croatia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Greece]], and [[Italy]] have sent a combined seven aircraft to Israel to assist in firefighting.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Turkey-Russia-among-countries-rushing-to-Israels-aid-to-fight-fires-473532 Keinon, Herb, \"Turkey, Russia Among Countries Rushing to Israel\u2032s Aid to Fight Fires,\" ''Jerusalem Post'', 24 November 2016, 12:19.]</ref>\n* The U.S.-led coalition has conducted over 16,000 airstrikes against Islamic State targets since beginning its air campaign against the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/heres-hoping-trump-flip-flops-even-more/2016/11/24/da04e8d6-b195-11e6-840f-e3ebab6bcdd3_story.html|title=Here\u2019s hoping Trump flip-flops even more|first1=Fareed|last1=Zakaria|first2=Fareed|last2=Zakaria|date=24 November 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\n;25 November\n*The watchdog group [[Airwars]] announces that air and [[artillery]] strikes by the U.S.-led coalition have combined to kill between 84 and 87 civilians and wound more than 160 other civilians in and around Mosul, Iraq, since the coalition's ground offensive to clear Islamic State forces from Mosul began on 17 October. A [[United States Central Command]] spokesman responds that \"the liberation of Mosul is an operation that is an order of magnitude larger and more complex than\" operations to liberate \"any of the previous cities that have been liberated\" from the Islamic State, adding that U.S. military forces extensively review proposed strikes, using intelligence and surveillance to verify targets before launching them and noting that coalition strikes have destroyed dozens of Islamic State [[car bomb]]s and tunnels in around Mosul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-mosul-campaign-reported-civilian-deaths-in-us-strikes-climb/2016/11/25/e4ca84e0-b33b-11e6-bc2d-19b3d759cfe7_story.html|title=In Mosul campaign, reported civilian deaths in U.S. strikes climb}}</ref>\n* A U.S.-based [[Evergreen 747 Supertanker]]\u2014the world's largest aerial firefighting aircraft, based on the [[Boeing 747-400]] \u2013 arrives in Israel to assist in battling major wildfires that have been burning for four days. [[Azerbaijan]] also sends a firefighting plane and [[Egypt]] sends two helicopters to help battle the fires.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/US-Supertanker-lands-in-Israel-to-assist-with-raging-fires-473685 Anonymous, \"US Supertanker Lands in Israel to Assist With Raging Fires,\" ''Jerusalem Post'', 25 November 2016, 20:08.]</ref>\n\n;26 November\n*In the [[November 2016 Butig clash]]: [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated militant organization [[Maute group]] which passes in the occupied town of [[Butig]] in [[Lanao del Sur]], [[Philippines]]. [[Philippine Air Force]] [[SIAI-Marchetti SF.260]] dropped {{convert|150|lb|kg}} bombs, all roads will close to the public.<ref name=thirdday>{{cite news|last1=Zambrano|first1=Chiara|title=Troops bombard Maute militants as fighting enters third day|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/28/16/troops-bombard-maute-militants-as-fighting-enters-third-day|accessdate=28 November 2016|work=ABS-CBN News|agency=ABS-CBN News. Agence France-Presse|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n;27 November\n*[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Foreign Minister of Malaysia]] [[Anifah Aman]] says [[Malaysia]] will any deployment of both fixed wing aircraft and helicopters to the [[Philippines]], including Basilan. The reach agreement will allow both [[Malaysian Armed Forces]] and the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP) to launch an offensive in combat against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]], resulting over the phase.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* After a firefight begins between Islamic State-affiliated Syrian rebels and a reconnaissance unit of the [[Israel Defense Forces]]\u2032 [[Golani Brigade]] along the ceasefire line between Israel and Syria in the [[Golan Heights]], the [[Israeli Air Force]] spots a ground vehicle armed with a heavy [[machine gun]] and destroys it with a rocket, killing four Syrian rebels. An Israeli military spokesman describes the incident as the \"first substantial fight\" between Israeli forces and an Islamic State affiliate in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israeli-forces-kill-4-islamic-state-allies-in-golan-heights-firefight/2016/11/27/40165fb6-ffe3-4dd6-a23a-5231f1a4c057_story.html|title=Israeli forces kill 4 Islamic State allies in Golan Heights firefight}}</ref>\n* Israel approves the purchase of 17 additional [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] fighter aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/11/29/its-been-a-topsy-turvy-few-weeks-for-the-f-35-program/|title=It\u2019s been a topsy-turvy few weeks for the F-35 program}}</ref>\n\n;28 November\n*The first scheduled commercial airline flight between the [[United States]] and [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], since the early 1960s takes place as an [[American Airlines]] jet arrives at Havana's [[Jose Marti International Airport]] from [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]]. [[JetBlue]] initiates Havana service later in the day with a flight from [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-airlines-cuba-1129-biz-20161128-story.html|title=First commercial Havana-bound flights touch down amid transition for U.S., Cuba|first=Lauren Zumbach, Robert|last=Channick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/jetblue-launches-flights-kennedy-airport-havana-article-1.2889845|title=JetBlue launches flights from Kennedy Airport to Havana}}</ref>\n*[[LaMia Airlines Flight 2933]], an [[British Aerospace 146|Avro RJ85]] (registration CP-2933), crashes in [[Colombia]] after its crew declares electrical and fuel emergencies. The crash kills 71 of the 77 people on board, including 19 members of the [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Chapecoense de Futebol]] [[association football|football]] (soccer) team, and leaves all six survivors injured. Prominent survivors include football team members [[Alan Ruschel]], [[Jakson Follmann]], and [[Neto (footballer, born 1985)|Neto]]. Their teammate [[Marcos Danilo Padilha|Danilo]] survives initially but later dies in a hospital.\n\n;29 November\n* Iraqi forces advancing on Mosul call upon more than a dozen U.S. surveillance aircraft \u2013 including [[General Atomics MQ-1 Predator|MQ-1 Predator]] and [[General Atomics MQ-9 Reaper|MQ-9 Reaper]] \u2013 and 43 U.S. combat planes \u2013 including [[United States Air Force]] [[B-52H Stratofortress]]es, [[F-15 Eagle]]s, and [[F-22 Raptor]]s and [[United States Marine Corps]] [[AV-8B Harrier]]s\u2014as well as [[electronic warfare]] aircraft and [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s for support against Islamic State targets. The aircraft fire more than 80 [[precision-guided munition]]s and destroy four [[car bomb]]s, four [[Mortar(weapon)|mortar]] systems and an Islamic State compound, among other targets.<ref name=ryan20161220/>\n* [[United Airlines]] begins service between the United States and Havana, Cuba, with a flight from [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2016/11/29/united-airlines-passengers-celebrate-first-flight-newark-cuba/94604576/|title=United Airlines, passengers celebrate first flight from Newark to Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;30 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] officially announces that it will discontinue its [[Wet lease|wet-lease]] agreements for aircraft in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/posts/795675403904270|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n\n;1 December\n\n* A [[ski]]-equipped [[Lockheed LC-130|Lockheed LC-130 Hercules]] of the [[New York Air National Guard]]'s [[109th Airlift Wing]] evacuates [[Apollo 11]] [[astronaut]] [[Buzz Aldrin|Edwin \"Buzz\" Aldrin]], the second man to walk on the moon, from the [[South Pole]] after he falls ill while there with a tour group. The LC-130 flies him to [[McMurdo Station]] on [[Antarctica]]'s [[Ross Island]]. He then flies on a [[Safair]] cargo plane to [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]], where he arrives on 2 December for hospitalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/12/01/ailing-buzz-aldrin-second-man-on-the-moon-is-being-medically-evacuated-from-the-south-pole/|title='Ailing' Buzz Aldrin, the second man to walk on the moon, is safely evacuated from the South Pole}}</ref>\n* [[Delta Air Lines]] makes its first flight to [[Cuba]] in 55 years. The flight departs [[Miami International Airport]] in [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]], and arrives at [[Jose Marti International Airport]] in [[Havana]]. Later in the day, Delta inaugurates additional U.S.-Cuba routes with flights to Havana from [[New York City]]'s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] and from [[Hartsfield-Jackson International Airport]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelpulse.com/news/airlines/delta-air-lines-returns-to-cuba-after-55-years.html|title=Delta Air Lines Returns to Cuba After 55 Years}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that it has identified 54 additional civilian deaths attributable to airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition in [[Iraq]] and [[Syria]] between 31 March and 22 October 2016, bringing to 173 the number of civilian deaths the [[United States]] claims have been the result of coalition airstrikes since the air campaign began in [[2014 in aviation#June|June 2014]]. The announcement revises a [[2016 in aviation#July|July 2016]] Department of Defense announcement of 55 civilian deaths during the air campaign and a [[United States Central Command]] finding announced on [[2016 in aviation#November|9 November 2016]] that the campaign had killed 64 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/01/u-s-led-coalition-in-iraq-and-syria-acknowledges-54-civilians-killed-in-airstrikes/|title=U.S.-led coalition in Iraq and Syria acknowledges 54 civilians killed in airstrikes}}</ref>\n\n;2 December\n\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will start service to [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], from [[Sofia Airport]] in [[Sofia, Bulgaria|Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]], starting in April 2017. It will become the first Bulgarian airline to offer service to [[Southeast Asia]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;4 December\n*Airstrikes in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] kill at least 50 people during the day, with one report putting the death toll at 52. Observers suspect the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] or [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] of having conducted the attacks. Dozens of the deaths occur in two strikes which target rural marketplaces in [[Kafr Nabl]] and [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrian-army-tells-rebels-in-aleppo-to-leave-or-dieat-least-50-civilians-reported-killed-in-airstrikes-on-idlib-province/2016/12/04/d6b02738-ba67-11e6-94ac-3d324840106c_story.html|title=Syrian army tells rebels in Aleppo to leave or die}}</ref>\n\n;5 December\n*A [[Russian Naval Aviation]] [[Sukhoi Su-33]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Flanker D\") crashes into the [[Mediterranean Sea]] after an [[Arresting gear|arresting cable]] snaps while it is attempting to land on the [[Russian Federation Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov|Admiral Kuznetsov]]''. The pilot survives. It is the second aircraft ''Admiral Kuznetsov'' has lost since beginning combat operations off [[Syria]]; the first was a [[Mikoyan MiG-29K]] (NATO reporting name \"Fulcrum D\") which crashed in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-just-lost-its-second-warplane-in-a-month-of-syria/2016/12/05/f8353be8-bad8-11e6-817f-e3b588251d1e_story.html|title=Russian jets keep crashing, and it may be an aircraft carrier\u2019s fault}}</ref>\n\n;6 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that a dry-lease term contract with [[White Airways]] to buy two [[Boeing 777]] aircraft starting in 2017 to supplement the existing four [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]]. [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Portugal)|Foreign Minister of Portugal]] [[Augusto Santos Silva]] claims that the [[Bulgaria]] \u2013 [[Portugal]] bilateral agreement negotiations will be announced in spring 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/posts/799511193520691|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n*U.S. [[President of the United States|President]]-elect [[Donald Trump]] [[Twitter|tweets]] that the [[United States Air Force]] contract to replace the fleet of aging [[Boeing VC-25]] aircraft that operate as [[Air Force One]] with two new aircraft based on the [[Boeing 747-8]] at a cost of $4,000,000,000 is too expensive and should be canceled. The U.S. Air Force and [[Boeing]] counter that the old aircraft are in need of replacement and that the special requirements for presidential aircraft inevitably lead to a high price for them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/06/citing-cost-overruns-trump-says-boeings-contract-to-build-air-force-one-should-be-canceled/|title=Citing high cost, Trump says Boeing\u2019s contract to build Air Force One should be canceled}}</ref>\n*The [[United States Department of Justice]] approves the purchase of [[Virgin America]] by [[Alaska Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/12/06/alaska-airlines-merger-virgin-america-gets-ok-doj/95049528/|title=Justice Dept. OKs Alaska Airlines-Virgin America merger}}</ref>\n\n;7 December\n*After its pilot reports the failure of one of its engines, [[Pakistan International Airlines Flight 661]], an [[ATR 42-500]] (registration AP-BHO), crashes near [[Havelian]], [[Pakistan]], killing all 47 people on board. Pakistani recording artist, television personality, fashion designer, actor, singer-songwriter, preacher, and televangelist [[Junaid Jamshed]] is among the dead.\n\n;8 December\n* After U.S. pilots drop leaflets warning the drivers of Islamic State [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] of the impending attack, [[United States Air Force]] [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]] aircraft destroy 168 of the trucks near [[Palmyra]], Syria, as part of [[Operation Tidal Wave II]].<ref name=warrick20161231>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/take-them-back-to-the-19th-century-inside-the-economic-war-against-the-islamic-state/2016/12/30/5f91f514-ceb7-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html|title=Inside the economic war against the Islamic State}}</ref>\n\n;10 December\n*[[Stara Zagora Airport]] in southern Bulgaria announces that much as paving the way for a potential commercial passenger service will begin in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] awards this Air Operator's Certificate to [[Stara Zagora]], [[Gorna Oryahovitsa]], and [[Ruse, Bulgaria|Ruse]] with bring to start in 2017. [[Bulgaria Air]] said it will add five [[ATR 72-500]]s converted from ten airliners, many as possible order for an [[ATR 72-600]] to be leased initially.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;11 December\n* [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces retake Palmyra, Syria, from the [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]]. Unlike in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]], when Russian Federation Air Force strikes played a key and effective role against the Islamic State in the Syrian government's recapture of Palmyra, Russian airstrikes on 10 and 11 December are ineffective in stopping the Islamic State advance. Although [[human rights]] organizations have accused the Russian Federation Air Force of intensive bombing of civilian targets during the [[Syrian Civil War]], [[Russia]] claims that its pilots were unable to respond effectively to the Islamic State's advance on Palmyra because Russian pilots were unwilling to endanger civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/battle-rages-for-palmyra-as-islamic-state-is-poised-to-retake-control/2016/12/11/396552ea-bf9a-11e6-afd9-f038f753dc29_story.html|title=Syrian troops pull out as Islamic State militants sweep back into ancient Palmyra}}</ref>\n* [[Iran Air]] finalizes a deal to buy 80 airliners from [[Boeing]] at a cost of $16,600,000,000. The deal includes 50 [[Boeing 737 MAX 8]]s, 15 [[Boeing 777-300ER]]s, and 15 [[Boeing 777-9]]s. Iran Air plans to take delivery of the first planes in 2018, with deliveries completed over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/adfb6564faac4b148d7418803f7e6576/iran-says-its-finalized-166b-boeing-deal-buy-80-planes|title=Iran seals deal with Boeing to buy 80 planes worth $16.6B}}</ref>\n\n;12 December\n* In the wake of 7 December crash of its Flight 661, Pakistan International Airlines grounds the five ATR 42 and [[ATR 72]] airliners in its fleet after the [[Pakistan Civil Aviation Authority]] decides to conduct \"shakedown tests\" of the airline's entire fleet of [[ATR (aircraft manufacturer)|ATR]] aircraft.<ref name=hassan20161213>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/pakistan-pia-idINKBN1421TW|title=Pakistan International Airlines chairman resigns days after plane crash|first=Reuters|last=Editorial}}</ref>\n* Supported by Syrian government and Russian airstrikes, Syrian government ground forces reduce the rebel-held portion of [[Aleppo]], Syria, to a small sliver of territory that is no more than a tenth of what they used to control in the city, leaving the Syrian government poised to reconquer the entire city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-forces-push-aleppo-rebels-to-brink-as-city-nears-total-collapse/2016/12/12/0e7e7e82-c079-11e6-afd9-f038f753dc29_story.html|title=Syrian forces push Aleppo rebels to brink as city nears 'total collapse'}}</ref>\n* After hours of delay due to [[fog]] at their departure point outside [[Milan]], [[Italy]], the [[Israeli Air Force]]'s first two [[F-35 Lightning II]] fighters, flown by U.S. pilots, arrive at [[Nevatim Airbase]] in [[Israel]]. Plans call for Israeli pilots to fly them for the first time the following day. Israel plans to acquire 50 of the aircraft at a total cost of around $5,000,000,000.<ref name=booth20161212>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israel-waited-a-long-time-for-its-f-35-jets-then-it-waited-some-more/2016/12/12/2590ab1c-c089-11e6-a52b-a0a126eaf9f7_story.html|title=Israel finally receives the first of its $5 billion order of U.S.-made F-35 jets}}</ref>\n* U.S. President-elect Donald Trump [[Twitter|tweets]] that the F-35 Lightning II's \"cost is out of control. Billions of dollars can and will be saved on military (and other) purchases after 20 January [2017],\" the day of the [[United States presidential inauguration]]. The stock price for the F-35's manufacturer, [[Lockheed Martin]] falls over 4 percent at one point after Trump's tweet, and closes for the day down 2.47 percent.<ref name=booth20161212/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/12/trump-takes-aim-at-pentagons-revolving-door-and-lockheed-martins-400-billion-f-35-program/|title=Trump takes aim at Pentagon\u2019s 'revolving door' and Lockheed Martin\u2019s $400 billion F-35 program}}</ref>\n\n;13 December\n* A [[United States Marine Corps]] [[MV-22 Osprey]] crashes in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Okinawa]] after a hose connected to it during an [[aerial refueling]] exercise breaks and damages one of its propellers. Its five-man crew is rescued, two of them with non-life-threatening injuries. It is the first crash of an Osprey in [[Japan]]. Following the crash, the [[Government of Japan]] calls for an end to Osprey flights in Japan, and on 14 December the U.S. military will ground all Ospreys in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-osprey-crash-idUSKBN14302J|title=U.S. grounds Osprey aircraft in Japan after Okinawa crash|date=14 December 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The chairman of Pakistan International Airlines, Azam Saigol, resigns for \"personal reasons.\" He had been under pressure to resign due to concerns about the airline's safety record following the 7 December crash of Pakistan International Airlines Flight 661.<ref name=hassan20161213/>\n\n;14 December\n*A ceasefire agreement to allow Syrian rebels and civilians to evacuate the last part of Aleppo, Syria, that the reels hold breaks down almost as soon as it begins, and, after a heavy storm clears the area, airstrikes in support of Syrian government forces resume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/aleppo-evacuation-deal-for-rebels-stalls-amid-disagreements-and-renewed-shelling/2016/12/14/ebc3290c-c1a3-11e6-92e8-c07f4f671da4_story.html|title=Aleppo evacuation deal for rebels shatters, violence surges}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] says a finalize its agreement to buy four aircraft (via freighter configuration) for establishing the cargo revenue operations with maiden flights scheduled for 2017. The cargo unit will be called Bulgaria Air Cargo, which played a key role for logistics and mail support for [[Europe]] and [[Asia]] from a hub at [[Sofia Airport]]. It also announced a cargo handing service should be being consideration.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* For the first time, [[Amazon.com]] makes a delivery to a customer using an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]. The [[Amazon Prime Air]] delivery takes place in the [[United Kingdom]]. The customer's order \u2013 for an [[Amazon Fire TV]] device and a bag of [[popcorn]] \u2013 arrives 13 minutes after it was placed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/12/14/amazon-makes-its-first-drone-delivery-to-a-real-customer/|title=Amazon makes its first drone delivery to a real customer}}</ref>\n\n;15 December\n* The [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Defense]] reports that China's first [[aircraft carrier]], ''[[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning|Liaoning]]'', had completed its first live-fire exercises \"a few days\" earlier. During the exercises, which included air interception, sea-based attacks and [[air defense]], reconnaissance, [[early warning]] and anti-missile defense, ''Liaoning'''s [[Shenyang J-15]] jets reportedly carried live ordnance and successfully fired missiles at targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/12/16/show-force-chinas-1st-aircraft-carrier-carries-out-1st-live-fire-exercise.html|title=Show of force: China's first aircraft carrier carries out first live-fire exercise|date=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n;18 December\n* Flying in poor weather and low cloud cover, an [[Indonesian Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130H Hercules]] carrying 12 [[metric ton]]s of food supplies and [[cement]] [[2016 Indonesian Air Force Lockheed C-130 Hercules crash|crashes]] on [[New Guinea]]'s Mount Lisuwa while on approach to [[Wamena Airport]] in [[Wamena]], [[Papua (province)|Papua]], [[Indonesia]], killing all 13 people on board.\n*A [[Royal Air Force]] [[C-130J Hercules]] lands at [[Saint Helena Airport]], becoming the first fixed-wing military aircraft ever to land on [[Saint Helena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatthesaintsdidnext.com/2016/12/18/raf-c-130-hercules-first-military-flight-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=C130 Hercules at St Helena Airport: First Military Flight Landing |publisher=Whatthesaintsdidnext.com |date=18 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that sixteen additional regular, charter or seasonal destinations will be introduced in 2017 with its arriving of wide body aircraft. [[Sofia Airport]] Chief Executive Officer Hristo Shterionov said that the Sofia hub should potential new long haul destinations to include the US and Asia.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* Since the coalition air campaign against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria began in [[2014 in aviation#August|August 2014]], coalition forces have conducted over 16,000 airstrikes at a cost of $12.5 million per day, killing an estimated 50,000 Islamic State personnel. The coalition has launched an average of 56 strike sorties per day since the campaign began.<ref name=ryan20161220/>\n\n;22 December\n*After over four years of airstrikes against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, by the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] and [[Russian Federation Air Force]], the Syrian government declares that its forces have retaken the entire city. Targets for the airstrikes have included residential areas and hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrian-military-says-it-has-retaken-control-of-prized-city-of-aleppo/2016/12/22/7e1ff74c-c7be-11e6-acda-59924caa2450_story.html|title=Syrian military says it has retaken control of key city of Aleppo}}</ref>\n*An intoxicated Russian man, Ruslan Nurtdinov, rams his car into the [[Airport terminal|terminal]] at [[Kazan International Airport]] outside [[Kazan]], Russia. Pursued by security personnel on foot, Nurtdinov drives his car through the terminal, passing check-in desks, a [[baggage carousel]], security checkpoints, and departure gates before coming to a halt at a railway platform, where he is arrested. He claims that he is trying to meet his girlfriend, who was scheduled to arrive at the railway platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/24/fighting-love-russian-man-sparks-security-scare-driving-airport/|title='I was fighting for love!' Russian man sparks security scare by driving into airport \u2013 to meet his girlfriend}}</ref>\n*U.S. President-elect [[Donald Trump]] [[Twitter|tweets]] that he might reconsider the purchase of the F-35 Lighting II due to its expense and cost overruns and seek a cheaper alternative, and that he \"has asked [[Boeing]] to price out a comparable [[F-18 Super Hornet]].\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-a-day-of-tweets-trump-suggests-major-change-on-national-security-issues/2016/12/22/4d709da8-c873-11e6-8bee-54e800ef2a63_story.html|title=In a day of tweets, Trump suggests major change on national security issues}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n;23 December\n*Two men claiming to be supporters of the late Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] and to have a [[hand grenade]] hijack [[Afriqiyah Airways Flight 209]], an [[Airbus A320]] (registration 5A-ONB) with 118 people on board, during a domestic flight in [[Libya]] from [[Sebha]] to [[Tripoli]] and force it to fly to [[Malta International Airport]] in [[Malta]] where they demand [[political asylum]] in [[Europe]] so that they can establish a political party that represents the former Gaddafi regime. They surrender to Maltese authorities and no one is injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/23/flight-diverted-malta-amid-potential-hijack-situation/|title=Libyan plane hijack: Two hijackers 'with grenades threaten to blow up' Afriqiyah Airways flight in Malta |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]| date=23 December 2016| accessdate =23 December 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Vesna Vulovi\u0107]], the sole survivor of the crash of [[JAT Flight 367|JAT Yugoslav Airlines Flight 367]] on [[1972 in aviation#January|26 January 1972]], dies in her apartment in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], at age 66. After the airliner exploded and broke into two pieces at an altitude of {{convert|33330|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over [[Czechoslovakia]], she fell to earth in the aircraft's tail section, setting a record for surviving the longest fall without a parachute which still stands at the time of her death.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.voanews.com/a/stewardess-survived-1972-plane-crash-record-fall/3649265.html|title=Serbia Stewardess Who Survived 1972 Plane Crash, Record Fall Dies at 66|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=24 December 2016| accessdate =24 December 2016}}</ref>\n*Returning from a book-promotion trip to the [[United Kingdom]], American actress and writer [[Carrie Fisher]] suffers a major [[heart attack]] aboard [[United Airlines]] Flight 935, a [[Boeing 777-200]] making a 10-hour-58-minute nonstop flight from [[London]] to [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]. She will die on 27 December at [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]] in Los Angeles without ever regaining consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucelee/2016/12/23/carrie-fisher-hospitalized-from-heart-attack-on-airplane/#370de2179baa|title=Carrie Fisher Hospitalized After Cardiac Arrest on Airplane|first=Bruce Y.|last=Lee}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/205880_carrie_fisher_never_regained_consciousness_after_heart_attack/|title=Carrie Fisher Never Regained Consciousness After Going into Cardiac Arrest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://flightaware.com/live/flight/UAL935/history/20161223/0920Z/EGLL/KLAX|title=United (UA)  #935 \u2708 23-Dec-2016  \u2708 LHR / EGLL - KLAX \u2708 FlightAware}}</ref>\n\n;25 December\n*The [[Government of Malaysia]] says that conducting airstrike in the southern Philippines \u2013 mainly [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]] by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]] won't captures of [[Basilan Province|Basilan]] and [[Sulu Province|Sulu]]. However, the two governments as with the Philippines (Malaysia's neighboring border) discuss to a decision will be made.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*A [[Russian Armed Forces|Russian military]] [[Tupolev Tu-154]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Careless\") transport aircraft [[2016 Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 crash|crashes]] into the [[Black Sea]] just after takeoff from [[Sochi International Airport]] in [[Sochi]], Russia, for a flight to [[Khmeimim (air base)|Khmeimim Air Base]] in [[Latakia]], Syria, killing all 92 people on board. Sixty-four members of the [[Alexandrov Ensemble]], better known internationally as the \"Red Army Choir\" \u2013 including its director, [[Valery Khalilov]] \u2013 traveling to Syria to perform for Russian troops are among the dead, as are nine journalists, three each from [[Channel One Russia]], [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]], and [[Zvezda (TV channel)|Zvezda]]. Also killed is Russian humanitarian [[Elizaveta Glinka]], commonly known in Russia as \"Doctor Liza,\" making the trip to accompany a shipment of medicine to a hospital in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/no-survivors-found-after-russian-military-plane-with-92-on-board-crashes-en-route-to-syria/2016/12/25/d4bca3f0-ca7c-11e6-a22f-f4d703887285_story.html|title=Russia focusing on pilot error or technical issues rather than terrorism in plane crash}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that reducing 16 to 12 flights (five out of [[Sofia Airport]], four out of [[Varna Airport]] and three out of [[Burgas Airport]]) with unspecified date scheduled for 2017. Bulgarian Transport Ministry's spokesman said that the ticket sales will be added, and the Sofia Airport will be the long haul operational hub.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;26 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that its first [[Boeing 767-300]] will be delivered in March 2017, followed by three more to follow in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Air Moldova]] announces that it will procure two more [[Airbus A320]]s which will enter service in 2017, bringing the airline's fleet of A320s to four.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;29 December\n*U.S. military officials report that a coalition airstrike targeting a van in a hospital compound parking lot in [[Mosul]], Iraq, carrying Islamic State personnel who had just left a [[recoilless rifle]] position may have killed an undetermined number of civilians inadvertently. They announce that an investigation of the incident will follow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/reinforced-iraqi-forces-restart-delayed-assault-on-mosul/2016/12/29/fc315e38-cd9e-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html|title=Reinforced Iraqi units resume offensive to take Mosul from Islamic State}}</ref>\n*A [[Cessna CitationJet/M2|Cessna 525 Citation]] [[corporate jet]] (registration N614SB) with six people on board crashes into [[Lake Erie]] during its initial climb after takeoff from [[Cleveland Burke Lakefront Airport]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]], [[Ohio]]. The [[United States Coast Guard]] will call off the unsuccessful search for survivors on 31 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20161229-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Cessna 525C Citation CJ4 N614SB Cleveland-Burke Lakefront Airport, OH (BKL)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;31 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that the next candidate of the 2017 Best Airline in the Balkans and it is expected in April 2017. The airline's Chief Executive Officer Hristo Todorov said it will begin interview on [[ch-aviation]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Philippine Airlines]] announces that the accepting to join the [[Oneworld]] airline alliance in the future. It will become the second airline in southeast Asia to join the alliance, following [[Malaysia Airlines]].\n* Coalition aircraft have destroyed over 1,200 Islamic State [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] since [[2015 in aviation#October|October 2015]] in [[Operation Tidal Wave II]].<ref name=warrick20161231/>\n* According to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|United Nations High Commission for Refugees]], the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] has conducted 3,936 airstrikes in [[Yemen]] during 2016.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-idUSKCN1AW1HK Aboudi, Sami, \"Pace of airstrikes, clashes in Yemen sharply higher in 2017: report,\" Reuters, 16 August 2017, 8:57 a.m.]</ref>\n* U.S. airlines have cancelled only 1.17 percent of their flights during 2016, their best annual performance in the 22 years the [[United States Department of Transportation]] has collected data on the issue; their previous record low had been 1.24 percent in 2002. They also have lost or misplaced luggage at a rate of 2.70 bags per 1,000 customers, the lowest rate since the Transportation Department began collecting data in 1987, and have \"bumped\" ticketed passengers from overbooked flights at a rate of 0.62 per 10,000 passengers, the lowest annual rate since the Transportation Department began tracking the issue in 1995. U.S. airlines also have shown improvements over 2015 in on-time arrival rates and in the number of customer complaints in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-us-flight-cancellations-baggage-problems-fall-to-historic-lows-2017-2|title=US flight cancellations and baggage issues have fallen to historic lows}}</ref>\n\n==First flights==\n===January===\n*29 January \u2013[[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737 MAX 8]] \u2013 N8701Q<ref>Dwyer-Lindgren, Jeremy. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/01/29/boeings-new-737-max-takes-off-maiden-flight/79516468/ \"Boeing's new 737 MAX completes its maiden flight\"]. [[USA Today]], 29 January 2016. Retrieved 28 May 2016.</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 [[Enstrom TH180]] \u2013 N180TH<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Pilot|date=April 2016|title=Enstrom TH180 flying.. then not|page=16|publisher=Archant Specialist}}</ref>\n*9 February \u2013 [[Airbus A320neo|Airbus A321neo]] \u2013 D-AVXB\n\n===March===\n*2 March \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW109|AgustaWestland AW109 Trekker]] \u2013 I-AGGR<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Pilot|date=April 2016|title=First flight of AW109 Trekker|page=16|publisher=Archant Specialist}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 4 April \u2013 [[Skyleader UL-39 Albi]] \u2013 OK-UUH 01<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Air-Britain Aviation World|publisher=[[Air-Britain]]|title=Aero Friedrichshafen|year=June 2016|volume=68|issue=2|author=Nigel Hitchman|issn=1742-996X}}</ref>\n* 22 April \u2013 [[Mitsubishi X-2 Shinshin]] \u2013 51-0001<ref>Pittaway, Nigel. \"ShinShin's Maiden Flight\". ''Air International'', June 2016, Vol. 90, No. 6. p. 5. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n* 28 April \u2013 [[Kamov Ka-62]] \u2013 RA-62002<ref>Maldenov, Alexander. \"Ka-62\". ''[[Air International]]'', June 2016, Vol. 90, No. 6. pp. 6\u20137. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 17 May \u2013 [[Diamond Dart 450]] \u2013 OE-VDA<ref name=firstFlightPR>{{cite press release |url= http://www.diamond-air.at/media-center/press-releases/news/article/maiden-flight-of-the-diamond-aircraft-dart-450.html |title= Maiden flight of the Diamond Aircraft DART-450 |publisher= Diamond Aircraft |date= 17 May 2016 |access-date= 19 June 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160531045203/http://www.diamond-air.at/media-center/press-releases/news/article/maiden-flight-of-the-diamond-aircraft-dart-450.html |archive-date= 31 May 2016 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 23 May \u2013 [[Embraer E-Jet E2 family|Embraer E190-E2]] \u2013 PR-ZEY\n* 31 May \u2013 [[HAL HTT-40]]<ref>Pittaway, Nigel. \"HTT-40 First Flight\". ''Air International'', July 2016, Vol. 91, No. 1, p. 16. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 21 July \u2013 [[Tecnam P2012 Traveller]] \u2013 I-PTFC<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarsfield|first=Kate|title=Tecnam P2012 Traveller takes flight|publisher=Flightglobal|date=25 July 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/tecnam-p2012-traveller-takes-flight-427793/}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 17 August \u2013 [[Hybrid Air Vehicles HAV 304 Airlander 10|Hybrid Air Vehicles Airlander 10]] \u2013 G-PHRG<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com 2016-08-18\"/>\n\n===October===\n* 26 October \u2013 [[Beriev A-100]]\n\n===November===\n* 4 November \u2013 [[Bombardier Global 7000]] \u2013 C-GLBO<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/11/04/news/companies/bombardier-global-7000-first-flight/index.html|title=$73 million Bombardier jet makes first flight|first=Jon|last=Ostrower|date=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 21 November \u2013 [[Stratos 714]] \u2013 N403KT<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/vlj-start-up-completes-first-flight-of-stratos-714-431973/|title=VLJ start-up completes first flight of Stratos 714|date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 24 November \u2013 [[Airbus A350 XWB|Airbus A350-1000]] \u2013 F-WWIL<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/first-a350-1000-successfully-completes-first-flight/|title=First A350-1000 successfully completes first flight}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 17 December \u2013 [[Gulfstream G500/G600|Gulfstream G600]] \u2013 N600G<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarsfield|first=Kate|title=Gulfstream G600 takes to the skies|publisher=Flightglobal|date=19 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/gulfstream-g600-takes-to-the-skies-432545/}}</ref>\n* 20 December\n**[[Avicopter AC352]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/chinas-ac352-conducts-maiden-flight-432623/|title=China's AC352 conducts maiden flight|website=flightglobal.com}}</ref>\n**[[Boeing BTX-1]] \u2013 N381TX<ref name=\"ff\">{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-and-saab-complete-first-t-x-flight-432611/|title=Boeing and Saab complete first T-X flight|date=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Entered service==\n\n* 25 January \u2013 [[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus A320neo]] with [[Lufthansa]]\n* 28 June \u2013 [[Comac ARJ21|Comac ARJ21-700]] with [[Chengdu Airlines]]\n* 15 July \u2013 [[Bombardier CSeries|Bombardier CS100]] with [[Swiss Global Air Lines]]\n* 2 August \u2013 [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II|Lockheed Martin F-35A Lightning II]] with the [[United States Air Force]]\n*14 December  \u2013 [[Bombardier CSeries|Bombardier CS300]] with [[airBaltic]]\n\n==Retirements==\n;14 January\n*The [[Boeing 747]] from the [[Air France]] fleet.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;23 November\n*The [[Airbus A340]] from the [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] fleet. The last flight is by an [[Airbus A340#A340-300|A340-300]] registered EC-GUP.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{Aviation timelines navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2016 in aviation| ]]\n[[Category:Aviation by year]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aviation-related events during the year of 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{very long|date=July 2019}}\n{{yearbox\n|in?=in aviation\n|cp=20th century\n|c=21st century \n|cf=22nd century\n|yp1=2013\n|yp2=2014\n|yp3=2015\n|year=2016\n|ya1=2017\n|ya2=2018\n|ya3=2019\n|dp3=1980s\n|dp2=1990s\n|dp1=2000s (decade){{!}}2000s\n|d=2010\u20132019{{!}}2010s\n|dn1=2020s\n|dn2=2030s\n|dn3=2040s\n}}\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\nThis is a list of '''aviation-related events from 2016''':\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n\n*During the month, the [[Government of Italy]] gives permission for armed U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs) to fly strike missions from [[Naval Air Station Sigonella]] on [[Sicily]] \u2013 where the [[United States]] has based unarmed surveillance UAVs since [[2011 in aviation|2001]] \u2013 against Islamic State targets in [[Libya]], but only if they are \"defensive,\" meaning that they are flown to protect [[United States special operations forces|U.S. special operations forces]] operating in and near Libya or rescuers attempting to retrieve downed U.S. pilots. [[Italy]] continues to prohibit U.S. offensive strikes from Italian territory, and also reserves to itself the right to veto any U.S. mission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-quietly-agrees-to-armed-u-s-drone-missions-over-libya-1456163730|title=Italy Quietly Agrees to Armed U.S. Drone Missions Over Libya|first1=Gordon|last1=Lubold|first2=Julian E.|last2=Barnes|date=23 February 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n;2 January\n* Indian aerial surveillance platforms detect a group of gunmen entering an [[Indian Air Force]] base at [[Pathankot]], [[India]], and Indian Air Force security forces exchange fire with them in a housing area. Four of the gunmen and two Indian Air Force security personnel are killed. Gunfire erupts again two hours later, and Indian helicopters fire on gunmen in the base later in the day. Indian security forces finally declare the base secure in the late afternoon, 14 hours after the intrusion began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3f724972b8f142edb1c07486cde4c277/gunmen-attack-air-force-base-northern-india-1-killed|title=Anonymous, \"Gunmen attack Indian air base near Pakistan border; 2 killed,\" Associated Press, January 1, 2016, 9:47 PM EST.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/36cbdce4c8fe4aada082aed9bd64ce3d/4-gunmen-2-troops-dead-attack-indian-air-base|title=Anand, Channi, \"India air force base attack leaves 4 gunmen, 2 troops dead,\" Associated Press, January 2, 2016, 8:46 AM EST.}}</ref><ref name=\"lakshmi20160104\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indian-troops-battling-militants-at-key-air-force-base/2016/01/03/6b33d358-17b2-48fc-92c6-a8cf415fa791_story.html|title=Indian troops battle militants at key air force base}}</ref>\n\n;3 January\n* Combat again breaks out at India's air base at Pathankot after security forces discover two militants still hiding on the base. Security forces reportedly kill the militants.<ref name=\"lakshmi20160104\"/>\n* An official at the [[United States Embassy]] in [[Addis Ababa]] announces that by mutual agreement with the [[Government of Ethiopia]] the [[United States]] had shut down its military [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] base at [[Arba Minch Airport]] in [[Arba Minch]] in southern [[Ethiopia]] in [[2015 in aviation#September|September 2015]]. The two countries had agreed that the base, which had opened in 2011, was no longer necessary. It is the first public announcement that the base had been closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/embassy-official-us-shuts-drone-operation-ethiopia-36063848|title=International News: Latest Headlines, Video and Photographs from Around the World \u2013 People, Places, Crisis, Conflict, Culture, Change, Analysis and Trends|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/01/04/pentagon-shutters-african-drone-base-moves-aircraft-to-other-hotspots/|title=Pentagon shutters African drone base, moves aircraft to other hot spots}}</ref>\n\n;4 January\n* [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[civil aviation]] authority suspends all civilian flights between Saudi Arabia and [[Iran]]. The move, which comes a day after Saudi Arabia severed [[diplomatic relations]] with Iran, raises doubts about the future ability of [[Islam]]ic pilgrims from Iran to visit [[Mecca]] and of [[Shiite]] pilgrims from Saudi Arabia to visit religious sites in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bahrain-cuts-ties-with-tehran-as-crisis-widens-in-saudi-iran-split/2016/01/04/145c8824-b271-11e5-8abc-d09392edc612_story.html|title=Mideast tensions soar as Saudi Arabia rallies countries to cut ties with Iran}}</ref>\n* John Boggs files suit against William Merideth for shooting down his [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) in [[Bullitt County, Kentucky|Bullitt County]], [[Kentucky]], with a [[shotgun]] as the UAV hovered over Merideth's property, asserting that the drone was in public [[airspace]] when it was shot down and requesting [[USD|$1,800]] in damages and clarification as to how high above private property public airspace begins. Merideth had claimed the UAV was spying on his family and violating his privacy. The case promises to spur the U.S. judicial system to clarify where private property rights end and federal jurisdiction begins in U.S. [[airspace]], with a significant potential impact on future private and commercial UAV operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techworm.net/2016/01/drone-owner-sues-neighbour-for-shooting-down-his-drone.html|title=Drone owner sues neighbour for shooting down his aircraft with a shotgun|date=7 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/01/13/you-may-be-powerless-to-stop-a-drone-from-hovering-over-your-own-yard/|title=You may be powerless to stop a drone from hovering over your own yard}}</ref>\n\n;5 January\n* When two [[United States Air Force]] [[Sikorsky HH-60 Pave Hawk]] helicopters attempt to evacuate wounded Afghan military personnel near [[Marjah]], [[Afghanistan]], one strikes a wall and is disabled and the other is ordered to abort the mission under heavy ground fire. One American is killed and two wounded in the incident; they are the first U.S. casualties in Afghanistan in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/01/05/one-u-s-soldier-killed-two-wounded-in-helmand-province-afghanistan/|title=One U.S. soldier killed, two wounded in Helmand province, Afghanistan}}</ref>\n\n;7 January\n* [[Iran]] claims that an airstrike by the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] operating against rebel forces in [[Yemen]] struck its [[embassy]] in [[Sana'a]] overnight. Local residents and press observers report no signs of damage at the embassy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iran-claims-saudi-airstrike-on-yemen-embassy-amid-deepening-tensions/2016/01/07/fc6131ae-b52f-11e5-a76a-0b5145e8679a_story.html|title=Iran claims Saudi airstrike hit its embassy in Yemen}}</ref>\n* A report by the [[inspector general]] of the [[United States Department of Transportation]] to the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) expresses a concern that airline pilots have become so reliant on automation technology to fly their aircraft that they have lost the skills necessary to take manual control of an airliner in order to deal promptly and effectively with unforeseen events. The FAA responds that it will require enhancements in pilot training for the manual flight of aircraft, and the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] endorses the need for well-trained aircrew aboard airliners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/does-using-an-autopilot-dull-the-skills-of-us-commercial-pilots/2016/01/13/00e458fe-ba13-11e5-829c-26ffb874a18d_story.html|title=Does autopilot dull the skills of U.S. airline pilots?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oig.dot.gov/sites/default/files/FAA%20Flight%20Decek%20Automation_Final%20Report%5E1-7-16.pdf|title=\"Enhanced FAA Oversight Could Reduce Hazards Associated With Increased Use of Flight Deck Automation\" Federal Aviation Administration, Report Number: AV-2016-013, January 7, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n;8 January\n* [[West Air Sweden]] [[West Air Sweden Flight 294|Flight 294]], a [[Bombardier CRJ200|Canadair CL-600-2B19 Regional Jet CRJ-200PF]] (registration SE-DUX) on a domestic cargo flight in [[Norway]] carrying mail and packages from [[Oslo]] to [[Troms\u00f8]], suddenly goes into a steep descent after a brief [[Mayday]] call and crashes near [[Akkajaure]], [[Sweden]], killing its crew of two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160108-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Canadair CL-600-2B19 Regional Jet CRJ-200PF SE-DUX Oajev\u00e1gge|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;9 January\n\n* [[Tracey Curtis-Taylor]] completes a solo flight from [[Farnborough Airport]] in [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]], [[England]], to [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], in the [[Boeing-Stearman Model 75]] open-[[cockpit]] [[biplane]] ''Spirit of Artemis''. During the 100-day, {{convert|21000|km|mi|adj=on}} flight, begun on [[2015 in aviation#October|1 October 2015]], she has flown over 23 countries and made 50 refueling stops. The flight recreates the [[1930 in aviation|1930]] [[Croydon]]-to-[[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] flight of [[Amy Johnson]], the first solo flight between the [[United Kingdom]] and Australia by a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-34400824|title=Bi-plane pilot in Amy Johnson UK to Australia flight|date=1 October 2015|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35271182|title=Tracey Curtis-Taylor finishes UK to Australia biplane flight|date=9 January 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;10 January\n* As a show of force after a 6 January [[nuclear weapon]]s test by [[North Korea]], a [[Guam]]-based U.S. Air Force [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52H Stratofortress]] flies to [[South Korea]], where it circles over [[Osan Air Base]] flanked by a U.S. Air Force [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] and a [[Republic of Korea Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]] before returning to Guam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-nuclear-idUSKCN0UN0Y420160111|title=U.S. flies B-52 over South Korea after North's nuclear test|date=11 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;12 January\n* An unarmed Iranian unmanned aerial vehicle flies near the [[French Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle|Charles de Gaulle]]'' and directly over the [[United States Navy]] aircraft carrier {{USS|Harry S Truman|CVN-75}} as they operate in [[international waters]] in the [[Persian Gulf]]. Iran will announce the flight and release purported video from it on 29 January \u2013 implying that the video had been taken earlier that day rather than on 12 January \u2013 and a [[United States Fifth Fleet]] spokesman will respond by calling the flight \"abnormal and unprofessional.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/4fd95402fde146079290278bfae506b7/iran-says-it-flew-drone-over-us-aircraft-carrier|title=Karimi, Nasser, and John Gambrill, \"Iran flies unarmed military drone over US aircraft carrier,\" Associated Press, January 29, 2016, 2:29 PM EST.}}</ref>\n* An air-and-bus bridge begins operating as a pilot program to help 8,000 [[Cuba]]n immigrants stranded in [[Costa Rica]] since [[Nicaragua]] closed its border to them on 13 November 2015 by allowing them to fly out of Costa Rica and reach [[Mexico]], from which they can emigrate to the United States. The first flight of the air-and-bus bridge departs [[Liberia, Costa Rica|Liberia]], Costa Rica, during the evening as part of regional agreement to help the Cubans bypass Nicaragua.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6b77f374b14a461d9212c3ddeeaf4f2d/stranded-cuban-migrants-make-plans-cross-mexico|title=Sherman, Christopher, and Maria Verza, \"Stranded Cuban migrants make plans to cross Mexico,\" Associated Press, January 14, 2016, 12:36 PM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;13 January\n* An [[Israeli Air Force]] aircraft strikes a group of [[Palestinian people|Palestinians]] \u2013 members of the [[Al-Aqsa Martyrs Brigade]] \u2013 on a beach in the northern [[Gaza Strip]] near the Israeli border fence, killing one and injuring three others. The [[Israel Defense Force]] claims that they were planting explosives with which to target Israeli soldiers patrolling the border on the other side of the fence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6e0660ebc87449799d381baad5c69ef8/israeli-military-airstrike-targets-gaza-militants-1-killed|title=Anonymous, \"Israeli military: Airstrike targets Gaza militants, 1 killed,\" Associated Press, January 13, 2016, 5:49 AM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;14 January\n* [[Air France]] officially retires the [[Boeing 747]] from its fleet with Flight 744, a scenic flight by a [[Boeing 747-400]] with 432 people on board, including 380 paying passengers, in formation with 12 [[Dassault/Dornier Alpha Jet]]s of the [[French Air Force]]'s [[Patrouille de France]] aerobatic team. The airliner takes off from [[Charles de Gaulle Airport]] in [[Paris]] and makes a clockwise circuit that takes it over [[Lyon]], [[Geneva]], [[Marseille]], [[Montpellier]], [[Bordeaux]], and [[Deauville]] before returning to Charles de Gaulle Airport, offering passengers scenic views of [[Mont Blanc]], [[Normandy]], and [[Mont Saint-Michel]] along the way. The Boeing 747 had been part of the Air France fleet since 1974 and the 68 Boeing 747s the airline had operated had carried 250 million passengers. In the future plans to use its [[Airbus A380]]s and [[Boeing 777]]s for long-haul flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/15/aviation/air-france-boeing-747-retired-farewell/index.html|title=Air France retires Boeing 747s|first=Jim |last=Bittermann|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-14/air-france-grounds-747-after-40-years-as-icon-lives-on-at-klm|title=Air France Retires Its Last 747 After 40 Years|date=14 January 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avgeekery.com/air-france-says-au-revoir-747-stunning-flyby/|title=Air France Says Au Revoir to the 747 With This Stunning Flyby \u2013 Avgeekery.com \u2013 News and stories by Aviation Professionals}}</ref>\n* Two [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion]] helicopters of [[HMH-463|Marine Heavy Helicopter Squadron 463 (HMH-463)]], each carrying six Marines, [[2016 U.S. Marine helicopter collision|collide and crash]] in a fireball late in the evening over the [[Pacific Ocean]] north of [[Oahu]] just off [[Haleiwa, Hawaii|Haleiwa]], [[Hawaii]], and crash, leaving all 12 Marines missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/15/us/hawaii-military-aircraft-collision/index.html|title=Helicopter crash in Hawaii: Search for 12 missing Marines|author1=Michael Martinez |author2=Ben Brumfield |author3=Tina Burnside|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] will call off the search for the Marines on 19 January,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hawaii-marines-crash-idUSKCN0UY08H|title=Search called off for Marines missing since helicopter crash off Hawaii|date=20 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref> and the Marine Corps officially will declare them dead on 20 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hawaii-marines-crash-idUSKCN0V00A7|title=Twelve Marines declared dead after helicopter crash off Hawaii|date=22 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;15 January\n* A late-evening U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle-launched [[air-to-ground missile]] strike kills three suspected [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members as they drive in a car in Yemen's [[Shabwa Governorate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-drone-idUSKCN0UU0TI|title=Drone strike kills three suspected militants in Yemen|date=16 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully fires the engines of the first stage of [[Falcon 9]] rocket it had used to launch a satellite into orbit and then landed successfully on land in [[2015 in aviation#December|December 2015]], the first time in a history a rocket stage had made a soft, controlled landing. The firing of the engines demonstrates the feasibility of reusing the rocket stage, an important step in the development of reusable rockets that make space launches less expensive.<ref name=\"davenport20160117\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/01/17/elon-musks-spacex-to-attempt-another-rocket-landing-this-time-with-a-twist/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX successfully launches rocket but falls short on landing at sea}}</ref>\n\n;16 January\n* Speaking at the conclusion of a missile exercise at [[Skwierzyna]], [[Poland]], involving U.S. and Polish military forces, Polish [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Minister of National Defense]] [[Antoni Macierewicz]] says that the [[Government of Poland]] wants a permanent presence of [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) and U.S. military forces in Poland, including [[MIM-104 Patriot]] [[surface-to-air missile]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5339b118be984e89a6110505056996d3/polands-defense-chief-we-want-constant-nato-us-presence|title=Anonymous \"Poland's defense chief: We want constant NATO, US presence,\" Associated Press, January 16, 2016, 12:35 PM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;17 January\n* After successfully launching the [[Jason-3]] satellite into orbit from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] in [[California]], the first stage of a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket touches down on a landing platform in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|200|mi|km}} off California softly enough to land successfully, but topples over when of its landing legs fails to lock in place and collapses. It is SpaceX's third attempt to land a Falcon 9 first stage at sea; the two previous attempts, both in [[2015 in aviation|2015]], also had been unsuccessful, although SpaceX had made history's first successful landing of a reusable rocket stage \u2013 also of a Falcon 9 \u2013 on land in December 2015.<ref name=\"davenport20160117\" />\n* Just before midnight, aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike a police facility in Sana'a, Yemen, used by both security forces and the [[Houthi]] rebels as an assembly point, killing 26 people and injuring 15. The dead and wounded are all policemen and Houthi rebels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-01-18/airstrike-targets-police-facility-in-yemens-capital|title=al-Haj, Ahmed, \"Airstrike by Saudi-led coalition hits building used by police in Yemeni capital, killing at least 26,\" Associated Press, January 18, 2016, 2:49 p.m..}}</ref>\n\n;21 January\n* An air strike by the Saudi-led coalition against a rebel-held facility at [[Ras Isa]] on Yemen's [[Red Sea]] coast used to load [[tanker truck]]s with refined petroleum products for distribution in rebel-held areas of Yemen destroys trucks and starts a large fire, killing at least nine and perhaps as many as 16 people and injuring at least 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-oil-idUSKCN0UZ2NP|title=Yemen oil port fire from Saudi-led air strike kills at least nine|date=22 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;22 January\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike targets across Yemen, killing dozens of people. Houthi rebels in [[Saada Governorate]] report that the strikes kill 26 people in [[Dahyan]], including the driver of a [[Doctors Without Borders]] ambulance. Strikes against rebel weapon depots on the mountain of [[Nahdeen]] kill another 22 people, and strikes in [[Hodeida]] targeting trucks carrying smugged oil from the port there to rebel forces kill another 10 people. Strikes also target gatherings of Houthis and rebel [[Yemeni Army]] units allied with them in [[Al Jawf Governorate]], [[Dhamar, Yemen|Dhamar]], ad [[Taiz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/22/saudi-led-airstrikes-kill-dozens-in-yemen.html|title=Saudi-led airstrikes kill dozens in Yemen}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] announces that after the 2016 season it will end its support of the use of [[ultralight aircraft]] to lead [[whooping crane]]s on their migration from [[Wisconsin]] to the [[Florida Gulf Coast]] each autumn in [[Operation Migration]]. A conclusion by experts in whooping crane [[biology]] that human intervention such as ultralight flights impairs the ability of the cranes to learn the parenting skills necessary to raise chicks in the wild prompts the decision to end support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/1/24/feds-to-end-whooping-crane-wisconsin-florida-migration-support.html|title=Whooping crane migration program ending}}</ref>\n\n;26 January\n\n* The [[United States Department of the Treasury]] announces the lifting of major U.S. trade and travel restrictions on [[Cuba]]. The new regulations allow [[Codeshare agreement|code sharing]] between U.S. and Cuban airlines, airplane-leasing deals in the United States for Cuba, and permission for U.S. airline crews to travel to Cuba.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-opens-greater-channels-for-trade-air-links-with-cuba/2016/01/26/a36e13f2-c437-11e5-9693-933a4d31bcc8_story.html|title=U.S. opens greater channels for trade, air links with Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;28 January\n* [[Iran]] agrees to buy 118 airliners \u2013 73 [[Wide-body aircraft|wide-body]] and 45 [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrow-body]] \u2013 from [[Airbus]] in a deal worth [[USD|$]]27,000,000,000. The purchase consists of 12 [[Airbus A380|A380]], 16 [[Airbus A350-1000|A350-1000]], 45 [[Airbus A330|A330]], and 45 [[Airbus A320 family|A320-family]] aircraft. The deal is contingent on Airbus receiving export licenses from the [[United States]], where 10 percent of parts for Airbus aircraft are manufactured. Iran, which first plans to focus on expansion of its airports and more urgent [[civil aviation]] needs, does not plan to take delivery of the airliners until ca. 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-europe-airbus-idUSKCN0V62D6|title=Airbus signs Iran deal for 118 planes worth $27 billion|date=28 January 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n\n;1 February\n* Two evening airstrikes by U.S. aircraft operating as part of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) intervention in [[Afghanistan]] level the [[Islamic State of Afghanistan]] \"Voice of the Caliphate\" radio station, knocking it off the air during its nightly illegal propaganda broadcast from [[Nangarhar Province]]'s [[Achin District]]. The strikes combined with [[Afghan Army]] ground operations kill 29 Islamic State supporters, including eight who worked for the radio station and an associated [[Internet]] operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/02/us-airstrikes-destroy-isis-voice-caliphate-radio-station-in-afghanistan.html|title=US airstrikes destroy ISIS' 'Voice of the Caliphate' radio station in Afghanistan|date=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Nato-strikes-Islamic-State-radio-station-in-Afghanistan/articleshow/50824638.cms|title=Nato strikes Islamic State radio station in Afghanistan|work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n;2 February\n* [[Daallo Airlines Flight 159]], an [[Airbus A321-100]] (registration SX-BHS) with 81 people on board flying from [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]], to [[Djibouti City]], [[Djibouti]], experiences an explosion which sets one passenger on fire and blows a hole in the fuselage, through which the burning passenger is sucked from the plane at an altitude of {{convert|14000|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}. The airliner returns to Mogadishu and lands safely. The burned body of the man sucked from the plane is found near [[Balad, Somalia|Balad]], Somalia; two other people on board the plane suffer minor injuries.\n\n;7 February\n* A strike by unidentified aircraft hits a medical technology college in [[Derna, Libya|Derna]], [[Libya]], killing four people. The area is held by a coalition of [[Islamic militant]] groups who have been defending it from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/02/07/world/middleeast/ap-ml-libya.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrike Hits College in Eastern Libyan City, Killing 4,\" Associated Press, February 7, 2016, 10:39 a.m. EST.}}</ref>\n\n;8 February\n* [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Justin Trudeau]] announces that [[Canada]] will withdraw its six [[CF-18 Hornet]]s from bombing missions against the Islamic State within two weeks, but will extend its non-combat air support to the U.S.-led air campaign against the Islamic State until 31 March 2017, using one [[CC-150 Polaris]] [[aerial refueling]] aircraft and up to two [[CP-140 Aurora]] reconnaissance planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/canada-pull-jets-syria-iraq-weeks-160209042506120.html|title=Canada to end ISIL air strikes within weeks}}</ref>\n* A panel of the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] proposes history's first worldwide standards for [[carbon dioxide]] emissions for aircraft; the standards would apply to all new aircraft designs beginning in 2020 and to all newly delivered aircraft beginning in 2023. Environmental groups criticize the standard for not addressing emissions by existing aircraft or new aircraft designed before 2020 or delivered before 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/02/08/u-n-group-proposes-airline-emissions-cuts-but-environmentalists-say-its-not-enough/|title=U.N. panel proposes historic cuts to aircraft emissions \u2013 but environmentalists say it\u2019s not enough}}</ref>\n\n;10 February\n\n* During a flight from [[Punta Cana]] in the [[Dominican Republic]] to [[Moscow]] with 355 passengers on board, an [[Orenair]] [[Boeing 777-200]] (registration VP-BHB) experiences an engine failure and smoke in the cabin.<ref name=\"tah\">{{cite web | url =http://avherald.com/h?article=493c6485|title=Incident: Orenair B772 at Punta Cana on Feb 10th 2016, engine shut down in flight, burst tyre and smoke on landing|work=The Aviation Herald| date=11 February 2016| accessdate =12 February 2016}}</ref> The crew shuts down the malfunctioning engine, the smoke ceases, and the aircraft performs an [[emergency landing]] in Punta Cana during which a tire bursts and sparks appear.<ref name=\"tah\"/> The passengers and crew evacuate via [[evacuation slide]]s with no injuries.<ref name=\"tah\"/>\n* The president of the [[National Air Traffic Controllers Association]] (NATCA), Paul Rinaldi, tells the [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]] that NATCA supports a [[United States House]] bill that would create a federally chartered corporation to operate the [[air traffic control]] system in the [[United States]] and transfer 38,000 U.S. federal government workers, including 14,000 NATCA air traffic controllers who work for the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]], to the new corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/air-traffic-controllers-ready-to-break-away-from-faa/2016/02/10/12e6b14e-cf5a-11e5-b2bc-988409ee911b_story.html|title=Air traffic controllers ready to break away from FAA}}</ref>\n\n;15 February\n\n* Villagers and rebel forces in southwestern [[Somalia]] claim that a U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) has crashed in a village there. The United States responds that all of its UAVs have returned safely from their missions and are accounted for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/9f4e5402136c44c7a37e94d3ba73af8c/somalia-residents-say-us-drone-crashes-rebel-held-village|title=Guled, Abdi, \"US denies reports that 1 of its drones crashed in Somalia,\" Associated Press, February 15, 2016, 11:28 AM EST.}}</ref>\n\n;17\u201318 February\n* [[Turkish Air Force]] jets bomb Kurdish camps in northern [[Iraq]] hours after a suicide car bomb killed 28 people in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]], on 17 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/turkish-air-strikes-pkk_us_56c59113e4b0c3c55053d26f|title=Turkish Air Strikes Hit PKK Camps in Northern Iraq After Ankara Bombing|last=Reuters|date=18 February 2016|via=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\n;18 February\n* The [[United States Government]] grants [[Boeing]] a license allowing the company to enter into talks with airlines in [[Iran]] about sales of airliners. Iran's aging airliner fleet and lack of [[Boeing 777]]s raises the possibility of significant sales for Boeing, although the company will require additional approval from the [[United States Government]] ensuring the legitimacy of any transactions before actually selling Iran any aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/boeing-to-enter-talks-with-iranian-airlines/2016/02/19/59c65f00-d73f-11e5-9823-02b905009f99_story.html|title=Boeing to enter talks with Iranian airlines}}</ref>\n\n;19 February\n* Flying from bases in the [[United Kingdom]], [[United States Air Force]] [[F-15 Eagle]]s strike an Islamic State camp on the outskirts of [[Sabratha]], [[Libya]], killing Islamic State leader [[Noureddine Chouchane]] and 48 other Islamic State personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/reports-airstrikes-target-suspected-islamic-state-base-in-libya/2016/02/19/e622c12a-d6f7-11e5-be55-2cc3c1e4b76b_story.html|title=U.S. strike on Libya camp escalates campaign against Islamic State}}</ref><ref name=\"gibbonsneff201603037\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/07/u-s-drone-strike-kills-more-than-150-in-somalia/|title=U.S. airstrike kills more than 150 at Somalia terrorist camp, military says}}</ref>\n* In a ceremony in a [[hangar]] in [[Mojave, California|Mojave]], [[California]], Sir [[Richard Branson]] unveils [[Virgin Galactic]]'s new [[VSS Unity|VSS ''Unity'']], a [[SpaceShipTwo]]-class rocket-powered [[Sub-orbital spaceflight|suborbital]] [[spaceplane]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/02/19/richard-bransons-virgin-galactic-unveils-new-spacecraft/|title=Richard Branson\u2019s Virgin Galactic unveils new spacecraft 'Unity'}}</ref>\n\n;20 February\n* The [[Government of Serbia]] claims that the 19 February U.S. airstrike in Sabratha, Libya, killed two [[Serbia]]n diplomats. The [[United States Department of Defense]] responds that it does not believe the Serbians were at the targeted location during the airstrike and that the condition of their bodies is inconsistent with death in the airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/02/24/serbia-says-a-u-s-strike-in-libya-killed-two-of-its-diplomats-heres-why-the-pentagon-disagrees/|title=Serbia says a U.S. strike in Libya killed two of its diplomats; here\u2019s why the Pentagon thinks it didn\u2019t}}</ref>\n\n;21 February\n* British [[Royal Navy]] [[test pilot]] [[Eric Brown (pilot)|Eric \"Winkle\" Brown]] dies at the age of 97 at [[East Surrey Hospital]] in [[Redhill, Surrey|Redhill]], [[England]]. Surviving 11 plane crashes and the 1941 sinking of the [[escort aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Audacity|D10}}, he is credited with flying 487 different types of aircraft, more than anyone else in history, and with making 2,407 [[aircraft carrier]] landings, also a world record, as well as with making the first carrier landing in history, landing a [[de Havilland Sea Vampire]] aboard {{HMS|Ocean|R68}} in [[1945 in aviation|1945]]. Although he had retired in [[1970 in aviation|1970]], he had continued flying until [[1994 in aviation|1994]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-35626854|title=Eric 'Winkle' Brown: Celebrated British pilot dies, aged 97|date=21 February 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/eric-brown-unflappable-british-test-pilot-who-set-world-records-dies-at-97/2016/02/22/059d7a26-d974-11e5-925f-1d10062cc82d_story.html|title=Eric Brown, unflappable British test pilot who set world records, dies at 97}}</ref>\n\n;22 February\n\n* Russia requests permission to fly surveillance flights over the United States under the [[Treaty on Open Skies]] using [[Tupolev Tu-154]] (NATO reporting name \"Careless\") aircraft equipped with new, high-powered [[digital camera]]s. The request prompts a debate within the United States Government over whether it is a small concession worth making in order to keep the treaty viable or a violation of the spirit of the treaty that would allow surveillance unintended when the treaty was signed in 1992. The treaty, signed by 34 countries, has been in force since [[2002 in aviation|2002]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/23/world/europe/russia-wants-closer-look-from-above-the-us.html|title=Russia Wants Closer Look From Above the U.S.|first1=Eric|last1=Schmitt|first2=Michael R.|last2=Gordon|date=22 February 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 February\n* [[Tara Air Flight 193]], a [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter]] on a domestic flight in [[Nepal]] from [[Pokhara Airport]] in [[Pokhara]] to [[Jomsom Airport]] in [[Jomsom]], crashes and burns near [[Dana, Nepal|Dana]] in [[Myagdi District]] ten minutes after takeoff, killing all 23 people on board.\n\n;25 February\n* In the morning, [[Turkish Army]] [[Bell AH-1 Cobra]] attack helicopters attack a group of [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] personnel as they travel through a mountainous area near the [[\u0130dil]] district of Turkey's [[\u015e\u0131rnak Province]], killing nine of them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-military-helicopt/2544894.html|title=Tattersall, Nick, \"Turkish military helicopters kill nine in strikes on PKK targets,\" Reuters, 24 February 2016, 19:20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225103457/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-military-helicopt/2544894.html|archivedate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n* In the evening, Turkish Air Force jets based at [[Diyarbakir]], Turkey, strike Kurdistan Workers Party logistical centers, ammunition depots, and shelters in northern Iraq,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-warplanes-strike/2546502.html|title=Cakan, Seyhmus, \"Turkish warplanes strike PKK targets in northern Iraq \u2013 sources,\" Reuters, 25 February 2016, 03:35|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304141519/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/turkish-warplanes-strike/2546502.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;26 February\n* An [[Air Kasthamandap]] [[PAC 750XL]] (registration 9N-AJB) with 11 people on board [[2016 Air Kasthamandap crash|crash-lands]] at [[Chilkhaya]], [[Nepal]], killing both crew members and injuring all nine passengers.\n* An [[Azur Air]] [[Boeing 767-300]] makes a safe emergency landing in [[Tashkent]], [[Uzbekistan]], during a flight from [[Moscow]] to [[Phuket (city)|Phuket]], [[Thailand]], after an indicator shows low engine oil pressure.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://ria.ru/incidents/20160226/1380664212.html|title=\u0421\u041a \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0438 Boeing \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0448\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0435|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]| language=Russian|date=26 February 2016| accessdate =26 February 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'', grounded at [[Kalaeloa Airport]] in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalealoa]], [[Hawaii]], since [[2015 in aviation#July|3 July 2015]] due to battery damage caused by overheating during its attempt to become the first manned [[solar-powered aircraft]] to circumnavigate the Earth, makes it first test flight after repairs. Taking off from Kalealoa Airport, ''Solar Impulse 2'' flies over the [[Pacific Ocean]] for 90 minutes, reaching an altitude of {{convert|8000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} before returning. The [[Solar Impulse]] team plans to resume the [[circumnavigation]] in late [[2016 in aviation#April|April 2016]] with a flight from Hawaii to [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/solar-impulse-2-returns/42077/|title=Refurbished Solar Impulse 2 returns to the skies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manufacturing.net/news/2016/03/solar-impulse-2-undergoes-successful-test-flight|title=Solar Impulse 2 Undergoes Successful Test Flight|date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;27 February\n* Airstrikes attributed to the Saudi-led coalition targeting advancing rebel forces hit a market area in the [[Nehm]] region outside [[Sana'a]], [[Yemen]], killing at least 30 people and injuring at least 30 more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-35678326|title=Yemen conflict: air strike on market 'kills 30 people'|date=27 February 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;29 February\n* An American tourist turns over to authorities in [[Mozambique]] what appears to be part of the skin of a [[Boeing 777]] [[horizontal stabilizer]] found over the preceding weekend on a [[sandbar]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] just off the country's coast, raising expectations that it will turn out to be debris from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a Boeing 777 missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|8 March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/02/us/mh370-possible-debris-found/index.html|title=MH370: Likely piece of doomed plane found|author1=Rene Marsh |author2=Don Melvin|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* In the United States, the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA) announces that it has awarded a $20 million contract to [[Lockheed Martin]] to develop a quiet supersonic demonstration passenger aircraft using [[Quiet Supersonic Technology]] (QueSST). NASA hopes that the new technology, which allows aircraft flying at supersonic speeds to make only a soft thump instead of a loud and damaging [[sonic boom]], will prompt the development of a new generation of \"low-boom\" [[supersonic transport]]s that can fly over populated areas at supersonic speeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/29/us/nasa-quiet-supersonic-jet-contract-announced/index.html|title=NASA says it will build quiet supersonic passenger jet|first=Thom |last=Patterson|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* The United States has conducted 135 airstrikes in Yemen since its air campaign there began, five of them since 1 January. The strikes have killed more that 650 [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] personnel and 105 civilians.<ref name=\"gibbonsneff20160322\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/22/u-s-targets-al-qaeda-in-yemen-airstrike-that-kills-dozens-pentagon-says/|title=U.S. targets al-Qaeda in Yemen airstrike that kills dozens, Pentagon says}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n;3 March\n* A man finds a 40-by-40-centimeter (about 15.5-by-15.5-inch) square-shaped piece of debris with a blue border on a beach on [[R\u00e9union]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] in almost the same place he found a [[flaperon]] from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]] in [[2015 in aviation#July|July 2015]]. He turns it in to authorities the following day, raising hopes that it is also from Flight 370, missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|8 March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-malaysia-airlines-flight-370-part-20160306-story.html|title=Man who found MH370 flight part finds new item on La Reunion island|first=Tribune news|last=services}}</ref>\n\n;4 March\n\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully launches a [[satellite]] payload into space using an upgraded [[Falcon 9]] rocket, but its attempt to land the rocket's first stage on a floating platform \u2013 termed an \"autonomous space port droneship\" by SpaceX founder [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 is only partially successful: although the first stage lands on the platform, the landing is too hard for a successful recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/03/04/after-a-series-of-delays-spacex-launches-upgraded-falcon-9-rocket/|title=After a series of delays, SpaceX launches upgraded Falcon 9 rocket}}</ref>\n* The U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) responds to the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s (FAA) [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]] rejection of the NTSB's [[2014 in aviation#April|April 2014]] recommendation that the FAA establish licensing requirements and safety standards for commercial [[Balloon (aircraft)|balloon]] tour operators and make them subject to FAA safety inspections, regulating them in a manner similar to the way it regulates commercial airplane and helicopter tour operators. In its response, the NTSB informs the FAA that it finds the rejection unacceptable and that its recommendation remains open.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2016/07/30/least-16-people-died-hot-air-balloon-crash-texas-sheriff-says/87773736/|title=At least 16 dead in hot air balloon crash in Texas}}</ref><ref name=\"staging.hosted.ap.org\">{{cite web|url=http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_HOT_AIR_BALLOON_CRASH_TEXAS?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-07-30-22-15-19|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/safety/safety-recs/recletters/A-14-011-012.pdf|title=National Transportation Board Safety Recommendation April 7, 2014.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.recsearch/Recommendation.aspx?Rec=A-14-011|title=Safety Recommendation A-14-011}}</ref>\n\n;5 March\n* A series of U.S. airstrikes by manned aircraft and unmanned aerial vehicles against an [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] training camp in [[Raso, Somalia|Raso]], [[Somalia]], kills over 150 Al-Shabaab personnel.<ref name=\"gibbonsneff201603037\"/>\n\n;7 March\n\n* [[African Parks Network]] announces that the remains of its employee, American anti-[[poaching]] pilot Bill Fitzpatrick, have been recovered from a crash site in [[Cameroon]]. Fiztpatrick had disappeared on 22 June 2014 during a flight to a job in [[Odzala-Kokoua National Park]] in the [[Republic of the Congo]]. Local residents had discovered the wreckage of Fitzpatrick's plane in April 2015, but the remote site and dense vegetation in the area had made it difficult for helicopters to land there and bureaucratic procedures of the [[Government of Cameroon]] also had delayed the recovery of Fitzpatrick's remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/fea7c73dab954f5dba2b66c1bf3acd98/american-pilots-remains-recovered-cameroon-crash-site|title=Anonymous, \"American pilot's remains recovered from Cameroon crash site,\" Associated Press, March 7, 2016, 11:25 AM EST.|access-date=8 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308121549/http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/fea7c73dab954f5dba2b66c1bf3acd98/american-pilots-remains-recovered-cameroon-crash-site|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Boeing]] announces that it has filed a [[patent]] for a self-cleaning [[airplane lavatory]] which can sanitize itself in three seconds using [[far-ultraviolet]] light. The lavatory also features a hands-free faucet, soap dispenser, trash flap, toilet lid, [[toilet seat]], and hand dryer, and Boeing reports that it also is designing a hands-free door latch and is studying the design of a hands-free system to lift and close the toilet seat so that all surfaces are exposed to the far-ultraviolet light during the cleaning cycle. Once Boeing offers the new lavatories to customers, it is expected to take years for airlines to update their fleets with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2016/03/07/boeing-designs-self-cleaning-plane-bathrooms/|title=Boeing designs self-cleaning plane bathrooms|date=7 March 2016|access-date=8 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308085444/http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2016/03/07/boeing-designs-self-cleaning-plane-bathrooms/|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;8 March\n* U.S. [[Special Operations Forces]] conduct a joint U.S.-Somali helicopter raid against al-Shabaab in Somalia. The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that U.S. forces play only an advisory role and do not accompany the Somali forces on the raid, although the helicopters employed are U.S. military helicopters flown by U.S. crews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/03/09/u-s-special-operations-forces-conduct-helicopter-raid-in-somalia/|title=U.S. Special Operations forces conduct helicopter raid in Somalia}}</ref>\n\n;9 March\n* A [[True Aviation]] [[Antonov An-26]] cargo plane (registration S2-AGZ) carrying a cargo of [[shrimp]] suffers the failure of an engine shortly after takeoff from [[Cox's Bazar Airport]] in [[Cox's Bazar]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[2016 True Aviation An-26 crash|crashes]] into the [[Bay of Bengal]] five minutes after takeoff while attempting to return to the airport, killing three of the four people on board and critically injuring the only survivor.\n* [[Amazon.com]] announces that it has agreed to lease 20 [[Boeing 767-300]] cargo aircraft from [[Air Transport Services Group]] as a first step toward operating its own fleet of planes, part of a larger effort to reduce its shipping costs and its reliance on [[FedEx]] and the [[United Parcel Service]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-finds-air-freight-partner-1457538676 Bensinger, Greg, \"Amazon Finds Air Freight Partner,\" ''Wall Street journal'', 9 March 2016, 8:33 p.m. EST.]</ref>\n\n;12 March\n* A South African family announces that it contacted aviation authorities in [[South Africa]] during the previous week to report a piece of debris their teenaged son had found on a beach in [[Mozambique]] on [[2015 in aviation#December|30 December 2015]] which they had taken home to South Africa. Aviation officials plan to examine it to see if it is from Malaysian Airlines Flight 370.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/11/africa/mh370-mozambique-possible-debris/index.html|title=MH370: 2nd possible debris piece found in Mozambique|author1=Steve Almasy |author2=Faith Karimi |author3=Radina Gigova|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* In response to a rocket attack on [[Israel]] from the [[Gaza Strip]] the previous evening, the [[Israeli Air Force]] conducts airstrikes against four [[Hamas]] sites in the Gaza Strip. In one of the aistrikes, an [[air-to-ground missile]] strikes a family home on the perimeter of one of the sites, killing two [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israel-retaliates-for-gaza-rocket-fire-with-air-strikes-hamas-hacks-israel-tv/2016/03/13/0214541e-f9ee-48e0-8402-39fc4838b65c_story.html|title=Israel retaliates for Gaza rocket fire with airstrikes; Hamas hacks Israeli TV}}</ref>\n\n;13 March\n* As a result of the accident investigation into the [[2015 in aviation#March|25 March 2015]] crash of [[Germanwings Flight 9525]], French aviation authorities call for stricter international monitoring of the mental health of pilots as well as guidelines under which doctors would be required to report pilots whose psychological condition might put flight safety at risk. In their report, the French also urge German authorities to limit the legal penalties imposed on doctors who breach patient confidentiality in good faith in order to report psychological problems among pilots and to clearly define the types of health issues in airline pilots that can represent an \"imminent danger\" to flight safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/14/world/europe/germanwings-crash-inquiry-urges-stricter-oversight-of-pilots-mental-health.html|title=Germanwings Crash Inquiry Urges Stricter Oversight of Pilots' Mental Health|first=Nicola|last=Clark|date=13 March 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;14 March\n* In response to a suicide car bomb explosion in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]], that killed at least 37 people the previous day, [[Turkish Air Force]] jets strike at least 18 [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] positions in northern [[Iraq]], including ammunition depots, bunkers, and shelters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkish-warplanes-strike-kurdish-militant-bases-after-deadly-ankara-attack/2016/03/14/1272f05e-e9d3-11e5-a6f3-21ccdbc5f74e_story.html|title=Turkish warplanes strike Kurdish militant bases after deadly Ankara attack}}</ref>\n\n;15 March\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition conduct two airstrikes on a busy market in [[MAstaba, Yemen|Mastaba]] in [[Yemen]]'s [[Hajja Governorate]], killing at least 119 people and wounding 47.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/urn:publicid:ap.org:eb6ab6b0c6f2452b93910735c981d0fc|title= Al-Haj, Ahmed, \"Witnesses: Warplanes bomb Yemeni market, killing dozens\", Associated Press, March 15, 2016, 3:03 PM EDT.}}</ref><ref name=\"AP20160317\">{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/66550de27e1a44e0b6ba3a95cb2901e7/un-yemen-says-death-toll-tuesdays-strike-now-119|title=Al-Haj, Ahmed, and Maggie Michael, \"Saudi to scale down Yemen campaign; strike death toll rises,\" Associated Press, MArch 17, 2016, 12:03 p.m. EDT.}}</ref>\n* An [[Ecuadorian Air Force]] [[IAI Arava]] carrying 22 members of the [[Ecuadorian Army]] for [[parachute]] training and an air force crew of three [[2016 Ecuadorian Air Force Arava crash|crashes]] in Hacienda la Palmira near [[Shell Mera]], [[Ecuador]], killing all on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35818100|title=Ecuador army plane crashes in Amazon region killing 22 \u2013 BBC News|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/15/americas/ecuador-plane-crash/index.html|title=Ecuador plane crash kills 22|website=CNN|access-date=2016-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brecorder.com/world/south-america/285314-ecuador-army-plane-crash-kills-all-22-aboard-president.html|title=Ecuador army plane crash kills all 22 aboard: president|website=Business Recorder|access-date=2016-03-17}}</ref><ref name=Flight>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160315-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident IAI Arava 201 E-206 Hacienda la Palmira, Pastaza|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2016-03-16}}</ref>\n\n;16 March\n* New [[United States Department of the Treasury]] regulations go into effect that among other things allow increased travel to [[Cuba]] by American citizens and allow U.S. airlines to open offices in Cuba. The changes are expected to improve the market for commercial air travel between the [[United States]] and Cuba.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/treasury-eases-restrictions-on-travel-to-cuba/2016/03/15/10a225ec-eaaf-11e5-b0fd-073d5930a7b7_story.html|title=Treasury eases restrictions on travel, other dealings with Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;17 March\n* [[Saudi Arabia]] announces that its military coalition will scale back its operations against [[Houthi]] rebels in Yemen \u2013 maintaining only \"small\" teams of coalition forces on the ground to advise, train, and equip Yemeni forces \u2013 but will continue to provide air support to Yemeni forces battling the rebels.<ref name=\"AP20160317\"/>\n* Boasting that Russia's 167-day intervention in Syria saved the regime of Syrian [[President of Syria|President]] [[Basher al-Assad]] from defeat at a coast of only [[USD|$]]480 million, Russian President Vladimir Putin says that Russia could restore its military presence in Syria in a metter of hours if necessary and will maintain a powerful surface-to-air missile force there. He warns that Russia will respond with force if any rebel group breaks the Syrian ceasefire and or any attacks against Russian forces still in Syria occur, and suggests that Russia will intervene militarily in Syria again if it believes the Assad regime is in danger of losing power.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/russia-could-redeploy-to-syria-in-hours-putin-says/2016/03/17/845f8810-ec37-11e5-97c2-e9c9557fa1b0_story.html|title=Russia could redeploy to Syria in hours, Putin says}}</ref>\n\n;19 March\n* [[Flydubai Flight 981]], a [[Boeing 737-800|Boeing 737-8KN]] (registration A6-FDN), aborts two landing attempts in poor visibility at [[Rostov-on-Don Airport]] in [[Rostov-on-Don]] in southern Russia, making a [[go-around]] after each attempt. During its second go-around, it suddenly goes into a rapid descent from an altitude of {{convert|4050|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and crashes, killing all 62 people on board. It is the first fatal accident in [[Flydubai]]'s seven-year history.\n* Unidentified aircraft strike Islamic State-held [[Raqqa]], Syria, killing at least 39 \u2013 and perhaps as many as 43 \u2013 people and reportedly injuring at least 50 others. Different observers report the attacking aircraft as either [[Russian Federation Air Force]] or [[Syrian Air Force]] jets.<ref name=\"mroue20160319\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/airstrikes-on-is-held-syrian-city-kill-wound-dozens/2016/03/19/57776b40-edce-11e5-a9ce-681055c7a05f_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=19 March 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n* Unidentified aircraft strike Islamic State targets in Palmyra, Syria, killing seven Islamic State personnel during a Syrian Arab Army offensive to retake Palmyra.<ref name=\"mroue20160319\"/>\n\n;21 March\n\n* A South African [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] finds a piece of debris on a beach in southern South Africa. The following day, [[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Transport (Malaysia)|Minister of Transport]], [[Liow Tiong Lai]], will announce the discovery and that the debris bears an aircraft engine manufacturer's and logo and will be examined to determine whether it is from the missing Malaysian Airlines Flight 370.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-march-22-2016/2016/03/22/9c62f5dc-f038-11e5-85a6-2132cf446d0a_story.html|title=World Digest: March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 March\n* [[2016 Brussels bombings|Two terrorist bombs detonate]] at [[Brussels Airport]] in [[Zaventem]], [[Belgium]], killing at least 11 people and injuring around 100 others. The airport will remain closed until 3 April, with flights re-routed to nearby cities. A third bomb later explodes at [[Maelbeek/Maalbeek metro station|Maelbeek (or Maalbeek) metro station]] in the [[City of Brussels]], killing another 20 people and injuring another 130. The Islamic State claims responsibility for all three bomb blasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/03/22/471391497/what-we-know-terrorist-bombing-at-brussels-airport|title=Terrorist Bombings Strike Brussels: What We Know}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35876809|title=Brussels attacks: Police hunt Zaventem bombings suspect|date=23 March 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref name=\"touni20160403\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2016-04-03/a-very-small-start-3-flights-to-depart-from-brussels|title=El Touni, Bishr, and Elaine Ganley, \"A Brussels Airlines plane heading to the Portuguese city of Faro took off from Brussels Airport on Sunday, the first passenger flight to leave the airport since suicide bombings on March 22 ripped through its check-in counters,\" usnews.com, April 3, 2016, 11:38 a.m.}}</ref>\n* U.S. aircraft conduct a strike against an [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] training camp in the mountains of Yemen. The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that the attack killed \"dozens\" of the group's personnel.<ref name=gibbonsneff20160322/>\n\n;27 March\n* Suspected U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle strikes hit courtyards in two villages in Yemen with air-to-ground missiles, killing eight al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula members. Later in the day, a U.S. aircraft bombs a former Yemeni government intelligence building in Yemen's [[Abyan Governorate]] that al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula is using as a base, killing 14 members of the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-march-28-2016/2016/03/27/ee819296-f41c-11e5-9804-537defcc3cf6_story.html|title=World Digest: March 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Portuguese [[regional airline]] [[Portug\u00e1lia]] is rebranded as Tap Express.\n\n;27\u201328 March (overnight)\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition strike rebel targets in the suburbs of [[Aden]], Yemen.<ref name=\"mukhashaf20160328\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-swap-idUSKCN0WU0BX|title=Saudi-led alliance says completes Yemen prisoner swap|date=28 March 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;28 March\n* Unidentified aircraft thought to belong to the Saudi-led coalition strike rebel targets in Yemen's [[Hadhramaut]] region southeast of [[Mukalla]].<ref name=\"mukhashaf20160328\"/>\n\n;29 March\n* A man claiming to be wearing an explosive belt [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacks]] [[EgyptAir Flight 181]] \u2013 an [[Airbus A320-200]] (registration SU-GCB) with 61 other people on board on a domestic flight in [[Egypt]] from [[Alexandria, Egypt|Alexandria]] to [[Cairo]] \u2013 and forces it to fly to [[Larnaca International Airport]] in [[Larnaca]], [[Cyprus]], which is closed to all traffic after the hijacked airliner's arrival. The man is arrested and no one aboard the airliner is harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/egyptair-plane-hijacked/2016/03/29/09dd65ee-f579-11e5-9804-537defcc3cf6_story.html|title=Plane hijacking rekindles concerns about Egyptian airport security}}</ref>\n* A chartered [[Aero Teknic]] [[Mitsubishi MU-2]] flying in bad weather [[2016 Aero Teknic MU-2 crash|crashes]] into the [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]] on approach to [[\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine Airport]] in the [[Magdalen Islands]] in [[Quebec]], [[Canada]], killing all seven people on board. Canadian television commentator and former [[Minister of Transport (Canada)|Minister of Transport]] [[Jean Lapierre]], his wife, two of his brothers, and a sister are among the dead. They had been traveling to Lapierre's father's funeral in eastern Quebec.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/quebec-plane-crash-kills-7-ex-minister-reported-among-dead/ar-BBr5DJw?ocid=ansmsnnews11|title=Lampert, Allison, \"Former Canadian Cabinet minister killed in plane crash,\" Reuters, March 29, 2016.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403035122/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/quebec-plane-crash-kills-7-ex-minister-reported-among-dead/ar-BBr5DJw?ocid=ansmsnnews11|archivedate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;31 March\n* Heavy airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition support the beginning of an offensive by Iraqi military forces to take the city of [[H\u012bt]], [[Iraq]], from the Islamic State. Over the previous week, the coalition has conducted 17 airstrikes against Islamic State targets in the H\u012bt area in preparation for the offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-04-01/trapped-civilians-stall-iraqi-forces-battling-is-in-anbar|title=George, Susannah, \"Iraqi counterterrorism forces slow advance against IS as tens of thousands of civilians trapped in Anbar province,\" Associated Press, April 1, 2016.}}</ref>\n* An airstrike by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle {{convert|20|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from [[Jilib]], [[Somalia]], hits a ground vehicle carrying senior [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] leader and [[al-Qaeda]] member [[Hassan Ali Dhoore]] and two other Al-Shabaab members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/04/01/pentagon-u-s-military-launches-drone-strike-on-al-shabab-leader-in-somalia/|title=Pentagon: U.S. military launches drone strike on al-Shabab leader in Somalia}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n;2 April\n* Since it began in [[2015 in aviation#October|October 2015]], the U.S.-led coalition in [[Operation Tidal Wave II]] has conducted over 200 airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] [[oil well]]s, [[Oil refinery|oil refineries]], [[oil pipeline]]s, and [[tanker truck]]s. Tidal Wave II is intended to degrade the Islamic State's finances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-led-strikes-putting-a-financial-squeeze-on-the-islamic-state/2016/04/02/e739a7be-f848-11e5-a3ce-f06b5ba21f33_story.html|title=U.S.-led strikes putting a financial squeeze on the Islamic State|work=The Washington Post|date=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;3 April\n* The [[Government of Australia]] announces that debris apparently from the interior of [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]] \u2013 a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]] \u2013 found by hotel guests on [[Mauritius]] during the previous week will be examined to ascertain whether or not it is from the missing airliner. It would be the first piece of the debris from the aircraft's interior to be recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/missing-jet/missing-mh370-suspected-debris-found-mauritian-island-be-examined-n549846|title=Missing MH370: Suspected Debris Looks Like 'Inside' of Plane|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n* Supported by [[Russian Federation Air Force]] airstrikes, [[Syrian Arab Army]] troops on the offensive against Islamic State forces retake [[Qaryatain]], [[Syria]].<ref name=\"aji20160404\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-04-04/air-strikes-kill-22-qaida-linked-militants-in-Syria|author=Aji, Albert |title=Syrian troops fire their guns in celebration amid smoldering buildings inside the town of Qaryatain, hours after recapturing it from Islamic State militants who had abducted and terrorized dozens of its Christian residents |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike against a senior [[al-Qaeda]] operational meeting in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] at the headquarters of [[Jund al-Aqsa]], which fights alongside the [[Nusra Front]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]], kills 21 [[Islamic militant]]s, including senior al-Qaeda member [[Abu Firas al-Souri]].<ref name=\"aji20160404\" />\n* On a limited basis, flight operations resume at [[Brussels Airport]] in [[Zaventem]], [[Belgium]], for the first time since the [[2016 Brussels bombings|terrorist bombings there]] on 22 March. Only three flights, all [[Brussels Airlines]] departures, operate from the airport during the day.<ref name=\"touni20160403\" />\n\n;4 April\n* During takeoff from [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport]] in [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]], [[Batik Air Flight 7703]], a [[Boeing 737-800|Boeing 737-8GP(WL)]] (registration PK-LBS) carrying 56 people, collides with a [[TransNusa Air Services]] [[ATR 42-600]] (registration PK-TNJ) being towed to a [[hangar]] with four people on board. The Boeing 737's left [[wing]] slices off the ATR 42's [[vertical stabilizer]] and outer left wing, and the Boeing 737's badly damaged left wing bursts into flames. All aboard both aircraft evacuate safely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Batik Air dan TransNusa Tabrakan di Runway Bandara Halim Perdanakusuma|url=http://news.detik.com/berita/3179649/batik-air-dan-transnusa-tabrakan-di-runway-bandara-halim-perdanakusuma}}</ref>\n* Supported by heavy airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition targeting Islamic State forces and position, [[Iraqi Armed Forces|Iraqi government forces]] enter the city of [[H\u012bt]], [[Iraq]], a week after operations to retake it from the Islamic State began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iraqi-forces-face-heavy-resistance-in-isis-held-town-of-hit/|title=Iraqi forces face heavy resistance in ISIS-held town of Hit|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n* The [[Syrian Arab Army]] releases video revealing that Russian [[Kamov Ka-52]] Alligator (NATO reporting name \"Hokum B\") [[attack helicopter]]s are operating in Syria. The video \u2013 purportedly the first video of the Ka-25 in combat ever made public \u2013 shows Ka-25s firing rockets at Islamic State forces in Syria near Qaryatain.<ref name=\"sputnik20160404\">{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20160404/1037447550/ka-52-syria-action.html|title=WATCH: First Ever Footage of Russia's Ka-52 Helicopters in Action in Syria|last=Sputnik}}</ref><ref name=\"birnbaum20160412\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/weeks-after-pullout-from-syria-russian-military-is-as-busy-as-ever/2016/04/11/d150a004-fd77-11e5-a569-2c9e819c14e4_story.html|title=Weeks after 'pullout' from Syria, Russian military is as busy as ever}}</ref>\n* A [[Bell 206]] sightseeing helicopter crashes in the [[Smoky Mountains]] near [[Sevierville, Tennessee|Sevierville]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]], killing all five people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b0b077feeb19447c880b951a180393f8/5-killed-tourist-helicopter-crash-smoky-mountains|title=5 killed in tourist helicopter crash in Smoky Mountains}}</ref>\n* [[Alaska Air]] agrees to buy [[Virgin America]] for [[USD|$]]2,600,000,000; including debt and aircraft leases, the deal is worth about $4,000,000,000. The combined airline will have 1,200 daily departures and [[Airline hub|hubs]] in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], [[Alaska]]; [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]; [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]. Virgin America had operated since [[2007 in aviation|2007]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/04/04/investing/virgin-america-alaska-air-deal/index.html|title=Alaska Air buys Virgin America for $2.6 billion|first=Ivana Kottasova and Jackie|last=Wattles|date=4 April 2016|publisher=CNN Money}}</ref>\n\n;5 April\n* Traveling from his sanctuary in [[Turkey]] to mediate a dispute between the [[Nusra Front]] and other [[Islamist]] groups in Syria, [[Al-Qaeda]] leader [[Ahmed Refai Taha]] is killed by an [[air-to-ground missile]] fired by a U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] when his car stops for fuel near [[Idlib]], Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/double-game-even-as-it-battles-isis-turkey-gives-other-extremists-shelter/2016/07/10/8d6ce040-4053-11e6-a66f-aa6c1883b6b1_story.html|title=Double game? Even as it battles ISIS, Turkey gives other extremists shelter|work=The Washington Post|date=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n* A [[surface-to-air-missile]] fired from rebel-held territory in Syria near [[Aleppo]] shoots down a [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] reconnaissance plane. Its pilot ejects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/rebel-fighters-down-aircraft-near-syrian-battle-front-activists-say/2016/04/05/921de55c-fa9a-11e5-813a-90ab563f0dde_story.html|title=Suspected Islamist militants down Syrian aircraft near Aleppo battle front|work=The Washington Post|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Morecambe Bay Community Primary School]] in [[Morecambe]], [[England]], launches a [[helium balloon]] carrying a toy stuffed dog named Sam, a [[GoPro]] camera, and a [[GPS navigation device]] from the grounds of a hotel in Morecambe as part of a school science project. Ascending at {{convert|6|m|ft|abbr=off}} per second, the balloon reaches an altitude of {{convert|15|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} without incident, but bursts during its descent and plummets to the ground, landing in a field in [[Burnley]], {{convert|30|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} from its launch site, where the camera and GPS device are recovered. Sam is missing from the wreckage, prompting a search for the stuffed animal within a radius of {{convert|40|to|50|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} of the landing site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/find-sam-toy-dog-missing-space-morecambe-bay-burnley-a6973641.html|title=A group of schoolchildren have managed to launch a toy dog into space|date=7 April 2016|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n;6 April\n* A panel commissioned by the [[United States Government]] recommends that the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] lift its ban on [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs, or \"drones\") flying over people and issue new regulations that require only that UAVs fly no lower than {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} above people and come no closer to people than {{convert|10|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} while taking off or landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/ready-for-a-spy-in-the-sky-panel-says-faa-should-expand-commercial-drone-flights/2016/04/06/cd649ef0-fc0a-11e5-9140-e61d062438bb_story.html|title=Ready for a spy in the sky? Panel says FAA should expand commercial drone flights.|work=The Washington Post|date=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;7 April\n* Two hours into a flight to search for a [[skiff]] missing in the [[Pacific Ocean]] with three men aboard, the crew of a [[United States Navy]] [[P-8A Poseidon]] patrol plane spots the word \"HELP\" spelled out on a beach on uninhabited [[Fanadik Island]] in the [[Federated States of Micronesia]]. It was created by the three men, who soon are rescued by a small boat from the island of [[Pulap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/04/09/navy-rescues-3-castaways-who-wrote-help-with-palm-fronds-on-deserted-island.html|title=Navy rescues 3 castaways who wrote 'help' with palm fronds on deserted island|date=9 April 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n;8 April\n* After several unsuccessful attempts, [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform \u2013 which SpaceX refers to as an \"autonomous spaceport drone ship\" \u2013 floating in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] after a launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]]. The landing occurs nine minutes after liftoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/04/08/elon-musks-spacex-nails-landing-at-sea/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX nails landing at sea|work=The Washington Post |date=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Jetpack International vice president Nick Macomber crashes headfirst into the ground during a routine test flight of a [[jet pack]] he is flying in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], falling {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} to the ground after the jet pack malfunctions. He is injured, but is released from a hospital the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdvr.com/2016/04/08/jet-pack-crash-lands-pilot-in-burn-center/|title=Jet pack pilot released from hospital after crash|date=8 April 2016|publisher=KDVR}}</ref>\n\n;10 April\n* Unidentified aircraft conduct airstrikes around [[Raqqa]], Syria, killing dozens of Islamic State personnel and civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/17b151c625b244c0b760bdb4ffc8f8c8/islamic-state-launches-syria-offensive-captures-2-villages|title=Syrian cease-fire strained by new clashes ahead of talks|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n\n;11 April\n* Two Russian [[Sukhoi Su-24]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Fencer\") jets make numerous low-level passes in close proximity to the [[United States Navy]] [[guided-missile destroyer]] {{USS|Donald Cook|DDG-75}} while the ship is conducting deck landing drills with an allied military helicopter in the [[Baltic Sea]], forcing ''Donald Cook'' to suspend flight operations until the Su-24s leave the area. The ship's [[commanding officer]] criticizes one of the passes, made while the helicopter is refueling on ''Donald Cook'''s [[flight deck]], as unsafe.<ref name=eucom20160413>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/News-Article-View/Article/720536/navy-ship-encounters-aggressive-russian-aircraft-in-baltic-sea|title=Navy Ship Encounters Aggressive Russian Aircraft in Baltic Sea|publisher=U.S. Department of Defense}}</ref>\n\n;12 April\n* A Russian [[Mil Mi-28]]N (NATO reporting name \"Havoc\") [[attack helicopter]] crashes in Syria, killing its two-man crew. The Russian [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Ministry of Defense]] announces that the helicopter was not shot down and blames the crash on bad weather. The increasing number of reports of Russian helicopter operations in Syria since late March have led [[Western world|Western]] military analysts to conclude that Russia's supposed withdrawal of its military aviation forces from Syria in [[2014 in aviation#March|mid-March]] was in reality merely the replacement of some Russian Federation Air Force jets there with attack helicopters more suitable to the support of [[Syrian Arab Army]] ground operations against rebel forces.<ref name=\"birnbaum20160412\" />\n* Russian aircraft fly in close proximity to the U.S. Navy guided-missile destroyer USS ''Donald Cook'' (DDG-75) in the Baltic Sea for a second straight day. First, a [[Kamov Ka-27]] (NATO reporting name \"Helix\") helicopter makes seven low circles around ''Donald Cook'' (DDG-75) in what the ship's commanding officer criticizes as an \"unprofessional\" manner. Forty minutes later, two Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") jets make 11 close-range, low-level passes which ''Donald Cook'''s crew assesses as fitting a simulated attack profile.<ref name=eucom20160413 />\n\n;13 April\n* A [[Sunbird Aviation]] [[Britten-Norman BN-2T Turbine Islander]] [[2016 Sunbird Aviation crash|crashes]] {{convert|1|km|mi|abbr=on}} short of the runway at [[Kiunga, Papua New Guinea|Kiunga]], [[Papua New Guinea]], killing all 12 people on board.\n\n;14 April\n* [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Ashton Carter]] announces that the United States will begin to send combat aircraft to the [[Philippines]] on regular and more frequent rotations and will conduct more air patrols jointly with Philippine forces in the [[South China Sea]] in order to help reduce growing tensions between the Philippines and the [[People's Republic of China]] over their competing claims in the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/bd92d542c71d409a82cac13981b2f461/us-keep-300-troops-philippines-through-end-month|title=US sending commandos, combat aircraft to Philippines|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n\n;17 April\n* [[Air France]] resumes flights to [[Iran]] after an eight-year hiatus with a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Imam Khomeini International Airport]] in [[Tehran]], beginning a three-times-per-week service. Air France joins [[Lufthansa]] and [[Austrian Airlines]] in providing commercial air passenger service between [[Europe]] and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/04/17/air-france-resumes-flights-to-iran-after-8-years0.html|title=Air France resumes flights to Iran after 8 years|date=17 April 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n* In the first incident of its kind in the [[United Kingdom]], the pilot of a [[British Airways]] [[Airbus A320]] with 127 people on board reports that an object that he believes to be an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] struck the front of his plane at an altitude of {{convert|1700|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over [[Richmond Park]], [[London]], while his airliner was on approach to land at [[Heathrow Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36067591|title='Drone' hits British Airways plane approaching Heathrow Airport|date=17 April 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"swinford20160421\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/21/drone-believed-to-have-hit-british-airways-flight-may-have-been/|title=Drone believed to have hit British Airways flight 'may have been a plastic bag'|work=Telegraph}}</ref> On 21 April, British [[Minister of State for Transport]] [[Robert Goodwill]] will announce that the object the airliner hit may have been a [[plastic bag]].<ref name=\"swinford20160421\" />\n\n;18 April\n* U.S. Secretary of Defense Ashton Carter announces that U.S. forces sent to assist the Iraqi armed forces in recapturing [[Mosul]] from the Islamic State will include [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3327956a32d7485a86725e141caa0b3b/carter-arrives-iraq-talks-how-beef-fightn|title=US to send 200 more troops, Apache helicopters to Iraq|publisher=AP}}</ref>\n* Making an implementation flight to test the route, ground operations, and handling, ahead of the beginning of scheduled airline services at [[Saint Helena Airport]], a [[Boeing 737-800]] operated by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]] for [[British Airways]] becomes the first passenger jet capable of seating 100 or more passengers to land on [[Saint Helena]]. High winds prevent the airliner from landing until its third attempt, indicating that [[wind shear]] conditions at the airport are dangerous for large commercial ircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |title=Pictures : Comair 737 arrives at new St Helena airport |publisher= [[FlightGlobal]] |date=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |title=British Airways flight struggles to land on St Helena runway |work=The Guardian |date=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;19 April\n* Four [[United States Air Force]] [[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 Thunderbolt II]] (nicknamed \"Warthog\") [[close air support]] aircraft of the [[51st Fighter Wing]] fly a patrol over the South China Sea west of [[Luzon]] from [[Clark Air Base]] in the Philippines. The [[maritime patrol]] mission is an unusual one for the A-10, but the U.S. Department of Defense announces that it is only the first of a planned series of joint South China Sea air patrols by U.S. and Philippine forces with goals of \"air- and maritime-domain awareness, personnel recovery, combating piracy, and [the] assurance [that] all nations have access to the regional air and maritime domains in accordance with [[international law]].\" The People's Republic of China, which claims the areas to be patrolled as its internal waters, condemns the planned patrols as reflecting a \"[[Cold War]] mentality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/get-ready-china-lethal-10-warthogs-are-patrolling-the-south-15886|title=Get Ready, China: Lethal A-10 Warthogs are Patrolling the South China Sea|first=David|last=Axe|work=The National Interest}}</ref>\n* A pro-Syrian-government aircraft strikes the main market in [[Maarat al-Nu'man]], [[Syria]], with two air-to-ground rockets while it is crowded with people shopping for fruits and vegetables, killing at least 37 people. It is unclear whether the attacking jet belonged to the Syrian Arab Air Force or the [[Russian Federation Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/pro-government-warplanes-bomb-a-rebel-town-that-hates-al-qaeda-killing-scores/2016/04/19/0a1d34ac-0641-11e6-bfed-ef65dff5970d_story.html|title=Pro-government warplanes bomb a rebel town that hates al-Qaeda, killing scores|work=The Washington Post|date=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 April\n* [[United States Central Command]] reveals that the authority to order airstrikes that might endanger civilians, originally given only to its top commander, has been delegated to its commander in [[Baghdad]] and his deputies.<ref name=\"lamothe20160422\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/04/22/u-s-military-doubles-the-number-of-civilians-it-admits-killing-in-anti-isis-fight/|title=U.S. military doubles the number of civilians it admits killing in anti-ISIS fight|work=The Washington Post|date=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;21 April\n* After a delay of almost 10 months, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) takes off from [[Kalaeloa Airport]] in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]], [[Hawaii]], bound for [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], on the ninth leg of its round-the-world flight to resume its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, with [[Bertrand Piccard]] at the controls, is expected to take about 62 hours. ''Solar Impulse 2'' had been at Kalaeloa since completing the eighth leg of its flight on [[2015 in aviation#July|3 July 2015]], delayed first by repairs necessitated by damage caused by an overheated battery and then by the need to wait for spring in the [[Northern Hemisphere]], when periods of daylight become long enough for the plane to charge its batteries in flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/04/21/travel/solar-impulse-2-plane/index.html|title=Solar Impulse 2 plane takes off from Hawaii to California \u2013 with no fuel|first=David |last=Molko|publisher=CNN|date=21 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/sciencefair/2016/04/20/solar-impulse-voyage-hawaii/83297824/|title=Sun-powered Solar Impulse resumes its round-the-world flight|work=USA Today|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] dismisses an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] [[lawsuit]] seeking access under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] to details of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s program of lethal airstrikes using unmanned aerial vehicles (or \"drones\") outside of the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and [[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]. The court finds that releasing such details to the public \"could reasonably be expected to damage [[national security]],\" and that \"[t]he agency's explanations as to why the records are classified are both 'logical' and 'plausible' and uncontroverted by evidence in the record.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/appeals-court-dismisses-lawsuit-seeking-access-to-records-on-lethal-drone-strikes/2016/04/21/8ae1321c-07d8-11e6-b283-e79d81c63c1b_story.html|title=Appeals court dismisses lawsuit seeking access to records on lethal drone strikes|work=The Washington Post|date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Doug Hughes is sentenced to four months in prison for an unauthorized [[gyrocopter]] flight from [[Pennsylvania]] he made on [[2015 in aviation#April|15 April 2015]] that ended with a landing on the [[United States Capitol Building]] grounds in [[Washington, D.C.]] He made the flight to protest the influence of money in American politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/gyrocopter-pilot-who-landed-at-us-capitol-to-be-sentenced/2016/04/20/3fe834ac-0703-11e6-bdcb-0133da18418d_story.html |title=Gyrocopter pilot who landed at U.S. Capitol sentenced to four months in prison|work=The Washington Post|date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force raids on rebel-held parts of Aleppo kill at least 19 people. Additional government airstrikes in Idlib Governorate also kill people in areas under rebel control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/deadly-airstrikes-in-syria-further-strain-cease-fire-as-peace-talks-near-collapse/2016/04/22/2e56c96e-0899-11e6-b283-e79d81c63c1b_story.html|title=Deadly airstrikes in Syria further strain cease-fire as peace talks near collapse}}</ref>\n* U.S. Central Command announces that between [[2015 in aviation#September|10 September 2015]] and [[2016 in aviation#February|2 February 2016]] its airstrikes in Iraq and Syria killed 20 civilians and injured 11 more. The airstrikes killed two civilians in [[Kabisa]], Iraq, on 10 September 2015; eight in [[Atshanah]], Iraq, while hitting an Islamic State [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] position on [[2015 in aviation#October|5 October 2015]]; one in [[Ramadi]], Iraq, during a strike against Islamic State combat personnel on [[2015 in aviation#November|12 November 2015]]; one near Raqqa, Syria, on [[2015 in aviation#December|10 December 2015]]; five in Ramadi while hitting an Islamic State checkpoint on 12 December 2015; one in [[Tishreen (city)|Tishreen]], Syria, on 24 December 2015; one in [[Mosul]], Iraq, on [[2016 in aviation#January|11 January 2016]]; and one in [[Al Ghazli]], Syria, on 2 February 2016. In a previous announcement, the [[United States Department of Defense]] had acknowledged killing 15 civilians and wounding 15 more during earlier airstrikes in Iraq and Syria.<ref name=\"lamothe20160422\" />\n\n;23 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force planes strike rebel-held areas of Aleppo for a second straight day. They hit a residential area and a market in the city's Tareeq al-Bab district, killing at least 12 people.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Piloted by Bertrand Piccard, ''Solar Impulse 2'' completes the ninth leg of its around-the-world flight attempt, landing at Moffatt Field in Mountain View, California, after a nonstop flight from Kalaeloa, Hawaii, of 62 hours 29 minutes, covering {{convert|2206|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} at an average speed of {{convert|35.31|kn|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|28327|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/solar-powered-plane-successfully-crosses-pacific-ocean-lands/story?id=38622335|title=Solar-Powered Plane Finishes Pacific Ocean Crossing|publisher=ABC News|date=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-9-from-Hawaii-to-Mountain_View_CA|title=9th Leg from Hawaii to San Francisco|access-date=24 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424075146/http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-9-from-Hawaii-to-Mountain_View_CA|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;24 April\n* Syrian Arab Air Force planes strike rebel-held areas in Aleppo for the third straight day, killing 16 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/least-14-killed-fighting-rages-syrias-aleppo-115338820.html|author1=Aji, Albert |author2=Philip Issa |title=At least 26 killed as fighting rages in Syria's Aleppo |agency=Associated Press |date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Ground forces of the Saudi-led coalition begin a ground offensive against [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] forces in southern [[Yemen]], advancing toward [[Mukalla]] and surrounding areas. Coalition aircraft supporting the offensive strike targets in Mukalla, hitting the city's cultural center and [[Riyan Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/war-in-yemen-takes-a-major-turn-with-offensive-against-al-qaeda/2016/04/24/b8e73a3e-0a2c-11e6-bc53-db634ca94a2a_story.html |title=War in Yemen takes a major turn with offensive against al-Qaeda|work=The Washington Post|date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;25\u201326 April (overnight)\n* An air-to-ground missile strike suspected to have been made by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle kills three prominent al-Qaeda leaders in [[Zinjibar]], Yemen.\n\n;26 April\n* The [[Government of Yemen|Yemeni government]] announces that Yemeni ground troops have retaken Mukalla from al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP) forces, adding that heavy airstrikes by the Saudi-led coalition combined with [[artillery]] fire had driven many AQAP members out of the city.\n*The Government of [[Saint Helena]] announces an indefinite delay to the opening of [[Saint Helena Airport]] to commercial traffic because of the problem the Comair Boeing 737-800 had encountered in landing on 18 April due to dangerous winds. The airport had been scheduled to open in May,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|title=MAINTAINING ACCESS TO ST HELENA & ASCENSION : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001524/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/#|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> but scheduled commercial air service will not begin until [[2017 in aviation#October|October 2017]].<ref name=bbc20171014>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003 Anonymous, \"First commercial flight lands on remote St Helena,\" bbc.com, 14 October 2017.]</ref>\n\n;27 April\n* Airstrikes by unidentified aircraft against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, collapse a hospital operated by [[Doctors Without Borders]] and the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]], killing at least 50 people, including patients and at least six hospital staff members. A [[Dentistry|dentist]] and two [[medical doctor]]s, one of them one of the area's last [[Pediatrics|pediatricians]], are among the dead.<ref name=\"cunningham20160428\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-destroys-doctors-without-borders-hospital-in-aleppo-killing-staff-and-patients/2016/04/28/e1377bf5-30dc-4474-842e-559b10e014d8_story.html|title=Airstrike destroys Syrian hospital amid fears of 'catastrophic' turn in fighting|work=The Washington Post|date=28 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cunningham20160429\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-syrias-battered-aleppo-ongoing-airstrikes-defy-international-outrage/2016/04/29/8e26c7c6-0d7c-11e6-bc53-db634ca94a2a_story.html|title=In Syria\u2019s battered Aleppo, death toll rises as international outrage mounts|work=The Washington Post|date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n;28 April\n* The Russian Ministry of Defense denies Russian involvement in the 27 April airstrike against a hospital in Aleppo, Syria.<ref name=\"cunningham20160428\" />\n\n;29 April\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas in Aleppo, Syria, by unidentified aircraft destroy a medical clinic and hit other targets. Airstrikes against rebel-held areas and rebel [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] barrages have combined to kill more than 200 people in Aleppo during the preceding week.<ref name=\"cunningham20160429\" />\n* Russia and the United States announce a renewed ceasefire in two parts of Syria where fighting in violation of the [[2015 in aviation#February|27 February]] ceasefire has escalated during April and that it is scheduled to begin at midnight on 29\u201330 April. The Russian Ministry of Defense announces that the ceasefire applies to [[Latakia Governorate]] and will last 72 hours, while the [[United States Department of State]] later announces that it also includes East Ghouta outside Damascus and has no expiration date. The agreement excludes Aleppo, where the heaviest fighting since the 27 February ceasefire has broken out.<ref>Bergen Airport, Flesland DeYoung, Karen, \"U.S., Russia push for new Syria cease-fire deal,\" ''The Washington Post'', 29 April 2016.</ref>\n* A [[Eurocopter EC225 Super Puma]] helicopter (registration LN-OJF) operated by [[CHC Helikopter Service]] loses its main [[Helicopter rotor|rotor]] in flight while carrying oil workers from the [[Gullfaks B]] oil field in the [[North Sea]] to [[Bergen Airport, Flesland|Bergen Airport]], [[Flesland]], in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], and [[CHC Helikopter Service Flight 241|crashes]] on Norway's Skitholmen islet between the islands of [[Tur\u00f8y]] and [[Toft\u00f8y]], killing all 13 people on board.\n* The commander of [[United States Central Command]], [[United States Army]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Joseph Votel]], announces that a U.S. Department of Defense investigation into a [[United States Air Force]] airstrike against a Doctors Without Borders hospital in [[Kunduz]], [[Afghanistan]], on [[2015 in aviation#October|3 October 2015]] did not amount to a [[war crime]] because American military personnel responsible for the strike attacked the hospital by mistake while attempting to support [[Afghan Armed Forces|Afghan troops]] and U.S. Army [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces]] in combat against [[Taliban]] forces. The incident resulted in 16 American military personnel facing disciplinary action for their role in it, but the investigation found that their misjudgments did not involve any criminal intent.<ref name=\"cunningham20160429\" />\n\n;30 April\n* Nearly 30 airstrikes hit rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria. It is the ninth day of lethal bombardments in the city, and they have killed nearly 250 people since beginning on 22 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-idUSKCN0XR0CT|title=Aleppo bombed as Syrian army begins 'calm' plan elsewhere|date=1 May 2017|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n;3 May\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Phoenix Goodyear Airport]] outside [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]], [[Arizona]], completing the tenth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun on 2 May at [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], [[California]], covers {{convert|691|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} in 15 hours 52 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|43.56|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|22001|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-10-from-San_Francisco-to-Phoenix|title=10th Leg from San Francisco to Phoenix}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/southwest-valley/2016/05/02/solar-impulse-aircraft-california-phoenix/83822062/|title=Solar plane lands in Phoenix area as global trek continues}}</ref>\n\n;5 May\n* [[Amazon.com]] and [[Atlas Air Worldwide Holdings]] announce a deal in which Amazon.com will acquire up to 30 percent of Atlas's stock and Atlas will acquire 20 [[Boeing 767-300]] cargo aircraft, lease them to Amazon.com for ten years, and operate them for Amazon.com for seven years via its [[Atlas Air]] subsidiary. Operations are expected to begin during the latter half of 2016 and grow to their maximum planned size by 2018. It is Amazon.com's second investment in an air cargo carrier \u2013 its first was announced on [[2016 in aviation#March|5 March]] \u2013 and it doubles the size of Amazon.com's air cargo fleet from 20 to 40 aircraft, all Boeing 767-300s.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-partners-with-atlas-air-worldwide-for-cargo-services-1462455676 Jamerson, Joshua, \"Amazon Partners with Atlas Air Worldwide for Cargo Services,\" ''Wall Street Journal'', 5 May 2016, 7:40 p.m. EDT.]</ref>\n\n;6 May\n* A U.S. airstrike against a ground vehicle driving near [[Ar-Rutbah]], [[Iraq]], kills four Islamic State members, including the \"military [[emir]]\" of [[Anbar Governorate]], [[Abu Wahib]], notorious for his appearances in Islamic State videos. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce his death on 9 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/09/notorious-islamic-state-leader-killed-in-airstrike-pentagon-says/|title=Notorious Islamic State leader killed in airstrike, Pentagon says}}</ref>\n* For the second time, [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform floating in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] after a launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]] which placed a Japanese satellite in orbit. The first successful landing had occurred four weeks earlier, on [[2016 in aviation#April|8 April 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4320750/spacex-falcon-9-rocket-lands-second/|title=SpaceX Successfully Lands a Rocket on a Drone Ship, Again}}</ref>\n\n;7 May\n* [[Turkish Air Force]] [[F-4 Phantom II]] and [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] aircraft strike [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] shelters, ammunition depots, and weapon positions in northern Iraq, including in the [[Qandil Mountains]], where the group's headquarters is located.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/d2fa95b2da424cfd83d196b04e179c0b/report-turkey-attacks-syria-55-militants-killed|title=Report: Turkey attacks IS in Syria; 55 militants killed}}</ref>\n\n;9 May\n* Airstrikes by the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]]-led coalition against a rebel military camp in [[Yemen]]'s [[Amran Governorate]] kill at least 10 Yemeni rebels and wound more than 15 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/airstrikes-saudi-led-coalition-yemen-kill-10-rebels-38980567|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;11 May\n* In a [[Freedom of navigation|freedom-of-navigation]] operation in the [[South China Sea]], the [[United States Navy]] [[guided missile destroyer]] {{USS|William P. Lawrence|DDG-110}} steams within {{convert|12|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} of [[Fiery Cross Reef]], which the [[People's Republic of China]] claims as its territory along with adjacent waters which the United States views as [[international waters]]. In response, China scrambles three jet fighters, which join three Chinese ships in monitoring the destroyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/10/china-scrambles-fighters-jets-as-u-s-destroyer-steams-past-disputed-island/|title=China scrambles fighter jets as U.S. destroyer steams past disputed island}}</ref>\n* [[Iran]]'s [[Ministry of Defense (Iran)|Minister of Defense]], [[Brigadier General]] [[Hossein Dehghan]], announces that Iran has taken delivery of at least one [[S-300 (missile)|S-300]] [[surface-to-air-missile]] system from [[Russia]], the first of five to be delivered under a 2007 contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iran-announces-delivery-of-russian-s-300-missile-defense-system/2016/05/10/944afa2e-16ae-11e6-971a-dadf9ab18869_story.html|title=Iran announces delivery of Russian S-300 missile defense system}}</ref>\n\n;12 May\n* [[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Transport (Malaysia)|Minister of Transport]], [[Liow Tiong Lai]], announces that two pieces of debris found in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]] \u2013 an engine cowling piece with a partial [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] logo discovered on the southern coast of [[South Africa]] and an interior panel piece from an aircraft cabin found on [[Rodrigues]] \u2013 \"almost certainly\" are from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b2d55dc21f4e4c4eb3b3dc472b1ff9aa/malaysia-2-more-pieces-almost-certainly-flight-370|title=Malaysia: 2 more pieces 'almost certainly' from Flight 370}}</ref>\n* After a [[Uganda]]n assault team comes under fire while attempting to secure an [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] checkpoint west of [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]], suspected of being used by the group to extort money from travelers, a U.S. special operations team assisting the Ugandans calls in a U.S. airstrike against the checkpoint. The strike kills five Al-Shabaab personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/may/12/us-airstrike-kills-5-al-shabaab-militants-somalia/|title=U.S. airstrike kills 5 al-Shabaab militants in Somalia|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n* Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Tulsa International Airport]] outside [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]], completing the eleventh leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun on 11 May at Phoenix Goodyear Airport in Phoenix, Arizona, covers {{convert|975|mi|km}} in 18 hours 10 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|53.67|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}r), reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|22001|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 11: Phoenix to Tulsa|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-11-from-Phoenix-to-Tulsa|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;13 May\n* Airstrikes suspected of having been conducted by [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] aircraft reportedly kill at least 12 people in [[Idlib]], [[Syria]], and injure at least 38 others. One report places the death toll at 15. Additional strikes reportedly occur around [[Zaara, Syria|Zaara]], Syria. The [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]]'s official [[Syrian Arab News Agency]] claims that the strikes targeted [[Nusra Front]] strongholds in [[Idlib Governorate]] and [[Hama]], and that they killed 30 members of the militant group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5b74c9a7c7f04cfbba896bac3b3992d6/airstrikes-kill-least-5-syria|title=Airstrikes kill at least 12 in northern Syria}}</ref>\n* [[United States Air Force]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Lori Robinson]], previously the commander of the U.S. Air Force's [[Pacific Air Forces]], takes command of [[United States Northern Command]], becoming the first woman to command a U.S. [[Unified Combatant Command|unified combatant command]]. She simultaneously becomes the [[commanding officer]] of the [[North American Aerospace Defense Command]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/05/13/air-force-gen-lori-robinson-becomes-first-woman-ever-to-lead-u-s-combatant-command/|title=Air Force Gen. Lori Robinson becomes first woman ever to lead U.S. combatant command}}</ref>\n\n;15 May\n* According to Turkish military sources, airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition and a [[Turkish Army]] [[artillery]] bombardment combine to kill 27 Islamic State personnel in northern Syria about {{convert|10|km|mi|abbr=off|sp=us}} from the Turkish border as they prepare to fire rockets into [[Turkey]]. The strikes and bombardment destroy five \"fortified defence posts\" and two \"gun posts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36302995|title=Islamic State: Turkish strikes in Syria 'kill 27 militants'|date=16 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;17 May\n* At least two Chinese [[Shenyang J-11]] fighters intercept a [[United States Navy]] [[Lockheed EP-3]] signals reconnaissance aircraft over the [[South China Sea]] in [[international airspace]] east of [[Hainan Island]]. The following day, a U.S. Department of Defense official says that the Chinese aircraft came within {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} of the EP-3 and that the interception was unsafe. China responds that its fighters maintained a safe distance.<ref name=\"idrees20160519\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southchinasea-china-usa-idUSKCN0YA0QX|title=China demands end to U.S. surveillance after aircraft intercept|date=20 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] announces that there were 764 reports of [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs, or \"drones\") sighted near airplanes in the [[United States]] in [[2015 in aviation|2015]], and that it has begun a research program to explore ways of detecting (UAVs) that are operating near airports. It also announces that the initial investigation of drone detection technology had taken place earlier in May 2016 at [[New York City]]\u2032s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[Queens, New York|Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], employing a technology used by the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]. The experiment tested the technology's capability to detect five kinds of UAVs, including common [[rotorcraft]] and more advanced [[Fixed-wing aircraft|fixed-wing]] UAVs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/worried-that-drones-might-strike-airplanes-faa-seeks-airport-detection-system/2016/05/17/92fb76d8-1c3c-11e6-9c81-4be1c14fb8c8_story.html|title=Worried that drones might strike airplanes, FAA seeks airport detection system}}</ref>\n\n;18 May\n* A [[Silk Way Airlines]] [[Antonov An-12]] cargo plane suffers an engine failure shortly after taking off from [[Dwyer Airport]] in southern [[Afghanistan]] and [[2016 Silk Way Airlines Antonov An-12 crash|crashes]], killing seven of its nine-member crew.\n* [[Saab Group|Saab]] debuts its new [[Saab JAS 39 Gripen|JAS 39 Gripen E]] fighter in a rollout at [[Link\u00f6ping]], [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/air-space/2016/05/18/gripen-e-debuts-saab-reports-continued-interest-c-variants/84537568/|title=gripen-e-debuts-saab-reports-continued-interest-c-variants|first=Defense|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;19 May\n* [[EgyptAir Flight 804]], an [[Airbus A320|Airbus A320-232]] (registration SU-GCC) on a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Cairo]], crashes into the [[Mediterranean Sea]] south of [[Karpathos]], killing all 66 people on board.\n* In response to a U.S. Defense Department accusation on 18 May that Chinese fighter aircraft made an unsafe interception of a U.S. Navy reconnaissance aircraft over the South China Sea on 17 May, the [[People's Republic of China]] demands that the United States cease reconnaissance flights in the vicinity of China.<ref name=\"idrees20160519\"/>\n\n;20 May \n* Russian [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Minister of Defense]] [[Sergei Shoigu]] proposes that Russia and the U.S.-led coalition conduct joint airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] and against ground convoys carrying weapons and reinforcements into Syria from Turkey. The U.S. Department of State responds that no agreement to conduct joint airstrikes exists, and the U.S. Department of Defense informs the press that it has no plans to expand cooperation with Russia in Syria beyond existing flight-safety communications intended only to deconflict coalition and Russian air operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-proposes-joint-airstrikes-with-us-led-coalition-in-syria/2016/05/20/3f679bfc-1e92-11e6-9c81-4be1c14fb8c8_story.html|title=Russia proposes joint airstrikes with U.S.-led coalition in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;21 May\n* A U.S. airstrike involving several unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) hits a ground vehicle driving on a road near [[Ahmad Wal]] in [[Pakistan]]'s [[Balochistan]] province, reportedly killing [[Taliban]] leader [[Akhtar Mansour]] and the driver of the vehicle. It is the first U.S. UAV strike in that part of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-on-taliban-leader-escalates-us-involvement-in-afghan-war/2016/05/22/f26ced5a-2014-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html |last1=Craig|first1=Tim|first2=Antonio|last2=Olivo|first3=Missy|last3=Ryan|title=U.S. takes war back to Pakistan with drone strike aimed at Taliban leader|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date= 22 May 2016|time= 8:39 a.m. EDT}}</ref>\n* An airstrike allegedly conducted by aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition flying into Syria from Turkey hits the Islamic State-held town of [[Arshaf]], Syria, near [[Mare']], killing seven members of one family and perhaps as many as 10 people in total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dccd1bb3528d476d8f4f6e30001e35f4/activists-suspected-coalition-airstrike-kills-syrian-family|title=Activists: Suspected coalition airstrike kills Syrian family}}</ref>\n* Flown by Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) arrives at [[Dayton International Airport]] in [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]], [[Ohio]],<ref name=nbc20160522>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/innovation/solar-impulse-2-lands-ohio-complete-latest-leg-global-trip-n578171|title=Solar Impulse 2 Lands in Ohio to Complete Latest Leg of Global Trip}}</ref> completing the twelfth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight, begun early in the day at Tulsa International Airport in Tulsa, Oklahoma,<ref name=nbc20160522/> covers {{convert|691|mi|km}} in 16 hours 34 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|41.72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|21000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=nbc20160522/><ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 12: Tulsa to Dayton|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-12-from-Tulsa-to-Dayton|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;22 May\n* [[Prime Minister of Iraq]] [[Haider al-Abadi]] announces that [[Iraqi Air Force]] [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]]s are bombing Islamic State targets in [[Fallujah]], Iraq, at the beginning of a drive by Iraqi military and security forces and militias allied with them to retake the city from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iraqi-military-preparing-to-retake-fallujah-from-islamic-state/2016/05/22/15c832cc-200c-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=Operation to retake Fallujah has begun, Iraqi prime minister says}}</ref>\n\n;23 May\n* U.S. airstrikes support Iraqi military and security forces and militias allied with them moving into Fallujah, Iraq. A U.S. spokesman for the U.S.-led coalition announces that coalition aircraft have struck 21 Islamic State targets in and around Fallujah since 17 May.<ref name=salim20160523>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi-military-claims-advances-in-jihadist-held-fallujah/2016/05/23/45b266c6-20e6-11e6-b944-52f7b1793dae_story.html|title=Iraqi military claims advances in Islamic State-held Fallujah}}</ref>\n* An Iraqi Air Force F-16 Fighting Falcon destroys an Islamic State bomb-making factory in Fallujah, Iraq, and hits Islamic State rocket launchers in the city.<ref name=salim20160523/>\n* The first two Dutch [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 both [[Royal Netherlands Air Force]] F-35A models \u2013 arrive in the [[Netherlands]], landing at [[Leeuwarden Air Base]]. They are the first examples of the F-35 to arrive in [[Europe]].<ref name=aviationistf35>{{cite web|url=https://theaviationist.com/category/f-35/page/2/|title=The Aviationist \u00bb F-35}}</ref>\n\n;24 May\n* Iraqi Air Force and U.S. aircraft strike Islamic State targets in and around Fallujah, Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/mixed-iraqi-force-prepares-for-push-into-militant-stronghold-of-fallujah/2016/05/24/475f6b98-21b0-11e6-b944-52f7b1793dae_story.html|title=Mixed Iraqi force prepares for push into militant stronghold of Fallujah}}</ref>\n\n;25 May\n* The brother of a taxi driver killed in the 21 May U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle strike that also killed Taliban leader Akhtar Mansour files a police report in Balochistan, Pakistan, requesting that his brother's death be investigated and noting that the United States claimed responsibility for the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-afghanistan-taliban-idUSKCN0YK0Q2|title=Brother of man killed in U.S. strike on Taliban chief files police report|date=30 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* Russia announces that is suspending airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] to allow rebels not affiliated with the group to distance themselves from it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-says-it-is-suspending-attacks-against-syrias-al-qaeda-franchise/2016/05/25/afd236b0-a40a-475e-af5c-030ee541a77f_story.html|title=Russia calls off attacks against Syria\u2019s al-Qaeda franchise}}</ref>\n* With Bertrand Piccard at the controls, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) flies from Dayton International Airport in Dayton, Ohio, to [[Lehigh Valley International Airport]] in [[Hanover Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Hanover Township]], [[Pennsylvania]], completing the thirteenth leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using a drop of fossil fuel. The flight covers {{convert|649|mi|km}} in 16 hours 49 minutes at an average speed of {{convert|38.63|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|15000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 13: Dayton to Lehigh Valley|url=http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-13-from-Dayton-to-Lehigh_Valley|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n* U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) Administrator [[Peter V. Neffenger]] says in testimony before the [[United States Congress]] that a projected 740 million people will pass through TSA security checkpoints at U.S. airports during the 2016 summer travel season, 97 million more than the 643 million who did in 2013, that the 45,000-strong TSA workforce is not large enough to prevent excessively long lines at the checkpoints, and that the recent cancellation of plans to lay off 1,600 TSA employees and hire 768 more will be insufficient to reduce lines. He reports that he plans to convert part-time TSA employees into full-time ones and to increase the number of enrollees in trusted traveler programs from 9.5 million to 25 million as ways of reducing airport security waits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/tsa-chief-takes-another-crack-at-explaining-long-airport-security-lines/2016/05/25/b9c95534-2270-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=TSA chief Neffenger takes another crack at explaining long airport security lines}}</ref>\n\n;26 May\n* An airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition in Fallujah, Iraq, kills Maher al-Bilawi, the commander of Islamic State forces in the city.<ref name=reuters20160528>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-iraq-falluja-idUSKCN0YI1AD|title=Islamic State commander in Falluja killed, U.S. military says|date=28 May 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* An [[American Airlines]] vice president, Kerry Philipovitch, and executives from the airport authorities of [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]], testify before the U.S. Congress asking it to take action to reduce security lines at Transportation Security Administration (TSA) checkpoints at U.S. airports. Philipovitch says, \"We have never seen TSA wait times that affect airlines and passengers throughout the United States like we\u2019ve seen in recent months...More needs to be done, and fast. Programs that had been in place to drive efficiency and increase security throughout were eliminated without adding commensurate resources required to support longer passenger processing times.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/american-airlines-something-needs-to-be-done-and-fast-about-tsa-lines/2016/05/26/5811e50e-2338-11e6-aa84-42391ba52c91_story.html|title=American Airlines: Something 'needs to be done, and fast' about TSA lines}}</ref>\n\n;27 May\n* [[Korean Air Flight 2708]], a [[Boeing 777-300]] (registration HL7534), suffers an engine failure during its takeoff roll at [[Haneda Airport]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], that results in a fire. The flight crew aborts the takeoff, and the 319 people aboard evacuate the aircraft. Twelve of them are injured in the incident.\n* The U.S.-led coalition has conducted 20 airstrikes against Islamic State targets in Fallujah, Iraq, since 24 May, killing 70 Islamic State personnel.<ref name=reuters20160528/>\n* Russia warns that it will escalate its air campaign in Syria if the United States does not respond positively to its long-standing proposal to conduct joint airstrikes in Syria with the [[Russian Federation Air Force]].<ref name=sly20160531>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/airstrikes-kill-dozens-near-a-hospital-in-syria-as-violence-escalates/2016/05/31/edc5bd03-0b09-4bf6-a182-69cda8b75a3e_story.html|title=Airstrikes kill dozens near a hospital in Syria as violence escalates}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike kills [[Abdullahi Haji Da\u2019ud]], Al-Shabaab's top commander, as he travels in southern Somalia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/1/abdullahi-daud-key-al-shabaab-leader-killed-us-air/|title=Abdullahi Da\u2019ud, key al-Shabaab leader, killed by U.S. airstrike in Somalia|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n* A Vietnamese man, Minh Quang Pham, is sentenced in [[New York City]] to 40 years in prison for providing material support to [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] in a 2011 plot to bomb [[Heathrow Airport]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scnow.com/news/national/wire/article_8cf9d08e-5b29-5d4e-8634-4925712117b5.html|title=Anonymous, \"40 years for Vietnamese man accused in plot to bomb Heathrow\", Associated Press, May 27, 2016.}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* A [[World War II]]-era [[P-47 Thunderbolt]] crashes into the [[Hudson River]] off [[Edgewater, New Jersey|Edgewater]], [[New Jersey]], killing its pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/small-plane-carrying-people-lands-hudson-river-article-1.2652690|title=Vintage World War II plane crashes in Hudson River; pilot killed}}</ref>\n* [[SpaceX]] successfully lands the first stage of its [[Falcon 9]] rocket on a platform at sea, the fourth time it has made such a landing. The landing, made aboard a platform in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|422|mi|km}} off the coast of [[Florida]] after launching a communications satellite into orbit, is particularly challenging because of the distance the rocket travels to deliver its payload and the large amount of energy required, subjecting the first stage to extreme speeds and re-entry heating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/05/27/elon-musks-spacex-does-it-again-nails-fourth-landing-in-a-row/|title=Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX does it again. Nails fourth landing.}}</ref>\n\n;29 May\n* [[Lufthansa]] announces that it will suspend service to [[Venezuela]] beginning on 18 June, saying that Venezuela owes it millions of [[United States dollar]]s in ticket revenues and that Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult to convert ticket sales revenue to dollars that can be sent abroad. Lufthansa adds that it hopes to restore service to Venezuela in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36407570|title=Lufthansa to suspend flights to Venezuela|date=29 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;30 May\n* Intense late-evening strikes by three unidentified aircraft \u2013 reported by some observers to be Russian \u2013 against buildings around the National Hospital in [[Idlib]], Syria, kill at least 23 and perhaps as many as 50 people and injure about 250 others. Over the preceding weekend, Russian Federation Air Force and [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] aircraft had conducted hundreds of strikes against rebel-held areas in [[Aleppo]], Syria.<ref name=sly20160531/>\n* [[LATAM Airlines Group]] announces that its subsidiary airlines will suspend service to Venezuela, making it the second airline company to do so. Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult for airlines to convert ticket sales revenue to [[United States dollar]]s to cover their costs of operating in Venezuela. LATAM plans for its subsidiary airlines to cease service between [[Caracas]], Venezuela, and [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]], first, with suspension of service between Caracas and [[Lima]], [[Peru]], and between Caracas and [[Santiago]], [[Chile]], to halt by 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-36414733|title=Second airline suspends flights to Venezuela|date=30 May 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;31 May\n* The U.S. Transportation Security Administration reports that the major delays expected at its security checkpoints at U.S. airports over the 2016 [[Memorial Day]] weekend did not materialize. From 26 May through 30 May, wait times in security lines averaged less than 10 minutes in regular security lines nationwide, with the majority of the 10.3 million passengers having a wait time of less than 30 minutes. The longest wait was at [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]], where passengers waited 75 minutes on 26 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/tsa-says-most-airport-security-lines-werent-so-bad-over-memorial-day-weekend/2016/05/31/a537e9f8-2731-11e6-b989-4e5479715b54_story.html|title=TSA says most airport security lines weren\u2019t so bad over Memorial Day weekend}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n* With international sanctions having largely prevented [[Iran]] from purchasing new airliners or spare parts for its commercial aircraft since the [[Iranian Revolution]] of 1979, 88 of Iran's 250 commercial aircraft are grounded due to a lack of spare parts.<ref name=gambrell20160922>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_IRAN_AIRBUS_BOEING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME|title=Gambrell, John, \"US grants Airbus, Boeing permission to sell aircraft to Iran,\" Associated Press, September 22, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n;1 June\n* The [[French Navy]] [[survey ship]] ''[[French ship Laplace (A 793)|Laplace]]'' detects signals in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] believed to be from the [[flight recorder]] of [[EgyptAir Flight 804]], an [[Airbus A320|Airbus A320-232]] which crashed on [[2016 in aviation#May|19 May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/02/world/middleeast/egyptair-black-box.html|title=Black Box From Missing EgyptAir Flight 804 Is Said to Be Detected|first1=Nicola|last1=Clark|first2=Nour|last2=Youssef|date=1 June 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;2 June\n* In an extremely unusual coincidence, two U.S. military flight demonstration [[Aviation squadron|squadrons]] suffer crashes on the same day. A [[United States Air Force]] [[United States Air Force Thunderbirds|Thunderbirds]] [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] crashes in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], [[Colorado]], just after the Thunderbirds perform a [[Flypast|flyover]] for the 2016 [[graduation]] ceremony at the [[United States Air Force Academy]]; its pilot ejects safely. Hours later, a [[United States Navy]] [[Blue Angels]] [[F/A-18 Hornet]] crashes in [[Smyrna, Tennessee|Smyrna]], [[Tennessee]], while practicing for an [[air show]], killing its pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/02/air-force-f-16-crashes-just-minutes-after-flying-over-air-force-academy-graduation/|title=In bizarre coincidence, a Blue Angels F-18 and a Thunderbirds F-16 crash on same day}}</ref>\n\n;3 June\n* The [[United Nations Security Council]] agrees to request formally that the [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] allow airlifts of food and medical supplies to civilians in besieged, rebel-held areas of [[Syria]]. Plans call for [[United Nations]] representatives to make the request in [[Damascus]], Syria, on 5 June. The Syrian government has not permitted deliveries of humanitarian aid to besieged areas despite a 1 June deadline set by an international task force for it to permit full ground access to the areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/un-security-council-will-formally-request-syrian-approval-of-humanitarian-air-drops/2016/06/03/a733e73a-29ce-11e6-ae4a-3cdd5fe74204_story.html|title=U.N. Security Council to formally request Syrian approval of humanitarian airdrops}}</ref>\n* The U.S. Navy announces that [[Carrier Air Wing Seven]] aboard the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Harry S. Truman|CVN-75}} has begun launching airstrikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] targets from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] during the day. It is the first time that aircraft from a U.S. aircraft carrier have struck targets in the [[Middle East]] from the Mediterranean since the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|beginning of the Iraq War]] in [[2003 in aviation|2003]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/03/as-pressure-mounts-on-the-islamic-states-capital-u-s-aircraft-carrier-starts-striking-from-the-mediterranean/|title=As pressure increases on Islamic State\u2019s capital, U.S. aircraft carrier starts striking from the Mediterranean|publisher=}}</ref>\n* A [[Guardian Air]] [[Dassault Falcon 20]] air ambulance arrives at [[Saint Helena Airport]] to make the first [[medical evacuation]] flight in the history of [[Saint Helena]]. It departs the following morning, taking a critically ill baby and its mother to [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|title=FIRST EVER MEDEVAC FLIGHT \u2013 CRITICALLY ILL SAINT TRANSFERRED TO CAPE TOWN : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917192453/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;4 June\n* Turkish officials sink a 36-year-old [[Airbus A300]] in the [[Aegean Sea]] off [[Ku\u015fadas\u0131]], [[Turkey]], to serve as an [[artificial reef]] and recreational [[Underwater diving|dive]] site. The fourth aircraft sunk off the Turkish coast recently, it reportedly is the largest aircraft ever sunk for use as a reef or dive site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/06/06/turkey-sinks-an-airbus-jumbo-jet-in-aegean-sea-to-attract-fish-and-tourists/|title=Turkey sinks an Airbus jumbo jet in Aegean Sea to attract fish \u2013 and tourists}}</ref>\n\n;5 June\n* During a flight from [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]], to [[London]], [[England]], Malaysian Airlines Flight 1, an [[Airbus A380]] with 378 people on board, encounters severe turbulence over the [[Bay of Bengal]]. Some passengers and crew suffer minor injuries. The airliner returns safely to Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/06/05/world/asia/ap-as-malaysia-airline-turbulence.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Malaysia Airlines Passengers Injured Due to Turbulence,\" Associated Press, June 5, 2016, 12:12 P.M. EDT.}}</ref>\n* [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] warns the [[People's Republic of China]] not to declare to an [[air defense identification zone]] over the [[South China Sea]], saying that to do so would be a \"provocative and destabilizing act.\"<ref name=denyer20160608>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-spy-plane-buzzed-by-chinese-jets-in-unsafe-intercept/2016/06/08/160d607f-770a-484c-8339-62c0816487fe_story.html|title=U.S. spy plane buzzed by Chinese jets in 'unsafe' intercept}}</ref>\n\n;6 June\n* [[Foreign Minister of Russia]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announces that [[Russia]] will intensify its airstrikes in the area around [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]], in support of [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] forces defending against a [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] offensive there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/assad-pledges-more-bloodshed-in-syria-says-the-peace-process-has-failed/2016/06/07/efcd0e96-2cb6-11e6-b9d5-3c3063f8332c_story.html|title=Assad pledges more bloodshed in Syria, says the peace process has failed}}</ref>\n\n;7 June\n* Two Chinese [[Chengdu J-10]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Firebird\") fighters intercept a U.S. Air Force [[Boeing RC-135]] reconnaissance plane in [[international airspace]] over the [[East China Sea]] in what the [[United States Pacific Command]] describes the next day as an \"unsafe\" manner. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] responds that the Chinese pilots did nothing unsafe and protests what it calls \"frequent close reconnaissance on China's coast by U.S. military aircraft.\"\n* In testimony before the [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]], U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) Administrator [[Peter V. Neffenger]] says that it is reducing passenger delays at TSA security checkpoints at airports in the [[United States]] by focusing on speeding the processing of passengers at seven major airports ([[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]] in the [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]-[[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] area of [[Texas]]; [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]; [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]]; [[Los Angeles International Airport]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[Miami International Airport]] in [[Miami-Dade County, Florida]], [[California]]; [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]]; and [[O'Hare International Airport]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]). He adds that the success of the program over the 2016 [[Memorial Day]] weekend has spurred TSA to expand it to airports at [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]; [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]]; [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]], [[Michigan]]; [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], Florida; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], Texas; [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]; [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]; [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], Florida; [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]; [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]]; [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], California; and [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]; and at New YorkCity's [[LaGuardia Airport]]. He informs the committee that he expects 768 newly trained TSA agents to join the lines during June, and, if the [[United States Congress]] approves it, will shift 2,784 part-time TSA workers to full-time work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/focusing-on-keeping-lines-moving-at-mega-airports-tsa-says-its-doing-better/2016/06/07/a45bbc98-2ca5-11e6-9de3-6e6e7a14000c_story.html|title=TSA says it\u2019s improving at keeping lines moving at mega-airports}}</ref>\n\n;8 June\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, kill 15 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/06/08/syrian-activists-airstrikes-aleppo/85589260/|title=Syrian activists say airstrikes in Aleppo kill at least 15}}</ref>\n\n;9 June\n* According to the [[Al Sumaria]] television network, an airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition on this date against an Islamic State headquarters in [[Nineveh Governorate]] in northern [[Iraq]] near the border with Syria wounds the Islamic State leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]] and several other Islamic State personnel. The following day, a spokesman for the coalition announces that the coalition cannot confirm the strike or any injury to al-Baghdadi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-baghdadi-idUSKCN0YW0QT|title=U.S, Iraqi officials can't confirm report Islamic State leader wounded|date=10 June 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;10 June\n* Over eastern [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Luminati Aerospace]]'s solar-powered [[VO-Substrata]] aircraft makes its first test flight open to the public, flying from an airfield at [[Calverton, New York|Calverton]], New York, for about 20 minutes with a pilot at the controls, although it is also configured for unmanned flight. It is the prototype for a fleet of solar-powered [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s Luminati Aerospace hopes to build starting in late 2016 that will fly at altitudes of more than {{convert|60000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and provide [[Internet]] service to over 4,000,000,000 people worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2daadfec9c824c9c8bb682b56ea0c216/aerospace-firm-unveils-solar-powered-aircraft|title=Aerospace firm successfully tests solar-powered aircraft}}</ref>\n* [[United States Department of Defense]] officials announce that in late May 2016 [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] granted U.S. military commanders in [[Afghanistan]] expanded powers to assist Afghan military and security forces in combat against the [[Taliban]]. Among them is the authority to order U.S. airstrikes in support of Afghan offensive operations against the Taliban in limited circumstances in which the strikes are expected to have \"strategic effect.\" Previously, U.S. airstrikes in Afghanistan had been authorized only to defend U.S. personnel, protect Afghan forces facing serious danger, or conduct counterterrorism operations against [[al-Qaeda]] or the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/09/defense-official-u-s-to-begin-striking-taliban-advise-regular-afghan-soldiers-again/|title=U.S. widens war in Afghanistan, authorizes new action against Taliban}}</ref>\n* The [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] makes its international airshow debut when two [[Royal Netherlands Air Force]] F-35A aircraft perform during the ''Luchtmachtdagen 2016'' airshow at [[Leeuwarden Air Base]] in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=aviationistf35/>\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] grants permission to six U.S. airlines \u2013 [[American Airlines]], [[Frontier Airlines]], [[JetBlue]], [[Silver Airways]], [[Southwest Airlines]], and [[Sun Country Airlines]] \u2013 to provide the first scheduled airline service between the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]] in over 50 years, joining 46 non-U.S. airlines that already serve Cuba. The airlines are to provide 155 round-trip flights per week between five U.S. cities (Chicago, Illinois; Fort Lauderdale, Florida; Miami, Florida; Minneapolis, Minnesota; and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania) and nine Cuban destinations ([[Camag\u00fcey]], [[Cayo Coco]], [[Cayo Largo del Sur]], [[Cienfuegos]], [[Holgu\u00edn]], [[Manzanillo, Cuba|Manzanillo]], [[Matanzas]], [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]], and [[Santiago de Cuba]]). Flights are expected to begin in the autumn of 2016 and early in the winter of 2016\u20132017. A decision on flights by U.S. airlines to [[Havana]] is expected later in the summer of 2016. Although U.S. law still prohibits tourist travel to Cuba, it permits a dozen other categories of travel, including family visits, official business, journalist visits, professional meetings and educational and religious activities, and the [[United States Government]] has relaxed oversight of travel to the point that U.S. travelers are allowed to design their own \"people-to-people\" cultural exchanges in Cuba that in essence permit leisure travel under the guise of a cultural exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/389c209f926940ee97c44128c13a832f/us-airlines-start-scheduled-flights-cuba|title=US airlines to start scheduled flights to Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;11 June\n* An estimated 2,000 people gather outside [[Ramstein Air Base]] in [[Germany]] to protest the base's alleged role in supporting the U.S. \"drone war,\" the U.S. practice of using unmanned aerial vehicles to strike terrorist targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/europe/no-drone-war-thousands-converge-in-protest-outside-ramstein-1.414238|title='No Drone War.' Thousands converge in protest outside Ramstein}}</ref>\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) flies from [[Lehigh Valley International Airport]] in [[Hanover Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Hanover Township]], [[Pennsylvania]], to [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]], completing the 14th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any [[fossil fuel]]. The flight covers {{convert|164.5|mi|km}} in 4&nbsp;hours 41&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|35.14|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|3002|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 14: Lehigh Valley to New York|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-14-from-Lehigh_Valley-to-New_York|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;12 June\n* A man throws a homemade explosive device made out of a beer bottle at the ticketing counter in the check-in area of Terminal 2 at [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport]] at [[Shanghai]], [[China]]; it explodes, injuring four people with flying glass. He then slashes his own throat with a knife, injuring himself seriously.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/three-injured-as-home-made-explosives-detonated-at-shanghai-airport/2016/06/12/be34b036-2e11-47fd-9fb0-e0acaa84ddc3_story.html|title=Explosive device at Shanghai airport leaves 5 injured}}</ref>\n* An unmanned aerial vehicle operating without permission near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]], forces the airport to close for 69 minutes.<ref name=bbc20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37493404|title=Dubai airport grounds flights due to 'drone activity'|date=28 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes ascribed to Russian aircraft hit Syria's rebel-held [[Idlib Governorate]]. A series of them against targets in [[Idlib]], including one that hits a popular market, kills at least 21 people, while a strike in [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]] that collapses an apartment building kills six others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-june-12-2016/2016/06/12/fe7acb86-309e-11e6-8ff7-7b6c1998b7a0_story.html|title=World digest: June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;12\u201313 June (overnight)\n* An airstrike on a ground vehicle in [[Yemen]]'s [[Shabwa Governorate]] kills three [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members in the vehicle. The strike is suspected of having been conducted by a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b139df4d42904c2db908c404a57b5f82/suspected-us-drone-kills-3-al-qaida-suspects-yemen|title=Suspected US drone kills 3 al-Qaida suspects in Yemen}}</ref>\n\n;13 June\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) charges [[Amazon.com]] with shipping a [[hazardous material]] as air cargo, alleging that the company shipped a caustic [[drain cleaner]] without properly declaring, packaging, or labeling it, including emergency response information with it, or training employees in how to handle it, and that a package of the drain cleaner leaked at a [[United Parcel Service]] facility and came in contact with nine workers. The FAA asks that Amazon.com be fined $350,000 for the incident. The FAA alleges that Amazon.com violated hazardous materials regulations on 24 other occasions between February 2013 and September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-06-13/amazon-fined-by-u-s-faa-for-shipping-dangerous-cargo-on-planes|title=Amazon Fined by U.S. FAA for Air Shipment of Dangerous Cargo|date=13 June 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;14 June\n* The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) asks pilots in to avoid flying too low over [[walrus]] haul-out sites along the [[Chukchi Sea]] coast of northern [[Alaska]] because of the danger of frightening the walruses into stampeding and injuring and killing one another and nearby humans. Although the FAA says it does not plan to establish formal flight path and altitude restrictions on flights near walrus haul-out sites, it reminds pilots that harassing walruses is illegal under the U.S. [[Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972]]. Earlier in 2016, the FAA had instructed airplane pilots to fly no closer than {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} to walrus haul-outs and no lower than an altitude over {{convert|2000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and helicopter pilots to fly no closer than {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} and no lower than {{convert|3000|ft|km}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2016/06/23/the-grim-reason-pilots-need-to-worry-about-walruses/|title=The grim reason pilots need to worry about walruses}}</ref>\n\n;15 June\n* The [[Government of Egypt]] announces that it has found and made images of the wreckage of Egyptair Flight 804 on the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea. The Airbus A320-232 had crashed on 19 May 2016, killing all 66 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/dde4f3596024470486050521ae995328/egypt-says-it-has-found-plane-wreckage|title=Egypt says it has found plane wreckage|access-date=16 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616221758/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dde4f3596024470486050521ae995328/egypt-says-it-has-found-plane-wreckage|archive-date=16 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* After it successfully launches a [[satellite]] into Earth orbit, the first stage of [[SpaceX]]'s [[Falcon 9]] rocket fails to make what would have been the fifth successful landing of a reusable booster rocket when one of its booster engines fails, causing it to descend far too quickly toward the floating platform in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Florida]] on which SpaceX intended it to land. The rapid descent causes it to make what SpaceX founder [[Elon Musk]] deems the \"hardest impact\" ever by a Falcon 9 first stage and results in its destruction \u2013 what Musk terms its \"rapid unscheduled disassembly.\" Musk adds that upgrades to correct the problem could be in service by the end of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/06/15/spacexs-latest-rocket-landing-ended-in-a-rapid-unscheduled-disassembly/|title=SpaceX\u2019s latest rocket landing ended in a 'rapid unscheduled disassembly'}}</ref>\n\n;16 June\n* The [[cockpit voice recorder]] from Egyptair Flight 804 is recovered from a depth of about {{convert|9800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} in the Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36551464|title=EgyptAir MS804 crash: Voice recorder recovered from sea|date=16 June 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;17 June\n* Two [[Japan Air Self-Defense Force]] fighter aircraft scramble to intercept two Chinese fighters over the [[East China Sea]] near the Japanese-controlled [[Senkaku Islands]] (called the Diaoyu Islands in China). In [[2016 in aviation#July|July]], the [[People's Republic of China]] will criticize the Japanese pilots' actions during the encounter.<ref name=\"ap20160705\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/china-confirms-close-encounter-japan-fighter-jets-over-east-china-sea/|title=China confirms fighter jet encounter with Japan}}</ref>\n* [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] strikes on rebel targets in Aleppo, Syria, during the evening kill at least seven people, with one report placing the death toll at nine. According to [[Doctors Without Borders]], one of the strikes puts Aleppo's biggest hospital out of service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/848713a21a0141f496c0c97bbeb0e99f/2-syrian-media-activists-seriously-wounded-explosion|title=Strikes on Syria's divided Aleppo kill 7; activists wounded}}</ref>\n* The [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] releases images which suggest that the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] used [[cluster bomb]]s in a raid against U.S.-backed Syrian rebels near [[Al-Tanf]], Syria, earlier in the week that killed two people and wounded four. The images show what appears to be the tail section of a Russian RBK-500 cluster bomb.<ref name=gibbonsneff201606818>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/18/images-suggest-that-russia-cluster-bombed-u-s-backed-syrian-fighters/|title=Images suggest that Russia cluster-bombed U.S.-backed Syrian fighters}}</ref>\n* The [[flight data recorder]] from Egyptair Flight 804 is recovered from a depth of about {{convert|9800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} in the Mediterranean Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/17/middleeast/egyptair-wreckage-found/index.html|title=EgyptAir Flight 804: Second black box found|author1=Michael Pearson |author2=Lorenza Brascia|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Later in the day, the [[Government of Egypt]] announces that the aircraft's cockpit voice recorder and flight data recorder had suffered extensive damage prior to their recovery, necessitating repairs that will delay processing of the information they recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jun/17/egyptair-flight-ms804-extensively-damaged-black-boxes-will-need-repairs-before-analysis|title=EgyptAir flight MS804: repairs needed to 'extensively damaged' black boxes|first=Associated|last=Press|date=17 June 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n* At a conference of [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] Administrator [[Charles Bolden]] announces plans for the [[NASA X-57 Maxwell|X-57 Maxwell]], a 14-motor, all-electric airplane. The program is intended spur the development of more energy-efficient and cleaner [[general aviation]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/18/science/nasa-electric-plane-x57.html|title=NASA Unveils Plans for Electric-Powered Plane|first=Kenneth|last=Chang|date=17 June 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;18 June\n* Touring [[Fallujah]], Iraq, the day after the [[Government of Iraq]] declared victory in its operation to retake Fallujah from the Islamic State, [[Lieutenant General]] Abdelwahab al-Saedi, the [[Iraqi Army]] commander of the operation, tells the press that an estimated 300 to 700 Islamic State personnel had been in the city when the operation began and that most had been killed by airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/after-gains-on-the-islamic-state-in-fallujah-iraqi-forces-strike-south-of-mosul/2016/06/18/0414a862-34bb-11e6-ab9d-1da2b0f24f93_story.html|title=Inside Fallujah, Iraqi forces dodge snipers and car bombs in final fight for the city}}</ref>\n* A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman announces that during a [[video teleconference]] the Department of Defense had \"expressed strong concerns\" to the [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Russian Miniistry of Defense]] about the Russian Federation Air Force's use of cluster bombs in a raid in Syria earlier in the week.<ref name=gibbonsneff201606818/>\n\n;19 June\n* Aircraft supporting a Syrian government ground offensive against Islamic State forces holding Tabqa air base strike the nearby city of [[Al-Thawrah]], Syria, with [[cluster munition]]s, reportedly killed 10 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2f834ca0edea4fd284cd8cff8c9e5063/activists-say-8-syrians-killed-trying-cross-turkey|title=Syrian forces advance on IS-held air base}}</ref>\n* During a [[parachute]] failure test, [[Blue Origin]] lands its [[New Shepard]] [[Reusable launch system|reusable space launch system]] in [[West Texas]], the fourth time the same Blue Origin rocket has made a [[Sub-orbital spaceflight|suborbital flight]] into space and landed intact. During the unmanned flight, New Shepard's capsule and rocket separate and controllers deliberately induce a parachute failure to test the capsule's ability to land safely after the failure of one of its three parachutes. The rocket, using [[wing]]s and firing of its engine to make its descent, lands about seven minutes before the capsule, and both landings are successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/reusable-rocket-clears-fourth-trial-run-at-bezos-space-exploration-firm/2016/06/19/90a89978-366e-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Reusable rocket clears fourth trial run at Bezos space-exploration firm}}</ref>\n* The [[Terrafugia Transition]] [[Roadable aircraft|roadable airplane]] receives exemptions from the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration as a \"light sport aircraft.\" The administrative action puts the United States on track to legalize a flying car for consumer use for the first time. Provided that their roadable aircraft overcome various regulatory barriers, manufacturers of such aircraft expect them to enter the consumer market over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/06/20/flying-cars-just-took-a-big-step-closer-to-being-legal/|title=Flying cars just took a big step closer to being legal}}</ref>\n\n;20 June\n* With [[Bertrand Piccard]] at the controls, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) departs John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City to begin the 15th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for the nonstop [[transatlantic flight]] to [[Seville Airport]] in [[Seville]], [[Spain]], to cover {{convert|3564|mi|km}} and take at least 90 hours.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 15: New York to Sevillerk|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-15-from-New_York-to-Seville |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;21 June\n* After a 10-hour flight from [[Rothera Research Station]] on the [[Antarctic Peninsula]], a Canadian [[Kenn Borek Air]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter]] lands at [[Amundsen\u2013Scott South Pole Station]] at the [[Geographic South Pole]] in [[Antarctica]] to evacuate two workers there who have fallen ill. It is only the third flight to the station to take place during the Antarctic winter during the 60 years since the station opened in 1956; generally, no flights to the station occur from February to October each year. After a layover at the Amundsen-Scott station, the plane makes a 10-hour return flight to the Rothera station the following day with the patients on board. It is only the third time that anyone has been evacuated from the South Pole during the Antarctic winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/06/16/a-rare-risky-mission-is-underway-to-rescue-sick-scientists-from-the-south-pole/|title=Plane takes off from the South Pole in rare, risky effort to rescue sick workers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/06/22/rescuers-succeed-in-evacuating-sick-workers-at-the-south-pole/|title=Rescuers succeed in evacuating sick workers at the South Pole}}</ref>\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] releases U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) regulations for the use of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs, or \"drones\") by hobbyists in the [[United States]]. They require drone pilots to keep their UAVs in sight, to operate them only in daylight, and to fly them no higher than an altitude of {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and prohibit their operation over strangers. The regulations also require that hobbyists' UAVs weigh no more than {{convert|55|lb|kg}} and prohibit them from flying over the [[District of Columbia]]. The FAA reports that 2.5 million UAVs will be sold to hobbyists in the United States during 2016 and that 7 million will be sold in 2020. The new regulations require U.S. commercial UAV operators to be vetted by the U.S. [[Transportation Security Administration]] and to pass an aeronautical knowledge examination administered at an FAA-approved test center, but do not address over-the-horizon operations by commercial UAVs; the FAA reports that there are 10,602 registered commercial UAVs in the United States and projects that 600,000 UAVs intended for commercial use will be sold in the United States during 2016 and that 2.7 million will be sold for commercial use in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/white-house-rolls-out-rules-for-drone-operations/2016/06/21/0508557a-3763-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Before feared spike in drone crashes, White House sets new rules}}</ref>\n* The [[Boeing|Boeing Company]] announces a tentative deal in which [[Iran Air]], which is seeking to upgrade its aging fleet of pre-1979 Boeing aircraft with new [[Boeing 737]]s and [[Boeing 777]]s, has signed an agreement expressing its \"intent\" to buy airliners from Boeing in the first major U.S. trade deal with [[Iran]] following a 2015 nuclear accord between Iran and the United States. The deal is expected to face political and regulatory hurdles, but if it proceeds on schedule the first new Boeing airliners are expected to arrive in Iran in October 2016. Depending on the number of new aircraft purchased and the number of leased and older aircraft ultimately included in the transaction, the deal could be worth up to $25,000,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/boeing-reaches-tentative-plane-sale-pact-with-iran-in-first-major-post-sanction-outreach/2016/06/21/2f38e7c6-379d-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=Boeing reaches tentative plane-sale deal with Iran in first major post-sanctions outreach}}</ref>\n\n;22 June\n* The [[Australian Transport Safety Bureau]] announces that a piece of aircraft debris found in a pile of seaweed and wood in the [[Indian Ocean]] off [[Kangaroo Island]] off the coast of [[South Australia]] on 9 June is not from [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 370]], a [[Boeing 777]] missing since [[2014 in aviation#March|March 2014]] with 239 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/22/asia/mh370-debris-kangaroo-island-atsb/index.html|title=Officials: Australian plane debris not from MH370|first=Ben |last=Westcott|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n;23 June\n* Airstrikes combine with [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] attacks to kill eight people in Aleppo, Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/939c655a16c9442b8229e7602426923b/shelling-and-airstrikes-kill-8-syrian-city-aleppo|title=US-backed forces enter IS bastion in Syria amid clashes}}</ref>\n* Flown by Bertrand Piccard, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) lands at Seville Airport in Seville, Spain, completing the 15th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. The nonstop transatlantic flight from John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City, begun on 20 June, covers {{convert|3890.5|mi|km}} in 71&nbsp;hours 8&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|54.7|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}, reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leg 15: New York to Seville|url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-15-from-New_York-to-Seville |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n* An [[Air Serbia]] [[Airbus A330]] lands at John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York City after a nonstop flight from [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], inaugurating the airline's first transatlantic route and Serbia's first nonstop airline service to the United States by a local airline since [[Jat Airways]], the national airline of the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]], discontinued the route in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/06/23/new-airline-us-first-nonstop-serbia-flight-24-years/86281150/|title=USA-Serbia nonstops now flying for first time in 24 years}}</ref>\n* [[Aerom\u00e9xico]] announces that it is suspending service to [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]], due to the complicated economic situation in Venezuela. It is the third airline to halt service to Venezuela. Venezuela's currency controls make it difficult for airlines to convert ticket sales revenue to [[United States dollar]]s to cover their costs of operating in Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/aeromexico-latest-airline-suspend-flights-venezuela-40085608|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;24 June\n* A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman announces that U.S. forces have conducted airstrikes against the Taliban in southern Afghanistan during the previous week. The strikes follow a decision by President Barack Obama earlier in June to expand U.S. airstrikes in Afghanistan to assist Afghan forces in offensive operations against the Taliban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/us-launches-first-airstrikes-against-afghan-taliban/2016/06/24/e96e8c3e-3a29-11e6-af02-1df55f0c77ff_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=24 June 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-june-24-2016/2016/06/24/1533bf98-3a15-11e6-9ccd-d6005beac8b3_story.html|title=World Digest: June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;25 June\n* Airstrikes reportedly made by Russian planes kill at least 30 people in the Islamic State-held town of [[Qourieh]] in Syria's [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]]. One report puts the death toll a 46.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/6b87ecb1cf54418594d5cd231edd088d/hundreds-syrian-kurds-flee-held-areas-amid-abductions|title=Hundreds of Syrian Kurds flee IS-held areas amid abductions}}</ref>\n\n;26 June\n* A [[National Army of Colombia]] [[Mil Mi-17]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter crashes in mountainous terrain in [[Caldas Department]] in central [[Colombia]], killing all 17 people on board. Its wreckage is not found until the following day.\n\n;27 June\n* After the crew of [[Singapore Airlines Flight 368]], a [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777-312ER]] (registration 9V-SWB), sees an oil leak warning for its right engine two hours into a flight from [[Singapore Changi Airport]], [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], to [[Milan\u2013Malpensa Airport]], [[Ferno]], [[Italy]], the crew opts to return to Singapore Changi. Upon landing there, the right engine catches fire, and the fire quickly engulfs the entire right wing. It is extinguished in five minutes, and none of the 241 people on board are injured. \n* [[President of Turkey|Turkish president]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] sends an apology in writing to [[President of Russia|Russian president]] [[Vladimir Putin]] for the [[Turkish Air Force]]'s downing of a Russian Federation Air Force aircraft over Syria in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-apologizes-for-shooting-down-russian-warplane-last-year/2016/06/27/d969e0ea-3c6d-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Turkish president apologizes for downing of Russian warplane last year}}</ref>\n\n;28 June\n* A three-person suicide team armed with [[Kalashnikov rifle]]s and [[suicide bomb]]s attacks the international terminal at [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]] in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], blowing themselves up in the terminal's arrival and departure areas and in a nearby parking lot. The attack kills at least 44 people and injures more than 230 others. All flights into and out of the airport are temporarily suspended after the attack, and the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration temporarily grounds all flights to and from Istanbul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36658187|title=Istanbul Ataturk airport attack: 41 dead and more than 230 hurt|date=29 June 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/turkey-ataturk-airport-attack-explosions-gunfire-latest-a7108241.html|title=Dozens killed after suicide bombers attack airport in Istanbul|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=cunningham20160629>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-urges-world-to-stand-firm-against-terrorism-after-airport-carnage/2016/06/29/6457228c-3d70-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Turkey and the Islamic State appear to be headed toward outright war}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkish-police-conduct-raids-on-suspected-islamic-state-hideouts-after-deadly-airport-attack/2016/06/30/2b91d61a-3e5e-11e6-9e16-4cf01a41decb_story.html|title=Istanbul airport attackers identified as Russian, Uzbek and Kyrgyz nationals}}</ref>\n\n;29 June\n* Iran announces that it has suspended all commercial flights to Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport.<ref name=cunningham20160629/>\n* After a nonstop transatlantic flight from [[Marine Corps Air Station Beaufort]], [[South Carolina]], three Lockheed Martin F-35B Lightning II aircraft arrive at [[RAF Fairford]] in the [[United Kingdom]], making the first landing in the United Kingdom by any variant of the F-35. A [[Royal Air Force]] F-35B lands first, followed by two [[United States Marine Corps]] F-35Bs that accompanied it on the flight. Supporting the flight are two [[United States Air Force]] [[McDonnell Douglas KC-10 Extender|KC-10A Extender]] tankers, a U.S. Marine Corps [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|KC-130J Super Hercules]] tanker, and a Royal Air Force C-130J Super Hercules [[search-and-rescue]] plane.<ref name=aeroresource20160629>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeroresource.co.uk/news/f-35-arrives-uk/|title=First F-35 Lightning IIs arrive in United Kingdom \u2013 AeroResource}}</ref>\n\n;29\u201330 June (overnight)\n* U.S. and British planes and Iraqi planes and [[attack helicopters]] attack two large [[convoy]]s of ground vehicles carrying Islamic State combatant personnel and their families attempting to flee Fallujah, Iraq. The strikes destroy at least 150 vehicles and kill about 250 people; the Iraqi armed forces claim that the strikes destroy 798 vehicles including eight [[car bomb]]s and kill hundreds of Islamic State combat personnel, with the U.S.-led coalition responsible for 117 of the vehicles and three of the car bombs and Iraqi aircraft destroying the rest. A spokesman for the U.S.-led coalition says that coalition aircraft attempted to avoid striking portions of the convoys it thought included civilians. The U.S. aircraft participating in the attack had been called away from supporting Syrian rebel forces attempting to capture [[Bukamal]], Syria, from the Islamic State and, lacking air support, the Syrian rebels are defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/06/30/iraqi-gunships-u-s-jets-target-islamic-state-convoys-outside-fallujah-and-ramadi/|title=Iraqi, U.S. aircraft bomb convoy of Islamic State fighters fleeing Fallujah with their families}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/07/06/u-s-jets-abandoned-syrian-rebels-in-the-desert-then-they-lost-a-battle-to-isis/|title=U.S. jets abandoned Syrian rebels in the desert. Then they lost a battle to ISIS.}}</ref>\n\n;30 June\n* [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Ashton Carter]] announces that earlier in the week the United States offered to share intelligence with Russia to improve Russian targeting of terrorist groups in Syria if Russia agrees to cease airstrikes against civilians and against rebel groups that have agreed to a ceasefire and to use its influence with the [[Government of Syria]] to force the regime of [[Bashar al-Assad]] to sign on to the ceasefire. The United States offer does not include joint military planning, joint targeting, or coordination of Russian airstrikes with U.S. airstrikes or other U.S. operations in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-offers-to-share-syria-intelligence-on-terrorists-with-russia/2016/06/30/483a2afe-3eec-11e6-84e8-1580c7db5275_story.html|title=U.S. offers to share Syria intelligence on terrorists with Russia}}</ref>\n* U.S. Air Force F-35 Lightning II aircraft deploy outside the United States for the first time when three F-35A aircraft of the [[56th Fighter Wing]] land at RAF Fairford in the United Kingdom after a nonstop transatlantic flight supported by a U.S. Air Force KC-10A Extender tanker.<ref name=aeroresource20160629/>\n\n===July===\n*[[Tunisair]] inaugurates its first [[Transatlantic flight|transatlantic]] service, operating between [[Tunis]] and [[Montreal]].\n\n;1 July\n* A U.S. airstrike in southern [[Yemen]] kills two members of [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=ap20160708>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5f02012d830d4c68aeeb14898b6b5fd9/us-says-2-drone-strikes-yemen-killed-4-al-qaida-members|title=US Central Command: 2 Yemen strikes kill 4 al-Qaida members}}</ref>\n* A [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] fighter aircraft crashes near [[Jeiroud]] in a rebel-held part of [[Syria]] during what the [[Government of Syria]] claims was a training flight. Rebels capture and interrogate its pilot, then shoot him to death.<ref name=Issa20160702>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ae6ef8f5175547e6909af374791bc168/airstrikes-kill-25-opposition-area-near-syrian-capital|title=Syrian activists say airstrikes on rebel-held area kill 25}}</ref>\n* A Russian [[Ministry of Emergency Situations (Russia)|Ministry of Emergency Situations]] [[Ilyushin Il-76]] [[aerial firefighting]] plane (registration RA-76840) [[2016 Ministry of Emergency Situations fire fighting Il-76 crash|crashes]] in the [[Kachugskiy District]] near [[Lake Baikal]] in [[Russia]] while fighting a [[forest fire]], killing all 10 people on board. Its wreckage will be found on 3 July.\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] releases a report claiming that between 2009 and the end of 2015 the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] and the [[United States armed forces]] have carried out a combined 473 airstrikes using [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (or \"drones\") against terrorist targets in countries where it defines the [[United States]] as not being at war \u2013 not named in the report, but including [[Libya]], [[Pakistan]], [[Somalia]], and [[Yemen]] \u2013 killing between 2,372 and 2,581 \"combatants\" and inadvertently killing between 64 and 116 civilians. The report excludes deaths in [[Afghanistan]], [[Iraq]], and [[Syria]], which are countries in which the administration deems the [[United States]] to be at war. Critics of the report claim that it underestimates civilian casualties; the [[Long War Journal]] puts the civilian death toll at 212, the [[New America Foundation]] estimates it at 219, and the [[Bureau of Investigative Journalism]] claims it is at least 325.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/white-house-releases-its-count-of-civilian-deaths-in-counterterrorism-operations-under-obama/2016/07/01/3196aa1e-3fa2-11e6-80bc-d06711fd2125_story.html|title=White House releases its count of civilian deaths in counterterrorism operations under Obama}}</ref>\n\n;2 July\n* [[State of Israel|Israeli]] aircraft strike four [[Hamas]] training sites in the [[Gaza Strip]], damaging buildings but harming no one. The strike is in response to a rocket attack against Israel from the Gaza Strip the previous day that damaged an empty [[kindergarten]] building without killing or injuring anyone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_ISRAEL_PALESTINIANS?SITE=AP|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held Jeiroud, Syria \u2013 suspected of being Syrian government strikes conducted in retaliation for the kiliing of a captured Syrian Arab Air Force pilot by rebels in the area the previous day \u2013 kill at least 25 people. One report puts the overall death toll at 31, and another report claims that seven medical personnel are among those killed in at least 40 air attacks against the town during the day.<ref name=Issa20160702/>\n\n;3 July\n* Airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition support an offensive by U.S.-backed Syrian rebel forces against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] positions near [[Manbij]], Syria, but the Islamic State succeeds in repelling the rebel attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-july-3-2016/2016/07/03/a670d282-411f-11e6-88d0-6adee48be8bc_story.html|title=World Digest: July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;4 July\n* China protests the \"provocative actions\" of two [[Japan Air Self-Defense Force]] fighter aircraft on [[2016 in aviation#June|17 June]] when they intercepted two Chinese fighters over the [[East China Sea]] near the Japanese-controlled [[Senkaku Islands]] (called the Diaoyu Islands in China), claiming that the Chinese fighters were on a routine patrol when the Japanese aircraft locked onto them with [[fire control radar]] and adding that the Chinese planes took \"tactical measures\" before the Japanese aircraft left the area.<ref name=\"ap20160705\"/><ref name=rajagopalan20160704>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-japan-idUSKCN0ZL28B|title=China criticizes Japan over 'dangerous' jet scramble|date=5 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* A U.S. airstrike in Yemen's [[Shabwa Governorate]] kills two members of Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula.<ref name=ap20160708/>\n\n;5 July\n* [[Japan]] denies that its aircraft engaged in any provocative or dangerous activities while intercepting two Chinese fighters over the East China Sea on 17 June, adding that its aircraft scrambled to intercept Chinese military aircraft about 200 times between 1 April and 30 June 2016, up from about 80 times during the same period in [[2015 in aviation|2015]].<ref name=\"ap20160705\"/><ref name=rajagopalan20160704/>\n\n;7 July\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] announces that it has tentatively awarded eight U.S. airlines \u2013 out of 12 that applied for them \u2013 nonstop flights between the [[United States]] and [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], with the awards to be finalized at the end of July and service to begin during the autumn of 2016. The flights are: [[Alaska Airlines]] from [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[American Airlines]] from [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]], and [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]; [[Delta Airlines]] from [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], Miami, and [[New York City]]'s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]; [[Frontier Airlines]] from Miami; [[JetBlue]] from [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]] and [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], Florida, and John F. Kennedy International; [[Southwest Airlines]] from Fort Lauderdale and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida; [[Spirit Airlines]] from Fort Lauderdale; and [[United Airlines]] from [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]], and [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]]. The flights will provide the first scheduled commercial air service between the United States and Havana since the early 1960s. Among rejected routes is a proposed United Airlines service from [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/eight-us-airlines-will-fly-between-american-cities-and-havana/2016/07/07/8184c5a8-4464-11e6-bc99-7d269f8719b1_story.html|title=Eight U.S. airlines will fly between American cities and Havana}}</ref>\n\n;8 July\n* On the last day of a three-day ceasefire declared by the [[Syrian Arab Army]] but widely violated, unidentified jets belonging to either the Syrian Arab Air Force or the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] strike rebel-held [[Darkush]], Syria \u2013 a vacation spot for Syrians \u2013 during the [[Eid al-Fitr]] holiday weekend, killing at least 23 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-idlib-idUKKCN0ZO1BZ|title=Almost 50 killed in Syria on ceasefire's last day: monitor|first=Reuters|last=Editorial}}</ref>\n* Islamic State forces shoot down a helicopter near [[Palmyra]], Syria, killing two Russian pilots on board. Russia claims the helicopter was a Syrian [[Mil Mi-25]] helicopter the Russians were flying on a training mission when they were diverted to take action against an Islamic State ground attack, which they thwarted before they were shot down by a U.S.-made [[BGM-71 TOW]] missile. News reports and independent experts, however, claim that the downed helicopter actually was a [[Mil Mi-35|Mil Mi-35M]] [[attack helicopter]] belonging to the Russian armed forces and operating on a combat mission, and that whatever shot it down was very unlikely to have been a BGM-71 TOW.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/12/russia-just-lied-about-losing-a-gunship-to-isis-heres-why-thats-not-surprising/|title=Russia may have lied about losing a gunship to ISIS}}</ref>\n\n;9 July\n* A U.S. air-to-ground missile strike by an unmanned aerial vehicle in [[Afghanistan]] targeting members of the [[Islamic State-Khorasan Province]] group kills five [[Islamist]] militants including Umar Narai, also known as Khalifa Umar Mansoor, a leader of the [[Tariq Gidar Group]] who masterminded a [[2014 Peshawar school massacre|2014 attack]] by the [[Pakistani Taliban]] on a school in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]], that killed 148 people and injured 114.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-taliban-idUSKCN0ZT21O|title=Pakistan says leader of school attack killed in U.S. drone strike|date=14 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* Supported by airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition, Iraqi ground forces recapture [[Qayyarah Airfield West|Qayyarah Air Base]] in the [[Qayyarah subdistrict]] of [[Mosul District]] in [[Nineveh Governorate]], Iraq, from the Islamic State. The commander of Iraqi counterterrorism forces credits the coalition airstrikes with destroying 60 Islamic State car bombs. With a runway capable of handling heavy cargo planes and room for many helicopters, the newly captyured air base promises to allow the support of further Iraqi advances into Islamic State-held territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/07/11/seizure-of-key-air-base-near-mosul-raises-prospect-of-u-s-escalation-against-isis/|title=Pentagon will send hundreds more troops to Iraq following seizure of key airfield}}</ref>\n* Using a plane chartered by the [[World Food Programme]], the [[United Nations]] begins an airlift of humanitarian aid to an estimated 275,000 people in Syria's [[Al-Hasakah Governorate]] who have been cut off from food and other supplies for six months. The first flight delivers 40 [[metric ton]]s of food, arriving during the evening at [[Kamishly Airport]] in [[Qamishli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/airlifts-food-cut-off-families-northeast-syria-40470850|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref> Plans call for the plane to make at least 25 flights between [[Damascus]], Syria, and Qamishli over the course of a month, delivering over 1,000 metric tons of food, medicine, and other relief supplies to Kamishly Airport.<ref>[http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/wfp-flight-delivers-40-tonnes-food-in-syria-2016-07-11-1.635371 Wam, \"WFP flight delivers 40 tonnes food in Syria,\" emirates247.com, 11 July 2016.]</ref>\n\n;10 July\n* Syrian government air raids strike a rebel-held neighborhood in [[Aleppo]] and a [[diesel fuel]] market in [[Turmanin]]. The Aleppo strike reportedly kills 10 people, while the air raids on Turmanin set several [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] on fire and kill at least eight and perhaps as many as 14 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/7292729de44a4616af8bf27f1b41b616/air-raids-hit-diesel-market-syria-killing-8|title=More fighting in Syria's Aleppo, Idlib kills at least 26}}</ref>\n* In a briefing ahead of the opening of the [[Farnborough International Airshow]], the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Boeing]]'s commercial aircraft unit, Ray Conner, says that his company is seeing strong interest among airlines in a new mid-range airliner that could seat between 200 and 270 passengers and have a range of between {{convert|4500|and|5100|nmi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}}, creating a new, larger market beyond that of the [[Boeing 757]] and [[Airbus A321neo]]. The first all-new Boeing aircraft since the [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]], the new airliner would cost $10,000,000,000 to $15,000,000,000 to develop and be the company's biggest potential product development over the next 10 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-10/boeing-sees-airline-thirst-for-new-mid-range-jetliner-family|title=Boeing Sees Airline Thirst for New Mid-Range Jetliner Family|date=10 July 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;11 July\n* With [[Andr\u00e9 Borschberg]] at the controls, ''[[Solar Impulse 2]]'' (registration HB-SIB) departs [[Seville Airport]] in [[Seville]], [[Spain]], to begin the 16th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for the two-day nonstop solo flight to [[Cairo International Airport]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to pass over the [[Mediterranean Sea]], [[Tunisia]], [[Algeria]], [[Malta]], [[Italy]], and [[Greece]].<ref name=solar16>{{cite web|title=Leg 16: Seville to Cairo |url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-16-from-Seville-to-Cairo |publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n*A [[Portuguese Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] transport aircraft crashes just after takeoff from [[Montijo Air Base]], [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]], killing its entire three-man crew.<ref name=airlive20160711>{{cite web|url=http://www.airlive.net/breaking-a-lockheed-c-130-hercules-just-crashed-in-portugal/|title=BREAKING A Lockheed C-130 Hercules started to burn on take off from Portugal - AIRLIVE.net|first=Melanie|last=Kraft}}</ref>\n\n;12 July\n* [[Fedor Konyukhov]] departs [[Northam, Western Australia|Northam]], [[Western Australia]], to begin an attempt to circumnavigate the world solo in a [[hot-air balloon]]. He will complete the journey on 23 July.<ref name=Aljazeera20160724>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/07/fedor-konyukhov-breaks-world-hot-air-balloon-record-160723101753237.html|title=Fedor Konyukhov breaks world hot air balloon record}}</ref>\n* After nearly 45 years, the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] announces it has closed its investigation of the [[1971 in aviation#November|24 November 1971]] hijacking of Northwest Airlines Flight 305 by a man identifying himself as \"Dan Cooper\" \u2013 and misidentified by the press as \"[[D. B. Cooper]],\" the name by which he goes down in history \u2013 who parachuted from the airliner with $200,000 he had demanded and was never seen or heard from again. The \"D. B. Cooper\" skyjacking is the only unsolved American [[aircraft hijacking]] case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2016/07/12/the-d-b-cooper-case-has-baffled-the-fbi-for-45-years-now-it-may-never-be-solved/|title=The D.B. Cooper case has baffled the FBI for 45 years. Now it may never be solved.}}</ref>\n\n;13 July\n* The day after the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]] ruled against the [[People's Republic of China]] in ''[[Philippines vs. China]]'' regarding a [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|territorial dispute]] with the [[Philippines]] in the [[South China Sea]], two Chinese civilian aircraft fly to Chinese-claimed islands in the South China Sea, one each landing at [[Mischief Reef]] and [[Subi Reef]]. Both return to China later in the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/china-faces-dilemma-after-ruling-double-down-or-cool-down/2016/07/13/7ae5edfc-486b-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Beijing\u2019s dilemma after South China Sea ruling: Double down or cool down?}}</ref>\n* An airstrike hits a market in rebel-held [[Ariha, Syria|Ariha]], Syria, killing at least nine and perhaps as many as 12 people. Another airstrike targeting a market in rebel-held [[Al-Rastan]], Syria, kills reportedly kills 16 people and wounds dozens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b1d44e6217aa4c98bda824a5d3155b8b/air-raids-northern-and-central-syria-kill-and-wound-many|title=Air raids in northern and central Syria kill and wound many}}</ref>\n* Flown by Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) lands at Cairo International Airport in Cairo, Egypt, completing the 16th leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. The nonstop flight from Seville Airport in Seville, Spain, began on 11 July and passes over the Mediterranean Sea and portions of southern [[Europe]] and [[North Africa]], covering {{convert|2326|mi|km}} in 48&nbsp;hours 50&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|45.8|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}. ''Solar Impulse 2'' passes over the [[Giza pyramid complex]] before landing at Cairo International.<ref name=solar16/>\n* At a meeting of the [[NATO-Russia Council]], Russian diplomats propose to the representatives of [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO) member countries that all aircraft flying over the [[Baltic Sea]] do so with their [[Transponder (aeronautics)|transponders]] on as a way of improving air safety. Although NATO requires all aircraft flown under its command to fly with their transponders on, the aircraft of NATO member countries do not always turn them on when flying separately from NATO control, and Russian aircraft also have flown with them off. The NATO representatives welcome the proposal and promise to study it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-vents-anger-over-natos-latest-moves/2016/07/13/37404e7c-48fb-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Russia offers plan to improve air safety over Baltics}}</ref>\n* Citing a need to strike back against those responsible for terrorist attacks in [[France]] in [[January 2015 \u00cele-de-France attacks|January 2015]] and [[November 2015 Paris attacks|November 2015]], [[President of France]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] announces that the [[French Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91)|Charles de Gaulle]]'' will deploy to the [[Middle East]] to participate in operations against the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0ZT276|title=France to deploy aircraft carrier against Islamic State: Hollande |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n;14 July\n* A series of airstrikes on rebel-held districts of Aleppo, Syria, reportedly kill 12 people.<ref name=eldeeb20160714>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-07-13-13-30-30|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* The Islamic State reportedly shoots down a Syrian Arab Air Force jet near the military airport at [[Deir ez-Zor]], Syria, killing its pilot. The Islamic State releases a video purportedly showing the pilot's body strung up on a pole, and the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] reports that his body had been [[Crucifixion|crucifed]].<ref name=eldeeb20160714/>\n* [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] meets in [[Moscow]] with [[President of Russia]] [[Vladimir Putin]] to discuss a U.S. proposal supported by senior [[United Nations]] officials to \"integrate\" U.S. and Russian air operations against Islamic State and [[Jabhat al-Nusra]] targets in Syria and halt Syrian government and Russian air attacks against civilians and moderate Syrian rebel forces that are parties to a widely violated February 2016 ceasefire agreement. The proposal calls for Russia to pressure the Syrian government to ground all Syrian military aircraft and restrict Russian airstrikes to Islamic State and Jabhat al-Nusra targets, and for U.S. airstrikes against Jabhat al-Nusra \u2013 previously conducted only rarely to avoid direct U.S. involvement in the [[Syrian Civil War]] \u2013 to expand alongside strikes against Islamic State targets in Syria. Under the proposal, Russia and the United States \u2013 via a Joint Implementation Group headquartered in [[Amman]], [[Jordan]] \u2013 would share intelligence and strike planning for Jabhat al-Nusra leadership targets, headquarters, training camps, logistical depots, and supply lines, with other areas off-limits to airstrikes by either country, and a \"liaison body\" would ensure that Russia and the United States inform one another at least a day in advance of planned strikes against agreed-upon targets. The proposal calls for implementation of an agreement by 31 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/kerry-says-iran-deal-has-made-world-a-safer-place-one-year-later/2016/07/14/a954071c-484f-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=Kerry arrives in Moscow with a proposal for Syria in hand}}</ref> The following day, Kerry and [[Foreign Minister of Russia]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announce after day-long talks that the two countries have reached an agreement that could reduce civilian casualties and improve targeting of terrorist groups, but they reveal no details to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-and-russia-have-plan-to-quell-conflict-in-syria-but-wont-say-what-it-is/2016/07/15/4cfb6a72-4850-11e6-8dac-0c6e4accc5b1_story.html|title=U.S. and Russia have plan to quell conflict in Syria but won\u2019t say what it is}}</ref>\n* [[Airbus]] and [[Boeing]] experience their lowest airliner sales totals at the [[Farnborough Air Show]] in six years, securing deals for about 400 aircraft worth about $50,000,000,000, only half their sales at the previous year's show. American, European, and [[Persian Gulf]] carriers make almost no deals, and only carriers in [[Asia]] make large orders. No orders materialize for the [[Boeing 777]], [[Airbus A330neo]], or [[Bombardier C-Series]], and [[Airbus A380]] production rates are greatly reduced. Industry analysts blame the reduced sales on uncertainty over the future of the global economy and on the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|23 June 2016 vote]] to leave the [[European Union]], popularly known as the \"Brexit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-14/air-show-pop-fizzles-as-airbus-boeing-orders-at-six-year-low|title=Air-Show Pop Fizzles as Airbus, Boeing Orders at Six-Year Low|date=14 July 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n;15\u201316 July (overnight)\n* A group of military officers in [[Turkey]] \u2013 mostly from the [[Turkish Air Force]], [[Turkish Army]] armored forces, and police and security organizations \u2013 [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|attempts a ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']] against the government of [[President of Turkey|President]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]. In [[Ankara]], [[Esenbo\u011fa International Airport]] closes. In [[G\u00f6lba\u015f\u0131, Ankara|G\u00f6lba\u015f\u0131]], just outside Ankara, pro-''coup'' military helicopters attack the police special forces headquarters, the police air force headquarters, and the headquarters of [[T\u00fcrksat (company)|T\u00fcrksat]], leaving 42 dead and 43 injured. Pro-''coup'' helicopters also attack the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|parliament]] building in Ankara; the [[Government of Turkey|Turkish government]] declares a [[no-fly zone]] over the city and a pro-government Turkish Air Force [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]] shoots down a pro-''coup'' helicopter in the area. In [[Istanbul]], pro-''coup'' military forces move into [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]], forcing it to close and all flights there to be cancelled, and [[Turkish Air Force]] jets fly low over the city, generating [[sonic boom]]s. In [[Marmaris]], two or three helicopters attack a hotel where Erdo\u011fan had been vacationing and discharge troops who exchange gunfire with police officers, killing two and injuring eight of the police. At [[Incirlik Air Base]], from which [[United States Air Force]] aircraft are operating as part of the [[American-led intervention in Syria]], authorities close all access and cut power to the base, but normal operations there are restored within 24 hours. The ''coup'' attempt soon is defeated, and one Turkish military [[Black Hawk helicopter]], escorted by [[Hellenic Air Force]] F-16s, makes an emergency landing at [[Alexandroupoli Airport]] in [[Alexandroupoli]], [[Greece]], where Greek authorities arrests its eight occupants \u2013 who request [[political asylum]] \u2013 for making an illegal landing; their helicopter is returned to Turkey on 17 July.\n\n;17 July\n* [[Israel]] fires two [[MIM-104 Patriot]] [[surface-to-air missile]]s at an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) that flies from Syria into airspace over the Israeli-controlled [[Golan Heights]]. The UAV turns away and flies back into Syria.<ref name=reuters20160717>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-syria-interception-idUSKCN0ZX0OR|title=Israel launches anti-aircraft missiles at Syrian drone: army|date=17 July 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* According to Syrian rebels, the Syrian military conducts a rare air raid along the border with [[Jordan]], striking the village of al-Shajara, Syria, held by [[Shuhada al-Yarmouk]], group thought to be aligned with [[al-Qaeda]].<ref name=reuters20160717/>\n* Libyan militia forces fighting against the [[United Nations]]-backed [[Government of Libya]] shoot down a French helicopter in [[Libya]], killing three French soldiers on board. On 19 July, the Libyan government will announce that the helicopter had been shot down by an [[Islamist]] militia; on 20 July the [[Government of France]] will make its first public admission that French [[special forces]] are operating in Libya, and President of France Fran\u00e7ois Hollande will announce that the three dead soldiers were carrying out \"dangerous intelligence operations\" when their helicopter was shot down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36843186|title=Libya attack: French soldiers die in helicopter crash|date=20 July 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*An experienced pilot is killed after crashing while performing at an airshow in [[Cold Lake, Alberta]], [[Canada]]. He was flying a [[North American T-28 Trojan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/experienced-pilot-dies-after-plane-crashes-at-cold-lake-air-show-1.3683081|title=Pilot Bruce Evans dead after plane crash at Cold Lake Air Show}}</ref>\n\n;18 July\n* Airstrikes against Islamic State-held areas in Syria by the U.S.-led coalition kill 15 people in [[Manbij]] and six people in nearby [[Tokhar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/article/6783267/2016/07/18/coalition-raids-kill-21-civilians-syria|title=Anonymous, \"Coalition raids kill 21 civilians in Syria,\" Agence France-Presse, July 18, 2016, 11:05 a.m.}}</ref> [[United States Central Command]] announces that during the day the coalition conducted 18 airstrikes, destroying 13 Islamic State fighting positions, two car bombs, and seven other Islamic State ground vehicles.<ref name=mroue20160719>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-activists-airstrikes-on-is-held-villages-in-syria-kill-56-2016-7|title=Activists: Airstrikes on IS-held villages in Syria kill 56}}</ref>\n* The pilot and copilot of [[Air Transat]] Flight 725, an [[Airbus A310]] with about 250 passengers on board, are arrested at [[Glasgow Airport]] for being drunk as they prepare to fly the aircraft from [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], to [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. The airline suspends them the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/19/pilots-arrested-glasgow-toronto-flight-suspicion-too-drunk-to-fly|title=Pilots arrested on suspicion of being too drunk to take Glasgow-Toronto flight|first=Press|last=Association|date=19 July 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/air-transat-pilots-arrest-1.3684955 Lupton, Andrew, and Errol Nazareth, \"2 Air Transat pilots charged with being impaired before Glasgow to Toronto flight\", ''CBC News'', 19 July 2016, 6:41 AM EDT.]</ref>\n* After launching a [[Dragon spacecraft]], the first stage of a [[SpaceX]] [[Falcon 9]] rocket returns to make a soft landing at the [[Kennedy Space Center]] in [[Cape Canaveral, Florida|Cape Canaveral]], [[Florida]], landing about eight minutes after liftoff. It is only the second time a Falcon 9 first stage has made a successful landing on land, and it is the first such landing since [[2015 in aviation#December|21 December 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2016/07/18/spacex-sends-supplies-to-space-station-lands-another-falcon-rocket/|title=SpaceX sends supplies to space station, lands another Falcon rocket \u2013 Spaceflight Now|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref>\n* The [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] agrees to pay 2.6 million [[euro]]s to the relatives of Italian aid worker Giovanni Lo Porto, who was mistakenly killed in a [[Central Intelligence Agency]] unmanned aerial vehicle strike in Pakistan in [[2015 in aviation#January|January 2015]]. On 16 September 2016, [[United States Government]] officials will confirm the settlement publicly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-agrees-to-pay-nearly-3-million-to-family-of-italian-killed-in-cia-strike/2016/09/16/5c213af6-7c1a-11e6-bd86-b7bbd53d2b5d_story.html|title=U.S. agrees to pay nearly $3 million to family of Italian killed in CIA strike}}</ref>\n\n;19 July\n* The U.S.-led coalition strikes Islamic State-held territory in northern Syria to help counter an Islamic State ground offensive against the U.S.-backed [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF). According to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights, 56 civilians die in the strikes, while other reports put the death toll as high as 212; for example, the Islamic State claims that U.S. strikes kill 160 civilians in Tokhar, and the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates (Syria)|Syrian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Expatriates]] claims a strike by French aircraft against Tokhar kills 120 civilians. An SDF spokesman disputes the claims of civilian deaths, saying that the strikes have killed large numbers of Islamic State personnel, and that the Islamic State has simply buried them quickly and falsely claimed that civilian deaths have occurred.<ref name=mroue20160719/> The U.S. military announces that U.S. aircraft have conducted 18 strikes in the Manbij area over the previous 24 hours \u2013 out of 450 in the area since [[2016 in aviation#May|May]] \u2013 and that it is launching an investigation to determine whether the allegations of civilian casualties are true.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/scores-of-civilians-killed-in-suspected-us-strikes-in-syria/2016/07/19/0246d5e0-89a4-458a-9c50-50095c9a12d9_story.html|title=Suspected U.S. airstrikes in Syria kill scores of civilians, activists say}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/21/an-airstrike-in-syria-killed-entire-families-instead-of-isis-fighters/|title=An airstrike in Syria killed entire families instead of ISIS fighters}}</ref> By late August, [[United States Central Command]] will report that it has concluded that the Tokhar strike \u2013 conducted by U.S. Air Force [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]] and [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52H Stratofortress]] aircraft using 500-pound (227-kg) [[GBU-31]] and [[GBU-54]] [[laser-guided bomb]]s to knock out a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] position \u2013 killed 85 Islamic militants and 10 civilians, while Syrian activists claim that all or most of the 95 dead were civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-500-pound-bombs-struck-their-targets-in-a-syrian-village-but-whom-did-they-kill/2016/08/26/30324884-649d-11e6-be4e-23fc4d4d12b4_story.html|title=500-pound bombs struck their targets in a Syrian village. But who was killed?}}</ref> \n* Since the U.S.-led coalition's air campaign in Iraq and Syria against the Islamic State began in [[2014 in aviation#August|August 2014]], U.S. aircraft have carried out over 10,500 strikes and the rest of the coalition combined has conducted 3,200.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-assembles-allied-nations-to-plot-out-next-stage-of-islamic-state-fight/2016/07/19/5adf337c-4da9-11e6-aa14-e0c1087f7583_story.html|title=Pentagon assembles allied nations to plot out next stage of Islamic State fight}}</ref>\n;20 July\n* A [[network router]] fails in [[Southwest Airlines]]\u2032 computer system and back-up systems fail to activate, causing a 12-hour outage that cripples the airline's flight operations throughout the [[United States]]. Normal operations will not resume fully until 24 July, by which time Southwest will have cancelled about 2,300 of the approximately 19,500 flights scheduled during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20160725-2300-canceled-flights-later-southwest-airlines-recovers-from-technical-outage.ece|title=2,300 canceled flights later, Southwest Airlines recovers from technical outage  \u2013 Southwest Airlines \u2013 Dallas News|date=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n;22 July\n* An [[Indian Air Force]] [[Antonov An-32]] with 29 people on board [[2016 Indian Air Force An-32 disappearance|disappears]] over the [[Bay of Bengal]] during a flight from [[Tambaram]], [[India]], to [[Port Blair]] in the [[Andaman Islands]].\n\n;23 July\n* [[Fedor Konyukhov]] lands near [[Bonnie Rock, Western Australia|Bonnie Rock]], [[Western Australia]], setting a new world record for the fastest around-the-world flight in a [[hot-air balloon]] and becoming the second person in history \u2013 after [[Steve Fossett]] in [[2002 in aviation|2002]] \u2013 to pilot a [[Balloon (aircraft)|balloon]] around the world solo. He also sets a new speed record for an around-the-world balloon flight, completing it in 11 days, breaking the record Fossett set during his 2002 flight by two days. Departing Northam, Western Australia, on 12 July, he has flown over [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], the [[Pacific Ocean]], [[South America]], the [[Cape of Good Hope]] and the [[Southern Ocean]] before landing at Bonnie Rock, covering a distance of {{convert|34820|km|mi|abbr=on}} and reaching altitudes of {{convert|10000|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=Aljazeera20160724/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/jul/24/russian-adventurer-fedor-konyukhov-breaks-record-for-flying-solo-around-the-world|title=Russian adventurer Fedor Konyukhov breaks record for flying solo around the world|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=23 July 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n;23\u201324 July (overnight)\n* Syrian government airstrikes hit five medical clinics in Syria's [[Aleppo Governorate]] \u2013 four in Aleppo and one in [[Atarib]] \u2013 and a [[blood bank]] in Aleppo. The strikes kill at least five people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/07/24/world/middleeast/ap-ml-syria.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Intense Airstrikes in Syria's Aleppo Province Hit 5 Clinics,\" Associated Press, July 24, 2016, 12:51 P.M. EDT.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/07/syria-civil-war-airstrikes-hit-aleppo-hospitals-160724090834185.html|title=Syria civil war: Air strikes hit Aleppo hospitals}}</ref>\n\n;24 July\n* Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) departs [[Cairo International Airport]] in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], to begin the 17th and final leg of its attempt to become the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Plans call for a two-day nonstop solo flight to [[Al Bateen Executive Airport]] in [[Abu Dhabi]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]], where the journey had begun on [[2015 in aviation#March|9 March 2015]].<ref name=solar17>{{cite web|title=Leg 17: Cairo to Abu Dhabi |url= http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-17-from-Cairo-to-Abu_Dhabi|publisher=Solar Impulse}}</ref>\n\n;25 July\n* The U.S. [[Environmental Protection Agency]] issues an \"endangerment finding\" \u2013  a scientific assessment describing a danger to the environment \u2013 that determines that emissions from commercial airplane engines including [[carbon dioxide]], [[methane]], and [[nitrous oxide]] pose health risks to Americans and contribute to [[climate change]]. It is a first step in what could be a years-long process leading to the regulation of commercial aircraft engine emissions by the [[United States Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/07/25/white-house-takes-aim-at-a-fast-growing-source-of-emissions-airplanes/|title=White House takes aim at a fast-growing source of emissions: airplanes}}</ref>\n\n;26 July\n* A U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle-launched [[air-to-ground missile]] strike in Afghanistan's [[Nangarhar Province]] kills the Islamic State leader [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]]. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce his death on 12 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/us-drone-strike-killed-islamic-state-leader-afghanistan-41340026|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n* ''Solar Impulse 2'' (registration HB-SIB) becomes the first solar-powered aircraft to fly around the world and the first aircraft to do so without using any fossil fuel. Flown by [[Bertrand Piccard]], it completes the final leg of its journey, flying nonstop from Cairo International Airport in Cairo, Egypt, to Al Bateen Executive Airport in Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates \u2013 where its round-the-world flight had begun on [[2015 in aviation#March|9 March 2015]] \u2013 covering {{convert|1673|mi|km}} in 48&nbsp;hours 37&nbsp;minutes at an average speed of {{convert|34.4|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|27999|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref>[http://www.solarimpulse.com/leg-17-from-Cairo-to-Abu_Dhabi \"We Are in Abu Dhabi\"], Solar Impulse, 26 July 2016</ref> Flown alternately by Piccard and Andr\u00e9 Borschberg, ''Solar Impulse 2'' has made the {{convert|42428|km|abbr=on}} trip in 17 legs over 505&nbsp;days, spending 558&nbsp;hours 7&nbsp;minutes in the air at an average speed of {{convert|47.2|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and reaching a maximum altitude of {{convert|29114|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}.\n\n;28 July\n* Syrian Arab Air Force aircraft drop leaflets over Aleppo, Syria, informing residents that the Government of Syria will allow them to escape the surrounded city via three safe corridors and that rebel soldiers wishing to lay down their arms would be granted safe passage through a fourth corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrias-jabhat-al-nusra-splits-from-al-qaeda-and-changes-its-name/2016/07/28/5b89ad22-54e6-11e6-b652-315ae5d4d4dd_story.html|title=Syria's Jabhat al-Nusra splits from al-Qaeda and changes its name}}</ref>\n\n;29 July \n* According to the [[International Air Transport Association]], commercial air traffic to and from [[Venezuela]] has dropped 30 by percent since the [[Venezuelan bol\u00edvar]] began a steep decline in value in 2013 despite a rapid increase in air travel almost everywhere else in the world. International air carriers have accumulated about $4,000,000,000 in almost worthless bol\u00edvars which the [[Government of Venezuela]] prohibits them from converting into [[hard currency]], prompting various airlines since 2014 \u2013 including [[Aerom\u00e9xico]], [[Air Canada]], [[Alitalia]], [[LATAM]], and [[Lufthansa]] \u2013 to cease service to Venezuela and others to reduce flights or provide service with smaller planes; only Venezuelan airlines are permitted to pay for fuel with bol\u00edvars, all other carriers being required to pay in [[United States dollar]]s. [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport (Venezuela)|Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport]] in [[Caracas]], long a major [[Airline hub|hub]] for airlines serving [[South America]], has been replaced in that role by airports such as [[El Dorado International Airport]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], which now handles three times as many passengers as Caracas, and [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]] in [[Callao]], [[Peru]], which has enjoyed a 35 percent increase in passengers over the previous two years. Caracas has become so dangerous that [[Copa Airlines]] crews are prohibited from leaving their hotel rooms when staying there, massive shipments of [[cocaine]] originating in Caracas have been interdicted in the airport's terminal, and gunfights between police and criminals occur every few months in the airport's parking lots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/29/venezuela-was-once-an-aviation-gateway-to-south-america-now-its-an-outcast/|title=Venezuela was once an aviation gateway to South America. Now it\u2019s an outcast.}}</ref> \n* A medical transport plane crashes in northern California in the [[United States]]. All four people on board the [[Piper PA-31 Navajo]] die.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2857019/small-medical-plane-crashes-in-california-4-killed/|title=Small medical plane crashes in California, 4 killed}}</ref>\n\n;30 July\n* A [[hot-air balloon]] operated by the company Heart of Texas Hot Air Balloon Rides [[2016 Lockhart hot air balloon crash|catches fire and crashes]] in a field in [[Maxwell, Texas|Maxwell]], [[Texas]], killing all 16 people on board. It is the deadliest ballooning accident in U.S. history and the second-deadliest in world history, exceeded only by [[2013 Luxor hot air balloon crash|a hot-air balloon crash]] in [[Egypt]] in [[2013 in aviation#February|February 2013]] that killed 19 people.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\"/><ref name=\"staging.hosted.ap.org\"/>\n* [[Skydiving|Skydiver]] Luke Aikins becomes the first person in history to jump from an airplane into a net on the ground without wearing a [[parachute]]. Jumping from an altitude of {{convert|25000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, he lands safely after a two-minute freefall in a 100-by-100-foot (30.5-meter-by-30.5-meter) net at the [[Big Sky Ranch]] in [[Simi Valley]], California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SKYDIVING_WITHOUT_PARACHUTE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|title=Rodgers, John, \"Skydiver becomes first person to jump and land without chute,\" Associated Press, July 31, 2016, 9:52 AM EDT.}}</ref>\n\n;31 July\n* In response to a rebel offensive attempting to break the Syrian government's [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|siege of Aleppo]], Syria, that begins during the day, helicopters drop barrel bombs on the city's rebel-held neighborhood of Bustan al-Basha. Later in the day, jets \u2013 presumably of the Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force \u2013 bomb rebel-held areas in the eastern part of the city. During the day, people in rebel-held areas of the city burn [[tire]]s to create plumes of black smoke in an attempt to interfere with visibility for attacking aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/syrian-activists-hospital-bombed-daraa-province-132127626.html|title=Anonymous, \"Syrian rebels launch push aimed at breaking Aleppo siege,\" Associated Press, July 31, 2016.}}</ref>\n\n=== August ===\n* During the month, [[Delta Air Lines]] sends a letter of protest to the U.S. [[General Services Administration]], complaining that GSA's award to [[JetBlue Airways]] of the U.S. government contract routes from [[New York City]] to [[Dubai]] and from New York City to [[Milan]], Italy, in 2015 violates the 1981 [[Fly America Act]] \u2013 which requires U.S. federal government employees, their families, and federal consultants and contractors to travel aboard U.S. carriers when on official business paid for by the U.S. government \u2013 because JetBlue has no aircraft that can fly that far and will book its passengers to those destination on its codeshare partner [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], a [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE) airline based in Dubai. Delta joins [[American Airlines]] and [[United Airlines]] in arguing that they should be selected for such routes to reduce the disadvantage they face when competing with Emirates, the UAE's [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[Etihad Airways]], and [[Qatar]]'s [[Qatar Airways]], all of which receive substantial subsidies from their governments. The GSA responds that JetBlue offers cheaper prices that Delta, American, and United and that its selection does not violate the Fly America Act, regardless of its use of foreign codeshare partners for the routes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/latest-skirmish-in-war-to-control-international-travel-has-the-fly-america-act-been-violated/2016/08/30/4c23a380-6e1b-11e6-9705-23e51a2f424d_story.html|title=Latest skirmish in war to control international travel: Has the Fly America Act been violated?}}</ref>\n\n;1 August\n* The [[Government of Singapore]] restructures its Air Accident Investigation Bureau to establish the [[Transport Safety Investigation Bureau]] as an independent government agency responsible for investigating aviation and marine accidents and incidents in [[Singapore]].\n* Syrian rebels shoot down a Russian [[Mil Mi-8]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter in [[Syria]]'s [[Idlib Governorate]] during fighting around [[Aleppo]], Syria, killing all five people on board. [[Russia]] claims the helicopter was returning to its base after delivering a cargo of humanitarian goods to Aleppo. It is the deadliest single incident for the Russian military since it began its intervention in Syria in [[2015 in aviation#September|September 2015]]. Videos show rebels abusing the bodies of the dead Russian crew and passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/S/SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-08-01-16-04-02|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* At the request of [[Libya]]'s [[Government of National Accord]] (GNA), U.S. manned and unmanned military aircraft conduct two strikes against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces in [[Sirte]], Libya, destroying a [[T-72]] [[tank]] and two other ground vehicles. They are the first strikes requested by the GNA and the first direct U.S. military intervention in the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan Civil War]]. [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] approves the strikes, but [[United States Africa Command]] commander [[General (United States)|General]] [[Thomas D. Waldhausen]] receives the authority to approve future strikes. The [[United States Navy]] [[amphibious assault ship]] {{USS|Wasp|LHD-1}} is operating off Libya, carrying [[United States Marine Corps]] [[AV-8B Harrier]] aircraft and helicopters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/01/united-states-strikes-islamic-state-stronghold-in-libya-expands-campaign-against-militant-group/|title=U.S. strikes Islamic State stronghold in Libya, expanding campaign against militant group}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/story/military/war-on-is/2016/08/01/us-air-strikes-sirte-libya-islamic-state/87909908/|title=404|first=Military|last=Times}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n;2 August\n* [[IndiGo]] Flights 6E-813 and 6E-136 \u2013 each with at least 100 people on board \u2013 narrowly avoid a mid-air collision over [[Guwahati]], [[India]], when Flight 6E-813 goes into a steep dive to avoid Flight 6E-136, approaching from the opposite direction, 25 seconds before a likely collision. The emergency maneuver leaves six people on board Flight 6E-813 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mid-air-scare-over-guwahati-as-two-indigo-flights-cross-path/story-Z6Zac1UjMNTohhUiJj6wIL.html|title=Guwahati: Mid-air scare for passengers as two Indigo flights cross path|date=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Airstrikes attributed to the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] or [[Russian Federation Air Force]] kill 11 people in [[Atarib]], Syria. People in rebel-held portions of Aleppo, Syria, burn [[tire]]s to create plumes of dark black smoke in an attempt to interfere with airstrikes.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* The [[United States Air Force]] announces that its first [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]] of [[F-35A Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 the [[34th Fighter Squadron]] at [[Hill Air Force Base]], [[Utah]] \u2013 is combat-ready. The F-35A is the second variant of the F-35 to be declared ready for combat, following the [[United States Marine Corps]]'s F-35B variant. The U.S. Air Force is the largest customer for the F-35, planning to buy 1,763 F-35A aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/breaking-news/2016/08/02/f35-ioc-air-force-operational-acc-combat/87948142/|title=f35-IOC-air-force-operational-ACC-combat|first=Defense|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;3 August\n* After [[air traffic control]] at [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), instructs [[Emirates Flight 521]] \u2013 a [[Boeing 777-300|Boeing 777-31H]] (registration A6-EMW) arriving from [[Thiruvananthapuram]], India \u2013 to abort its landing and conduct a [[go-around]], the airliner instead crashes on the runway and catches fire. All 300 people on board evacuate the airliner with 14 suffering non-life-threating injuries. A firefighter dies during the rescue operation after the crash, and the plane is destroyed by the fire and a series of explosions that follow the evacuation of the passengers and crew; it is the first [[hull loss]] and most serious accident in the airline's history. The airport closes for 5\u00bd hours after the crash, and several incoming flights divert to [[Sharjah International Airport]] outside [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]], UAE, and [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] in [[Jebel Ali]], UAE. Emirates flights experience widespread disruption throughout the airline's system.\n\n;4 August\n* A Pakistani helicopter manned by seven Pakistani [[civil engineer]]s flying from [[Pakistan]] to Russia for routine maintenance crash-lands in [[Afghanistan]]'s [[Logar Province]]. The [[Taliban]] takes either six of its occupants or all seven of them hostage, according to various reports. The [[Pakistan Army]] requests U.S. military assistance in recovering the captured Pakistanis,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-ambush-convoy-with-us-european-tourists-in-afghanistan-injuring-6/2016/08/04/863e68a4-5a37-11e6-9aee-8075993d73a2_story.html|title=Taliban ambushes tourist convoy in west, takes helicopter crew hostage in east}}</ref>\n* [[Amazon.com]] unveils ''Prime One'', a [[Boeing 767]] which is the first of the company's 40 leased cargo planes \u2013 all Boeing 767s \u2013 branded as \"Prime Air,\" a new air cargo service tasked with delivering goods to [[Amazon Prime]] customers. Although Prime Air already is operating 11 of the Prime Air aircraft, ''Prime One'' is the first to operate in Prime Air livery. Its [[Aircraft registration|tail number]], N1997A, is selected as an Amazon prime marketing gimmck because 1997 is a [[prime number]]. ''Prime One'' makes its first flight in the new livery the following day at the [[Seafair]] festival in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. Amazon plan to phase the remaining aircraft into service over the next several years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/2016/0805/Amazon-unveils-Prime-Air-its-new-cargo-plane|title=Amazon unveils Prime Air, its new cargo plane|first=Christina|last=Beck|date=5 August 2016|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/08/05/amazons-latest-weapon-in-the-e-commerce-wars-its-own-air-force/|title=Amazon\u2019s latest weapon in the e-commerce wars: Its own air force}}</ref>\n\n;5 August\n* [[ASL Airlines Hungary Flight 7332]], a [[Boeing 737-400|Boeing 737-476SF]] cargo aircraft, slides off a runway at [[Il Caravaggio International Airport]] in [[Bergamo]], [[Italy]], while landing in bad weather conditions. It crashes through a perimeter fence and rolls onto a four-lane highway, narrowly avoiding collisions with cars on the highway and destroying several cars in an adjacent parking lot. Both people aboard the aircraft are uninjured. The airport is closed for three hours after the crash, with incoming flights diverted to [[Milan\u2013Malpensa Airport]] in [[Milan]], Italy.\n* [[Black Lives Matter]] protesters block a roadway into [[Heathrow Airport]] outside [[London]], temporarily bringing ground traffic into the airport to a halt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/08/05/black-lives-matter-protest-blocks-access-to-londons-heathrow-airport/|title=Black Lives Matter branches out to U.K., launches protests}}</ref>\n* In response to a July 2016 court order to release to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] a May 2013 Presidential Policy Guidance (PPG) document laying out the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]'s guidelines for airstrikes by [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (popularly called \"drones\"), the [[United States Government]] releases a declassified, redacted version of the PPG. It requires \"near certainty\" that the terrorist target is at the targeted location, that no civilians be injured or killed in the strike, that the target poses a \"continuing and imminent\" threat to Americans, that capture of the target is not feasible, and that all relevant domestic and international laws are obeyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/newly-declassified-document-sheds-light-on-how-president-approves-drone-strikes/2016/08/06/f424fe50-5be0-11e6-831d-0324760ca856_story.html|title=Newly declassified document sheds light on how president approves drone strikes}}</ref>\n\n;6 August\n* The [[People's Republic of China]]'s [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] announces that it has conducted [[combat air patrol]]s over disputed areas in the [[South China Sea]] \u2013 the [[Spratly Islands]], [[Scarborough Shoal]], and nearby areas \u2013 \"to enhance combat capabilities to deal with various security threats\" as well as to protect China's sovereignty and maritime interests. It says the flights include bombers, fighters, early warning aircraft, and reconnaissance planes, and that at least some of the aircraft are capable of [[Aerial refueling|refueling in mid-air]], but it does not say when the flights occurred. In July 2016, after a 12 July 2016 ruling against its South China Sea territorial claims by the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]], it also announced that it had made such flights and that doing so would become \"regular practice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/4761dde1297741b2bc803e0a0f9f55e6/chinas-air-force-flies-combat-patrol-over-disputed-islands|title=China's air force flies combat patrol over disputed islands}}</ref>\n* A series of airstrikes by unidentified aircraft destroy a hospital operated by [[Doctors Without Borders]] in [[Millis, Syria|Millis]] in Syria's Idlib Governorate, killing 13 people and injuring at least six. A [[United States Department of Defense]] spokesman announces that U.S. aircraft have not conducted any airstrikes near Idlib Governorate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/547a7c3ae69d4d358d25ad9a755a3e74/msf-says-hospital-it-supports-syria-bombed-13-killed|title=MSF says a hospital it supports in Syria bombed, 13 killed}}</ref>\n\n;8 August\n* [[Delta Air Lines]] experiences computer problems that force it to cancel 451 of its nearly 6,000 daily flights, delaying tens of thousands of passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/delta-airlines-computer-systems-crash-causing-flight-delays-and-cancellations/2016/08/08/7d5e8fa0-5d72-11e6-af8e-54aa2e849447_story.html|title=Delta computers crash, causing delays and cancellations. Experts say it shouldn\u2019t have happened.}}</ref> Before the airline recovers, it cancels 2,300 flights over three days.<ref name=investors20160902>[http://www.investors.com/news/flight-cancellations-hurt-deltas-august-figures-threatens-q3/ Peters, Bill, \"Delta Says Flight Cancellations Cost $100 Million, Cites Other Industry Woes,\" ''Investor\u2032s Business Daily'', 2 September 2016.]</ref> On 2 September, Delta will announce that the cancellations cost it $100 million in revenue, or two percent of passenger unit revenue, a metric for unit revenue as it relates to a carrier's flight capacity and distance flown which dropped 9.5% in August.<ref name=investors20160902/>\n\n;9 August\n* The [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] conducts its first airstrikes in [[Yemen]] since a much-violated ceasefire in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] began on 11 April 2016. The coalition's aircraft strike a [[potato]] processing factory inside a [[Yemeni Army]] maintenance camp in [[Sana'a]], killing at least 14 people working there. One estimate puts the death toll at 16. At least 10 other people are injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/09/saudi-led-airstrikes-yemen-food-factory-kill-people|title=Saudi-led airstrikes on Yemen food factory kill at least 14 people|first=Saeed Kamali|last=Dehghan|date=9 August 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref> The strikes begin a stepped-up effort by the coalition after five months of relative calm in the air campaign in Yemen.<ref name=almujahed20160813>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-airstrike-hits-a-school-in-northern-yemen-killing-10-children/2016/08/13/07039cf2-617c-11e6-84c1-6d27287896b5_story.html|title=Saudi airstrike hits a school in northern Yemen, killing 10 children}}</ref>\n\n;10 August\n* According to Syrian activists, [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] helicopters drop barrel bombs on rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, killing at least two people.<ref name=ap201608110951>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/08/11/strikes-islamic-state-syria/88558178/|title=Airstrikes on Islamic State-held city in Syria kill at least 20 civilians}}</ref> Khaled Harah, one of the best-known members of [[Syrian Civil Defense]] for his rescue of a baby from a collapsed building in 2014 and his testimony before the [[United Nations Security Council]] about violence in Aleppo, is buried in the rubble of a building and killed. The following day, activists will claim that some people on the ground suffered breathing problems after the attack and allege that at least one of the barrel bombs contained [[chlorine gas]]; the Syrian government will deny that it used any [[chemical weapon]]s.<ref name=ap201608110951/> On 13 August, the [[Syrian American Medical Society]] will claim that a bomb dropped by a jet during the day contained chlorine gas and killed three people.<ref name=loveluck20160813>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/aleppos-humanitarian-crisis-worsens-as-islamic-state-loses-key-syrian-city/2016/08/13/04a1c01e-60a6-11e6-84c1-6d27287896b5_story.html|title=Aleppo\u2019s humanitarian crisis worsens while Islamic State loses key Syrian city}}</ref>\n* An [[Iraqi Air Force]] helicopter crashes in [[Iraq]]'s [[Maysan Governorate]] southwest of [[Amarah]] while attempting an [[emergency landing]] after a technical malfunction, injuring all nine people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iraqinews.com/iraq-war/iraqi-military-helicopter-falls-south-iraq/|title=Anonymous, \"Iraqi military helicopter falls south of Iraq,\" iraqinews.com, August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;11 August\n* Airstrikes on Islamic State-held [[Raqqa]], Syria, kill at least 20 civilians and perhaps as many as 24 civilians and six other people whose military or civilian status could not immediately be determined. According to Syrian activists, Russian Federation Air Force jets are responsible for the strikes.<ref name=ap201608110951/>\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Turkish Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] announces that the [[Turkish Air Force]] will resume airstrikes against Islamic State targets in Syria as part of the U.S.-led coalition and offers to carry out joint operations against the Islamic State with [[Russia]]. [[Turkey]] had discontinued airstrikes against the Islamic State in Syria after shooting down a Russian Federation Air Force aircraft in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]] and subsequently experiencing tension in its relationship with Russia.\n* [[JetBlue]] Flight 429, an [[Airbus A320]] bound from [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], to [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], encounters severe turbulence over [[South Dakota]]. It diverts to [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]], South Dakota, where 20 passengers and two crew members are hospitalized with injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/da6b6bc5447541db99e10d047d4cc6fe/turbulence-leaves-more-20-injured-jetblue-flight|title=People thrown 'like little rag dolls' in JetBlue turbulence|access-date=12 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812125602/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/da6b6bc5447541db99e10d047d4cc6fe/turbulence-leaves-more-20-injured-jetblue-flight|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;12 August\n* Airstrikes against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 18 people. The strikes \u2013 suspected of having been conducted by the Syrian Arab Air Force or Russian Federation Air Force.<ref name=loveluck20160813/> \u2013 hit the only hospital for women and children in [[Kafr Hamrah]], killing at least four people and burying at least 10 others who are pulled alive from the rubble; a market in [[Urum al-Kubra]], killing at least six people; and the village of [[Hayan]], killing at least 10 people. Prayers are cancelled for the day in [[Idlib]] because of the intensity of the airstrikes.\n* Mohammad Hassan Chaudhary, a 20- or 21-year-old (sources differ) [[schizophrenic]] man who allegedly has no flight training, steals a privately owned [[Piper PA-38 Tomahawk]] at [[Markham Airport]] in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], and crashes it near Landsdowne Place mall in [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], Ontario. The incident sparks concerns about security at private airports in Canada, as Chaudhary, wbo dies in the crash, stole the aircraft with relative ease, and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] investigate the matter as a \"national security issue.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2879025/man-dead-after-small-plane-crashes-on-street-in-peterborough/|title=Markham man killed after stolen small plane crashes in Peterborough}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2890098/rcmp-investigating-peterborough-plane-crash-as-national-security-issue/|title=RCMP investigated Peterborough plane crash as 'national security issue'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2892781/peterborough-plane-crash-should-there-be-more-security-at-private-airports/|title=Peterborough plane crash: Should there be more security at private airports?}}</ref>\n\n;13 August\n* A member of the provincial council of Afghanistan's [[Helmand Province]] claims that an ongoing [[Taliban]] offensive to capture [[Lashkar Gah]] would have surrounded the city if not for the recent addition of U.S. airstrikes in support of Afghan forces defending the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taliban-push-toward-strategic-provincial-afghan-capital/2016/08/13/53c04fe4-615f-11e6-9fd0-0b47b4fac0a4_story.html|title=Taliban pushes toward strategic provincial capital in Afghanistan}}</ref>\n* A [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] airstrike in northern [[Yemen]] hits a school in [[Sa'dah]], killing 10 children and injuring 28 others. Local reports state that the children were students taking exams at the time of the strike, while a spokesman for the Saudi-led coalition claims that the strike hit a rebel training camp and the children were rebel recruits.<ref name=almujahed20160813/>\n\n;14 August\n* Aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition conduct airstrikes in support of an offensive by [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] ''[[peshmerga]]'' troops against Islamic State forces in [[Iraq]] east of [[Mosul]] that captures five villages. One of the strikes destroys a [[car bomb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/ap/top-news/peshmerga-launch-operation-to-clear-villages-east-/nsFqc/|title=Szlanko, Balint, and Qassim Abdul-Zahra, \"Iraqi Kurds advance near Islamic State-held city,\" Associated Press, Sunday, Aug. 14, 2016, 5:30 p.m.}}</ref>\n* Aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition conduct airstrikes in support an offensive by pro-government troops in Yemen against [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] forces that captures [[Zinjibar]] and [[Ja\u02bf\u0101r]]. The strikes kill more than 40 Islamic militants and destroy several of their ground vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_YEMEN?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n* [[Boko Haram]] releases a video in which one of the [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|girls the group kidnapped in 2014]] from a school in [[Chibok]], [[Nigeria]], claims that [[Nigerian Air Force]] strikes against Boko Haram have killed some of the girls. The video also shows what purportedly are the bodies of kidnapped schoolgirls allegedly killed in an air raid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2151cbf4262e4ed3a93cfe5b865e931f/boko-haram-some-abducted-chibok-girls-killed-air-strikes|title=Boko Haram: Some abducted Chibok girls killed in air strikes}}</ref>\n* Reports 45 minutes apart of shots fired in two different terminals at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[Queens, New York|Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], lead to a panic in which thousands of people are evacuated from the terminals and all air traffic at the airport is grounded. After police find no signs of any shots having been fired, a senior law enforcement official announces that it appears that loud cheering, clapping, and banging by people watching television coverage of [[Jamaica]]n [[Sprint (running)|sprinter]] [[Usain Bolt]] competing in the [[100 metres|100-meter dash]] during the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] had been misinterpreted as the sounds of a fight and gunfire.<ref>[http://www.businessinsider.com/jfk-airport-terror-alert-may-have-been-sparked-by-people-cheering-for-usain-bolt-at-the-olympics-2016-8 Bates Daniel, \"Shooting alert at JFK Airport may have been sparked by people cheering for Usain Bolt in the Olympics,\" ''Evening Standard'' via businessinsider.com, 15 August 2016, 8:01 a.m. EDT.]</ref>\n\n;15 August\n* An airstrike by the Saudi-led coalition hits a Doctors Without Borders hospital in Yemen's [[Hajjah Governorate]], killing 19 people injuring 24. It is at least the fourth airstrike by the coalition against a Doctors Without Borders hospital in Yemen since the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] began in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-hits-doctors-without-borders-hospital-in-northwestern-yemen/2016/08/15/f1f44aa2-62ff-11e6-b4d8-33e931b5a26d_story.html|title=Airstrike hits Doctors Without Borders hospital in northwestern Yemen}}</ref><ref name=almosawa20160816>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/19/world/middleeast/yemen-doctors-without-borders-hospitals.html|title=Doctors Without Borders Is Pulling Staff After Hospital Bombings in Yemen|first1=Shuaib|last1=Almosawa|first2=Rod|last2=Nordland|date=18 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* Six people were killed in a small plane crash in [[Alabama]], United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/alabama-plane-crash-kills-married-couples-mississippi-41393981|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;16 August\n* Russian Federation Air Force [[Tupolev Tu-22M]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Backfire\") bombers fly from a base near [[Hamadan]], [[Iran]], to hit Islamic State and [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] targets in northern and eastern Syria. It is the first time that Russian aircraft conduct strikes against targets in Syria from bases in Iran. Russian fighters based in Syria join the bombers over Syria. The Russians inform U.S. military forces of the bombers' flight over Iraqi and Syrian territory in advance in accordance with an agreement to deconflict air operations over Syria with the United States. The bombers previously had made {{convert|2000|km|abbr=on}} flights from bases in Russia to strike Syrian targets, but the use of Iranian bases reduces the distance to {{convert|400|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}}, allowing them to carry larger payloads and use less fuel and allowing Russia to intensify its air campaign against rebel forces in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-uses-iranian-air-base-to-bomb-syria/2016/08/16/6b2a30e2-6393-11e6-96c0-37533479f3f5_story.html|title=Strikes from Iranian air base show Russia\u2019s expanding footprint in the Middle East}}</ref> The following day, an Iranian lawmaker will confirm that Russian aircraft are using Iran's Shahed Nojah Air Basem adding that Russian fighter aircraft are using the base only to refuel.<ref name=ap20160817>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/the-latest-syrian-media-say-7-killed-in-aleppo-shelling/15936497/|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrikes on Rebel-Held Syrian City Kill 17,\" Associated Press, August 17, 2016.|access-date=18 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820161613/http://www.wral.com/the-latest-syrian-media-say-7-killed-in-aleppo-shelling/15936497/|archive-date=20 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Syrian activists report an airstrike against a [[field hospital]] in rebel-held [[Daret Azzeh]] in Syria's [[Aleppo Governorate]] just after the hospital's staff and patients had evacuated it. Reportedly scoring a direct hit on the hospital, the strike injures one person.<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* [[Air Djibouti]] relaunches flight operations, using a [[Boeing 737-400]]. It is the first time the airline has flown since [[2002 in aviation|2002]].\n\n;17 August\n* Unidentified aircraft conduct airstrikes against rebel-held Idlib, Syria, killing 17 people and injuring at least 30 others.<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force [[Sukhoi Su-24]] (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") aircraft conduct the Syrian government's first airstrikes against forces of the Kurdish [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) in Syria's [[Hasakah Governorate]] near [[Hasakah]], killing several Kurds. The bombs fall near U.S. and coalition [[special operations forces]] working on the ground with the YPG but inflict no casualties on them. As the strike begins, the U.S. military contacts Russian forces in Syria to inform them that U.S. aircraft would respond if forces of the U.S.-led coalition were under attack; the Russians reply that the Syrians are conducting the strike. Coalition forces on the ground are unable to contact the Syrian jets, and U.S. fighter aircraft scrambled to intercept the Syrians arrive as the Syrian jets leave the area. The incident prompts the U.S.-led coalition to maintain increased [[combat air patrol]]s over the area and to warn the Syrian government not to interfere with coalition ground forces in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/18/politics/us-ypg-syria-bombed/index.html|title=Key ally in Syria bombed while US troops 'nearby'|first=Ryan|last=Browne}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-military-comes-under-attack-syrian-regime-airstrikes-n634521|title=The U.S. military came under attack from Syrian Regime airstrikes}}</ref><ref name=gibbonsneff20160819>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-jets-scramble-as-syrians-bomb-near-american-forces/2016/08/19/bef78558-6636-11e6-be4e-23fc4d4d12b4_story.html|title=U.S. jets scramble as Syrians bomb near American forces}}</ref>\n* The [[Ministry of Defense (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defense]] announces that Russian aircraft have conducted airstrikes against rebel targets in eastern Syria from bases in Iran for the second straight day, flying from a base southwest of [[Tehran]].<ref name=ap20160817/>\n* The [[Hybrid Air Vehicles]] [[Hybrid Air Vehicles HAV 304 Airlander 10|Airlander 10]] [[hybrid airship]] makes its first flight, a 30-minute flight at [[RAF Cardington|Cardington Airfield]] in [[Bedfordshire]], [[England]]. Although larger [[airship]]s existed in the early 20th century, the 302-foot-long (92-meter-long) Airlander 10 is the world's largest existing operational aircraft at the time of the flight.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com 2016-08-18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/08/18/historys-largest-aircraft-just-took-flight-but-observers-are-stuck-on-what-it-looks-like/|title=World\u2019s largest aircraft just took flight. But, observers are stuck on what it looks like.}}</ref>\n\n;18 August\n* Doctors Without Borders announces that it is evacuating its staff from six hospitals in northern Yemen, saying that the Saudi-led coalition's bombing of the area is \"indiscriminate\" and the coalition's assurances of protection for health workers are \"unreliable.\" The group explains that airstrikes have continue to target its hospitals despite its provision of the [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] coordinates of its hospitals to the coalition and two meetings with high-ranking military officials of the coalition over the last previous eight months in which the officials promised that aerial bombing of hospitals would end.<ref name=almosawa20160816/>\n\n;19 August\n* Two Syrian Arab Air Force Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") aircraft attempt to transit the area near Hasakah, Syria, where Syrian aircraft had come close to bombing U.S. and coalition special operations forces on the ground while attacking Kurdiish forces the previous day. Fighter aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition intercept them and, according to a U.S. Department of Defense spokesman, \"encouraged\" the Syrian aircraft to leave the area \"without further incident.\"<ref name=gibbonsneff20160819/>\n\n;21 August\n* After a rocket fired from the [[Gaza Strip]] lands in [[Sderot]], [[Israel]], [[Israeli Air Force]] aircraft join [[Israel Defense Forces]] [[tank]]s in bombarding the Gaza Strip town of [[Beit Hanoun]]. As the evening progresses, Israeli aircraft strike at least 30 targets belonging to [[Hamas]], the [[Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine]], and other militant groups in the Gaza Strip. The strikes slightly injure two people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israeli-palestinians-rocket-idUSKCN10W0HZ|title=Gaza militant rocket hits Israel, Israel responds with air strikes, shells|date=22 August 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[United States Army]] [[Lieutenant General (United States)|Lieutenant General]] [[Stephen J. Townsend]], the new commander of [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve]] \u2013 the military command responsible for the U.S.-led coalition's operations against the Islamic State \u2013 announces that U.S. and allied forces will intensify airstrikes against Islamic State targets in support of planned offensives by Syrian rebel ground forces against Raqqa, Syria, and by Iraqi government ground forces against Mosul, Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/21/new-commander-will-increase-tempo-of-u-s-operations-in-conclusive-stage-of-isis-fight/|title=New commander will increase tempo of U.S. operations in conclusive stage of ISIS fight}}</ref>\n\n;22 August\n* A U.S. military spokesman in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, announces that [[Embraer EMB 314 Super Tucano|Embraer A-29 Super Tucano]] light attack aircraft flown by U.S.-trained Afghan pilots have deployed to [[Kunduz]], Afghanistan, to operate against Taliban forces conducting an offensive to capture the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-forces-consolidate-gains-around-kunduz/2016/08/22/aab91c04-686c-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=Taliban forces consolidate gains around Kunduz}}</ref>\n* A spokesman for the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)|Iranian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] announces that Iran no longer will permit Russian aircraft to use bases in Iran, apparently because of Iran's displeasure with the publicity given the Russian deployment of aircraft to Iran by Russia's public announcement of it. The spokesman says that the Russian use of [[Hamadan Airbase]] outside [[Hamadan]], Iran, was \"temporary, based on a Russian request\" and was \"finished for now,\" adding that \"Russia has no base in Iran.\" Since beginning strikes against rebel targets in Syria on 16 August, Russia had operated Tupolev Tu-22M (NATO reporting name \"Backfire\") bombers, [[Sukhoi Su-34]] (NATO reporting name \"Fullback\") strike aircraft, [[Sukhoi Su-30]]SM (NATO reporting name \"Flanker C\") fighters, and [[Sukhoi Su-35]]S (NATO reporting name \"Flanker E\") fighters from Hamadan, launching at least three strikes into Syrian territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iran-ends-russian-use-of-air-base-because-of-unwanted-publicity/2016/08/22/87364e5e-2dbe-4544-889b-2cb7f233fc62_story.html|title=Iran ends Russian use of air base because of unwanted publicity}}</ref>\n\n;23 August\n* The [[Nigerian Army]] claims that \"the most unprecedented and spectacular air raid\" by the Nigerian Air Force against a village in the [[Sambisa Forest]] in northeastern Nigeria's [[Borno State]] on 19 August as members of Boko Haram met for morning prayers mortally wounded the group's leader, [[Abubakar Shekau]] \u2013 the fourth time Nigerian forces have claimed to have killed him \u2013 and killed three other top Boko Haram commanders. A separate Nigerian Air Force announcement claims that the strike killed 300 Boko Haram personnel. Neither of the reports can be verified, and later in the day Nigerian forces claim merely to have seriously wounded Shekau in the strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted2.ap.org/APDEFAULT/cae69a7523db45408eeb2b3a98c0c9c5/Article_2016-08-23-AF--Nigeria-Boko%20Haram/id-18047b5206214dd393c9bedc9bc53a63|title=Associated Press|first=AP|last=Story}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/23/nigeria-says-boko-haram-commanders-killed-airstrike-wounded-abubakar-shekau|title=Nigeria says Boko Haram commanders killed in airstrike|first=Ruth|last=Maclean|date=23 August 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/24/world/africa/boko-haram-abubakar-shekau-airstrike.html|title=Boko Haram Leader Is Wounded in Airstrike, Nigeria\u2019s Military Says|first=Dionne|last=Searcey|date=23 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37163949|title=Boko Haram crisis: Nigeria air strike 'kills commanders'|date=23 August 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 August\n* [[Turkish Army]] forces enter Syria to assist [[Free Syrian Army]] troops in capturing [[Jarabulus]] from the Islamic State. Turkish Air Force and U.S. aircraft conduct airstrikes in support of the offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/turkey-launches-operation-against-islamic-state-held-town-on-border/2016/08/24/4983b9d2-b71a-446e-967e-894bf4b9a845_story.html|title=Turkish troops enter Syria to take on ISIS, backed by U.S. warplanes}}</ref>\n* The [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) announce that they have cleared their forces of wrongdoing in two airstrikes against targets in the [[Gaza Strip]] that killed civilians during the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict]]. They find that a [[2014 in aviation#July|20 July 2014]] airstrike that killed seven members of one family at the refugee camp in [[Bureij]] was justified because the house was in use as a Hamas military [[Command and control|command-and-control]] center and because the strike killed a senior Hamas commander and three members of the family who were Hamas members; that a [[2014 in aviation#August|1 August 2014]] airstrike against a house in [[Rafah]] that killed 15 members of one family also was justified because the house was in use by Hamas as a military command-and-control center; that [[international law]] permits attacks on houses used for military purposes; and that one of the dead family members in the 1 August strike was a senior Hamas commander. The IDF also finds that the deaths of 12 members of a family in Rafah on 21 July 2014 were due to [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] fire rather than an Israeli airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3caf434feda5453dbd9df7477363489a/israel-clears-forces-several-deadly-2014-gaza-war-cases|title=Israel clears forces in several deadly 2014 Gaza war cases}}</ref>\n\n;25 August\n* A weeklong search in the [[Federated States of Mirconesia]] for a couple aboard a missing sailboat ends when a [[United States Navy]] helicopter investigating a report from the previous evening of a light seen on uninhabited [[Fayu Atoll]] discovers a large \"[[SOS]]\" drawn in the sand and spots the couple waving. The couple is rescued by boat on 26 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/couple-stranded-fayu-micronesia-desert-island-rescued-after-writing-sos-message-on-beach-a7212776.html|title=Couple stranded on desert island rescued after writing SOS message on beach|date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n;26 August\n* Russian news media report that the [[Government of Russia|Russian government]] has asked the [[Government of Turkey|Turkish government]] for information on Turkish air operations over Syria. A spokesman for the Russian Ministry of Defense explains that Russia wishes to use the information \"to prevent air incidents because it will be the first time when Turkish warplanes will intensively bomb targets in Syria and [they] may meet Russian warplanes in midair.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/kerry-meets-lavrov-in-geneva-in-bid-to-forge-truce-deal-in-syrian-war/2016/08/26/95aaf690-6af9-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=U.S., Russia say they are close to cooperation deal in Syrian war}}</ref>\n\n;27 August\n* Syrian warplanes attack a funeral in [[Al-Nayrab]], Syria, with a barrel bomb, then return to strike with another barrel bomb after rescue workers arrive. The attacks reportedly kill more than two dozen people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrike-in-east-aleppo-hits-childrens-funeral/2016/08/27/2917db58-6c69-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=Airstrike in east Aleppo hits funeral}}</ref>\n* The Turkish Air Force conducts airstrikes against Kurdish targets in [[Al-Amarna]], Syria, south of Jarabulus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/how-turkeys-offensive-into-syria-is-opening-up-a-hornets-nest/2016/08/27/c1edd776-6bb8-11e6-91cb-ecb5418830e9_story.html|title=How Turkey\u2019s offensive into Syria is opening up a hornet\u2019s nest}}</ref>\n* The left engine of Southwest Airlines Flight 3472 (registration N766SW) \u2013 a [[Boeing 737-700]] flying from [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], to [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Florida]], with 104 people on board \u2013 explodes at an altitude of {{convert|30700|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, damaging the engine [[nacelle]] and tearing a gash in the airliner's [[fuselage]]. The aircraft makes an [[emergency landing]] at [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]], Florida, without injury to anyone on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airlive.net/breaking-southwest-boeing-737-sw3472-looses-part-of-left-engine-after-explosion/|title=BREAKING Southwest Boeing 737 #WN3472 loses part of left engine after inflight explosion - AIRLIVE.net|first=Melanie|last=Kraft}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/scare-sky-after-passenger-jet-engine-suffers-major-malfunction-n638811|title=Passenger jet suffers major engine malfunction in mid-air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url = http://avherald.com/h?article=49d2d7e3\n  |title = Accident: Southwest B737 near Pensacola on Aug 27th 2016, uncontained engine failure\n  |author = Simon Hradecky\n  |date = 27 August 2016\n  |work = [[The Aviation Herald]]\n}}</ref>\n\n;28 August\n* Russia lifts its ban on charter flights to Turkey. The ban had been in place since Turkey shot down a Russian Federation Air Force Sukhoi Su-24 (NATO reporting name \"Fencer\") near the Turkish border with Syria in [[2015 in aviation#November|November 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/business/357469-turkey-charter-ban-lifted/|title=Russia lifts ban on charter flights to Turkey, airlines start submitting requests}}</ref> On 29 August, the executive director of the [[Association of Tour Operators of Russia]] will announce that the first charter flights will take place on 4\u20135 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rbth.com/news/2016/08/29/first-charter-flights-from-russia-to-turkey-will-fly-on-sept-4-5_625109|title=First charter flights from Russia to Turkey will fly on Sept. 4\u20135|last=TASS|date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Iranian state television airs video of a Russian-supplied mobile [[S-300 (missile)|S-300]] (NATO reporting name \"SA-10 Grumble\") [[surface-to-air missile]] system deployed around the nuclear site at [[Fordo]], Iran. It is not clear whether the system is fully operational or that it will remain at the site.<ref name=karimi20160829>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/31bb5fa1ccdd4ac38269a045d1608b04/iran-deploys-s-300-air-defense-around-nuclear-site|title=Iran deploys S-300 air defense around nuclear site}}</ref>\n* Just after police at [[Los Angeles International Airport]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], California, detain a man in the terminal carrying a plastic sword and dressed as [[Zorro]], a report of shots fired leads to a panic in which police evacuate terminals, people run onto the airfield, and flights to and from the airport are halted. The loud noises mistaken for shots turn out to be harmless, and the man dressed as Zorro, who tells police he had come to meet an arriving passenger, is released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2016/08/29/man-dressed-as-zorro-detained-at-lax-moments-before-false-active-shooter-reports-surfaced/|title=Man Dressed as Zorro Detained at LAX Moments Before False Active Shooter Reports Surfaced|date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n* American [[reality television]] personality [[Darrell Ward]], a star of the television series ''[[Ice Road Truckers]]'', and his pilot are killed when their [[Cessna 182 Skylane Skylane]] (registration N9936T) crashes on a highway and catches fire while trying to land at an airstrip at [[Rock Creek, Montana|Rock Creek]], [[Montana]], at the end of a flight from [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]], Montana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planecrashinfo.com/famous2010s.htm|title=Famous people who died in aviation accidents}}</ref>\n\n;29 August\n* Iranian state television reports that Iran has put into operation the [[Nazir (radar)|Nazir]] [[radar]] system, which it claims can detect radar-evading aircraft, [[ballistic missile]]s, [[cruise missile]]s, and unmanned aerial vehicles flying at altitudes of over {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}.<ref name=karimi20160829/>\n* The first nationwide regulations governing the use of unmanned aerial vehicles (popularly known as \"drones\") go into effect in the United States. They apply only to commercial-purpose UAVs weighing {{convert|55|lb|kg|abbr=off}} or less including payload, and require that the UAVs fly only during daylight, remain within sight of their operators, not fly directly over people not involved in their operation, fly no higher than an altitude of {{convert|400|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, and fly no faster than {{convert|100|mph|km/h|order=flip|abbr=on}}; operations outside these parameters require a waiver from the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA). They also require that UAV pilots pass a written test of aeronautical knowledge administered by the FAA to receive an FAA certification to operate UAVs \u2013 the FAA has received about 3,000 requests for such certifications \u2013 although UAV pilots are not required to possess a formal license. The regulations do not apply to privately owned UAVs operated by hobbyists. They also do not address the operation of UAVs over private property, although the FAA recommends that UAV operators receive the permission of property owners before operating UAVs over their property and specific permission to take photographs and videos over their property if the UAVs are to be used for those purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/29/as-of-today-its-finally-legal-to-fly-drones-commercially/|title=As of today, it\u2019s finally legal to fly drones commercially}}</ref>\n\n;30 August\n* The Islamic State announces that its chief spokesman, [[Abu Mohammad al-Adnani]], has been killed in an airstrike. The U.S. Department of Defense reports that it targeted Adnani in a \"precision strike\" in [[Al-Bab]], Syria, with an [[AGM-114 Hellfire]] [[air-to-ground missile]] fired by an unmanned aerial vehicle but says it cannot confirm his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/08/30/islamic-state-reports-death-of-spokesman-and-senior-leader-in-aleppo/|title=In potential blow to propaganda power, Islamic State reports death of senior leader in Syria}}</ref> On 31 August, Russia will claim that a strike by a Russian Federation Air Force Sukhoi Su-34 (NATO reporting name \"Fullback\") killed as many as 40 Islamic State personnel on 30 August, one of whom was Adnani, but offers no evidence for its claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russian-claims-airstrike-that-killed-senior-islamic-state-leader/2016/08/31/4b551701-c880-4c0c-ac92-24df06c1195c_story.html|title=Russian military claims it killed senior ISIS strategist}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Sutter]], the American engineer known as the \"father of the 747\" who served as chief engineer for the design and development of the [[Boeing 747]] in the 1960s, leading a team of 4,500 people including 2,700 engineers, dies at the age of 95.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/joe-sutter-boeing-engineer-who-led-project-to-build-the-first-jumbo-jet-dies-at-95/2016/08/31/9564bc62-6f8f-11e6-9705-23e51a2f424d_story.html|title=Joe Sutter, Boeing engineer who led project to build the first jumbo jet, dies at 95}}</ref>\n\n;31 August\n* An airstrike in [[Saada]], Yemen, by the Saudi-led coalition kills at least 16 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/08/31/world/middleeast/ap-ml-yemen.html?_r=0|title=Anonymous, \"Yemeni Rebels: Saudi-Led Airstrikes Kill 16 Civilians,\" Associated Press, August 31, 2016, 11:04 a.m. EDT.}}</ref> According to one report, the dead are an [[imam]] and 15 members of his extended family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-idUSKCN1161MA|title=Air strike kills 16 members of Yemeni imam's family|date=31 August 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The first scheduled commercial air service between the United States and [[Cuba]] in over 50 years begins with [[JetBlue Airways]] Flight 387 \u2013 an [[Airbus A320]] \u2013 making a flight from [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], to [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]], Cuba. It is also the first scheduled commercial passenger jet flight between the two countries in history, propeller-driven airliners having been in use when flights ceased in the early 1960s. Among passengers on the first flight are [[United States Secretary of Transportation]] [[Anthony Foxx]] and JetBlue [[Chief Executive Officer]] Robin Hayes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/01/world/americas/cuba-us-first-flight-jetblue.html|title=Scheduled Flights to Cuba From U.S. Begin Again, Now With Jet Engines|first=Frances|last=Robles|date=31 August 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=ap20160831>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/27c0276eeb4d4294aef559960f653132/historic-commercial-flight-us-cuba-set-take|title=Historic commercial flight from US lands in Cuba}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of Transportation]] announces that it has selected [[Alaska Airlines]], American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, JetBlue Airways, [[Southwest Airlines]], [[Spirit Airlines]], and United Airlines to provide scheduled airline service to [[Havana]], Cuba, requiring them to begin service within 90 days. The airlines are to provide the service from [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]; [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], [[North Carolina]]; Fort Lauderdale, [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida; [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]]; Los Angeles, California; [[New York City]]; and [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]].<ref name=ap20160831/>\n* A private [[Cessna]] aircraft hired by a woman so that her boyfriend could celebrate his birthday by seeing New Orleans, Louisiana, from the air and carrying the woman, her boyfriend, and a pilot, crashes into [[Lake Pontchartrain]] after flying into a rainstorm. The crash kills the woman's boyfriend and the plane's pilot, but her boyfriend pushes her from the plane moments before the crash, saving her life. A private boat rescues her from the lake and she is taken to a hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fox43.com/2016/08/31/man-pushes-girlfriend-from-plane-saves-her-life-before-dying-in-crash/|title=Man pushes girlfriend from plane, saves her life before dying in crash|date=31 August 2016}}</ref>\n* A mid-air collision over a remote area near [[Russian Mission, Alaska|Russian Mission]], [[Alaska]], between a [[Hageland Aviation]] [[Cessna 208B Grand Caravan]] carrying three people and a [[Renfro's Alaskan Adventures]] [[Piper PA-18 Super Cub]] carrying two people kills everyone aboard both planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20160831-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Cessna 208B Grand Caravan EX N752RV Russian Mission Airport, AK (RSH)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref> Mid-air collisions are rare in the [[United States]] and usually happen near airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-37239683|title=Five killed in Alaska mid-air collision|date=1 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n\n;1 September\n* Suspected [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]] airstrikes kill at least 25 civilians in [[Syria]]'s [[Hama Governorate]].<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ab4d169b4fed4c818a0d238b7c6bb494/syrian-activists-airstrikes-hama-province-kill-25-people Issa, Philip, \"Syrian Activists Airstrikes Hama Province Kill 25 People\" ''Associated Press'', 1 September 2016, 10:35 PM EDT.]</ref>\n\n;2 September\n* The Syrian rebel group [[Jaish al-Izzah]] claims to have shot down a \"Russian helicopter\" with a [[BGM-71 TOW]] [[anti-tank missile]] during the day as the helicopter was landing outside [[Rahbat al-Khattab]] northwest of [[Hama]], Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/1.739981|title=Syrian Rebels Shoot Down Helicopter Amid Hama Offensive|date=2 September 2016|via=Haaretz}}</ref> According to one report, the helicopter was Russian- or French-made and operated by the Syrian government, and two people aboard it were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/middleeast/20160903/1044914418/hama-helicopter-downing.html|title=Syrian Source Confirms Government Helicopter Downing by Terrorists in Hama|last=Sputnik}}</ref>\n\n;3 September\n* [[Iraqi Air Force]] fighter aircraft drop leaflets to residents of [[Shirqat]] and [[Zuwiyah]], Iraq. The leaflets ask them to support and assist Iraqi forces and their allies advancing into the area during an offensive against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].<ref name=dolomari20160915>[http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/e60bef37-6271-43ef-9315-e79aa4890d1d/PHOTOS--Iraqi-planes-drop-seven-million-leaflets-on-Mosul Dolomari, Mewan, \"Iraqi planes drop seven million leaflets on Mosul,\" kurdistan24.net, 15 September 2016.]</ref>\n\n;4 September\n* A U.S. [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] fires an [[air-to-ground missile]] at a gathering of [[al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] members in [[Yemen]]'s [[Shabwah Governorate]], killing six of them.<ref name=ryan20160908>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-reminder-of-the-permanent-wars-dozens-of-us-airstrikes-in-six-countries/2016/09/08/77cde914-7514-11e6-be4f-3f42f2e5a49e_story.html|title=A reminder of the permanent wars: Dozens of U.S. airstrikes in six countries}}</ref>\n* Supported by [[Russian Federation Air Force]] strikes, [[Syrian Arab Army]] forces close off the \"[[Ramouseh]] corridor,\" completing an encirclement of rebel-held portions of [[Aleppo, Syria|Aleppo]], Syria, and cutting them off from reinforcement and supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-still-trying-for-a-syria-ceasefire-deal-with-russia/2016/09/05/c56d710a-72ec-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Obama and Putin unable to reach cease-fire agreement for Syria}}</ref>\n\n;5 September\n* Since 3 September, U.S. aircraft have conducted about 20 strikes against Islamic State targets in [[Iraq]], centering on [[Nineveh Province]] and [[Mosul]] but also in [[Anbar Province]]; at least 25 strikes against Islamic State targets in northern and eastern [[Syria]], at least 20 strikes against Islamic State targets in [[Sirte]], [[Libya]]; and several counterterrorism strikes in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=ryan20160908/>\n* U.S. forces conduct two airstrikes in [[Tortoroow]], [[Somalia]], in defense of [[Africa]]n peacekeeping forces that had come under attack by [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]].<ref name=ryan20160908/>\n\n;6 September\n* Visiting [[Laos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] pledges that the [[United States]] will provide $90 million in additional aid to Laos to help in cleaning up an estimated 80 million unexploded bombs remaining in that country after the U.S. air campaign there during the [[Vietnam War]]. Between 1964 and 1973, the United States conducted 580,000 bombing raids over Laos, dropping an estimated 270 million [[cluster bomb]]s, in an effort to cut off supplies passing through Laos to [[Viet Cong]] and [[North Vietnamese Army]] forces operating in [[South Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/obama-pledges-90-million-to-help-clear-remnants-of-us-bombing-in-laos/2016/09/06/f7d9db6a-6ee1-11e6-993f-73c693a89820_story.html|title=Obama pledges $90 million to help clear remnants of U.S. bombing in Laos}}</ref>\n* A Syrian government aircraft drops a barrel bomb containing [[chlorine gas]] on the rebel-held [[Sukkari]] neighborhood of Aleppo. According to [[Syrian Civil Defense]], 120 people are hospitalized with breathing problems after the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/chlorine-attack-deepens-fears-among-besieged-aleppo-residents/2016/09/06/96c86796-7441-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Chlorine attack deepens fears among besieged Aleppo residents}}</ref> The following day, medical workers claim that they treated 70 people for breathing problems and that two of them had died on 7 September.<ref name=issa20160907>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3cd742c399bd41709ca38534aaed69ff/un-fighting-displaces-100000-central-syria-8-days|title=Aleppo bombed as US and Russia plan Syria talks}}</ref>\n* A Mexican police helicopter crashes in [[Mexico]]'s [[Michoac\u00e1n]] state, killing three police officers and the pilot, during a police operation to capture leaders of criminal groups and drug cartels in [[Apatzing\u00e1n]], including the [[Knights Templar Cartel]]. An initial report that the helicopter was shot down by a criminal group later comes into question, prompting an investigation into the cause of the crash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salazar|first1=Juan Ignacio|title=Mexico probes if gang downed police helicopter|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/criminals-down-police-helicopter-mexico-four-dead-011310542.html|website=yahoo.com|publisher=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;7 September\n* A U.S. airstrike near [[Raqqa]], Syria, kills Islamic State minister of information [[Wael Adel Salman al-Fayad]], also known as Abu Mohamed Furqan. The [[United States Department of Defense]] will announce the successful strike on 16 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/16/u-s-strike-kills-another-senior-islamic-state-militant-official-says/|title=Pentagon says Raqqa strike kills Islamic State information minister}}</ref>\n* A Syrian government airstrike in the rebel-held al-Sukkari neighborhood of Aleppo, Syria, kills at least 10 civilians.<ref name=issa20160907/>\n\n;8 September\n* Afghan [[attack helicopter]]s support Afghan ground troops opposing a [[Taliban]] ground offensive in street-to-street fighting in [[Tarinkot]], Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-launch-surprise-surge-into-former-southern-afghan-stronghold/2016/09/08/c63eb570-75d1-11e6-b786-19d0cb1ed06c_story.html|title=Taliban launches surprise surge into former southern Afghan stronghold}}</ref>\n* An evening airstrike by unidentified aircraft against a meeting of [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] commanders in the village of [[Kafr Naha]] on the western outskirts of Aleppo, Syria, kills commander [[Abu Omar Saraqib]]. The strike also reportedly kills or injures other senior members of the group, including the commander [[Abu Muslem al-Shami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37314280|title=Syria conflict: Senior militant leader 'killed' near Aleppo|date=9 September 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-syrian-rebel-commander-killed-in-airstrike-1473428873|title=Top Syrian Rebel Commander Killed in Airstrike|first=Maria|last=Abi-Habib|date=9 September 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n* A [[Diamond DA20|Diamond DA20C]] with two people on board collides with a [[Beech F-33|Beech F-33A]] carrying only a pilot near [[West Georgia Regional Airport]] in [[Carroll County, Georgia|Carroll County]], [[Georgia, United States|Georgia]], in mid-air killing all three people on board the planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myfox8.com/2016/09/08/3-killed-in-mid-air-collision-near-west-georgia-airport/|title=3 killed in mid-air collision near west Georgia airport|date=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;10 September\n* A series of airstrikes by aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition on a water well in [[Beit Sadaan]], Yemen, kill at least 30 people and wound at least 17, according to the [[United Nations]], although [[Houthi]] rebels claim that the strikes kill or wound 100 people. Later strikes in the sequence of air raids on the well reportedly kill first responders attempting to help the wounded from earlier strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-air-defense-shoots-down-missile-fired-from-yemen/2016/09/12/153486fc-78b9-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=- The Washington Post}}</ref>\n* In [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John F. Kerry]] and [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Russia)|Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Sergei Lavrov]] announce a ceasefire agreement between the [[United States]] and [[Russia]] intended to lead to a negotiated settlement that will end the [[Syrian Civil War]]. The ceasefire between the Syrian government and opposition groups is to begin at sundown on 12 September. If the ceasefire holds for seven days, the agreement as outlined by Kerry calls among other things for the protection of civilians in Syria from airstrikes, for the United States and Russia to make arrangements to conduct coordinated airstrikes in Syria against [[Jabhat Fateh al-Sham]] and the Islamic State, and for the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] to resume combat missions only over yet-to-be-selected areas that contain no rebel forces.<ref name=sly20160910>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/doubts-concerns-greet-syria-cease-fire-deal/2016/09/10/0f9f13f4-76e0-11e6-9781-49e591781754_story.html|title=Doubts, concerns greet Syria cease-fire deal as violence surges}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/09/09/politics/syria-ceasefire-kerry-lavrov/index.html|title=Kerry announces US-Russia deal on Syrian ceasefire|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Elise Labott|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force jets strike a busy market in [[Idlib]], Syria, killing at least 36 people, and various neighborhoods in Aleppo, Syria, killing at least another 45 people.<ref name=sly20160910/> Airstrikes from the day resulted in the deaths of over 100 people, all civilians, and the injuring of also more than 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/us-and-russia-announce-syria-peace-plan-10571819|title=More Than 100 Dead in Attacks Before Syria Truce}}</ref>\n\n;11 September\n* As part of an effort to improve [[crowd control]] at the annual [[Hajj]] pilgrimage and avoid a repeat of a [[2015 Mina stampede|disastrous stampede]] that killed hundred of people in September 2015, authorities in [[Saudi Arabia]] deploy unmanned aerial vehicles to monitor pilgrims ascending [[Mount Arafat]], east of [[Mecca]], at the climax of the 2016 Hajj.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N1BN05K?sp=true|title=Drones keep watch as pilgrims ascend Mount Arafat for haj climax|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n;12 September\n* A ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War under an agreement between Russia and the United States goes into effect at sundown, but is almost immediately violated during the evening. Among the violations is a barrel-bomb attack against a neighborhood of Aleppo by Syrian government helicopters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ceasefire-in-syria-set-to-take-hold-as-scores-die-in-air-strikes/2016/09/12/c93bbf4e-7850-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=Syrian cease-fire backed by U.S. and Russia gets off to rocky start}}</ref>\n\n;14 September\n* Iraqi Air Force aircraft drop 7 million leaflets over Iraq's [[Nineveh Governorate]] \u2013 2 million over the center of [[Mosul]], 500,000 each over [[Hamdaniya]], [[al-Ba\u2019aaj]], [[al-Hazar]], and [[Talafar]], and 250,000 each over [[Bashiqa]], [[Hamam Alil]], [[al-Shura]], [[al-Mahaliya]], [[al-Hmidat]], [[Bartila]], [[al-Namroud]], [[Qahtaniyah, Iraq|Qahtaniyah]], [[Til Abta]], [[al-Ayaziya]], and [[al-Qirwan]]. The leaflets inform civilians of a planned offensive to retake Mosul from the Islamic State and asks civilians in the governorate to stop fighting for the Islamic State, avoid Islamic State bases and help the anti-Islamic State coalition target the bases, and support advancing Iraqi troops and their allies.<ref name=dolomari20160915/>\n* Based on the results of a [[United States Navy]] investigation into a fatal crash while the [[Blue Angels]] flight demonstration [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]] was practicing for an [[air show]] on [[2016 in aviation#June|2 June]], the Blue Angels receive orders to eliminate the [[split S]] maneuver from their shows until further notice, put dive recovery rules with specific airspeed limitations in place, use a greater safety buffer between aircraft and the ground for the remainder of the air show season, and make positive radio confirmation with instruments that measure altitude prior to takeoff. The Navy also directs that after the conclusion of the current air show season a safety team review the Blue Angels' training, maintenance and culture; review their aerial maneuvers in order to increase safety; and determine adjustments to future air show schedules to allow more rest for pilots and support staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/15/navy-will-alter-how-the-blue-angels-stunt-team-flies-after-investigation-of-fatal-crash/|title=After investigation, Navy\u2019s Blue Angels will stop using maneuver that killed a pilot}}</ref>\n\n;16 September\n* The [[United States Air Force]] announces the grounding of 15 [[F-35A Lightning II]] aircraft \u2013 13 belonging to the U.S. Air Force and two to the [[Royal Norwegian Air Force]] \u2013 due to \"peeling and crumbling\" insulation inside their fuel tanks. The insulation problem also affects another 42 F-35A aircraft still in production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/09/16/air-force-grounds-15-f-35-joint-strike-fighters-because-of-peeling-and-crumbling-insulation/|title=Air Force grounds 15 F-35 Joint Strike Fighters because of 'peeling and crumbling' insulation}}</ref>\n* [[Bulgaria]]'s national airline [[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will make commercial flights to the [[United States]] for the first time since the 1990s. It plans to begin its new transatlantic service in March 2017.\n\n;17 September\n* Believing that they are attacking Islamic State forces, aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition \u2013 which the Syrian government claims are two [[F-16 Fighting Falcon]]s and two [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]]s flying into Syria from Iraq \u2013 mistakenly strike Syrian Arab Army forces in Syria's [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]]. The strike destroys approximately six ground vehicles according to a [[United States Central Command]] estimate before Russia alerts Central Command that the strike is targeting Syrian Arab Army forces; the aircraft then cease fire and the United States express regret over the strike. Russia and Syria claim that the targeted forces were fighting against the Islamic State and that the strike killed 62 Syrian soldiers and wounded 100. It is the first combat engagement between the U.S.-led coalition and Syrian forces since the coalition began air raids in Syria in [[2014 in aviation|2014]]. Arguing that the strike is a ceasefire violation that may be evidence of U.S. military support for the Islamic State in the Syrian Civil War, Russia calls an emergency Saturday-evening meeting of the [[United Nations Security Council]] to discuss the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/russia-and-syria-blame-us-led-coalition-for-deadly-strike-on-syrian-troops/2016/09/17/8dabf5d6-7d03-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=U.S. admits carrying out airstrike that Russia says killed 62 Syrian soldiers}}</ref>\n\n;18 September\n* The U.S.-led coalition in Afghanistan comnducts two airstrikes against a highway in Afghanistan's [[Urozgan Province]] on the outskirts of [[Tarinkot]] in support of Afghan forces in combat against the [[Taliban]]. Local officials claim that the strikes mistakenly kill eight Afghan police officers, with the second strike killing people who were attempting to help those injured in the first strike; the coalition does not comment on the allegation. The strikes are among several the coalition carries out during the day, including in [[Kabul Province]].<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-airstrikes-in-afghanistan-killed-eight-policemen-say-local-officials-1474300170 Amiri, Ehsanullah, and Jessica Dona, \"U.S. Airstrikes in Afghanistan Killed Eight Policemen, Local Officials Say\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 19 September 2016, 11:49 a.m. EDT.]</ref>\n* Warplanes \u2013 suspected of being Syrian Arab Air Force or Russian Federation Air Force aircraft \u2013 strike rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo, Syria, killing at least one person and injuring several others. Another suspected Syrian or Russian airstrike in Syria's [[Daraa Governorate]] kills eight people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/barrel-bombs-fall-on-aleppo-with-ceasefire-deal-close-to-unraveling/2016/09/18/64d2589c-7d1e-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=New violence in Syria threatens cease-fire, as U.S. and Russia blame each other}}</ref>\n* Iranian state television announces that [[Iran]] is reducing the number of airliners it agreed to purchase from [[Airbus]] in [[2016 in aviation#January|January]] from 118 to 112.<ref name=gambrell20160922/>\n\n;19 September\n* The Syrian government declares an end to a week-long nationwide ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War and the Syrian Arab Air Force conducts at least 35 airstrikes and barrel-bomb attacks against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria. One air raid strikes a ground convoy as it unloads aid packages at a warehouse operated by the [[Syrian Arab Red Crescent]] west of Aleppo, Syria, hitting the warehouse, destroying at least 18 of the convoy's 31 trucks, and killing about 20 civilians, including at least 12 humanitarian aid workers, most of them truck drivers. The United States claims that only Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force aircraft could have conducted the strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrias-7-day-grace-period-ends-with-no-aid-and-cease-fire-in-tatters/2016/09/19/633ecd72-7dea-11e6-ad0e-ab0d12c779b1_story.html|title=At least 12 aid workers killed in Syria airstrike}}</ref>\n* [[United States Secretary of the Air Force]] [[Deborah Lee James]] announces that the new bomber under development by [[Northrop Grumman]] for the U.S. Air Force's [[Long-Range Strike Bomber]] program will be named the [[Northrop Grumman B-21 Raider|B-21 Raider]]. The B-21 is expected to reach [[initial operational capability]] in the mid-2020s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.af.mil/News/ArticleDisplay/tabid/223/Article/948366/the-b-21-has-a-name-raider.aspx|title=The B-21 has a name: Raider}}</ref>\n\n;20 September\n* Bulgaria Air confirms the lease of 14 new [[Boeing 737]] aircraft, which will replace the [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320s]] currently operated by the airline. The deal is valued at more than $8,000,000,000.\n* A military helicopter belonging to the [[Libyan National Army]] crashes near [[Tobruk]], killing all eight people on board, including the [[Libyan National Army|Libyan armed forces']] commander-in-chief, [[Idris Younis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/09/20/485524/Libya-Helicopter-Crash-Tobruk|title=PressTV-'Military helicopter crash kills 8 in Libya'}}</ref>\n\n;21 September\n* After the Russian Ministry of Defense claims that a U.S. unmanned aerial vehicle was in the vicinity of the 19 September airstrike on a humanitarian aid convoy and warehouse outside Aleppo, Syria, and implies that it could have conducted the attack, the U.S. Department of Defense responds that no manned or unmanned aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition were in the area at the time.<ref name=deyoung20160921>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-calls-on-russia-and-syria-to-ground-all-aircraft-in-northwest-syria/2016/09/21/ea602cbc-8013-11e6-8d0c-fb6c00c90481_story.html|title=U.S. calls on Russia and Syria to ground all aircraft in northwest Syria}}</ref> At the U.N. Security Council, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry accuses Moscow of inventing its \"own facts\"<ref name=deyoung20160921/> to explain the air attack, which the United States had blamed on the Russian Federation Air Force, adding that \"We don\u2019t get anywhere by ignoring facts and denying common sense;\"<ref name=deyoung20160921/> he calls for Russia and Syria to \"immediately ground all aircraft\" flying in areas of northwest Syria where the convoy was hit.<ref name=deyoung20160921/>\n* The [[United States Department of the Treasury]]'s [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] grants [[Airbus]] and [[Boeing]] licenses to sell airliners to [[Iran]]. Airbus's license covers the first 17 [[Airbus A320|A320s]] and [[Airbus A330|A330s]] that Iran agreed to purchase in a [[2016 in aviation#January|January]]; although based aboard, the company required U.S. Government permission because at least 10 percent of the airliners' components are manufactured in the United States. Boeing's license allows it to sell 80 airliners and lease another 29 new [[Boeing 737]]s to Iran.<ref name=gambrell20160922/>\n\n;22 September\n* Throughout the day, suspected Syrian Arab Air Force and Russian Federation Air Force aircraft strike targets in rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria; twenty-one people die in evening air raids on two Aleppo neighborhoods, and scores have died in airstrikes in the city since 19 September.<ref name=deyoung20160922>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-russia-continue-to-exchange-charges-amid-effort-to-salvage-cease-fire/2016/09/22/303bd2bc-80f1-11e6-8327-f141a7beb626_story.html|title=U.S., Russia continue to exchange charges amid effort to salvage cease-fire}}</ref> At the U.N. Security Council, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry repeats his 21 September call for Syria and Russia to ground their aircraft in northeastern Syria, saying that \"the only way\" for the Syrian ceasefire to succeed is \"if the ones who have the air power in this part of the conflict simply stop using it...\u2009. Absent a major gesture like this, we don\u2019t believe there is a point in making more promises, issuing more plans.\"<ref name=deyoung20160922/> The U.S. [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[Joseph Dunford]], tells the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]] that \"I would not agree that coalition aircraft ought to be grounded...I do agree that Syrian regime aircraft and Russian aircraft should be grounded...There's no reason to ground our aircraft...We\u2019re not barrel-bombing civilians; we\u2019re not causing collateral damage.\"<ref name=deyoung20160922/>\n* The [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO) rules that the [[European Union]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]] have failed to halt illegal subsidies to Airbus that the WTO had ordered them to stop in [[2011 in aviation|2011]] despite reporting in late 2011 that they had done so. The WTO adds that the subsidies \u2013 which total $22,000,000,000 over ten years \u2013 have cost the economy of the United States tens of billions of dollars and cost Boeing nearly 400 potential airliner sales in 2012 and 2013 alone. The ruling is a sweeping victory for the United States and its [[aerospace industry]], which has disputed European aircraft subsidies for 40 years and first filed a complaint with the WTO about Airbus subsidies in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/09/22/wto-rules-europe-illegally-subsidized-airlines-handing-victory-to-obama-administration-ahead-of-trade-fight/|title=WTO rules Europe illegally subsidized airlines, handing victory to Obama administration ahead of trade fight}}</ref>\n\n;23 September\n* After the Syrian government announces an offensive against rebel forces in and around Aleppo, Syria, the previous evening, Syrian government aircraft pound rebel-held areas of Aleppo during the day, conducting more than 70 strikes and dropping at least 100 bombs. Observers describe the strikes during the day as the most intense of the Syrian Civil War. Targets include at least three of the four [[Syrian Civil Defense]] in the eastern part of the city; damaging [[fire truck]]s and [[ambulance]]s; two of the centers are knocked out. More than 70 strikes have hit the Aleppo area since 21 September; since the collapse of the ceasefire in Syria on 19 September, airstrikes have killed scores of people, including at least 30 in Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/un-hopes-to-soon-resume-aid-convoys-inside-syria/2016/09/22/b0fcb2c0-80ad-11e6-b002-307601806392_story.html|title=Syria ignores Kerry and launches an offensive to recapture Aleppo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-airstrikes-hammer-aleppo-amid-expanding-offensive-against-rebels/2016/09/23/4d247c50-818a-11e6-b002-307601806392_story.html|title=Syrian airstrikes hammer Aleppo amid expanding offensive against rebels}}</ref>\n\n;24 September\n* Syrian and Russian airstrikes against rebel-held areas in and around Aleppo, Syria, continue to escalate, reaching levels unseen previously in the five-year Syrian Civil War, with reports indicating at least 92 people killed since dawn.<ref name=loveluck20160924>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-and-russian-airstrikes-continue-major-offensive-to-take-back-aleppo/2016/09/24/cebf5bb4-81cf-11e6-8327-f141a7beb626_story.html|title=Syrian and Russian airstrikes continue major offensive to take back Aleppo}}</ref> [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] suggests that the reported systematic use of [[Incendiary device|incendiary weapons]] and \"[[bunker buster]]\" bombs may be a [[war crime]].<ref name=loveluck20160924/>\n\n;25 September\n* Intense Russian and Syrian airstrikes in and around rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 85 people, with observers claiming that attacking aircraft are employing [[white phosphorus munitions]], [[cluster munitions]], and incendiary and \"bunker buster\" bombs. Since 19 September, the strikes have destroyed so many ambulances that humanintarian aid workers and first responders have great difficulty responding to reports of casualties. At the U.N. Security Council, [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Samantha Power]] accuses Russia of \"barbarism\" and claims the strikes are a war crime, while the [[Permanent Representative of Russia to the United Nations]], [[Vitaly Churkin]], responds that the collapse of the ceasefire is due to transgressions by U.S.-backed rebel forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/us-accuses-russia-of-barbarism-and-war-crimes-in-syria/2016/09/25/c3a00750-833d-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=U.S. accuses Russia of 'barbarism' and war crimes in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;26 September\n* In the first week since the collapse of the ceasefire in the Syrian Civil War, Syrian and Russian aircraft have dropped at least 1,700 bombs on the rebel-held eastern portion of Aleppo, Syria.<ref name=sly20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/darkness-and-fear-in-aleppo-as-the-bombs-rain-down/2016/09/28/07b65246-842e-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Darkness and fear in Aleppo as the bombs rain down}}</ref>\n* The Russian government announces that it has radio location data implicating the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukrainian armed forces]] in the destruction of [[Malaysian Airlines Flight 17]] over eastern [[Ukraine]] in [[2014 in aviation#July|July 2014]] and has ruled out the possibility that a [[surface-to-air missile]] fired from territory held by pro-Russian separatists in [[Ukraine]] shot the airliner down.<ref name=roth20160928>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/dutch-probe-missile-brought-from-russia-downed-malaysia-airline-plane-over-ukraine/2016/09/28/05a9770c-84c5-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Dutch probe: Missile brought from Russia downed Malaysia Airlines plane over Ukraine}}</ref>\n\n;27 September\n* The U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] demonstrates its [[Next Generation Data Communications]] (also called \"Nexcom\" or \"Data Comm\") system \u2013 a component of its [[Next Generation Air Transportation System]] \u2013 to the media at [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] in [[Virginia]]. The system, already installed at [[air traffic control]] towers at 45 airports in the United States, is intended to replace the existing archaic U.S. system of communications between airline pilots and control towers \u2013 which requires printing out [[flight plan]]s in towers, discussion by radio between towers and pilots, and pilots writing down flight plans by hand in the [[cockpit]] \u2013 with all-digital communications, allowing improved speed and efficiency. The FAA plans to install the system at 50 more U.S. airports before the end of 2016, and then to install it at en route air traffic control centers across the United States, with a goal of achieving voiceless, in-flight communications between air traffic controllers and airliner pilots throughout the country by mid-2019. The FAA estimates that the new system will save air carriers $10,000,000,000 over the next 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atwonline.com/connected-aerospace/faa-touts-data-comm-installations-45-us-airport-atc-towers|title=FAA touts Data Comm installations at 45 US airport ATC towers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/new-direct-digital-link-between-tower-and-cockpit-will-speed-planes-on-their-way/2016/09/27/50eb9ec8-843b-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=New direct digital link between tower and cockpit will speed planes on their way}}</ref>\n\n;28 September\n* An Afghan official announces that an early-morning airstrike against a residential building in the [[Achin District]] in eastern Afghanistan's [[Nangarhar Province]] has killed 13 civilians. U.S. military forces in Afghanistan acknowledge that they carried out a \"counterterrorism airstrike\" in Achin and aare investigating whether any civilian casualties resulted from it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/eb969180d190470e9761c395e0a699fb/afghan-official-13-civilians-killed-airstrike-house|title=Afghan official: Airstrike hits house, killing 13 civilians}}</ref>\n* The United States conducts a predawn airstrike in northern [[Somalia]] in defense of troops from Somalia's [[Puntland]] region who report that they have come under fire from [[al-Shabaab (militant group)|al-Shabaab]] forces. Post-strike photographs show two burned-out [[armored vehicle]]s and a number of badly burned bodies at the scene of the strike. A U.S. Department of Defense spokesman claims that the strike killed nine al-Shabaab members and a Puntland police officer says it killed more than a dozen al-Shabaab personnel, while officials of Somalia's [[Galmudug]] [[Administrative divisions of Somalia|autonomous region]] claim that Puntland had tricked the United States into attacking Galmudug soldiers and that the strike had killed 22 of them. The U.S. Department of Defense announces that it will investigate whether the strike killed anyone other than al-Shabaab personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-somalia-security-idUSKCN11Y0UC|title=U.S. accused of killing 22 in misdirected Somalia air strike|date=28 September 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=guled20160930>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b5354cd3f76843e188ea8f801d536c7f/somalia-accuses-us-over-airstrike|title=Somalia accuses US over airstrike}}</ref>\n* During the predawn hours, airstrikes hit two hospitals and a bakery in eastern Aleppo, Syria. Both hospitals are put out of action, and two patients are killed.<ref name=sly20160928/>\n* The [[United States Department of State]] announces that the United States is making preparations to suspend all bilateral cooperation with Russia over Syria \u2013 including the sharing of information between the United States and Russia to support airstrikes against terrorist targets in Syria via a \"Joint Implementation Center\" \u2013 unless Russia takes steps to end the ongoing Syrian and Russian ground and air assault against rebel-held eastern Aleppo and moves to restore the ceasefire agreed to on 12 September. The announcement states that in a telephone conversation earlier in the day with Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergey Lavrov, U.S. Secretary of State John F. Kerry \"made clear that the United States and its partners hold Russia responsible for the situation, including the use of incendiary and 'bunker buster' bombs in an urban environment, a drastic escalation that puts civilians at great risk\" and \"informed [Lavrov] that the United States is making preparations to suspend U.S.-Russia bilateral engagement on Syria \u2013 including on the establishment of a Joint Implementation Center to coordinate [air]strikes on terrorist targets \u2013 unless Russia takes immediate steps to end the assault on Aleppo and restore the cessation of hostilities.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-threatens-to-suspend-all-bilateral-cooperation-with-russia-over-syria/2016/09/28/1ed4a554-8591-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=U.S. threatens to suspend bilateral engagement with Russia over Syria}}</ref>\n* A [[Netherlands|Dutch]] team investigating the crash of Malaysian Airlines Flight 17 in Ukraine in July 2014 announces that it has concluded that the airliner was shot down by a surface-to-air missile fired by a Russian-made [[Buk missile system]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Gadfly,\" U.S. Department of Defense designation SA-11) smuggled from Russia into an area of eastern [[Ukraine]] held by pro-Russian separatists a few hours before it fired at the airliner and returned to Russian territory the following day. The Dutch team says that it has identified over 100 people linked to the firing of the missile and that it will continue its investigation \u2013 extended into at least 2018 \u2013 \u2013in order to determine who ordered it fired. The U.S. Department of State notes that the Dutch team's findings match those of American investigators, while the Russian ministries of defense and foreign affairs dismiss some of the Dutch team's evidence and declare its investigation biased and Russian separatists in Ukraine claim they have no access to sophisticated surface-to-air missiles and blame the airliner's destruction on the Ukrainian armed forces.<ref name=roth20160928/>\n* \"Unauthorized...activity\" by an unmanned aerial vehicle near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), forces the airport to halt all arrivals and departures. Arrivals resume after about 35 minutes and full operations after about 67 minutes. The incident prompts UAE officials to announce plans to tighten the country's regulations regarding drone operations. A similar incident had caused the airport to close on [[2016 in aviation#June|12 June]].<ref name=bbc20160928/>\n\n;29 September\n* United Nations officials condemn the 28 September U.S. counterterrorism airstrike in Afghanistan's Achin District, saying it killed 15 civilians and wounded 12 others; they demand a complete investigation of the incident. Although the United States and the Afghan government claim that the strike targeted a residential compound used by Islamic State personnel, local Afghan officials claim that it killed and injured only civilians. U.S. military officials respond that they take \"all allegations of civilian casualties very seriously\" but add that the Islamic State continues \"to put innocent lives at risk by deliberately surrounding themselves with civilians and dressing in female attire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/un-officials-criticize-fatal-us-airstrike-in-afghanistan/2016/09/29/9d06d122-8672-11e6-a3ef-f35afb41797f_story.html|title=U.N. officials criticize fatal U.S. airstrike in Afghanistan}}</ref>\n* The [[Government of Somalia]] accuses the United States Government of killing 13 Somali soldiers in its 28 September airstrike against al-Shabaab forces and demands an explanation from the United States.<ref name=guled20160930/>\n* Russia responds to U.S. criticism of its air campaign in eastern Aleppo, Syria, by saying that the airstrikes are justified because the United States violated the ceasefire agreement of 12 September by failing to fulfill its promise to separate [[al-Qaeda]]- and Islamic State-linked forces from other rebel forces and because the ceasefire agreement had become unacceptable because it a;;owed \"terrorist groups to take necessary measures to replenish supplies [and] regroup forces.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/russia-says-us-criticism-of-its-actions-in-aleppo-disagrees-with-reality/2016/09/29/9da7cc48-8673-11e6-92c2-14b64f3d453f_story.html|title=Russia says U.S. criticism of its actions in Aleppo 'disagrees with reality'}}</ref>\n\n;30 September\n* Russian and Syrian aircraft conduct heavy airstrikes against rebel-held residential areas in eastern Aleppo, Syria, including the use of white phosphorus and cluster munitions; two more hospitals are among the targets hit during the day. The [[World Health Organization]] estimates that Russian and Syrian airstrikes have killed 338 people in Aleppo since 19 September. The [[Syrian Network for Human Rights]] estimates that Russian airstrikes have killed 3,624 civilians since they began on [[2015 in aviation#September|30 September 2015]], while the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] estimates that they have killed 3,804 civilians. A Russian government spokesman says that Russia has no intention of reducing its involvement in the Syrian Civil War and has no projected end date for its intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/no-sign-of-obamas-predicted-quagmire-as-russias-engagement-in-syria-escalates/2016/09/30/5b3e4d18-8723-11e6-ac72-a29979381495_story.html|title=No sign of Obama\u2019s predicted 'quagmire' as Russia\u2019s engagement in Syria escalates}}</ref>\n* Dutch Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Bert Koenders]] summons the Russian ambassador to the [[Netherlands]] to a meeting in [[The Hague]] to complain about Russian Government statements criticizing the Dutch team investigating the July 2014 crash of Malaysian Airlines Flight 17 in Ukraine. Koenders describes the Russian criticism as \"unsubstantiated\" and \"unacceptable,\" adding, \"Given the convincing nature of the evidence, Russia should respect the results that have been presented, rather than impugning the investigation and sowing doubt.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dutch-call-russian-ambassador-to-hague-meeting-over-flight-mh17-1475241060|title=Dutch Call Russian Ambassador to Hague Meeting Over Flight MH17|first=Maarten van|last=Tartwijk|date=30 September 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n\n;1 October\n* [[Iran]]'s [[Tasnim News Agency]] and [[Press TV]] report that the [[Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps]] has built a new [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] (UAV) with lethal attack capabilities. Named \"Saegheh\" (\"Thunderbolt\"), the new UAV reportedly is similar to a U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[RQ-170 Sentinel]] UAV that crashed in Iran in [[2011 in aviation#December|December 2011]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2a09bacb3a064aa6aef6049ed4145c20/iran-says-new-attack-drone-modeled-captured-us-aircraft|title=Iran says new attack drone modeled on captured US aircraft}}</ref>\n* Iraqi troops shoot down an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) measuring about {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us|spell=in}} long and {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us|spell=in}} wide in [[Iraq]] and discover that it has an explosive attached to its top.<ref name=schmidt20161011>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/12/world/middleeast/iraq-drones-isis.html|title=Pentagon Confronts a New Threat From ISIS: Exploding Drones|first1=Michael S.|last1=Schmidt|first2=Eric|last2=Schmitt|date=11 October 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] or [[Russian Federation Air Force]] aircraft bomb a major hospital known as \"M10\" in rebel-held eastern [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]], for the second time in a week, killing or wounding more than a dozen patients. Doctors at M10 report that the attack includes [[barrel bomb]]s, [[incendiary bomb]]s, and [[cluster munition]]s. Syrian government and Russian aircraft have dropped nearly 2,000 bombs on eastern Aleppo in less than two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/bombing-in-aleppo-puts-another-major-hospital-out-of-service/2016/10/01/1d6dacd8-8802-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|title=Bombing in Aleppo puts another major hospital out of service}}</ref>\n* [[Belavia]] retires its last two [[Tupolev Tu-154]]s from scheduled service, one of the last airlines to retire the Tu-154.\n\n;2 October\n* After [[Kurds in Iraq|Kurdish]] forces shoot down an Islamic State unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) in northern Iraq, take it back to their outpost to examine it, and begin to take it apart, a bomb in the UAV disguised as a battery explodes, killing two Kurdish soldiers and injuring two French paratroopers. It is the first time the Islamic State succeeds in using a UAV to kill people.<ref name=schmidt20161011/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/10/isis-uses-exploding-drones-to-kill-kurdish-troops.html|title=ISIS Uses Exploding Drones to Kill Kurdish Troops|first=Charley|last=Lanyon}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] says that it is interested in beginning passenger service at the airports in [[Stara Zagora]], [[Gorna Oryahovitsa]], and [[Ruse, Bulgaria|Ruse]], Bulgaria, in 2017, with a final decision on the service to be made in the coming months.\n* [[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will add 10 [[ATR 72-500]] airliners to its fleet to provide service on domestic routes, replacing the airline's [[ATR 42]]s. The airline is to take delivery of its first ATR 72-500 in early 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/166648687096617/photos/a.180194489075370.1073741828.166648687096617/190892348005584/?type=3|title=Log in or Sign Up to View}}</ref>\n*[[Argentina]]'s national airline [[Aerolineas Argentinas]] announces that it has converted its existing order for [[Boeing 737-800]] airliners to an order for the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] variant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49738-aerolineas-argentinas-converts-b737-800-order-to-max|title=Aerolineas Argentinas converts B737-800 order to MAX}}</ref>\n* In six flights flown by four [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17 Globemaster III]] and two [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]] aircraft provided by [[United States Transportation Command]], the [[United States Navy]] evacuates about 700 spouses and children and a number of family pets from [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] in [[Cuba]] to [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]], [[Florida]], as [[Hurricane Matthew]] approaches [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay]]. It is the first major airlift of non-essential residents from the Guantanamo Bay base since September 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=96983|title=Families Evacuating Naval Station Guantanamo Bay, Cuba|first=This story was written by Navy Region Southeast Public|last=Affairs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article105393586.html|title=Guant\u00e1namo Navy base begins evacuating 700 parents and kids, plus pets, ahead of Hurricane Matthew \u2013 Miami Herald}}</ref>\n\n;3 October\n* In support of [[Afghan Army]] and security forces fighting against [[Taliban]] ground offensives in [[Afghanistan]], [[Afghan Air Force]] aircraft conduct airstrikes around [[Kunduz]], while in [[Lashkargah]], U.S. aircraft strike Taliban forces and [[United States Army]] [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s operate in support of Afghan ground forces fighting to retake the city from Taliban insurgents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/taliban-opens-offensives-in-afghanistan-before-government-appeal-to-aid-donors/2016/10/03/d42e05d0-8938-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Taliban opens offensives in Afghanistan ahead of government appeal to donors}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of State]] announces that it is withdrawing U.S. personnel from [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], who had spent several weeks there planning the coordination of U.S. and Russian airstrikes against terrorist forces in Syria. The withdrawal comes as the [[United States]] abandons its efforts to work with [[Russia]] in Syria because of heavy civilian casualties resulting from intense Russian Federation Air Force and Syrian Arab Air Force airstrikes against rebel-held eastern Aleppo, Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-suspends-efforts-to-work-with-russia-on-syria-cease-fire/2016/10/03/b907dbe2-8991-11e6-bff0-d53f592f176e_story.html|title=U.S. abandons efforts to work with Russia on Syria}}</ref>\n* Since the spring of 2015, U.S. aircraft have flown more than 1,000 [[aerial refueling]] sorties in support of [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] aircraft engaged in combat in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]], providing them with tens of millions of pounds of fuel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-casualties-in-yemen-bring-charges-of-us-responsibility-for-saudi-actions/2016/10/03/29a9b606-864d-11e6-ac72-a29979381495_story.html|title=Civilian casualties in Yemen bring charges of U.S. responsibility for Saudi actions}}</ref>\n\n;4 October\n* U.S. military officials in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan, announce that one U.S. Army helicopter has fired at [[Taliban]] insurgent forces in Kunduz, Afghanistan, in defense of Afghan ground forces opposing a Taliban offensive there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-forces-battle-in-key-northern-city-amid-taliban-offensives-around-country/2016/10/04/7dd88736-8a1f-11e6-bff0-d53f592f176e_story.html|title=Afghan forces battle in key northern city amid Taliban offensives across country}}</ref>\n* Russia announces that it has added operational [[S-300 (missile system)|S-300]] (U.S. DoD designation \"SA-10,\" NATO reporting name \"Grumble\") [[surface-to-air missile]] systems to its air defense forces in Syria, where they join Russian [[S-200 (missile)|S-200]] (U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] designation \"SA-5,\" [[NATO reporting name]] \"Gammon\"), and [[Buk missile system|Buk]] (U.S. DoD designation \"SA-17,\" NATO reporting name \"Grizzly\") already there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/776de7fbc4bc4d14a8ef950e94bac593/russia-sends-more-air-defense-missiles-Syria|title=Russia sends more air defense missiles to Syria}}</ref><ref name=oliphant20161006>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/06/russian-air-defence-missiles-would-respond-if-us-launches-air-st/|title=Russia warns it will shoot down alliance jets over Syria if US launches air strikes against Assad}}</ref> The S-300 and S-400 missiles give Russian forces the capability to shoot down aircraft at a range of up to {{convert|250|mi|km}}, covering almost all of Syria, all of [[Cyprus]], and significant portions of [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Turkey]], and the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/russian-air-defense-raises-stakes-of-us-confrontation-in-syria/2016/10/17/85c89220-948c-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Russian air defense raises stakes of U.S. confrontation in Syria}}</ref>\n\n;6 October\n* Russia warns that it will view any airstrikes in Syria by the U.S.-led coalition against pro-Syrian-government forces as a threat to Russian military personnel and that its surface-to-air missile systems deployed in Syria would fire immediately at any aircraft appearing to pose a threat to them.<ref name=oliphant20161006/>\n* [[Finland]] notes what it suspects are two separate violations of its [[airspace]] by Russian [[Sukhoi Su-27]] (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighters over the [[Gulf of Finland]].<ref name=\"ap20161007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/finland-us-to-deepen-military-ties-through-pact/2016/10/07/fc8eaf7a-8cb7-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Finland, U.S. to deepen military ties through pact}}</ref>\n* At a meeting in [[Montreal]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO) overwhelmingly ratifies a 15-year agreement to curb [[Global warming|global-warming]]-related emissions from civil airliners on international flights (domestic flights already are covered separately by the [[Paris Agreement]] of December 2015, set to take effect in November 2016) by an estimated 2,500,000,000 tons between 2021 and 2035; it is the first international [[Climate change|climate-change]]-related pact to govern a single industry. Under the agreement, the maximum permissible emissions level permitted for commercial airlines beginning in 2021 will be set at the level of emissions in 2020; after that, and through 2035, airlines that exceed the 2020 limit will have to buy [[carbon credit]]s from other industries to compensate for exceeding the emissions limit. Participation is voluntary from 2021 through 2027, then mandatory from 2028 through 2035. The agreement is expected to cost airlines $5,300,000,000 annually and as much as $23,900,000,000 in 2035. Each of the ICAO's 191 member countries still must act on their own to put the agreement's limits into effect; 65 countries \u2013 including [[China]], the United States, and all 44 member countries of the [[European Union]]'s aviation conference \u2013 have agreed to participate, while Russia plans not to participate in the voluntary phase and [[India]] has expressed reservations about the agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_AIRCRAFT_EMISSIONS_AGREEMENT?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-10-06-13-25-15|title=Lowy, Joan, \"UN agreement reached on aircraft climate-change emissions,\" Associated Press, October 6, 2016, 1:54 p.m. EDT.}}</ref>\n\n;7 October\n* The [[Government of Finland]] announces its suspicions that Russian Sukhoi Su-27 (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighters violated Finnish airspace over the Gulf of Finland the previous day. Russia responds by denouncing the Finnish claim, asserting that its aircraft remained over [[international waters]].<ref name=\"ap20161007\"/>\n*[[Estonia]] announces that a Russian Sukhoi Su-27 (NATO reporting name \"Flanker\") fighter violated its airspace for less than a minute earlier in the day.<ref name=\"ap20161007\"/>\n*Russia ratifies a treaty with Syria which among other things grants it a permanent airbase in Syria at [[Khmeimim (air base)|Khmeimim]], effective retroactively to [[2015 in aviation#August|26 August 2015]], the date it was signed.<ref name=filipov20161007>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/10/07/russia-has-its-permanent-airbase-in-syria-now-its-looking-at-cuba-and-vietnam/|title=Russia has its permanent air base in Syria. Now it\u2019s looking at Cuba and Vietnam.}}</ref>\n*The Russian newspaper ''[[Kommersant]]'' reports that a Russian military official said that Russian forces in Syria are under orders to \"shoot to kill\" if they come under attack, presumably by aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition.<ref name=filipov20161007/> It also reports that Russia is considering deploying [[Sukhoi Su-25]] (NATO reporting name \"Frogfoot\") aircraft to Syria. Russia had withdrawn all Su-25s from Syria in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]].<ref name=filipov20161007/>\n*[[United States Secretary of State]] [[John F. Kerry]] calls for Russia and Syria to face [[war crime]]s charges for bombing civilian targets in Aleppo, Syria. Russian officials condemn the idea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/john-kerry-urges-war-crimes-probe-into-syrian-and-russian-bombing-of-civilians/2016/10/07/8056426c-8c9c-11e6-875e-2c1bfe943b66_story.html|title=Kerry urges war crimes probe into Syrian and Russian bombing of civilians}}</ref>\n*[[Qatar Airways]] announces that it has made a deal with [[Boeing]] worth up to $18,600,000,000 to buy up to 100 airliners. The deal includes purchasing 10 [[Boeing 777]]s and 30 [[Boeing 787]]s for a combined $11,700,000,000 and up to 60 [[Boeing 737]]s for as much as $6,900,000,000. The purchase of Boeing 737s marks the first Qatar Airways purchase of single-aisle airliners from Boeing since 2001. Qatar Airways had expressed frustration with [[Airbus]] over delays in the delivery of [[Airbus A320neo|A320neo]] airliners it had ordered, but says it will continue to work with Airbus for delivery of the A320neos despite its Boeing 737 order.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n*[[Belarus]]\u2032 national airline [[Belavia]] officially retires its last [[Tupolev Tu-154|Tupolev Tu-154M]] (NATO reporting name \"Careless\") airliner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49901-belaruss-belavia-ends-scheduled-tu-154m-operations|title=Belarus's Belavia ends scheduled Tu-154M operations}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] outlines [[Sofia Airport]] as its first international long-haul base, with flights to begin in March 2017 using a pair of [[Airbus A330-200]]s offering service to [[Beijing]], China; [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]; and [[New York City]] in the [[United States]]. Bulgaria Air also is contemplating service from Sofia to [[Mumbai]], India, and [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]].\n*[[Airbus]] officials indicate that three unwanted [[SriLankan Airlines]] [[Airbus A350 XWB|Airbus A350-900]]s may be delivered instead to Bulgaria Air.\n*Turkey's regional carrier [[Borajet]] signs a long-term lease agreement with [[AerCap]] involving five [[Embraer E-Jet E2 family|Embraer E-Jet E2]]s, consisting of three E190 E2s and two E195-E2s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49920-turkeys-borajet-confirms-emb-190-e2-lease-plans|title=Turkey's Borajet confirms EMB-190-E2 lease plans}}</ref>\n\n;8 October\n* The [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] conducts [[October 2016 Sana'a air raid|at least three airstrikes]] against the Grand Hall in [[Sana'a]], [[Yemen]], as mourners gather for the funeral of the father of a senior [[Houthi]] official, killing 140 people and injuring 534 others. It is one of deadliest single attacks since the Saudi coalition began its intervention in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] in [[2015 in aviation#March|March 2015]]. The [[Al-Arabiya]] satellite news network airs a report saying that various Saudi military officials deny that the coalition conducted the strike; [[Saudi Arabia]] often has denied involvement in airstrikes against civilian targets during its intervention in Yemen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/airstrike-killed-more-than-80-injured-hundreds-at-yemen-funeral/2016/10/08/64a31eae-8d74-11e6-8cdc-4fbb1973b506_story.html|title=Airstrike kills more than 100, injures hundreds at Yemen funeral}}</ref><ref name=oliphant20161009>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/09/saudi-arabia-promises-investigation-following-outrage-at-funeral/|title=Saudi Arabia promises investigation following outrage at Yemen funeral airstrike that killed 140}}</ref>\n* Russia vetoes a [[United Nations Security Council resolution]] intended to bring the Russian and Syran bombing of the rebel-held eastern portion of Aleppo, Syria, to an immediate end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-vetoes-unsecurity-council-resolution-to-end-aleppo-bombing/2016/10/08/bfc67d32-8d72-11e6-8cdc-4fbb1973b506_story.html|title=Russia vetoes U.N. Security Council resolution to end Aleppo bombing}}</ref>\n\n;9 October\n*An [[Afghan Army]] [[Mil Mi-17]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Hip\") helicopter crashes in [[Baghlan Province]] in northern Afghanistan, killing all eight Afghan Army soldiers on board. The [[Taliban]] claims to have shot it down, but the [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Defense]] says the crash resulted from a technical failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/world/1106281/seven-dead-as-afghan-army-helicopter-crashes-officials|title=Bangkok Post|first=Post Publishing|last=PCL.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/10/09/eight-killed-in-afghanistan-army-helicopter-crash.html|title=Eight killed in Afghanistan army helicopter crash|date=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Saudi Arabia]] promises an investigation into the Saudi-led coalition's deadly 8 October airstrike against a funeral in Yemen, adding that it will invite U.S. experts to take part.<ref name=oliphant20161009/>\n*The [[United Nations]] estimates that airstrikes by the Saudi-led coalition are responsible for 60 percent of the estimated 3,800 civilian deaths in Yemen since the airstrikes began in March 2015.<ref name=oliphant20161009/>\n\n;10 October\n*Airbus announces that its Chief Operating Officer for Customers [[John Leahy (executive)|John Leahy]] will visit Bulgaria in November, the first visit to southeastern Europe by an Airbus executive.\n*[[Air Madagascar]] announces the resumption services to [[China]] in 2017 with flights between [[Antananarivo]], [[Madagascar]], and [[Guangzhou]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/49926-air-madagascar-to-resume-china-flights-in-mid-1q17|title=Air Madagascar to resume China flights in mid-1Q17}}</ref>\n\n;11 October\n* Airstrikes targeting the rebel-held Bustan al-Qasr neighborhood of Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 14 people, with one report placing the number of dead at 16. Activists report the use of \"[[bunker buster]]\" bombs during the strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2016-10-11/syrian-opposition-activists-airstrikes-kill-8-in-aleppo|title=Anonymous, \"Airstrikes in Syria's Aleppo and shelling in south kill 20,\" Associated Press, 11 October 2016, 8:18 p.m.}}</ref>\n* A [[Piper PA-34 Seneca]] carrying a student pilot and his flight instructor crashes into a utility pole in [[East Hartford, Connecticut|East Hartford]], [[Connecticut]], and bursts into flames, killing the student and injuring the instructor, who tells investigators that the crash occurred after a physical altercation in the [[cockpit]] between the two men. The following day, the U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] announces that it believes that the crash was intentional and that it is transferring the crash investigation to the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/12/us/connecticut-plane-crash-possibly-intentional/index.html|title=Fatal plane crash in Connecticut was intentional, authorities suspect|author1=Rene Marsh |author2=Chris Boyette |author3=Shachar Peled|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/fbi-joins-connecticut-plane-crash-probe-tight-lipped/story?id=42746661|title=NTSB Cites 'Intentional Act' in Connecticut Plane Crash|work=ABC News|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;12 October\n*[[China Southern Airlines]] finalizes an order with [[Boeing]] for twelve [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787-9]] airliners, becoming China's first Boeing 787 customer. The deal is worth up to $3,200,000,000, and China Southern is to take delivery of the airliners between 2018 and 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-boeing-china-southern-20161012-story.html|title=Boeing wins $3.2 billion order from China Southern as 787 soars|first=Anand Krishnamoorthy and Julie|last=Johnsson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20161012/161019838/china-southern-airlines-to-buy-a-dozen-dreamliners-from-boeing-co|title=China Southern to buy 12 787 jets|first=David|last=Wren}}</ref>\n* The U.S. startup company Zipline uses an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) to deliver blood to a remote hospital in western [[Rwanda]]. Plans call for Rwanda to officially launch the world's first nationwide UAV delivery service on 14 October, with Zipline's UAVs operating 24 hours a day to make up to 150 deliveries a day. The 31-pound (14-kg) fixed-wing UAVs, which have an operational range of {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}}, fly below {{convert|500|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} to avoid commercial aircraft and drop packages to customers using disposable [[parachute]]s. Zipline plans to expand its operations into eastern Rwanda in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewashingtonpost.pressreader.com/the-washington-post|title=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2016/10/13/in-rwanda-life-saving-blood-now-drops-from-the-sky/|title=In Rwanda, lifesaving blood now drops from drones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37646474|title=Rwanda begins Zipline commercial drone deliveries|first=Dan|last=Simmons|date=14 October 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/13/13267868/zipline-drone-delivery-rwanda-blood-launch|title=Drones begin delivering blood in Rwanda|date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/10/13/technology/rwanda-drone-hospital/index.html|title=Rwanda's hospitals will use drones to deliver medical supplies|first=Matt|last=McFarland|date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trucks.com/2016/10/13/ups-zipline-drone-deliveries/|title=Zipline, UPS Begin Using Drones for Rwanda Blood Deliveries|first=Jerry|last=Hirsch|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;13 October\n*Airbus president [[Fabrice Br\u00e9gier]] holds talks with [[Ministry of Finance (Bulgaria)|Bulgarian Finance Minister]] [[Vladislav Goranov]] wants that the national airline [[Bulgaria Air]] agrees to possibility order for two next generation wide body airliners believed to be [[Airbus A350 XWB|A350-900]] worth up to $3,000,000,000. It is the first time that Br\u00e9gier and Goranov should visit in Sofia, to begin in November. A cooperation deal is signed between Airbus and Bulgaria whereas the company's subsidiary head office is located in [[Sofia, Bulgaria|Sofia]], with its renewal program of this new models.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* Former [[Premier of Alberta]] [[Jim Prentice]] is killed in the crash of a [[Cessna Citation family]] shortly after take-off from [[Kelowna, British Columbia|Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. The other three people on the plane also die.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jim-prentice-plane-crash-killed-1.3804941|title=Ex-Alberta premier Jim Prentice killed in B.C. plane crash with 3 others}}</ref>\n\n;14 October\n*[[Malaysia]]'s [[Ministry of Defence (Malaysia)|Minister of Defense]], [[Hishammuddin Hussein]], announces that Malaysia will send fixed-wing combat aircraft and helicopters to the [[Philippines]] for the first time since [[2013 in aviation#March|March 2013]]. The aircraft will support nearly 100 Malaysian troops in operations on [[Mindanao]] against the Islamic State-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]], [[Khalifa Islamiyah Mindanao]], and [[Maute group|Maute]] factions. The deployment awaits the completion of final negotiations.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n* During the preceding two weeks, aircraft of the U.S.-led coalition have conducted 66 strikes against Islamic State targets around [[Mosul]], Iraq, in preparation for a ground offensive by [[Iraqi Army]] and allied forces intended to recapture the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/mosul-offensive-poses-key-test-for-us-strategy-against-islamic-state/2016/10/14/d6c883a6-920c-11e6-9c85-ac42097b8cc0_story.html|title=Mosul offensive poses key test for U.S. strategy against Islamic State}}</ref>\n\n;15 October\n* The [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]-based [[Joint Incidents Assessment Team]] (JIAT), an investigative body created by the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen, issues a statement that the coalition wrongly [[October 2016 Sana'a air raid|bombed]] a funeral on 8 October in Sana'a, Yemen, killing more than 100 people. The JIAT finds that the strike occurred because someone affiliated with the chief of staff of [[President of Yemen]] [[Abdrabbuh Mansour Hadi]] had incorrectly assured the coalition that the funeral was a gathering of armed [[Houthi]] rebel leaders and that the coalition's air operations center ordered the attack without the approval of the coalition command and without following precautionary procedures designed to avoid strikes against civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-backed-saudi-led-coalition-claims-responsibility-for-yemen-funeral-attack-that-killed-more-than-150/2016/10/15/43a3adea-92bf-11e6-a6a3-d50061aa9fae_story.html|title=U.S.-backed, Saudi-led coalition found responsible for Yemen funeral attack that killed more than 100}}</ref>\n* The [[Turkish Air Force]] conducts strikes against Islamic State targets in support of a ground offensive by Syrian opposition groups intended take [[Dabiq, Syria]], from the Islamic State.<ref name=mroue20161015>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/25934af492684715b92c94485b23fdfa/turkey-backed-rebels-attack-stronghold-syria|title=Turkey-backed forces attack IS stronghold in Syria}}</ref>\n* Syrian Arab Air Force and Russian Federation Air Force raids hit rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo, Syria, and an air attack probably by either Russian or Syrian aircraft in [[Termanin]], Syria, kills at least eight people and injures dozens of others.<ref name=mroue20161015/> \n* A [[United States Department of Transportation]] ban announced the previous day on [[Galaxy Note 7]] [[smartphone]]s aboard any airliner flying within, to, or from the United States goes into effect throughout the country at 12:00 noon [[Eastern Daylight Time]]. [[Samsung Electronics]] already had recalled the Galaxy Note 7 because of reports of it catching fire or exploding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/10/14/wp/2016/10/14/samsung-galaxy-note-7-banned-from-airplanes/|title=The Samsung Galaxy Note 7 is officially banned from airplanes}}</ref>\n\n;16 October\n* Airstrikes by the Turkish Air Force and international coalition strike Islamic State targets in Dabiq and [[Arshak, Syria|Arshak]], Syria, as Turkish-backed Syrian opposition ground forces capture Dabiq from the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/a5b5d097a193499f900fb70a83cbdb3d/turkish-backed-syrian-opposition-captures-dabiq|title=Turkish-backed Syrian opposition captures Dabiq from IS}}</ref>\n\n;17 October\n* Aircraft and [[artillery]] of the U.S.-led coalition strike Islamic State targets around Mosul as a ground offensive to take Mosul, Iraq, from the Islamic State by [[Iraqi Army]] and police forces and Kurdish ''[[pesh merga]]'' forces begins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi-forces-ready-for-zero-hour-in-assault-on-mosul/2016/10/16/e899f83c-9246-11e6-bc00-1a9756d4111b_story.html|title=Iraqi forces begin assault to retake Mosul from Islamic State}}</ref>\n* Syrian government and Russian airstrikes in eastern Aleppo, Syria, kill at least 36 people.<ref name=mroue20161017>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/037dc6e614a14b0680a7ffb29e5de0c3/syrias-assad-seeks-egypts-help-fighting-terrorism|title=Russia sets brief cease-fire for Aleppo as strikes kill 36}}</ref>\n* The Russian government announces that Russia and the Syrian government will observe a unilateral cease fire from 8:00&nbsp;a.m. to 4:00&nbsp;p.m. on 20 October for a \"humanitarian pause\" to allow people to evacuate to [[Idlib Governorate]] from rebel-held areas in Aleppo.<ref name=mroue20161017/>\n\n;19 October\n* [[United States Secretary of Transportation]] [[Anthony Foxx]] announces new rules to protect airline passengers in the United States. They include an eventual requirement for airlines to refund baggage fees when baggage is \"substantially\" delayed, rather than only when it is lost; a requirement likely to go into effect in January 2018 for airlines to report the number of mishandled bags as a proportion of checked bags rather than in relation to the number of passengers carried; a requirement likely to go into effect by the end of 2016 for online airline booking services to disclose any bias they have toward booking on particular airlines; an eventual requirement for airlines to include regional airlines that operate as part of their networks when reporting their on-time performance; and, for the first time, a requirement likely to go into effect in 2018 for airlines to report the number of [[wheelchair]]s they mishandle. Foxx notes that the U.S. Department of Transportation expects 700 million passengers to travel on 9 million airline flights in the United States during 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/obama-administration-unveils-new-rules-to-protect-air-travelers/2016/10/19/1dc7cd3e-960e-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Obama administration unveils new rules to protect air travelers}}</ref>\n\n;19\u201320 October (overnight)\n* Turkish Air Force jets carry out 26 strikes against positions of the [[Kurds in Syria|Kurdish]] [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) in three villages \u2013 [[al-Hasiya]], [[Um al-Qura, Syria|Um al-Qura]], and [[Maarat Umm Hawsh]] \u2013 northeast of Aleppo, Syria, that the Kurdish-led [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] had recently captured from the Islamic State. Turkey claims that the strikes destroy nine buildings, an [[armored vehicle]], and four other ground vehicles belonging to the YPG. Reports of the number of casualties vary from 14 plus dozens wounded, according to the [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]], to 160 to 200 killed, according to the [[Turkish Armed Forces|Turkish armed forces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-kurds-idUSKCN12K0ER|title=Turkey bombs Syrian Kurdish militia allied to U.S.-backed force|date=20 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;20 October\n* Iraqi Army [[attack helicopter]]s support ground forces attacking Islamic State positions in [[Bartella]], Iraq, during the offensive to retake Mosul. Islamic State gunfire damages one helicopter, but it lands safely and its crew is evacuated.<ref name=morris20161020>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/new-kurdish-offensive-opens-on-mosuls-north-as-iraqi-forces-push-from-the-east/2016/10/20/19092040-9645-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=Iraq\u2019s U.S.-trained counterterrorism troops join attack on Mosul}}</ref>\n* Kurdish ''peshmerga'' forces suffer increased casualties during the day in combat against the Islamic State during the Mosul offensive. A statement by the Kurdish general command ascribes the increase to a lack of air support, saying that support and air cover by the U.S.-led coalition \"were not as decisive as in the past.\"<ref name=morris20161020/>\n* Russia and the Syrian government begin a three-day pause in their bombardment of rebel-held eastern Aleppo, Syria, to allow the delivery of humanitarian supplies and the evacuation of around 200 critically injured people. The ceasefire is longer than the eight-hour pause Syria and Russia had announced on 17 October, but less than the five days requested by international aid officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/aleppo-residents-in-rebel-held-areas-wary-of-russian-syrian-humanitarian-pause/2016/10/20/26d17fa2-96a8-11e6-bb29-bf2701dbe0a3_story.html|title=Aleppo residents in rebel-held areas wary of Russian-Syrian humanitarian pause}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]] warns Russia that it could face sanctions if its bombardment of civilians in Aleppo, Syria, continues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/european-leaders-threaten-new-sanctions-against-russia/2016/10/20/ce5f8240-960e-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=European leaders threaten new sanctions against Russia}}</ref>\n* [[American Airlines]] reports a drop of 56 percent in net income during the third quarter of 2016, with net income between 1 July and 30 September of $737.000,000 representing a decline from $1,700,000,000 from the same period in 2015. Planes flying less full and increased labor costs are factors in the decline, as is a large tax bill. Overall revenue for the quarter was $10,600,000,000, a decline of 1.1 percent from the same period in 2015. American is the world's largest airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2016/10/20/american-airlines-earnings/92451704/|title=American Airlines earnings drop 56% in 3Q, but meet expectations}}</ref>\n* The French start-up company Skylights releases the second iteration of its Bravo wearable headset device that allows airline passengers to view two-dimensional and three-dimensional movies and [[virtual reality]] entertainment content in their seats. The company has conducted trial runs of the technology over the previous year on European airlines, including [[Air France]], [[KLM]], and [[XL Airways France|XL Airways]], and hopes that rentable Bravo devices will become a mainstream form of in-flight entertainment aboard airliners around the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2016/10/20/the-airplane-is-preparing-to-land-please-remove-your-virtual-reality-headset/ |last=Overly|first= Steven|title=The airplane is preparing to land. Please remove your virtual reality headset|work=[[The Washington Post]] |date= 20 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;21 October\n*A [[Skol Airlines]] [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopter with at least 22 people on board [[2016 Skol Airlines Mil Mi-8 Siberia crash|crashes]] in Russia's [[Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug]], killing at least 19 people.\n*Amid growing complaints by the Iraqi Army and Kurdish ''peshmerga'' forces of inadequate air support by the U.S.-led coalition for their ground offensive to retake Mosul, Iraq, from the Islamic State, the [[United States Department of State]] envoy to the coalition, Special Presidential Envoy for the Global Coalition to Counter the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant [[Brett H. McGurk]], reports massive coalition airstrikes during the day in support of both forces. The airstrikes have involved aircraft ranging from attack helicopters to [[United States Air Force]] [[B-52H Stratofortress]] bombers. Iraqi ground forces also complain of insufficient aerial reconnaissance support by coalition unmanned aerial vehicles. The coalition's air power reportedly has been spread thin by the size and scope of the ground offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/iraqi--kurdish-forces-say-they-feel-let-down-by-level-of-us-led-air-support/2016/10/21/f37b0b02-97c2-11e6-9cae-2a3574e296a6_story.html|title=Iraqi, Kurdish forces say they feel let down by level of U.S.-led air support}}</ref>\n*Bulgaria Air announces that it will begin round-trip service to [[Turkey]], with flights between [[Sofia Airport]] in Sofia, Bulgaria, and [[Istanbul]]'s [[Atat\u00fcrk International Airport]] in Turkey commencing in January 2017. [[Turkish Airlines]] also will provide service between the two airports, with a codeshare partnership between the two airlines expected to come in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n*[[Turkish Airlines]] announces that it has suspended services to [[Najaf]], [[Sulaymaniyah]], and [[Basrah]], Iraq, because of the Iraqi and Kurdish offensive to retake Mosul from the Islamic State.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n* The [[Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden]] rules that unmanned aerial vehicles equipped with cameras are a form of surveillance device requiring a special surveillance permit to operate. The application process in [[Sweden]] for such permits is expensive, with no guarantee that a license will be granted, and the ruling causes consternation among UAV owners and the UAV industry in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/sweden-just-made-whole-lot-073337188.html|title=Sweden has just made it a whole lot harder to fly camera drones}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37761872|title=Sweden bans cameras on drones|date=25 October 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n* Amid border tensions between [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]], at least one and possibly two [[Venezuelan Air Force]] fighter aircraft approach [[Avianca]] Flight 011, a [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]] flying at an attitude of over {{convert|36000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over western Venezuela en route from [[Madrid]], [[Spain]], to [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], with 250 passengers aboard. The airliner makes a sharp turn off course to the north in order to reach Colombian [[airspace]] quickly. In the wake of the incident, Colombia suspends all flights by Colombian aircraft to and from Venezuela and orders its aircraft to avoid flying over Venezuelan airspace, and [[President of Venezuela]] [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] orders an investigation of the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/22/colombia-venezuela-airline-warplane-diplomatic-incident|title=Colombia airline avoids Venezuela after warplane approaches flight|last=Reuters|date=22 October 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=forero20161022>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/airline-suspends-venezuela-flights-after-plane-is-tracked-1477165809|title=Colombian Airline Avianca to Resume Flights to Venezuela|first=Juan|last=Forero|date=23 October 2016|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n;22 October\n* The humanitarian pause in the bombardment of Aleppo, Syria, that Russia and the Syrian government had declared on 20 October comes to an end during the evening as aircraft \u2013 presumably belonging to the Russian Federation Air Force or Syrian Arab Air Force \u2013 bomb rebel-held neighborhoods in eastern Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/cease-fire-crumbles-in-aleppo-as-fighting-resumes/2016/10/23/a30d7c16-9918-11e6-b3c9-f662adaa0048_story.html|title=Cease-fire crumbles in Aleppo as fighting resumes}}</ref> A planned evacuation of injured people and of civilians from eastern Aleppo \u2013 the main purpose of the pause \u2013 did not take place during the pause.<ref name=mroue20161024>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_SYRIA?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-10-24-10-55-48|title=News from The Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n;23 October\n* Following diplomatic talks between the [[Government of Colombia]] and the [[Government of Venezuela]], Colombia lifts its suspension of flights by Colombian aircraft to, from, and over Venezuela. It had instituted the flight ban after at least one Venezelan Air Force fighter aircraft approached an Avianca Boeing 787 Dreamliner over western Venezuela on the evening of 21 October, forcing the airliner to veer off course and into Colombian airspace.<ref name=forero20161022/>\n* A [[Morton County, North Dakota]], Sheriff's Department helicopter monitoring a protest at a [[Dakota Access Pipeline]] construction site in [[North Dakota]] reports that an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) operated by the protestors has approached it in a threatening manner. Law enforcement officers in [[North Dakota]] open fire on the UAV with \"less than lethal\" ammunition, damaging it, after which its operator lands it. Protestors claim that police shot at the UAV because they do not want their activities filmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/oct/23/north-dakota-pipeline-protesters-drone-shot-after-/|title=North Dakota pipeline protesters' drone shot after buzzing police helicopter|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/10/24/authorities-open-fire-at-unmanned-drone-during-north-dakota-pipeline-protests.html|title=Authorities open fire at unmanned drone during North Dakota pipeline protests|date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n;24 October\n*The [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] announces that [[Singapore]]'s low-cost carrier [[Jetstar Asia Airways]] would consider developing [[Manila]]'s [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] into an operational base in 2017. It will be the first foreign airline to set up a base in the [[Philippines]]. Ninoy Aquino International is also the base of [[Philippine Airlines]], [[Cebu Pacific]], [[AirAsia Philippines]], and [[Cebgo]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n*Airstrikes kill at least 13 people in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]].<ref name=mroue20161024/> In [[Moscow]], Russian Deputy Foreign Minister [[Sergei Ryabkov]] says that Russia is not planning another \"humanitarian pause\" in Syria anytime soon because rebel forces did not \"behave properly\" during the 20\u201322 October pause.<ref name=mroue20161024/> \n*A [[Luxembourg]]-registered [[CAE Aviation]] [[Fairchild Swearingen Metroliner|Fairchild SA227-AT Merlin IVC]] (registration N577MX) on a surveillance mission for the French [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes]] [[2016 Malta Fairchild Merlin crash|crashes]] just after takeoff from [[Malta International Airport]] in [[Malta]], killing its entire crew of five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20161024-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Swearingen SA227-AT Expediter N577MX Malta-Luqa Airport (MLA)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;25 October\n* British [[Secretary of State for Transport]] [[Chris Grayling]] announces that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] had decided to endorse the addition of a third runway at [[London]]'s [[Heathrow Airport]] after decades of delay. The construction project, under consideration since the 1970s and not expected to begin for years, will require the demolition of 738 homes in [[Harmondsworth]], [[Longford, London|Longford]], and [[Sipson]] and cost an estimated \u00a317,600,000,000. [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] postpones a vote in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on the matter until 2017, and the vote may not take place for as long as a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/26/world/europe/heathrow-airport-expansion.html|title=Third Heathrow Airport Runway Backed by British Government|first=Stephen|last=Castle|date=25 October 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bt.com/news/news-extra/how-the-cost-of-a-third-heathrow-runway-would-stack-up-11363990002861|title=How the cost of a third Heathrow runway would stack up}}</ref>\n* Disabled [[United States Army]] veteran Lisa McCombs, a sufferer of [[post-traumatic stress disorder]], files a lawsuit against [[American Airlines]] for a series of incidents between 25 and 27 October 2015 at [[Manhattan, Kansas|Manhattan]], [[Kansas]], and [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]], [[Texas]], while she was on her way to [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]], [[Mississippi]], in which airline personnel refused to allow her to board aircraft operated by the [[American Airlines Group]] subsidiary [[Envoy Air]] with her [[service dog]] and publicly humiliated and intimidated her when she protested that her dog was pre-approved to travel with her aboard the planes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/articles/combat-vet-sues-american-airlines-for-rejecting-her-service-dog|title=Combat vet sues American Airlines for rejecting her service dog|first=Army|last=Times}}</ref>\n* Legendary American [[World War II]], [[air show]], and [[test pilot]] [[Bob Hoover]] dies at the age of 94.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/top-pilot-who-stole-plane-to-escape-wwii-prison-camp-dies/2016/10/25/3edcb86a-9b25-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=- The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n;26 October\n*Russian or Syrian airstrikes against a residential area, an [[elementary school]], and a [[middle school]] in the village of [[Haas, Syria|Haas]] in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] kill at least 26 civilians, 15 to 20 of them children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-attack-idUSKCN12Q19D|title=Air strikes in Syria's Idlib kill 26, mostly children: rescuers, monitor|date=26 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n*Two [[Eritrean Air Force]] pilots defect to [[Ethiopia]], flying their jet fighters from [[Eritrea]] to [[Mek'ele]]. [[Ethiopian Air Force]] fighters escort them to Mek'ele after they enter Ethiopian [[airspace]]. It is the first time that Eritrean pilots have defected to Ethiopia with their jets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/eritrean-pilots-defect-ethiopia-jets-opposition-43096487|title=ABC News|first=ABC|last=News}}</ref>\n\n;27 October\n* The [[Government of Turkey]] issues warrants for the detention of 73 Turkish military pilots \u2013 two [[colonel]]s and 71 [[lieutenant]]s \u2013 suspected of involvement in the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|19 July 2016 attempted ''coup d'\u00e9tat'']] in [[Turkey]], bringing 45 of them in for detention, and arrests another 29 military pilots that already had been detained for their alleged participation in the ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]''. Eighteen other military pilots previously detained are released, although nine of them are placed on [[probation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-issues-warrants-for-73-pilots-linked-to-gulen/2016/10/27/92cdde68-9c1f-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=Sorry, we can\u2019t seem to find the page you\u2019re looking for.|date=27 October 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n* [[Eastern Air Lines Flight 3452]], a [[Boeing 737-700]] (registration N278EA) serving as the [[2016 United States presidential election|campaign]] plane for the 2016 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] nominee for [[Vice President of the United States|vice president of the United States]], [[Governor of Indiana]] [[Mike Pence]], skids off the runway while landing at [[La Guardia Airport]] in [[New York City]]. The airport's [[engineered materials arrestor system]] bed stops the plane before it reaches [[Grand Central Parkway]]. Neither Pence nor the other 47 people on board are injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/10/27/mike-pence-plane-laguardia/|title=Mike Pence's Plane Skids Off Runway While Landing at LaGuardia}}</ref>\n\n;28 October\n* The right engine of [[American Airlines Flight 383 (2016)|American Airlines Flight 383]], a [[Boeing 767-300ER]] (registration N345AN), suffers an [[Turbine engine failure|uncontained failure]] during the airliner's takeoff roll at [[O'Hare International Airport]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], with pieces of the engine flying from the aircraft; one of them strikes a [[United Parcel Service]] building {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} away, but no one on the ground is injured. The engine \u2013 a [[General Electric CF6]] \u2013 then catches fire. The crew aborts the takeoff and brings the plane to a stop {{convert|3000|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} before the end of the runway and all 170 people and a dog aboard the airliner exit via [[evacuation slide]]s. Twenty people suffer minor injuries during the evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/28/us/ohare-aircraft-incident/index.html|title=At Chicago O'Hare, American 767 catches fire on runway|author1=Steve Almasy |author2=Jon Ostrower |author3=Rene Marsh|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-chicago-airplane-engine-idUSKCN12T0Q7|title=American Airlines plane engine flung debris in rare failure|date=30 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* [[Fedex Express Flight 910]], a [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10|McDonnell Douglas MD-10-10F]] [[cargo aircraft]] (registration N370FE), suffers a [[landing gear]] collapse as it lands at [[Fort Lauderdale\u2013Hollywood International Airport]] in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]], [[Florida]]. The plane skids to a halt and a fire breaks out that destroys the left engine and [[wing]]. The aircraft's crew of three escapes.\n* The Government of Turkey announces that it expects the Turkish Air Force to take delivery of its first six [[Lockheed Martin F-35A Lightning II]] fighters in 2018 and has decided to order more for delivery in 2021 and 2022; U.S. officials familiar with the deal say the second order will be for 24 aircraft. Turkey plans eventually to purchase a total of 100 F-35A fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lockheed-fighter-turkey-idUSKCN12S2G1|title=Turkey expects first F-35 delivery in 2018, plans more orders|date=28 October 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;29 October\n* An unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) operating without permission near [[Dubai International Airport]] in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE), forces the airport to close for 84 minutes and prompts UAE authorities to close nearby [[Sharjah International Airport]] for a similar amount of time. It is the third time that an unauthorized drone flight has caused Dubai International Airport to close in 2016, previous incidents having occurred on [[2016 in aviation#June|12 June]] and [[2016 in aviation#September|28 September]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2016/10/30/Thousands-impacted-as-drone-halts-traffic-at-Dubai-airport.html|title=Anonymous, \"Thousands impacted as drone halts traffic at Dubai airport,\" Reuters, 30 October 2016.}}</ref>\n* Strikes by aircraft of the Saudi-led coalition targeting a security complex in [[Houthi]]-rebel-held [[Hodeidah]], Yemen, kill at least 43 people and injure scores more; one report puts the death total at 60. Most of the dead are inmates held in prisons in the complex. The coalition says that the complex was a legitimate target because the Houthis were using it as a [[Command and control|command-and-control]] center for their military operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/airstrikes-kill-more-than-40-and-wound-scores-in-yemeni-port-city/2016/10/30/4666dbfd-afa3-4f8f-9542-7ad77664d4ee_story.html|title=Airstrikes kill more than 40 and wound scores in Yemeni port city}}</ref>\n\n;30 October\n* [[Airbus]] announces that the [[Airbus A320neo|A320neo]] prototype could make to land in [[Bulgaria]] in November 2016, claims to be directly first to visit in [[southeastern Europe]]. The A320neo becomes the second leg of the European destination, after [[Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JajaDeleraINTL/status/792522697066418176|title=JDGlobal on Twitter}}</ref>{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;31 October\n* An [[Alfa Indonesia]] [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou|PEN Turbo DHC-4T Turbo Caribou]] (registration PK-SWW) on a domestic flight from [[Timika]] to [[Ilaga, Indonesia|Ilaga]], [[Indonesia]], [[2016 Alfa Indonesia DHC-4 crash|crashes]] into the side of Ilaga Pass near [[Jita, Indonesia|Jita]] in Indonesia's [[Papua (province)|Papua]] province on [[New Guinea]] at an altitude of {{convert|12800|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}}, killing all four people on board. Its wreckage is found the next day.\n\n===November===\n\n;1 November\n*China-based [[Donghai Airlines]] finalizes its order with [[Boeing]] for five [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787-9 Dreamliner]] airliners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/50599-chinas-donghai-airlines-commits-to-five-b787s|title=China's Donghai Airlines commits to five B787s}}</ref>\n\n;2 November\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] announces that [[Plovdiv Airport]] will close to all commercial traffic temporarily for runway work beginning in February 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n*The [[Lebanese Civil Aviation Authority]] announces a ban on [[Samsung Galaxy Note 7]] smartphones on its flights due to safety concerns based on the [[2016 in aviation#October|15 October]] ban the U.S. [[Federal Aviation Administration]] placed on them because of their tendency to catch fire or explode.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2016/Nov-02/379255-aviation-authority-bans-samsung-galaxy-note-7.ashx dailystar.com.lb Aviation authority bans Samsung Galaxy Note 7 \u2013 ''The Daily Star'' (Lebanon), 2 November 2016.]</ref>\n\n;3 November\n* Airstrikes supporting [[Government of Afghanistan|Afghan government]] troops fighting to push [[Taliban]] forces out [[Kunduz]], [[Afghanistan]], reportedly kill 30 civilians and injure 25 others in and around the city. One report puts the death toll at up to 100 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-civilians-killed-in-errant-airstrikes-in-kunduz-2-us-soldiers-killed-in-clashes/2016/11/03/4c9a76a6-a1ae-11e6-a44d-cc2898cfab06_story.html|title=2 U.S. troops killed fighting Taliban in Afghanistan; civilians hit by airstrike}}</ref><ref name=constable20161105>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/us-military-acknowledges-anti-taliban-airstrikes-killed-afghan-civilians/2016/11/05/ed303aee-a364-11e6-8864-6f892cad0865_story.html|title=U.S. military acknowledges anti-Taliban airstrikes killed Afghan civilians}}</ref> U.S. military officials will acknowledge on 5 November that the airstrikes inflicted casualties on civilians, but do not estimate the number of casualties.<ref name=constable20161105/>\n\n;5 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that the [[Airbus A320neo]] as its next generation candidate of narrow body airliners, [[Airbus]] said in a directly press statement. [[France|French]] foreign trade minister Matthias Fekl says renegotiations with the Balkan carrier as its order for up to six aircraft, any not it finalizes agreement.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Philippine Airlines]] announces that it will withdraw the [[Airbus A320]] from its fleet beginning in 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n;6 November\n*[[Slovakia]]-based [[Go2Sky]] announces it will add an [[Airbus A320]] to its fleet in late December 2016, becoming the first Slovak operator of [[Airbus]] aircraft. The A320 will become the fifth aircraft in the Go2Sky fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/photos/a.355324357939379.1073741827.159511714187312/782209621917515/?type=3|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n* [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] jets have scrambled over 600 times since 1 January to monitor Russian military air traffic around [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russian-warplanes-keep-buzzing-the-baltics-heres-how-nato-scrambles/2016/11/06/15c1ea6e-9df4-11e6-b552-b1f85e484086_story.html|title=Russian warplanes keep buzzing the Baltics. Here\u2019s how NATO scrambles.}}</ref>\n\n;7 November\n* Airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces near [[Ayn Issa]], [[Syria]], destroy six fighting position and seven ground vehicles, including two vehicles filled with explosives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/islamic-state-car-bombs-in-syria-hit-us-backed-forces-aiming-for-stronghold-raqqa/2016/11/07/901acbd2-a4d9-11e6-ba59-a7d93165c6d4_story.html|title=Islamic State sends car bombs against U.S.-backed forces advancing on Raqqa}}</ref> \n* A [[United States Department of Defense]] spokesman says that the [[United States]] is ready to conduct more airstrikes against Islamic State forces in [[Libya]] if the Libyan [[Government of National Accord]] requests them. The United States has conducted over 350 airstrikes against the Islamic State in Libya since [[2016 in aviation#August|August]], but none since 31 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-libya-airstrikes-idUSKBN1322M1|title=U.S. ready to resume air strikes in Libya if needed: Pentagon|date=7 November 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;8 November\n* Seven airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition targeting six Islamic State tactical units near Ayn Issa, Syria, destroy three fighting positions, a ground vehicle, and a [[car bomb]] facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-37922167|title=Syria conflict: Coalition strike 'kills 20 civilians near Raqqa'|date=9 November 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n;9 November\n* The [[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]] claims that a strike by the U.S.-led coalition in [[Heisha]], Syria, kill at least 20 civilians and injure 30 others. The coalition says it will investigate the claim of civilian casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-syria-airstrike-20161109-story.html|title=Activists blame U.S.-led coalition for airstrike in Syria that kills at least 20 people|first=Molly|last=Hennessy-Fiske|date=9 November 2016|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n* [[United States Central Command]] announces that it has reexamined its estimate of the number of civilians its airstrikes have killed in [[Iraq]] and Syria since its air campaign against the Islamic State began in 2014 based on allegations by activist groups and that has added 64 deaths to is estimate, bringing its estimate to a total of 119 civilians killed. It continues to investigate allegations of additional civilian deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/11/09/u-s-military-announces-that-civilian-casualties-in-iraq-and-syria-are-more-than-double-previous-estimate/|title=U.S. military announces that civilian casualties in Iraq and Syria are more than double previous estimate}}</ref>\n\n;11 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] Chief Executive Officer Hristo Todorov requests that the wide body airliners candidate  \u2013 [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-200]] and [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]] will yet to be selected before the launch of transatlantic service in 2017.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Taiwan]]-based [[TransAsia Airways]] officially retires the [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-300]] from its fleet.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n*Computer problems at [[Sabre Corporation]] cause check-in and flight delays on [[Alaska Airlines]], [[American Airlines]], [[JetBlue Airways]], [[Southwest Airlines]], and [[Virgin America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/business/computer-outage-briefly-grounds-flights-on-several-airlines/|title=Computer outage briefly grounds flights on several airlines|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n;13 November\n*Airstrikes targeting rebel-held areas in western [[Aleppo Governorate]] in Syria knock out a [[Syrian Civil Defense]] center in [[Atareb]] and kill three people. In northern [[Idlib Governorate]], an airstrike kills a woman and her four children. In the western [[Ghouta]] region outside [[Damascus]], an airstrike on a [[mosque]] in [[Khan al-Shih]] kills two people. And an explosion attributed to an airstrike at a crossing point between Syria's [[Syrian Kurds|Kurdish]]-held [[Afrin District]] and rebel-held parts of Aleppo Governorate kills at least eight\u2014as perhaps as many as 12\u2014people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/fab6efc20da84824b542166ccab34f3d/violence-northern-syria-kills-12|title=Violence in northern Syria kills 23}}</ref>\n\n;15 November\n*Syrian government and Russian forces renew their offensive against rebels in Syria. Heavy Syrian government airstrikes hit rebel-held eastern [[Aleppo]], Syria. Russia denies that it has struck Aleppo during the day, but announces that Russian aircraft and land-based and ship-launched [[cruise missile]]s have struck Islamic State targets and positions of an [[al-Qaeda]]-linked rebel group in Syria's [[Homs Governorate]] and [[Idlib Governorate]], claiming that the targets were industrial sites the groups were using to manufacture toxic substances used in [[weapons of mass destruction]]. A Russian [[aircraft carrier]] sees combat for the first time in history during the day, when the [[Russian Federation Navy]] carrier ''[[Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov|Admiral Kuznetsov]]'', operating in the eastern [[Mediterranean Sea]], launches [[Sukhoi Su-33]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Flanker D\") aircraft which strike targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russian-warplanes-from-mediterranean-carrier-join-syria-attacks/2016/11/15/fe0056d2-ab26-11e6-977a-1030f822fc35_story.html|title=Russian warplanes from Mediterranean carrier join Syria attacks}}</ref>\n*[[Will Rogers World Airport]] in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]], closes to commercial traffic for several hours \u2013 although a [[United States Government]] aircraft carrying prison inmates to a federal inmate transfer center is allowed to land \u2013 after a former Southwest Airlines employee who had been fired in 2015 uses a rifle to kill another Southwest Airlines employee just outside the airport, then shoots himself to death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/15/us/oklahoma-city-airport-shooting/index.html|title=Airline employee killed at Oklahoma City airport; suspect dead|author1=Keith Allen |author2=Steve Almasy|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/11/16/oklahoma-airport-shoot-airlines-employee/93958962/|title=Former Southwest Airlines employee named as shooter in Okla. airport murder}}</ref>\n*At [[Centennial Airport]] in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Boom Technology]] unveils the engineering design for its XB-1 Baby Boom supersonic technology demonstrator aircraft, a scaled-down version of a 45-passenger [[Supersonic transport|supersonic airliner]] it hopes to produce and place in service by 2023. The Baby Boom is expected to make its first flight in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/baby-boom-supersonic-demonstrator-unveiled |title= 'Baby Boom' Supersonic Demonstrator Unveiled |date= 15 November 2016 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/awincommercial/baby-boom-demonstrator-passes-design-review |title= 'Baby Boom' Demonstrator Passes Design Review |date= 15 June 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Daily |publisher= Aviation Week Network |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n\n;16 November\n*Syrian government airstrikes pound eastern Aleppo, Syria, badly damaging the city's last remaining children's hospital; Russia denies any involvement in strikes against eastern Aleppo, claiming to have conducted none there since 18 October. At least 87 people are killed in Aleppo Governorate during the day. Russian air and cruise missile strikes continue in Idlib Governorate, where 34 sites have been hit and six people killed and dozens wounded since 15 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/warplanes-bomb-childrens-hospital-as-assad-renews-aleppo-offensive/2016/11/16/a9784fa8-abd9-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=Warplanes bomb children\u2019s hospital as Assad renews Aleppo offensive}}</ref>\n\n;19 November\n*According to officials in Afghanistan, an airstrike by an unmanned aerial vehicle in [[Nangahar Province]] in eastern Afghanistan kills eight Islamic State personnel including [[Mullah Bozorg]], a top Islamic State commander.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/world-digest-nov-19-2016/2016/11/19/cf995b7e-ae8f-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html|title=World Digest: Nov. 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 November\n*After a U.S. military unmanned aerial vehicle spots Islamic State personnel [[Decapitation|beheading]] and shooting civilians in the [[Mosul]], Iraq, area, a U.S. [[laser-guided bomb]] is used to scatter the executioners.<ref name=ryan20161220>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/20/when-air-power-works-and-when-it-doesnt/|title=When air power works, and when it doesn\u2019t: A snapshot of U.S. operations against the Islamic State}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] confirms to acquire at least four [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]] aircraft in giving instead of [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-200]] already to enter service in 2017. In addition, the airline agrees to ten [[Airbus A320 family]] in anticipation to join the fleet with bringing the operator of A320 family to fifteen.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;21 November\n*The [[United States]] grants a license to [[Airbus]] to sell 106 airliners to [[Iran]]; it will announce that it has granted the license the following day. Airbus required the license because at least 10 percent of the airliners' parts are manufactured in the United States. Previously, Airbus had had a U.S. license to sell only 17 airliners to Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-aviation-usa-idUSKBN13H1W0|title=Exclusive: U.S. grants second Airbus license to sell planes to Iran|date=22 November 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n;22 November\n* Approximately 250 pilots who fly cargo aircraft for [[ABX Air]] go on strike, claiming the airline is violating their contract by giving them too many flight assignments. ABX Air says it views the strike as illegal. The strike affects package deliveries by ABX Air's two biggest customers, [[Amazon.com]] and [[DHL Express]], as the 2016 [[Christmas and holiday season|Christmas shopping season]] begins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/11/22/amazon-holiday-shipments/|title=Pilot Strike Could Delay Amazon's Holiday Shipments}}</ref>\n* The [[Government of Canada]] announces that it will buy 18 [[F-18 Super Hornet]]s from [[Boeing]] as a stopgap measure and begin a process of as long as five years to determine how to replace its aging fighter fleet, which consists of 77 [[McDonnell Douglas CF-18 Hornet]]s, a decline from what once had been a force of 138 CF-18s. The announcement is a blow to [[Lockheed Martin]], which had hoped to sell [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] fighters to [[Canada]]. Although Canada plans to remain one of the countries contributing to the development of the F-35, it has backed off its earlier plans to purchase F-35s.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/23/business/international/canada-to-buy-f-18s-from-boeing-to-shore-up-its-fighter-fleet.html ]</ref>\n\n;23 November\n*An airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition \"disables\" the fourth of five bridges across the [[Tigris]] in Mosul, Iraq, leaving only one bridge intact. Airstrikes had destroyed another bridge earlier in the week and two in October. The destruction of the bridges has disrupted Islamic State supply lines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/nov/23/is-claims-coalition-airstrike-disables-fourth-mosu/|title=Airstrike hits Mosul bridge, disrupting ISIS supply lines|work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n*[[Spain]]'s national airline [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] formally its last flight for the [[Airbus A340|Airbus A340-300]] from service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/50594-iberia-ends-a340-300-operations|title=Iberia ends A340-300 operations}}</ref>\n*A [[United States federal judge|U.S. federal judge]] in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], orders ABX Air pilots who had gone on strike the previous day to return to work. Their union says that it will obey the judge's order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/23/technology/airline-used-by-amazon-goes-to-court-as-pilot-strike-enters-day-2.html|title=Airline Used by Amazon Wins Order to End Cargo Pilots' Strike|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|date=23 November 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n;24 November\n* [[Turkey]] agrees to send a large firefighting aircraft to [[Israel]] to assist in [[aerial firefighting]] efforts against major wildfires burning there. [[Russia]], meanwhile, agrees to send two large firefighting aircraft to Israel. [[Croatia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Greece]], and [[Italy]] have sent a combined seven aircraft to Israel to assist in firefighting.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Turkey-Russia-among-countries-rushing-to-Israels-aid-to-fight-fires-473532 Keinon, Herb, \"Turkey, Russia Among Countries Rushing to Israel\u2032s Aid to Fight Fires,\" ''Jerusalem Post'', 24 November 2016, 12:19.]</ref>\n* The U.S.-led coalition has conducted over 16,000 airstrikes against Islamic State targets since beginning its air campaign against the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/heres-hoping-trump-flip-flops-even-more/2016/11/24/da04e8d6-b195-11e6-840f-e3ebab6bcdd3_story.html|title=Here\u2019s hoping Trump flip-flops even more|first1=Fareed|last1=Zakaria|first2=Fareed|last2=Zakaria|date=24 November 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\n;25 November\n*The watchdog group [[Airwars]] announces that air and [[artillery]] strikes by the U.S.-led coalition have combined to kill between 84 and 87 civilians and wound more than 160 other civilians in and around Mosul, Iraq, since the coalition's ground offensive to clear Islamic State forces from Mosul began on 17 October. A [[United States Central Command]] spokesman responds that \"the liberation of Mosul is an operation that is an order of magnitude larger and more complex than\" operations to liberate \"any of the previous cities that have been liberated\" from the Islamic State, adding that U.S. military forces extensively review proposed strikes, using intelligence and surveillance to verify targets before launching them and noting that coalition strikes have destroyed dozens of Islamic State [[car bomb]]s and tunnels in around Mosul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/in-mosul-campaign-reported-civilian-deaths-in-us-strikes-climb/2016/11/25/e4ca84e0-b33b-11e6-bc2d-19b3d759cfe7_story.html|title=In Mosul campaign, reported civilian deaths in U.S. strikes climb}}</ref>\n* A U.S.-based [[Evergreen 747 Supertanker]]\u2014the world's largest aerial firefighting aircraft, based on the [[Boeing 747-400]] \u2013 arrives in Israel to assist in battling major wildfires that have been burning for four days. [[Azerbaijan]] also sends a firefighting plane and [[Egypt]] sends two helicopters to help battle the fires.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/US-Supertanker-lands-in-Israel-to-assist-with-raging-fires-473685 Anonymous, \"US Supertanker Lands in Israel to Assist With Raging Fires,\" ''Jerusalem Post'', 25 November 2016, 20:08.]</ref>\n\n;26 November\n*In the [[November 2016 Butig clash]]: [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated militant organization [[Maute group]] which passes in the occupied town of [[Butig]] in [[Lanao del Sur]], [[Philippines]]. [[Philippine Air Force]] [[SIAI-Marchetti SF.260]] dropped {{convert|150|lb|kg}} bombs, all roads will close to the public.<ref name=thirdday>{{cite news|last1=Zambrano|first1=Chiara|title=Troops bombard Maute militants as fighting enters third day|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/11/28/16/troops-bombard-maute-militants-as-fighting-enters-third-day|accessdate=28 November 2016|work=ABS-CBN News|agency=ABS-CBN News. Agence France-Presse|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n;27 November\n*[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Foreign Minister of Malaysia]] [[Anifah Aman]] says [[Malaysia]] will any deployment of both fixed wing aircraft and helicopters to the [[Philippines]], including Basilan. The reach agreement will allow both [[Malaysian Armed Forces]] and the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP) to launch an offensive in combat against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]], resulting over the phase.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=November 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* After a firefight begins between Islamic State-affiliated Syrian rebels and a reconnaissance unit of the [[Israel Defense Forces]]\u2032 [[Golani Brigade]] along the ceasefire line between Israel and Syria in the [[Golan Heights]], the [[Israeli Air Force]] spots a ground vehicle armed with a heavy [[machine gun]] and destroys it with a rocket, killing four Syrian rebels. An Israeli military spokesman describes the incident as the \"first substantial fight\" between Israeli forces and an Islamic State affiliate in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israeli-forces-kill-4-islamic-state-allies-in-golan-heights-firefight/2016/11/27/40165fb6-ffe3-4dd6-a23a-5231f1a4c057_story.html|title=Israeli forces kill 4 Islamic State allies in Golan Heights firefight}}</ref>\n* Israel approves the purchase of 17 additional [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] fighter aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/11/29/its-been-a-topsy-turvy-few-weeks-for-the-f-35-program/|title=It\u2019s been a topsy-turvy few weeks for the F-35 program}}</ref>\n\n;28 November\n*The first scheduled commercial airline flight between the [[United States]] and [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], since the early 1960s takes place as an [[American Airlines]] jet arrives at Havana's [[Jose Marti International Airport]] from [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]]. [[JetBlue]] initiates Havana service later in the day with a flight from [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-airlines-cuba-1129-biz-20161128-story.html|title=First commercial Havana-bound flights touch down amid transition for U.S., Cuba|first=Lauren Zumbach, Robert|last=Channick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/jetblue-launches-flights-kennedy-airport-havana-article-1.2889845|title=JetBlue launches flights from Kennedy Airport to Havana}}</ref>\n*[[LaMia Airlines Flight 2933]], an [[British Aerospace 146|Avro RJ85]] (registration CP-2933), crashes in [[Colombia]] after its crew declares electrical and fuel emergencies. The crash kills 71 of the 77 people on board, including 19 members of the [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Chapecoense de Futebol]] [[association football|football]] (soccer) team, and leaves all six survivors injured. Prominent survivors include football team members [[Alan Ruschel]], [[Jakson Follmann]], and [[Neto (footballer, born 1985)|Neto]]. Their teammate [[Marcos Danilo Padilha|Danilo]] survives initially but later dies in a hospital.\n\n;29 November\n* Iraqi forces advancing on Mosul call upon more than a dozen U.S. surveillance aircraft \u2013 including [[General Atomics MQ-1 Predator|MQ-1 Predator]] and [[General Atomics MQ-9 Reaper|MQ-9 Reaper]] \u2013 and 43 U.S. combat planes \u2013 including [[United States Air Force]] [[B-52H Stratofortress]]es, [[F-15 Eagle]]s, and [[F-22 Raptor]]s and [[United States Marine Corps]] [[AV-8B Harrier]]s\u2014as well as [[electronic warfare]] aircraft and [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] [[attack helicopter]]s for support against Islamic State targets. The aircraft fire more than 80 [[precision-guided munition]]s and destroy four [[car bomb]]s, four [[Mortar(weapon)|mortar]] systems and an Islamic State compound, among other targets.<ref name=ryan20161220/>\n* [[United Airlines]] begins service between the United States and Havana, Cuba, with a flight from [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2016/11/29/united-airlines-passengers-celebrate-first-flight-newark-cuba/94604576/|title=United Airlines, passengers celebrate first flight from Newark to Cuba}}</ref>\n\n;30 November\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] officially announces that it will discontinue its [[Wet lease|wet-lease]] agreements for aircraft in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/posts/795675403904270|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n\n;1 December\n\n* A [[ski]]-equipped [[Lockheed LC-130|Lockheed LC-130 Hercules]] of the [[New York Air National Guard]]'s [[109th Airlift Wing]] evacuates [[Apollo 11]] [[astronaut]] [[Buzz Aldrin|Edwin \"Buzz\" Aldrin]], the second man to walk on the moon, from the [[South Pole]] after he falls ill while there with a tour group. The LC-130 flies him to [[McMurdo Station]] on [[Antarctica]]'s [[Ross Island]]. He then flies on a [[Safair]] cargo plane to [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]], where he arrives on 2 December for hospitalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/12/01/ailing-buzz-aldrin-second-man-on-the-moon-is-being-medically-evacuated-from-the-south-pole/|title='Ailing' Buzz Aldrin, the second man to walk on the moon, is safely evacuated from the South Pole}}</ref>\n* [[Delta Air Lines]] makes its first flight to [[Cuba]] in 55 years. The flight departs [[Miami International Airport]] in [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]], and arrives at [[Jose Marti International Airport]] in [[Havana]]. Later in the day, Delta inaugurates additional U.S.-Cuba routes with flights to Havana from [[New York City]]'s [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] and from [[Hartsfield-Jackson International Airport]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelpulse.com/news/airlines/delta-air-lines-returns-to-cuba-after-55-years.html|title=Delta Air Lines Returns to Cuba After 55 Years}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Department of Defense]] announces that it has identified 54 additional civilian deaths attributable to airstrikes by the U.S.-led coalition in [[Iraq]] and [[Syria]] between 31 March and 22 October 2016, bringing to 173 the number of civilian deaths the [[United States]] claims have been the result of coalition airstrikes since the air campaign began in [[2014 in aviation#June|June 2014]]. The announcement revises a [[2016 in aviation#July|July 2016]] Department of Defense announcement of 55 civilian deaths during the air campaign and a [[United States Central Command]] finding announced on [[2016 in aviation#November|9 November 2016]] that the campaign had killed 64 civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/01/u-s-led-coalition-in-iraq-and-syria-acknowledges-54-civilians-killed-in-airstrikes/|title=U.S.-led coalition in Iraq and Syria acknowledges 54 civilians killed in airstrikes}}</ref>\n\n;2 December\n\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that it will start service to [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], from [[Sofia Airport]] in [[Sofia, Bulgaria|Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]], starting in April 2017. It will become the first Bulgarian airline to offer service to [[Southeast Asia]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;4 December\n*Airstrikes in Syria's [[Idlib Governorate]] kill at least 50 people during the day, with one report putting the death toll at 52. Observers suspect the [[Russian Federation Air Force]] or [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] of having conducted the attacks. Dozens of the deaths occur in two strikes which target rural marketplaces in [[Kafr Nabl]] and [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrian-army-tells-rebels-in-aleppo-to-leave-or-dieat-least-50-civilians-reported-killed-in-airstrikes-on-idlib-province/2016/12/04/d6b02738-ba67-11e6-94ac-3d324840106c_story.html|title=Syrian army tells rebels in Aleppo to leave or die}}</ref>\n\n;5 December\n*A [[Russian Naval Aviation]] [[Sukhoi Su-33]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Flanker D\") crashes into the [[Mediterranean Sea]] after an [[Arresting gear|arresting cable]] snaps while it is attempting to land on the [[Russian Federation Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]] ''[[Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov|Admiral Kuznetsov]]''. The pilot survives. It is the second aircraft ''Admiral Kuznetsov'' has lost since beginning combat operations off [[Syria]]; the first was a [[Mikoyan MiG-29K]] (NATO reporting name \"Fulcrum D\") which crashed in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/russia-just-lost-its-second-warplane-in-a-month-of-syria/2016/12/05/f8353be8-bad8-11e6-817f-e3b588251d1e_story.html|title=Russian jets keep crashing, and it may be an aircraft carrier\u2019s fault}}</ref>\n\n;6 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that a dry-lease term contract with [[White Airways]] to buy two [[Boeing 777]] aircraft starting in 2017 to supplement the existing four [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-300]]. [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Portugal)|Foreign Minister of Portugal]] [[Augusto Santos Silva]] claims that the [[Bulgaria]] \u2013 [[Portugal]] bilateral agreement negotiations will be announced in spring 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/jajaseriesofficial/posts/799511193520691|title=Jaja Series}}</ref>\n*U.S. [[President of the United States|President]]-elect [[Donald Trump]] [[Twitter|tweets]] that the [[United States Air Force]] contract to replace the fleet of aging [[Boeing VC-25]] aircraft that operate as [[Air Force One]] with two new aircraft based on the [[Boeing 747-8]] at a cost of $4,000,000,000 is too expensive and should be canceled. The U.S. Air Force and [[Boeing]] counter that the old aircraft are in need of replacement and that the special requirements for presidential aircraft inevitably lead to a high price for them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/06/citing-cost-overruns-trump-says-boeings-contract-to-build-air-force-one-should-be-canceled/|title=Citing high cost, Trump says Boeing\u2019s contract to build Air Force One should be canceled}}</ref>\n*The [[United States Department of Justice]] approves the purchase of [[Virgin America]] by [[Alaska Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/12/06/alaska-airlines-merger-virgin-america-gets-ok-doj/95049528/|title=Justice Dept. OKs Alaska Airlines-Virgin America merger}}</ref>\n\n;7 December\n*After its pilot reports the failure of one of its engines, [[Pakistan International Airlines Flight 661]], an [[ATR 42-500]] (registration AP-BHO), crashes near [[Havelian]], [[Pakistan]], killing all 47 people on board. Pakistani recording artist, television personality, fashion designer, actor, singer-songwriter, preacher, and televangelist [[Junaid Jamshed]] is among the dead.\n\n;8 December\n* After U.S. pilots drop leaflets warning the drivers of Islamic State [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] of the impending attack, [[United States Air Force]] [[A-10 Thunderbolt II]] aircraft destroy 168 of the trucks near [[Palmyra]], Syria, as part of [[Operation Tidal Wave II]].<ref name=warrick20161231>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/take-them-back-to-the-19th-century-inside-the-economic-war-against-the-islamic-state/2016/12/30/5f91f514-ceb7-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html|title=Inside the economic war against the Islamic State}}</ref>\n\n;10 December\n*[[Stara Zagora Airport]] in southern Bulgaria announces that much as paving the way for a potential commercial passenger service will begin in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*[[Bulgaria]]'s [[Civil Aviation Administration (Bulgaria)|Civil Aviation Administration]] awards this Air Operator's Certificate to [[Stara Zagora]], [[Gorna Oryahovitsa]], and [[Ruse, Bulgaria|Ruse]] with bring to start in 2017. [[Bulgaria Air]] said it will add five [[ATR 72-500]]s converted from ten airliners, many as possible order for an [[ATR 72-600]] to be leased initially.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;11 December\n* [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] forces retake Palmyra, Syria, from the [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]]. Unlike in [[2016 in aviation#March|March]], when Russian Federation Air Force strikes played a key and effective role against the Islamic State in the Syrian government's recapture of Palmyra, Russian airstrikes on 10 and 11 December are ineffective in stopping the Islamic State advance. Although [[human rights]] organizations have accused the Russian Federation Air Force of intensive bombing of civilian targets during the [[Syrian Civil War]], [[Russia]] claims that its pilots were unable to respond effectively to the Islamic State's advance on Palmyra because Russian pilots were unwilling to endanger civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/battle-rages-for-palmyra-as-islamic-state-is-poised-to-retake-control/2016/12/11/396552ea-bf9a-11e6-afd9-f038f753dc29_story.html|title=Syrian troops pull out as Islamic State militants sweep back into ancient Palmyra}}</ref>\n* [[Iran Air]] finalizes a deal to buy 80 airliners from [[Boeing]] at a cost of $16,600,000,000. The deal includes 50 [[Boeing 737 MAX 8]]s, 15 [[Boeing 777-300ER]]s, and 15 [[Boeing 777-9]]s. Iran Air plans to take delivery of the first planes in 2018, with deliveries completed over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/adfb6564faac4b148d7418803f7e6576/iran-says-its-finalized-166b-boeing-deal-buy-80-planes|title=Iran seals deal with Boeing to buy 80 planes worth $16.6B}}</ref>\n\n;12 December\n* In the wake of 7 December crash of its Flight 661, Pakistan International Airlines grounds the five ATR 42 and [[ATR 72]] airliners in its fleet after the [[Pakistan Civil Aviation Authority]] decides to conduct \"shakedown tests\" of the airline's entire fleet of [[ATR (aircraft manufacturer)|ATR]] aircraft.<ref name=hassan20161213>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/pakistan-pia-idINKBN1421TW|title=Pakistan International Airlines chairman resigns days after plane crash|first=Reuters|last=Editorial}}</ref>\n* Supported by Syrian government and Russian airstrikes, Syrian government ground forces reduce the rebel-held portion of [[Aleppo]], Syria, to a small sliver of territory that is no more than a tenth of what they used to control in the city, leaving the Syrian government poised to reconquer the entire city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syrian-forces-push-aleppo-rebels-to-brink-as-city-nears-total-collapse/2016/12/12/0e7e7e82-c079-11e6-afd9-f038f753dc29_story.html|title=Syrian forces push Aleppo rebels to brink as city nears 'total collapse'}}</ref>\n* After hours of delay due to [[fog]] at their departure point outside [[Milan]], [[Italy]], the [[Israeli Air Force]]'s first two [[F-35 Lightning II]] fighters, flown by U.S. pilots, arrive at [[Nevatim Airbase]] in [[Israel]]. Plans call for Israeli pilots to fly them for the first time the following day. Israel plans to acquire 50 of the aircraft at a total cost of around $5,000,000,000.<ref name=booth20161212>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/israel-waited-a-long-time-for-its-f-35-jets-then-it-waited-some-more/2016/12/12/2590ab1c-c089-11e6-a52b-a0a126eaf9f7_story.html|title=Israel finally receives the first of its $5 billion order of U.S.-made F-35 jets}}</ref>\n* U.S. President-elect Donald Trump [[Twitter|tweets]] that the F-35 Lightning II's \"cost is out of control. Billions of dollars can and will be saved on military (and other) purchases after 20 January [2017],\" the day of the [[United States presidential inauguration]]. The stock price for the F-35's manufacturer, [[Lockheed Martin]] falls over 4 percent at one point after Trump's tweet, and closes for the day down 2.47 percent.<ref name=booth20161212/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2016/12/12/trump-takes-aim-at-pentagons-revolving-door-and-lockheed-martins-400-billion-f-35-program/|title=Trump takes aim at Pentagon\u2019s 'revolving door' and Lockheed Martin\u2019s $400 billion F-35 program}}</ref>\n\n;13 December\n* A [[United States Marine Corps]] [[MV-22 Osprey]] crashes in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Okinawa]] after a hose connected to it during an [[aerial refueling]] exercise breaks and damages one of its propellers. Its five-man crew is rescued, two of them with non-life-threatening injuries. It is the first crash of an Osprey in [[Japan]]. Following the crash, the [[Government of Japan]] calls for an end to Osprey flights in Japan, and on 14 December the U.S. military will ground all Ospreys in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-osprey-crash-idUSKBN14302J|title=U.S. grounds Osprey aircraft in Japan after Okinawa crash|date=14 December 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n* The chairman of Pakistan International Airlines, Azam Saigol, resigns for \"personal reasons.\" He had been under pressure to resign due to concerns about the airline's safety record following the 7 December crash of Pakistan International Airlines Flight 661.<ref name=hassan20161213/>\n\n;14 December\n*A ceasefire agreement to allow Syrian rebels and civilians to evacuate the last part of Aleppo, Syria, that the reels hold breaks down almost as soon as it begins, and, after a heavy storm clears the area, airstrikes in support of Syrian government forces resume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/aleppo-evacuation-deal-for-rebels-stalls-amid-disagreements-and-renewed-shelling/2016/12/14/ebc3290c-c1a3-11e6-92e8-c07f4f671da4_story.html|title=Aleppo evacuation deal for rebels shatters, violence surges}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] says a finalize its agreement to buy four aircraft (via freighter configuration) for establishing the cargo revenue operations with maiden flights scheduled for 2017. The cargo unit will be called Bulgaria Air Cargo, which played a key role for logistics and mail support for [[Europe]] and [[Asia]] from a hub at [[Sofia Airport]]. It also announced a cargo handing service should be being consideration.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* For the first time, [[Amazon.com]] makes a delivery to a customer using an [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]. The [[Amazon Prime Air]] delivery takes place in the [[United Kingdom]]. The customer's order \u2013 for an [[Amazon Fire TV]] device and a bag of [[popcorn]] \u2013 arrives 13 minutes after it was placed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2016/12/14/amazon-makes-its-first-drone-delivery-to-a-real-customer/|title=Amazon makes its first drone delivery to a real customer}}</ref>\n\n;15 December\n* The [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Defense]] reports that China's first [[aircraft carrier]], ''[[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning|Liaoning]]'', had completed its first live-fire exercises \"a few days\" earlier. During the exercises, which included air interception, sea-based attacks and [[air defense]], reconnaissance, [[early warning]] and anti-missile defense, ''Liaoning'''s [[Shenyang J-15]] jets reportedly carried live ordnance and successfully fired missiles at targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/12/16/show-force-chinas-1st-aircraft-carrier-carries-out-1st-live-fire-exercise.html|title=Show of force: China's first aircraft carrier carries out first live-fire exercise|date=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n;18 December\n* Flying in poor weather and low cloud cover, an [[Indonesian Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130H Hercules]] carrying 12 [[metric ton]]s of food supplies and [[cement]] [[2016 Indonesian Air Force Lockheed C-130 Hercules crash|crashes]] on [[New Guinea]]'s Mount Lisuwa while on approach to [[Wamena Airport]] in [[Wamena]], [[Papua (province)|Papua]], [[Indonesia]], killing all 13 people on board.\n*A [[Royal Air Force]] [[C-130J Hercules]] lands at [[Saint Helena Airport]], becoming the first fixed-wing military aircraft ever to land on [[Saint Helena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatthesaintsdidnext.com/2016/12/18/raf-c-130-hercules-first-military-flight-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=C130 Hercules at St Helena Airport: First Military Flight Landing |publisher=Whatthesaintsdidnext.com |date=18 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n;20 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that sixteen additional regular, charter or seasonal destinations will be introduced in 2017 with its arriving of wide body aircraft. [[Sofia Airport]] Chief Executive Officer Hristo Shterionov said that the Sofia hub should potential new long haul destinations to include the US and Asia.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n* Since the coalition air campaign against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria began in [[2014 in aviation#August|August 2014]], coalition forces have conducted over 16,000 airstrikes at a cost of $12.5 million per day, killing an estimated 50,000 Islamic State personnel. The coalition has launched an average of 56 strike sorties per day since the campaign began.<ref name=ryan20161220/>\n\n;22 December\n*After over four years of airstrikes against rebel-held areas of Aleppo, Syria, by the [[Syrian Arab Air Force]] and [[Russian Federation Air Force]], the Syrian government declares that its forces have retaken the entire city. Targets for the airstrikes have included residential areas and hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/syrian-military-says-it-has-retaken-control-of-prized-city-of-aleppo/2016/12/22/7e1ff74c-c7be-11e6-acda-59924caa2450_story.html|title=Syrian military says it has retaken control of key city of Aleppo}}</ref>\n*An intoxicated Russian man, Ruslan Nurtdinov, rams his car into the [[Airport terminal|terminal]] at [[Kazan International Airport]] outside [[Kazan]], Russia. Pursued by security personnel on foot, Nurtdinov drives his car through the terminal, passing check-in desks, a [[baggage carousel]], security checkpoints, and departure gates before coming to a halt at a railway platform, where he is arrested. He claims that he is trying to meet his girlfriend, who was scheduled to arrive at the railway platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/24/fighting-love-russian-man-sparks-security-scare-driving-airport/|title='I was fighting for love!' Russian man sparks security scare by driving into airport \u2013 to meet his girlfriend}}</ref>\n*U.S. President-elect [[Donald Trump]] [[Twitter|tweets]] that he might reconsider the purchase of the F-35 Lighting II due to its expense and cost overruns and seek a cheaper alternative, and that he \"has asked [[Boeing]] to price out a comparable [[F-18 Super Hornet]].\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-a-day-of-tweets-trump-suggests-major-change-on-national-security-issues/2016/12/22/4d709da8-c873-11e6-8bee-54e800ef2a63_story.html|title=In a day of tweets, Trump suggests major change on national security issues}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n;23 December\n*Two men claiming to be supporters of the late Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] and to have a [[hand grenade]] hijack [[Afriqiyah Airways Flight 209]], an [[Airbus A320]] (registration 5A-ONB) with 118 people on board, during a domestic flight in [[Libya]] from [[Sebha]] to [[Tripoli]] and force it to fly to [[Malta International Airport]] in [[Malta]] where they demand [[political asylum]] in [[Europe]] so that they can establish a political party that represents the former Gaddafi regime. They surrender to Maltese authorities and no one is injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/23/flight-diverted-malta-amid-potential-hijack-situation/|title=Libyan plane hijack: Two hijackers 'with grenades threaten to blow up' Afriqiyah Airways flight in Malta |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]| date=23 December 2016| accessdate =23 December 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Vesna Vulovi\u0107]], the sole survivor of the crash of [[JAT Flight 367|JAT Yugoslav Airlines Flight 367]] on [[1972 in aviation#January|26 January 1972]], dies in her apartment in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], at age 66. After the airliner exploded and broke into two pieces at an altitude of {{convert|33330|ft|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} over [[Czechoslovakia]], she fell to earth in the aircraft's tail section, setting a record for surviving the longest fall without a parachute which still stands at the time of her death.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.voanews.com/a/stewardess-survived-1972-plane-crash-record-fall/3649265.html|title=Serbia Stewardess Who Survived 1972 Plane Crash, Record Fall Dies at 66|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=24 December 2016| accessdate =24 December 2016}}</ref>\n*Returning from a book-promotion trip to the [[United Kingdom]], American actress and writer [[Carrie Fisher]] suffers a major [[heart attack]] aboard [[United Airlines]] Flight 935, a [[Boeing 777-200]] making a 10-hour-58-minute nonstop flight from [[London]] to [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]. She will die on 27 December at [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]] in Los Angeles without ever regaining consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucelee/2016/12/23/carrie-fisher-hospitalized-from-heart-attack-on-airplane/#370de2179baa|title=Carrie Fisher Hospitalized After Cardiac Arrest on Airplane|first=Bruce Y.|last=Lee}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/205880_carrie_fisher_never_regained_consciousness_after_heart_attack/|title=Carrie Fisher Never Regained Consciousness After Going into Cardiac Arrest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://flightaware.com/live/flight/UAL935/history/20161223/0920Z/EGLL/KLAX|title=United (UA)  #935 \u2708 23-Dec-2016  \u2708 LHR / EGLL - KLAX \u2708 FlightAware}}</ref>\n\n;25 December\n*The [[Government of Malaysia]] says that conducting airstrike in the southern Philippines \u2013 mainly [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]] by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]]-affiliated [[Abu Sayyaf]] won't captures of [[Basilan Province|Basilan]] and [[Sulu Province|Sulu]]. However, the two governments as with the Philippines (Malaysia's neighboring border) discuss to a decision will be made.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n*A [[Russian Armed Forces|Russian military]] [[Tupolev Tu-154]] ([[NATO reporting name]] \"Careless\") transport aircraft [[2016 Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 crash|crashes]] into the [[Black Sea]] just after takeoff from [[Sochi International Airport]] in [[Sochi]], Russia, for a flight to [[Khmeimim (air base)|Khmeimim Air Base]] in [[Latakia]], Syria, killing all 92 people on board. Sixty-four members of the [[Alexandrov Ensemble]], better known internationally as the \"Red Army Choir\" \u2013 including its director, [[Valery Khalilov]] \u2013 traveling to Syria to perform for Russian troops are among the dead, as are nine journalists, three each from [[Channel One Russia]], [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]], and [[Zvezda (TV channel)|Zvezda]]. Also killed is Russian humanitarian [[Elizaveta Glinka]], commonly known in Russia as \"Doctor Liza,\" making the trip to accompany a shipment of medicine to a hospital in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/no-survivors-found-after-russian-military-plane-with-92-on-board-crashes-en-route-to-syria/2016/12/25/d4bca3f0-ca7c-11e6-a22f-f4d703887285_story.html|title=Russia focusing on pilot error or technical issues rather than terrorism in plane crash}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that reducing 16 to 12 flights (five out of [[Sofia Airport]], four out of [[Varna Airport]] and three out of [[Burgas Airport]]) with unspecified date scheduled for 2017. Bulgarian Transport Ministry's spokesman said that the ticket sales will be added, and the Sofia Airport will be the long haul operational hub.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}{{Incomprehensible inline|date=December 2016|reason=Poor English, with no English-language source cited that would allow a clean-up to English Wikipedia standards.}}\n\n;26 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that its first [[Boeing 767-300]] will be delivered in March 2017, followed by three more to follow in May 2017.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Air Moldova]] announces that it will procure two more [[Airbus A320]]s which will enter service in 2017, bringing the airline's fleet of A320s to four.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;29 December\n*U.S. military officials report that a coalition airstrike targeting a van in a hospital compound parking lot in [[Mosul]], Iraq, carrying Islamic State personnel who had just left a [[recoilless rifle]] position may have killed an undetermined number of civilians inadvertently. They announce that an investigation of the incident will follow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/reinforced-iraqi-forces-restart-delayed-assault-on-mosul/2016/12/29/fc315e38-cd9e-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html|title=Reinforced Iraqi units resume offensive to take Mosul from Islamic State}}</ref>\n*A [[Cessna CitationJet/M2|Cessna 525 Citation]] [[corporate jet]] (registration N614SB) with six people on board crashes into [[Lake Erie]] during its initial climb after takeoff from [[Cleveland Burke Lakefront Airport]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]], [[Ohio]]. The [[United States Coast Guard]] will call off the unsuccessful search for survivors on 31 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20161229-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Cessna 525C Citation CJ4 N614SB Cleveland-Burke Lakefront Airport, OH (BKL)|first=Harro|last=Ranter}}</ref>\n\n;31 December\n*[[Bulgaria Air]] announces that the next candidate of the 2017 Best Airline in the Balkans and it is expected in April 2017. The airline's Chief Executive Officer Hristo Todorov said it will begin interview on [[ch-aviation]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Philippine Airlines]] announces that the accepting to join the [[Oneworld]] airline alliance in the future. It will become the second airline in southeast Asia to join the alliance, following [[Malaysia Airlines]].\n* Coalition aircraft have destroyed over 1,200 Islamic State [[Tank truck|tanker trucks]] since [[2015 in aviation#October|October 2015]] in [[Operation Tidal Wave II]].<ref name=warrick20161231/>\n* According to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|United Nations High Commission for Refugees]], the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition]] has conducted 3,936 airstrikes in [[Yemen]] during 2016.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-idUSKCN1AW1HK Aboudi, Sami, \"Pace of airstrikes, clashes in Yemen sharply higher in 2017: report,\" Reuters, 16 August 2017, 8:57 a.m.]</ref>\n* U.S. airlines have cancelled only 1.17 percent of their flights during 2016, their best annual performance in the 22 years the [[United States Department of Transportation]] has collected data on the issue; their previous record low had been 1.24 percent in 2002. They also have lost or misplaced luggage at a rate of 2.70 bags per 1,000 customers, the lowest rate since the Transportation Department began collecting data in 1987, and have \"bumped\" ticketed passengers from overbooked flights at a rate of 0.62 per 10,000 passengers, the lowest annual rate since the Transportation Department began tracking the issue in 1995. U.S. airlines also have shown improvements over 2015 in on-time arrival rates and in the number of customer complaints in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-us-flight-cancellations-baggage-problems-fall-to-historic-lows-2017-2|title=US flight cancellations and baggage issues have fallen to historic lows}}</ref>\n\n==First flights==\n===January===\n*29 January \u2013[[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737 MAX 8]] \u2013 N8701Q<ref>Dwyer-Lindgren, Jeremy. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2016/01/29/boeings-new-737-max-takes-off-maiden-flight/79516468/ \"Boeing's new 737 MAX completes its maiden flight\"]. [[USA Today]], 29 January 2016. Retrieved 28 May 2016.</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 [[Enstrom TH180]] \u2013 N180TH<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Pilot|date=April 2016|title=Enstrom TH180 flying.. then not|page=16|publisher=Archant Specialist}}</ref>\n*9 February \u2013 [[Airbus A320neo|Airbus A321neo]] \u2013 D-AVXB\n\n===March===\n*2 March \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW109|AgustaWestland AW109 Trekker]] \u2013 I-AGGR<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Pilot|date=April 2016|title=First flight of AW109 Trekker|page=16|publisher=Archant Specialist}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 4 April \u2013 [[Skyleader UL-39 Albi]] \u2013 OK-UUH 01<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Air-Britain Aviation World|publisher=[[Air-Britain]]|title=Aero Friedrichshafen|year=June 2016|volume=68|issue=2|author=Nigel Hitchman|issn=1742-996X}}</ref>\n* 22 April \u2013 [[Mitsubishi X-2 Shinshin]] \u2013 51-0001<ref>Pittaway, Nigel. \"ShinShin's Maiden Flight\". ''Air International'', June 2016, Vol. 90, No. 6. p. 5. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n* 28 April \u2013 [[Kamov Ka-62]] \u2013 RA-62002<ref>Maldenov, Alexander. \"Ka-62\". ''[[Air International]]'', June 2016, Vol. 90, No. 6. pp. 6\u20137. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 17 May \u2013 [[Diamond Dart 450]] \u2013 OE-VDA<ref name=firstFlightPR>{{cite press release |url= http://www.diamond-air.at/media-center/press-releases/news/article/maiden-flight-of-the-diamond-aircraft-dart-450.html |title= Maiden flight of the Diamond Aircraft DART-450 |publisher= Diamond Aircraft |date= 17 May 2016 |access-date= 19 June 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160531045203/http://www.diamond-air.at/media-center/press-releases/news/article/maiden-flight-of-the-diamond-aircraft-dart-450.html |archive-date= 31 May 2016 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 23 May \u2013 [[Embraer E-Jet E2 family|Embraer E190-E2]] \u2013 PR-ZEY\n* 31 May \u2013 [[HAL HTT-40]]<ref>Pittaway, Nigel. \"HTT-40 First Flight\". ''Air International'', July 2016, Vol. 91, No. 1, p. 16. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 21 July \u2013 [[Tecnam P2012 Traveller]] \u2013 I-PTFC<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarsfield|first=Kate|title=Tecnam P2012 Traveller takes flight|publisher=Flightglobal|date=25 July 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/tecnam-p2012-traveller-takes-flight-427793/}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 17 August \u2013 [[Hybrid Air Vehicles HAV 304 Airlander 10|Hybrid Air Vehicles Airlander 10]] \u2013 G-PHRG<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com 2016-08-18\"/>\n\n===October===\n* 26 October \u2013 [[Beriev A-100]]\n\n===November===\n* 4 November \u2013 [[Bombardier Global 7000]] \u2013 C-GLBO<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/11/04/news/companies/bombardier-global-7000-first-flight/index.html|title=$73 million Bombardier jet makes first flight|first=Jon|last=Ostrower|date=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 21 November \u2013 [[Stratos 714]] \u2013 N403KT<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/vlj-start-up-completes-first-flight-of-stratos-714-431973/|title=VLJ start-up completes first flight of Stratos 714|date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 24 November \u2013 [[Airbus A350 XWB|Airbus A350-1000]] \u2013 F-WWIL<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbus.com/presscentre/pressreleases/press-release-detail/detail/first-a350-1000-successfully-completes-first-flight/|title=First A350-1000 successfully completes first flight}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 17 December \u2013 [[Gulfstream G500/G600|Gulfstream G600]] \u2013 N600G<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarsfield|first=Kate|title=Gulfstream G600 takes to the skies|publisher=Flightglobal|date=19 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/gulfstream-g600-takes-to-the-skies-432545/}}</ref>\n* 20 December\n**[[Avicopter AC352]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/chinas-ac352-conducts-maiden-flight-432623/|title=China's AC352 conducts maiden flight|website=flightglobal.com}}</ref>\n**[[Boeing BTX-1]] \u2013 N381TX<ref name=\"ff\">{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-and-saab-complete-first-t-x-flight-432611/|title=Boeing and Saab complete first T-X flight|date=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Entered service==\n\n* 25 January \u2013 [[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus A320neo]] with [[Lufthansa]]\n* 28 June \u2013 [[Comac ARJ21|Comac ARJ21-700]] with [[Chengdu Airlines]]\n* 15 July \u2013 [[Bombardier CSeries|Bombardier CS100]] with [[Swiss Global Air Lines]]\n* 2 August \u2013 [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II|Lockheed Martin F-35A Lightning II]] with the [[United States Air Force]]\n*14 December  \u2013 [[Bombardier CSeries|Bombardier CS300]] with [[airBaltic]]\n\n==Retirements==\n;14 January\n*The [[Boeing 747]] from the [[Air France]] fleet.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n;23 November\n*The [[Airbus A340]] from the [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] fleet. The last flight is by an [[Airbus A340#A340-300|A340-300]] registered EC-GUP.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{Aviation timelines navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2016 in aviation| ]]\n[[Category:Aviation by year]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "De-cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_in_aviation"}
{"title_page": "Vivian Schiller", "text_new": "[[File:Vivian Schiller - International Journalism Festival 2015.JPG|thumb|Vivian Schiller]]\n'''Vivian Luisa Schiller''' (born September 13, 1961)<ref name=B&C>{{cite news |title=The Next Wave: 10 Women to Watch in Media |date=2003-10-20 |publisher=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |volume=133 |issue=42 |pages=16}}</ref> is the former president and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[National Public Radio]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99152497 |title=Vivian Schiller, NPR Biography |accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> and former head of news and journalism partnerships at [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://mashable.com/2014/10/08/vivian-schiller-resignation/ | work=Mashable | title=Vivian Schiller, Twitter's Head of News, Steps Down | date=2014-10-08}}</ref> She is also the former senior vice president and chief digital officer for [[NBC News]], including oversight of [[NBCNews.com]].<ref>http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/487235-NBC_News_Takes_Back_MSNBC_com_From_Microsoft.php</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nSchiller is the daughter of Ronald Schiller, a former editor at ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', and Lillian Schiller of [[Larchmont, New York]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/29/style/vivian-schiller-wed-in-atlanta.html |title=Vivian Schiller Wed in Atlanta |date=1992-03-29 |accessdate=2009-05-12 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> She graduated from [[Cornell University]] with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[Russian studies]] and Soviet studies, and a [[Master's degree]] in [[Russian language|Russian]] from [[Middlebury College]].<ref name=NYT2>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/01/business/media/01askthetimes.html |title=Talk to The Times: Senior Vice President and General Manager, NYTimes.com |date=2008-08-31 |accessdate=2009-05-12 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> After finishing her degrees, Schiller worked as tour guide and simultaneous Russian interpreter in the former Soviet Union.\n\n==Turner Broadcasting/CNN==\nIn 1988 she joined Turner Broadcasting as a production assistant. During her early years with the company, Schiller worked on documentaries, children's series and network specials for TBS Superstation and TNT including programs such as National Geographic Explorer, David Attenborough's Private life of Plants, Captain Planet the Planters, Tom & Jerry's Kids, The Golden Globe Awards,  and specials and series from the BBC, the Audubon Society, and the National Wildlife Federation.\n\nIn 1998, Schiller transferred to CNN, where she eventually became head of the documentary unit which produced special and series for CNN-US and CNN International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multichannel.com/news/orphan-articles/schiller-cokes-koonin-fill-key-turner-jobs/159676|title=Schiller, Cokes Koonin To Fill Key Turner Jobs|work=multichannel.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/02/07/vivian-schiller-to-head-cnn-s-documentary-division|title=Vivian Schiller to Head CNN's Documentary Division|work=Time Warner|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPrograms during that time included the Cold War, Beneath the Veil, Hank Aaron: Chasing the Dream and more. Schiller's division  won multiple awards under her supervision including Emmys, Peabody's, DuPont's and  Overseas Press Club Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20140103/|title=Advisory: CNN Re-Airing Groundbreaking 1998 Documentary - \"COLD WAR\"|work=gwu.edu|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0113254/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/cnn-presents-beneath-the-veil-and-unholy-war|title=The Peabody Awards - CNN Presents: \"Beneath the Veil\" and \"Unholy War\"|work=peabodyawards.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discovery Times Channel==\n\nIn 2002, Schiller was hired by The New York Times and Discovery Communications to develop and run a new joint venture network that would late become the Discovery Times Channel (the current-day [[Investigation Discovery]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentary.org/feature/old-grey-lady-ready-her-close-conversation-executives-behind-discovery-times-channel|title=The 'Old Grey Lady' Is Ready For Her Close-Up: A Conversation with the Executives Behind Discovery Times Channel|work=International Documentary Association|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe network commissioned and programmed hundreds of hours of critically acclaimed current affairs and history series and specials including the 10-part series \"Off To War\u201d which followed a unit of National Guardsmen from Arkansas during their deployment to Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2005-10-14/features/0510140280_1_iraq-returns-as-series-soldiers-discovery-times-channel|title=Documentary On Unit In Iraq Returns As Series|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==New York Times==\n\nIn 2006, after The New York Times and Discovery Communications  joint venture severed, Schiller joined the New York Times full-time to oversee original web video and then served as general manager of NYTimes.com, then the largest newspaper site in the world. While at The New York Times, Schiller was instrumental in integrating the newspaper and web newsrooms, including embedding web developers with journalists. Under Schiller's watch, the New York Times launched its first mobile presence, Facebook pages and Twitter accounts and grew audiences by double digits.<ref>[http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20060424005903/en/York-Times-Promotes-Vivian-Schiller-Senior-Vice#.VKEQ0sAAA]</ref>\n\n==NPR==\nIn late 2008 Schiller was named president and CEO of NPR. During her tenure, Schiller was widely credited with dramatically upgrading the network's digital presence, significantly expanding its revenue base, and attracting more listeners. She greenlit the network's first investigative unit and launched diversity initiatives that expanded the organizations output of multicultural programming for radio and online. Under her watch, NPR launched its mobile apps and expanded its digital output dramatically.\n\n===Juan Williams controversy===\nOn October 20, 2010, NPR fired political analyst [[Juan Williams]]. Initial reports indicated Williams was fired for his comments on ''[[Fox News]]'' that he gets \"nervous\" when he sees people in \"Muslim garb\" boarding a plane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Juan Williams fired by NPR |author=Andy Barr |newspaper=Politico |date=21 October 2010 |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/43951.html |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>  Speaking to the media, Schiller stated Williams was not fired for that particular incident, but for offering his controversial opinions on several occasions, which she deemed a breach of journalistic ethics for an NPR analyst.<ref>{{cite news |title=NPR axes, Fox defends Williams over Muslim remarks |author=Brett Zongker |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=21 October 2010 |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/top/all/7258567.html |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nSchiller then intensified the existing controversy over Williams' dismissal when she added that Williams should have kept his Muslim comments between himself and \"his psychiatrist or his publicist\u2014take your pick.\" Schiller quickly retracted her own remarks, stating, \"I spoke hastily and I apologize to Juan and others for my thoughtless remark.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NPR CEO: Williams' Views Should Stay Between Himself And 'His Psychiatrist' |author=Mark Memmott |newspaper=NPR |date=21 October 2010 |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2010/10/21/130728202/npr-ceo-williams-views-of-muslims-should-stay-between-himself-and-his-psychiatrist |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nJuan Williams, appearing soon after on Fox News Channel \"The O'Reilly Factor\" noted in his own defense that other journalist staff members of NPR had previously voiced their own personal opinions and observations without being reprimanded or terminated.  Williams speculated that his termination was occasioned by his frequent appearances on Fox News Channel programs in general, and not by any individual remarks he may have made.\n\nIn January 2011, due to concerns with the \"speed and handling of the termination process\" of Juan Williams, the NPR board decided to deny Schiller a 2010 bonus. At the same time, the board \"expressed confidence in Vivian Schiller's leadership going forward.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Top NPR official stepping down |author=James Rainey |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-npr-20110107,0,7743574.story |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |date=7 January 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation from NPR===\nIn March 2011, Vivian Schiller resigned as president and chief executive of National Public Radio amid controversy surrounding the former NPR fundraising executive Ronald Schiller, who is not related to Vivian Schiller.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704132204576190563679921804 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Russell | last=Adams | title=NPR Executive Cedes New Role at Aspen Institute | date=2011-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9LS0VAO0.htm|title=NPR CEO resigns after VP criticizes tea party|author=BEN NUCKOLS|work=Businessweek.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/10/business/media/10npr.html | work=The New York Times | first1=Elizabeth | last1=Jensen | first2=Brian | last2=Stelter | title=NPR Chief Resigns Amid Latest Imbroglio | date=2011-03-09}}</ref> Ronald Schiller has been secretly taped in a sting operation, where during a private conversation with two men posing as potential donors, he derided the \"tea party\" movement as a collection of \"gun-toting\" racists and \"fundamentalist Christians\" who have \"hijacked\" the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Vivian Schiller's departure was, in part, an attempt to show congressional budget-cutters that NPR could hold itself accountable.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-npr-resign-20110310,0,4587646.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=James | last=Oliphant | title=NPR president's resignation fuels foes of public broadcasting funding | date=2011-03-10}}</ref>\n\nDave Edwards, then chair of the NPR board of directors, sent the following message to the NPR staff regarding the resignation: \"It is with deep regret that I tell you that the NPR Board of Directors has accepted the resignation of Vivian Schiller as President and CEO of NPR, effective immediately. The Board accepted her resignation with understanding, genuine regret, and great respect for her leadership of NPR these past two years.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Memmott|first=Mark|title=NPR CEO Vivian Schiller Resigns|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/03/09/134388981/npr-ceo-vivian-schiller-resigns|work=National Public Radio Blog|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=9 March 2011}}</ref> She was succeeded on an interim basis by Joyce Slocum, the senior vice president of legal affairs and general counsel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/chief-executive-of-npr-resigns/ |title=Chief Executive of NPR Resigns |author=Lyons, Patrick |date=2011-03-09 |accessdate=2011-03-09 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==NBC News==\nAfter her resignation from NPR, Schiller was hired by NBC News president Steve Capus to oversee the acquisition of MSNBC Digital Networks, then a joint venture of Microsoft and NBCUniversal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/vivian-schiller-joins-nbc-news-as-chief-digital-officer_b69305|title=Vivian Schiller Joins NBC News as Chief Digital Officer|work=mediabistro.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\nSchiller led the company's efforts to acquire full ownership of the digital operation, and integrate it into the rest of NBC New in New York under a new name, NBCNews.com. That project culminated in the summer of 2013.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/16/business/media/msnbccom-renamed-nbcnewscom-as-microsoft-and-nbc-divorce.html]</ref>\n\nWhile at NBCNews.com, Schiller oversaw the acquisition of Stringwire, a live videostreaming platform for breaking news,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/business/media/nbc-buying-web-service-to-stream-phone-video.html?_r=0]</ref> and oversaw the network's education initiative \u201cEducation Nation.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschools.org/news/innovation-challenge|title=NBC News, CITI, and NewSchools Venture Fund to launch second-annual \"CITI Innovation Challenge\" at \"Education Nation\"|work=newschools.org|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==EveryBlock closing and reopening==\nIn February 2013, Schiller closed the NBC News-owned site EveryBlock, saying it \"wasn't a strategic fit.\" <ref name=\"Sonderman, Jeff\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/203437/nbc-closes-hyperlocal-pioneer-everyblock/|title=NBC closes hyperlocal, data-driven publishing pioneer EveryBlock |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17 |publisher=[[The Poynter Institute for Media Studies|Poynter]] |author=Sonderman, Jeff}}</ref> Schiller was widely criticized for her handling of the situation, as the site was turned off one morning with no prior warning to site users and providing no access to archives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.everyblock.com/2013/feb/07/goodbye/|title=Farewell, neighbors |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bostinno.com/2013/02/07/everyblock-closes-without-warning-to-the-shock-and-ire-of-its-audience/|title=EveryBlock Closes Without Warning to the Shock and Ire of Its Audience |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17}}</ref>\n\nSchiller was also criticized for not making a good-faith effort to sell the site before closing it. On the day the site was closed, Schiller said \"We looked at various options to keep this going, but none of them were viable.\"<ref name=\"Sonderman, Jeff\"/> Several days after the site had shut down, she said \"we are continuing to look into options very seriously.\" EveryBlock founder [[Adrian Holovaty]] said she \"poisoned the pie before trying to sell it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/203813/everyblock-could-still-be-sold-says-schiller-after-abrupt-closing-of-hyperlocal-pioneer/|title=EveryBlock could still be sold, says Schiller, after abrupt closing of hyperlocal pioneer |date=2013-02-11 |accessdate=2013-03-17 |publisher=[[The Poynter Institute for Media Studies|Poynter]] |author=Sonderman, Jeff}}</ref>\n\n==Twitter==\nIn January 2014, Schiller joined Twitter as head of news with responsibility for expanding the platform's relationships with news organizations. In July 2014, Global Media Head Katie Stanton expanded Schiller's responsibilities to chair of global news for the company, including setting strategy for partnerships with journalists around the world. Schiller left Twitter in October as part of CEO Dick Costolo's ongoing series of strategic pivots and executive changes and ousters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-ceo-dick-costolo-struggles-to-define-vision-1415323289|title=Twitter CEO Dick Costolo Struggles to Define Vision|author=Yoree Koh and Kirsten Grind|date=7 November 2014|work=WSJ|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Present ==\nSince leaving Twitter, Schiller has been working as an independent consultant and advisor to various domestic and international organizations, including to legacy companies as well start-ups such as Vocativ, a data-driven online news provider.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/former-npr-boss-nbc-exec-and-twitter-exec-vivian-schiller-has-a-new-part-time-gig-2014-11|title=Former NPR Boss, NBC Exec, and Twitter Exec Vivian Schiller Has A New Part-Time Gig|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-03-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nSchiller is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations. She sits on the boards of CUNY Journalism School; the Investigative News Network; Society for Science and the Public; and International Center for Journalism. She was the founding board chair for The News Literary Project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+road+less+traveled%3A+Vivian+Schiller%27s+circuitous+route+to+the+top...-a0194529307|title=The road less traveled: Vivian Schiller's circuitous route to the top of NPR.|work=thefreelibrary.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajrarchive.org/Article.asp?id=5103|title=American Journalism Review|work=ajrarchive.org|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Vivian Schiller}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box | title=President and CEO of [[National Public Radio]] | before=[[Kevin Klose]] | after=[[Gary Knell]]| years=2009&ndash;2011}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schiller, Vivian}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Middlebury College alumni]]\n[[Category:NPR personalities]]\n[[Category:The New York Times corporate staff]]\n[[Category:People from Larchmont, New York]]\n[[Category:CNN executives]]\n[[Category:NBC executives]]\n[[Category:Twitter people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Vivian Schiller - International Journalism Festival 2015.JPG|thumb|Vivian Schiller]]\n'''Vivian Luisa Schiller''' (born September 13, 1961)<ref name=B&C>{{cite news |title=The Next Wave: 10 Women to Watch in Media |date=2003-10-20 |publisher=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |volume=133 |issue=42 |pages=16}}</ref> is the former president and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[National Public Radio]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99152497 |title=Vivian Schiller, NPR Biography |accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> and former head of news and journalism partnerships at [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://mashable.com/2014/10/08/vivian-schiller-resignation/ | work=Mashable | title=Vivian Schiller, Twitter's Head of News, Steps Down | date=2014-10-08}}</ref> She is also the former senior vice president and chief digital officer for [[NBC News]], including oversight of [[NBCNews.com]].<ref>http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/487235-NBC_News_Takes_Back_MSNBC_com_From_Microsoft.php</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nSchiller is the daughter of Ronald Schiller, a former editor at ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', and Lillian Schiller of [[Larchmont, New York]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/29/style/vivian-schiller-wed-in-atlanta.html |title=Vivian Schiller Wed in Atlanta |date=1992-03-29 |accessdate=2009-05-12 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> She graduated from [[Cornell University]] with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[Russian studies]] and Soviet studies, and a [[Master's degree]] in [[Russian language|Russian]] from [[Middlebury College]].<ref name=NYT2>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/01/business/media/01askthetimes.html |title=Talk to The Times: Senior Vice President and General Manager, NYTimes.com |date=2008-08-31 |accessdate=2009-05-12 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> After finishing her degrees, Schiller worked as tour guide and simultaneous Russian interpreter in the former Soviet Union.\n\n==Turner Broadcasting/CNN==\nIn 1988 she joined Turner Broadcasting as a production assistant. During her early years with the company, Schiller worked on documentaries, children's series and network specials for TBS Superstation and TNT including programs such as National Geographic Explorer, David Attenborough's Private life of Plants, Captain Planet the Planters, Tom & Jerry's Kids, The Golden Globe Awards,  and specials and series from the BBC, the Audubon Society, and the National Wildlife Federation.\n\nIn 1998, Schiller transferred to CNN where she eventually became head of the documentary unit which produced special and series for CNN-US and CNN International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multichannel.com/news/orphan-articles/schiller-cokes-koonin-fill-key-turner-jobs/159676|title=Schiller, Cokes Koonin To Fill Key Turner Jobs|work=multichannel.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/02/07/vivian-schiller-to-head-cnn-s-documentary-division|title=Vivian Schiller to Head CNN's Documentary Division|work=Time Warner|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPrograms during that time included the Cold War, Beneath the Veil, Hank Aaron: Chasing the Dream and more. Schiller's division  won multiple awards under her supervision including Emmys, Peabody's, DuPont's and  Overseas Press Club Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20140103/|title=Advisory: CNN Re-Airing Groundbreaking 1998 Documentary - \"COLD WAR\"|work=gwu.edu|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0113254/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/cnn-presents-beneath-the-veil-and-unholy-war|title=The Peabody Awards - CNN Presents: \"Beneath the Veil\" and \"Unholy War\"|work=peabodyawards.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discovery Times Channel==\n\nIn 2002, Schiller was hired by The New York Times and Discovery Communications to develop and run a new joint venture network that would late become the Discovery Times Channel (the current-day [[Investigation Discovery]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentary.org/feature/old-grey-lady-ready-her-close-conversation-executives-behind-discovery-times-channel|title=The 'Old Grey Lady' Is Ready For Her Close-Up: A Conversation with the Executives Behind Discovery Times Channel|work=International Documentary Association|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe network commissioned and programmed hundreds of hours of critically acclaimed current affairs and history series and specials including the 10-part series \"Off To War\u201d which followed a unit of National Guardsmen from Arkansas during their deployment to Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2005-10-14/features/0510140280_1_iraq-returns-as-series-soldiers-discovery-times-channel|title=Documentary On Unit In Iraq Returns As Series|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==New York Times==\n\nIn 2006, after The New York Times and Discovery Communications  joint venture severed, Schiller joined the New York Times full-time to oversee original web video and then served as General Manager of NYTimes.com, then the largest newspaper site in the world. While at The New York Times, Schiller was instrumental in integrating the newspaper and web newsrooms, including embedding web developers with journalists. Under Schiller's watch, the New York Times launched its first mobile presence, Facebook pages and Twitter accounts and grew audiences by double digits.<ref>[http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20060424005903/en/York-Times-Promotes-Vivian-Schiller-Senior-Vice#.VKEQ0sAAA]</ref>\n\n==NPR==\nIn late 2008 Schiller was named President and CEO of NPR. During her tenure, Schiller was widely credited with dramatically upgrading the network's digital presence, significantly expanding its revenue base, and attracting more listeners. She greenlit the network's first investigative unit and launched diversity initiatives that expanded the organizations output of multicultural programming for radio and online. Under her watch, NPR launched its mobile apps and expanded its digital output dramatically.\n\n===Juan Williams controversy===\nOn October 20, 2010, NPR fired political analyst [[Juan Williams]]. Initial reports indicated Williams was fired for his comments on ''[[Fox News]]'' that he gets \"nervous\" when he sees people in \"Muslim garb\" boarding a plane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Juan Williams fired by NPR |author=Andy Barr |newspaper=Politico |date=21 October 2010 |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/43951.html |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>  Speaking to the media, Schiller stated Williams was not fired for that particular incident, but for offering his controversial opinions on several occasions, which she deemed a breach of journalistic ethics for an NPR analyst.<ref>{{cite news |title=NPR axes, Fox defends Williams over Muslim remarks |author=Brett Zongker |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=21 October 2010 |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/top/all/7258567.html |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nSchiller then intensified the existing controversy over Williams' dismissal when she added that Williams should have kept his Muslim comments between himself and \"his psychiatrist or his publicist\u2014take your pick.\" Schiller quickly retracted her own remarks, stating, \"I spoke hastily and I apologize to Juan and others for my thoughtless remark.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NPR CEO: Williams' Views Should Stay Between Himself And 'His Psychiatrist' |author=Mark Memmott |newspaper=NPR |date=21 October 2010 |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2010/10/21/130728202/npr-ceo-williams-views-of-muslims-should-stay-between-himself-and-his-psychiatrist |accessdate=21 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nJuan Williams, appearing soon after on Fox News Channel \"The O'Reilly Factor\" noted in his own defense that other journalist staff members of NPR had previously voiced their own personal opinions and observations without being reprimanded or terminated.  Williams speculated that his termination was occasioned by his frequent appearances on Fox News Channel programs in general, and not by any individual remarks he may have made.\n\nIn January 2011, due to concerns with the \"speed and handling of the termination process\" of Juan Williams, the NPR board decided to deny Schiller a 2010 bonus. At the same time, the board \"expressed confidence in Vivian Schiller's leadership going forward.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Top NPR official stepping down |author=James Rainey |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-npr-20110107,0,7743574.story |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |date=7 January 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation from NPR===\nIn March 2011, Vivian Schiller resigned as president and chief executive of National Public Radio amid controversy surrounding the former NPR fundraising executive Ronald Schiller, who is not related to Vivian Schiller.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704132204576190563679921804 | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Russell | last=Adams | title=NPR Executive Cedes New Role at Aspen Institute | date=2011-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9LS0VAO0.htm|title=NPR CEO resigns after VP criticizes tea party|author=BEN NUCKOLS|work=Businessweek.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/10/business/media/10npr.html | work=The New York Times | first1=Elizabeth | last1=Jensen | first2=Brian | last2=Stelter | title=NPR Chief Resigns Amid Latest Imbroglio | date=2011-03-09}}</ref> Ronald Schiller has been secretly taped in a sting operation, where during a private conversation with two men posing as potential donors, he derided the \"tea party\" movement as a collection of \"gun-toting\" racists and \"fundamentalist Christians\" who have \"hijacked\" the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Vivian Schiller's departure was, in part, an attempt to show congressional budget-cutters that NPR could hold itself accountable.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-npr-resign-20110310,0,4587646.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=James | last=Oliphant | title=NPR president's resignation fuels foes of public broadcasting funding | date=2011-03-10}}</ref>\n\nDave Edwards, then Chair of the NPR Board of Directors, sent the following message to the NPR staff regarding the resignation: \"It is with deep regret that I tell you that the NPR Board of Directors has accepted the resignation of Vivian Schiller as President and CEO of NPR, effective immediately. The Board accepted her resignation with understanding, genuine regret, and great respect for her leadership of NPR these past two years.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Memmott|first=Mark|title=NPR CEO Vivian Schiller Resigns|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/03/09/134388981/npr-ceo-vivian-schiller-resigns|work=National Public Radio Blog|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=9 March 2011}}</ref> She was succeeded on an interim basis by Joyce Slocum, the senior vice president of Legal Affairs and General Counsel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/chief-executive-of-npr-resigns/ |title=Chief Executive of NPR Resigns |author=Lyons, Patrick |date=2011-03-09 |accessdate=2011-03-09 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==NBC News==\nAfter her resignation from NPR, Schiller was hired by NBC News President Steve Capus to oversee the acquisition of MSNBC Digital Networks, then a joint venture of Microsoft and NBCUniversal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/vivian-schiller-joins-nbc-news-as-chief-digital-officer_b69305|title=Vivian Schiller Joins NBC News as Chief Digital Officer|work=mediabistro.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\nSchiller led the company's efforts to acquire full ownership of the digital operation, and integrate it into the rest of NBC New in New York under a new name, NBCNews.com. That project culminated in the summer of 2013.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/16/business/media/msnbccom-renamed-nbcnewscom-as-microsoft-and-nbc-divorce.html]</ref>\n\nWhile at NBCNews.com, Schiller oversaw the acquisition of Stringwire, a live videostreaming platform for breaking news,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/business/media/nbc-buying-web-service-to-stream-phone-video.html?_r=0]</ref> and oversaw the network's education initiative \u201cEducation Nation.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschools.org/news/innovation-challenge|title=NBC News, CITI, and NewSchools Venture Fund to launch second-annual \"CITI Innovation Challenge\" at \"Education Nation\"|work=newschools.org|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==EveryBlock closing and reopening==\nIn February 2013, Schiller closed the NBC News-owned site EveryBlock, saying it \"wasn't a strategic fit.\" <ref name=\"Sonderman, Jeff\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/203437/nbc-closes-hyperlocal-pioneer-everyblock/|title=NBC closes hyperlocal, data-driven publishing pioneer EveryBlock |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17 |publisher=[[The Poynter Institute for Media Studies|Poynter]] |author=Sonderman, Jeff}}</ref> Schiller was widely criticized for her handling of the situation, as the site was turned off one morning with no prior warning to site users and providing no access to archives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.everyblock.com/2013/feb/07/goodbye/|title=Farewell, neighbors |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bostinno.com/2013/02/07/everyblock-closes-without-warning-to-the-shock-and-ire-of-its-audience/|title=EveryBlock Closes Without Warning to the Shock and Ire of Its Audience |date=2013-02-07 |accessdate=2013-03-17}}</ref>\n\nSchiller was also criticized for not making a good-faith effort to sell the site before closing it. On the day the site was closed, Schiller said \"We looked at various options to keep this going, but none of them were viable.\"<ref name=\"Sonderman, Jeff\"/> Several days after the site had shut down, she said \"we are continuing to look into options very seriously.\" EveryBlock founder [[Adrian Holovaty]] said she \"poisoned the pie before trying to sell it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/top-stories/203813/everyblock-could-still-be-sold-says-schiller-after-abrupt-closing-of-hyperlocal-pioneer/|title=EveryBlock could still be sold, says Schiller, after abrupt closing of hyperlocal pioneer |date=2013-02-11 |accessdate=2013-03-17 |publisher=[[The Poynter Institute for Media Studies|Poynter]] |author=Sonderman, Jeff}}</ref>\n\n==Twitter==\nIn January 2014, Schiller joined Twitter as Head of News with responsibility for expanding the platform's relationships with news organizations. In July 2014, Global Media Head Katie Stanton expanded Schiller's responsibilities to Chair of Global News for the company including setting strategy for partnerships with journalists around the world. Schiller left Twitter in October as part of CEO Dick Costolo ongoing series of strategic pivots and executive changes and ousters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-ceo-dick-costolo-struggles-to-define-vision-1415323289|title=Twitter CEO Dick Costolo Struggles to Define Vision|author=Yoree Koh and Kirsten Grind|date=7 November 2014|work=WSJ|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Present ==\nSince leaving Twitter, Schiller has been working as an independent consultant and advisor to various domestic and international organizations, including to legacy companies as well start-ups such as Vocativ, a data-driven online news provider.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/former-npr-boss-nbc-exec-and-twitter-exec-vivian-schiller-has-a-new-part-time-gig-2014-11|title=Former NPR Boss, NBC Exec, and Twitter Exec Vivian Schiller Has A New Part-Time Gig|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-03-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nSchiller is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations. She sits on the boards of CUNY Journalism School; the Investigative News Network; Society for Science and the Public; and International Center for Journalism. She was the founding board chair for The News Literary Project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+road+less+traveled%3A+Vivian+Schiller%27s+circuitous+route+to+the+top...-a0194529307|title=The road less traveled: Vivian Schiller's circuitous route to the top of NPR.|work=thefreelibrary.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajrarchive.org/Article.asp?id=5103|title=American Journalism Review|work=ajrarchive.org|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Vivian Schiller}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box | title=President and CEO of [[National Public Radio]] | before=[[Kevin Klose]] | after=[[Gary Knell]]| years=2009&ndash;2011}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schiller, Vivian}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Middlebury College alumni]]\n[[Category:NPR personalities]]\n[[Category:The New York Times corporate staff]]\n[[Category:People from Larchmont, New York]]\n[[Category:CNN executives]]\n[[Category:NBC executives]]\n[[Category:Twitter people]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vivian_Schiller"}
{"title_page": "McDowell High School", "text_new": "{{For|the high school in [[Marion, North Carolina]]|McDowell High School (Marion, North Carolina)}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = McDowell High School\n| image = McDowell High School (logo).jpg\n| image_size = 150px\n| motto = The Right Place For Every Kid\n| established = 1954\n| type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| address = 3580 West 38th St\n| city = [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]]\n| state = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| principal = Brian Fuller\n| campus = Suburban\n| ratio = 15.55<ref name=NCES/>\n| staff = 141.55 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| enrollment = 2,201 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=4215330&ID=421533007320|title=McDowell HS|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| free_label = \n| free = \n| colors = Blue and White <br/>{{color box|#123057}} {{color box|White}}\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.mtsd.org/schools/mcdowell/main}}\n}}\n'''McDowell High School''' is a [[Public school (government funded)|public]] [[high school]] located in [[Millcreek Township, Erie County, Pennsylvania|Millcreek Township, Pennsylvania]] a suburb of [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]]. It is the only high school in the [[Millcreek Township School District]]. The school's [[mascot]] is the [[Troy|Trojan]].\n\n==Students==\nThere are approximately 2,500 students attending McDowell High School. The McDowell campus includes two buildings: McDowell Intermediate accommodating students in grades 9 and 10, and McDowell Senior accommodating grades 11 and 12. Students travel between facilities on the campus when attending classes.\n\n==Enrollment==\n\nAs of the 2015-16 school year:<ref name=\"enrollment\">{{cite web|title=McDowell High School|url=http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&State=42&County=Erie+County&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&SchoolPageNum=3&ID=421533007320|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Group\n! Number of students\n! Percent\n|-\n| All\n| 2,319\n| 100%\n|-\n| White\n| 2,066\n| 89.1%\n|-\n| Black\n| 77\n| 3.3%\n|-\n| Asian\n| 27\n| 1.2%\n|-\n| Hispanic\n| 85\n| 3.7%\n|-\n| Two or More Races\n| 57\n| 2.5%\n|-\n| American Indian/Alaskan Native\n| 5\n| 0.2%\n|-\n| Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander\n| 2\n| 0.1%\n|-\n| Male\n| 1215\n| 52.4%\n|-\n| Female\n| 1104\n| 47.6%\n|}\n\n==Renovations==\nThe Millcreek Township School Board has been in talks since 2009 for renovations to the McDowell property.  In December 2011, the school board announced four possible options for renovation, ranging in cost from $80 million to $100 million. The board has decided to create a new practice field for football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edline.net/pages/mtsd/High_School_Renovation_and_Con|title=Error|author=|date=|website=edline.net|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2012, by a vote of 8-1, the Millcreek Township School Board voted in favor of consolidating both McDowell Senior High and McDowell Intermediate at cost of $110 million.  During the meeting, school board members voted 6-3 in favor of moving Gus Anderson Field to the east side of Caughey Road, despite major student complaints for air condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goerie.com/article/20120731/NEWS02/307309906/Millcreek-OKs-$110M-McDowell-option|title=Article 404 - GoErie.com - Erie, PA|author=|date=|website=GoErie.com|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 7, 2013, the superintendent of Millcreek, Michael Golde, announced he was taking a medical leave and stepping down from his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erietvnews.com/story/21080039/golde-on-medical-leave-not-returning-as-millcreek-superintendent|title=Golde On Medical Leave, Not Returning As Millcreek Superintendent|author=|date=|website=erietvnews.com|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>  One week later, the school board announced plans for a new McDowell were being scaled back, due to the high cost of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2013302149934|title=Melrose Place Star Amy Locane-Bovenizer Sentenced to Three Years in Prison|first=TV|last=Guide|date=|website=goerie.com|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late February and early March, it was revealed the school district was between $6 million and $9 million in debt.  The final announced total was $8.8 million, as of April 12, 2013.  Due to the budget shortfall, the [[Millcreek Township School District]] announced the closure of two elementary schools, which officially ended the McDowell renovation project.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://goerie.com/school-closings-staff-cuts-tax-hike-sought-in-millcreek |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-04-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413233457/http://goerie.com/school-closings-staff-cuts-tax-hike-sought-in-millcreek |archive-date=2013-04-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, the Millcreek School Board approved nearly 2.4 million dollars to a renovation to the high school. There were renovations to the field, lockers and windows. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195855/http://www.goerie.com/millcreek-school-board-approves-mcdowell-renovations]\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n\n*[[Dan Briggs (musician)|Dan Briggs]], musician ([[Between the Buried and Me]])\n*[[Marc Brown (author)|Marc Brown]], author of ''[[Arthur (TV series)|Arthur]]'' television show\n*[[James Conner (American football)|James Conner]], All-American college football player and current [[NFL]] running back for [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n*[[Jim Corbett (American football)|Jim Corbett]], NFL player\n*[[David Greenberger]], artist\n*[[William Kowalski]], American-Canadian novelist and screenwriter\n*[[Katie Linendoll]], TV host, speaker and journalist, focused on technology and gadgets{{citation needed|reason=article does not mention her high school|date=May 2017}}\n*[[Connor McDavid]], center and team captain for NHL's [[Edmonton Oilers]]<ref>{{cite web | title = 2015 OHL Academic Players of the Year | publisher = Ontario Hockey League | date = April 30, 2015 | url = http://ontariohockeyleague.com/2015-ohl-academic-players-of-the-year/}}</ref>\n*[[Pat Monahan]], lead singer of [[Train (band)|Train]]\n*[[Mark L. Nelson|Mark Nelson]], chemist and inventor of the antibiotic Nuzyra\n*[[Brian Stablein]], former [[National Football League|NFL]] receiver ([[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Detroit Lions]], 1994-2000)\n*[[Jonathan Stark (actor)|Jonathan Stark]], television writer/producer \"[[Cheers]]\", \"[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]], \"[[Drew Carey Show|Drew Carey]]\", \"[[According to Jim]]\"\n*[[Dylan Strome]], professional ice hockey player\n*[[Travis Dermott]], professional ice hockey player\n*[[Chris Vrenna]], musician ([[Tweaker (band)|Tweaker]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Marilyn Manson]])\n*William Jeffress, basketball player\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Erie County, Pennsylvania School Districts}}\n\n{{Coord|42.0728|-80.1494|region:US-PA_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macdowell High School}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Schools in Erie County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the high school in [[Marion, North Carolina]]|McDowell High School (Marion, North Carolina)}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = McDowell High School\n| image = McDowell High School (logo).jpg\n| image_size = 150px\n| motto = The Right Place For Every Kid\n| established = 1954\n| type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| address = 3580 West 38th St\n| city = [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]]\n| state = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| principal = Brian Fuller\n| campus = Suburban\n| ratio = 15.55<ref name=NCES/>\n| staff = 141.55 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| enrollment = 2,201 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=4215330&ID=421533007320|title=McDowell HS|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| free_label = \n| free = \n| colors = Blue and White <br/>{{color box|#123057}} {{color box|White}}\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.mtsd.org/schools/mcdowell/main}}\n}}\n'''McDowell High School''' is a [[Public school (government funded)|public]] [[high school]] located in [[Millcreek Township, Erie County, Pennsylvania|Millcreek Township, Pennsylvania]] a suburb of [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]]. It is the only high school in the [[Millcreek Township School District]]. The school's [[mascot]] is the [[Troy|Trojan]].\n\n==Students==\nThere are approximately 2,500 students attending McDowell High School. The McDowell campus includes two buildings: McDowell Intermediate accommodating students in grades 9 and 10, and McDowell Senior accommodating grades 11 and 12. Students travel between facilities on the campus when attending classes.\n\n==Enrollment==\n\nAs of the 2015-16 school year:<ref name=\"enrollment\">{{cite web|title=McDowell High School|url=http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&State=42&County=Erie+County&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&SchoolPageNum=3&ID=421533007320|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Group\n! Number of students\n! Percent\n|-\n| All\n| 2,319\n| 100%\n|-\n| White\n| 2,066\n| 89.1%\n|-\n| Black\n| 77\n| 3.3%\n|-\n| Asian\n| 27\n| 1.2%\n|-\n| Hispanic\n| 85\n| 3.7%\n|-\n| Two or More Races\n| 57\n| 2.5%\n|-\n| American Indian/Alaskan Native\n| 5\n| 0.2%\n|-\n| Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander\n| 2\n| 